[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "10"]
[GameId "2141525847618640"]

{Welcome to the Club Player Sicilian and the world of the Löwenthal variation! We're in for a fun ride, with this version of the Open Sicilian giving Black quick and easy piece play.Lest you're not one hundred percent what the Löwenthal is, it's this:} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {[%csl Gd4]} 5. Nb5 a6 {[%csl Gb5]} (5... a6 {Black continues to make useful pawn moves with gain of tempi against the white knight. After the usual} 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {White does have the bishop-pair and there are potential weaknesses down the d-file, but crucially Black already leads in development, a factor we'll aim to fully exploit, no matter what variation White chooses. (Named after the great 19th Century Hungarian-English Master Johann Löwenthal 1810-1876, the Löwenthal is a mixture of easy development, solidity and activity. Depending on what White does, the Löwenthal Logician must react accordingly, be that with sensible development after an early exchange of queens or very actively, being prepared to gambit a pawn or two should White take positional liberties and allow Black to pursue a strong early initiative.We hope that you will have fun with your Löwenthal adventures, a variation of the Sicilian which isn't overly theoretical - bar in the main line with 8. [Qd1], where Black's early activity and pawn sacrifice lead to an especially lively game - as well as one in which you may well out-theorise your opponents.Good luck with the Löwenthal!)}) *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "The Early Moves"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "14"]
[GameId "2141525848187985"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {[%csl Gd4] This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810 - 1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see in Fifth move alternatives, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 $5 {[%csl Gb5] Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered 5... [d6] being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.} 6. Nd6+ {[%csl Re8]} Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {[%csl Gd6,Ge4,Gg2][%cal Gf6d6,Gf6g6,Gg8f6,Gg8e7,Gd7d5] Activating the black queen and forcing its counterpart to make a big choice: to advance to [c7], exchange on [f6] or retreat. This is the main line of the Löwenthal and 7...[Qf6] brings about a key tabiya, one first defended by the Russian Grandmaster Anatoly Lutikov 1933-1989.} ({Black can also play the solid} 7... Qe7 {, as covered on The Sturdy Löwenthal Sicilian course, but we prefer the more active and popular text move. Note that Black already leads in development and will be quick to complete development with ...[Nge7] and ...[O-O] or after} 8. Qf6 Nxf6 {. (A timely ...[Qg6] may also prove useful, tying White down a little to the defence of [e4] and [g2], all the while as Black looks to liberate the position with the ideal pawn break ...[d5].Of the 6,018 games to have reached this position in ChessBase's massive Mega Database 2024, 2389 40% saw White now retreat the queen to [d1], the move we'll concentrate on in this first theoretical section.Subsequent theory sections will consider the alternatives, with 8. [Qxf6] the second most popular choice in over-the-board practice 1680 games; 28%, and 8. [Qc7] third 750 games; 12%.)}) *

