[White "Key Ideas in the Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Black "The ...d5 Break Part IV"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1b1k1nr/1p1p1ppp/p1n3q1/4p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 9"]
[PlyCount "5"]
[GameId "2141525848286293"]

{(This is the main line of the Lowenthal 8.Qd1 Qg6 9.Nc3 ) . Here Black has two main moves, 9...[Nge7], which fights for control of [d5] and facilitates castling, and our recommendation, the immediate break.} 9... d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4] Yes, this is playable. Black stirs up trouble in the centre and all of White's recaptures have their downsides, as we'll now quickly note.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] By some margin White's main move, threatening a certain check.} ({A} 10. Qxd5 {A risky choice, since the queen will now get kicked around.} Be6 11. Qd3 {(( 11.Qc5? Nd4 Already Black has seized a strong initiative, with neither [c2] nor the white queen looking especially happy, in part because the light-squared bishop is tied to the defence of [g2]: 12.Bd3? Qxg2 13.Rf1 Rc8 With the [e5]-pawn taboo and ...[Nf3]+ imminent in any case, it's fast becoming a massacre.))} Rd8 {Continuing to hound the queen while also getting ready to head forwards with some effect with ...[Nb4].}) ({B} 10. exd5 $2 {The worst of the three possible captures.} Nd4 $1 {The correct way here to attack [c2], placing the knight in contact too with the [e2]- and [f3]-squares.} 11. Bd3 Qxg2 12. Be4 {Clearly fairly forced.} Qh3 {With ... [Nf6] and ...[Bg4] on their way, Black is already somewhat for choice.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Removing the en prise pawn while forcing White to decide how to block the check.} 11. Be3 {[%cal Rd5c7] By no means forced, but very much the main line.} Nd4 $1 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gd4c2,Ge4d5] Black ignores the check on [c7] and counters in turn against [c2]. We'll discuss this fascinating variation in much detail in the first part of the course, devoted to 8. [Qd1].} *

