[Black "The Early Attack on c2"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/1p1p1ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 0 9"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2141525848302678"]

{This queenless middlegame may at first sight not look like a bundle of fun for Black. White controls the [d5]-square for now and is set to augment that control with [Bg5]. However, it's Black's move and a key resource very much keeps us in the game.} 9... Nb4 $1 {[%csl Ga1,Gd5,Ge1][%cal Gb4c2] An active and fairly strong move, threatening to take on [c2], thereby forking the white king and rook. The knight leap also increases Black's control over [d5] and this important tabiya will be covered in the realm of 8. [Qxf6].} *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Ideas in the Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Black "The ...f5 Break"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/1p1pnppp/p1n3q1/4p3/2P1P3/4BP2/PP4PP/RN1QKB1R b KQ - 0 11"]
[PlyCount "7"]
[GameId "2141525848314967"]

{Black doesn't always have to strain every sinew trying to force through ...[d5] early on; there are also pawn breaks in the shape of ...[f5] and ...[b5]. The former is usually associated with Black having castled kingside at an early stage. Here we see White having set up a Maroczy Bind to thoroughly clamp down on the [d5]-square. However, his development is far from a thing of beauty and Black can immediately break out on the kingside.} 11... f5 $1 {[%cal Gf5e4,Ge7f5]} (11... f5 {Undermining e4 and looking to quickly gain a pretty serious initiative in the event of} 12. exf5 Nxf5 {.}) 12. Nc3 fxe4 13. fxe4 b5 $5 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gc8b7,Gc6d4] The third of Black's three pawn breaks now makes its presence felt. Already the white king is starting to feel the heat, with Black all set to press forwards with ...[b4] and perhaps also ...[Nd4].} 14. cxb5 $2 axb5 {[%csl Ge4,Gg2,Gg6][%cal Gb5b4] White is simply in some trouble here as capturing on [b5] will lead to the black queen landing on [e4] or [g2], with some effect.} *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Ideas in the Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Black "The ...b5 Break"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/1p1pnppp/p1n2q2/4p3/2P1P3/3Q4/PP3PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 9"]
[PlyCount "7"]
[GameId "2141525848331352"]

{White has concentrated on the light squares and clearly taken ...[d5] off the agenda for the time being, but the pawn on [c4] does create a hook for another pawn break.} 9... b5 $1 {[%cal Gb5c4] A strong early sacrifice. Black prepares to exchange on [c4] then play for ...[d5] after all, and this is a gambit White probably shouldn't accept.} 10. cxb5 $6 {[%csl Rc6]} axb5 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gb5b4,Gd7d5] Everything is now set for ...[O-O] followed by ...[d5], with ...[b4] also likely to be a pretty useful resource.} 11. Qxb5 $2 Nd4 {[%cal Gd4b5,Gd4c2] Threatening not just the queen, but a big fork.} 12. Qd3 d5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e4,Ge8g8,Gc8a6,Gc8f5] The opening has been a complete disaster for White, who might even resign in disgust here. Black will either go ...[Ba6] or combine an exchange on [e4] with castling and ...[Bf5].} *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Ideas in the Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Black "Combined Weakness of c2 & g2"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/1p3ppp/p4q2/3Pp3/3n4/8/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 12"]
[PlyCount "5"]
[GameId "2141525848347737"]

{White has greedily gone pawn-grabbing and one of our favourite motifs will now prove his undoing: an attack on [c2], combined with pressure against [g2].} 12... Qg6 {[%csl Gc2,Gg2][%cal Gd4c2] There's already just no good way to cover [c2].} 13. Bd3 {[%csl Rg6]} (13. Kd2 Bf5 {Here too the position fast begins to resemble a massacre.}) 13... Qxg2 {[%cal Gg2h1]} 14. Kd2 Bg4 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Gg4d1,Gg2f2,Gg2d5,Ge5e4] Black quite simply has far, far too many threats for White to cope with: ...[Bxd1], ...[Qxf2]+, ...[Nf3]+ and ... [Qxd5] followed by ...[e4].} *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Ideas in the Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Black "Kingside Pressure"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "1rb1k2r/1p3ppp/p2p1q2/3Ppn2/2P5/Q3B3/PP2BPPP/R3K2R b KQk - 0 14"]
[PlyCount "5"]
[GameId "2141525848376410"]

{The 8. [Qa3] variation can lead to some unusual and fascinating positions. It often sees an early knight exchange on [d5], leading to a transformation of the structure. Here White has followed up with [c2]-[c4], meaning he's unlikely to castle queenside. Black could castle and try to stir up trouble with the ...[b5] break, but a direct assault on the kingside is somewhat stronger.} 14... Qg6 {[%csl Gg2] Eyeing a traditional weak spot in the white camp, [g2].} 15. O-O Nh4 $1 {[%csl Gg1][%cal Gg6g2] Already Black threatens mate.} 16. g3 Bh3 {[%csl Gg1][%cal Gh3f1,Gg6e4] White is clearly under very heavy pressure, with ...[Qe4] as well as ...[Bxf1] threatened. Fortunately for him, he is still afloat here, but only if he finds 17. [Qa4]+, as we'll see in 8. [Qa3] chapter.} *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "8 Qd1 Qg6 9.Nc3 d5 10.Nxd5 with 11.Ne3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "26"]
[GameId "2141525848396891"]

1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. Nxd4 {White's main move, setting up the Open Sicilian.} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Our key Löwenthal central strike, refusing to allow the knight to settle on [d4].} 5. Nb5 {You'll face this critical move, eyeing the potential check on [d6], in the majority of your Löwenthal games, but especially at club level and online, the alternatives are sometimes seen.} a6 $5 {[%csl Gb5] 'Yes, go on then, we don't fear your check!' says Black, boldly kicking the knight again. This brings about the Löwenthal variation, whereas 5...[d6] would be a Kalashnikov.} 6. Nd6+ {[%csl Re8] You'll likely face this critical check in at least 90% of your Löwenthal games, although it's actually not quite compulsory.} Bxd6 {Naturally the knight had to go.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gg8f6,Gf6d6]} (7... Qf6 {(And this is another key move for us a solid alternative is 7...Qe7, activating our own queen, forcing White into a big decision with his, and angling for active development and a certain lead in the activity stakes after)} 8. Qxf6 Nxf6 {.}) 8. Qd1 {The main line and most common continuation, retreating the queen all the way back to avoid her being attacked or obstructing White's development.} Qg6 {[%csl Ge4,Gg2][%cal Gg6e4] An important move, not only attacking the e-pawn, but pressuring [g2] to make it hard for White to develop the kingside.} 9. Nc3 {Natural development as White may also think he has taken control of [d5] for good...} d5 $5 {[%csl Gc2,Ge4,Gg2][%cal Gd5d4] ...only for Black to gambit so. This ambitious break 9...[Nge7] is the alternative is a key cornerstone of our repertoire and good practical choice. With [e4] under fire and 10...[d4] threatened, White pretty much must accept the pawn, but how?} (9... d5 {The good news is that} 10. exd5 $2 Nd4 {is already very awkward for White, and if} 11. Bd3 {(to defend [c2])} Qxg2 {, and 10.Qxd5 Be6 also gives Black easy development and good compensation.}) 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical way to capture, threatening a fork.} Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gc6d4] Regaining the pawn with check and now ...[Nd4] may be an important follow-up, countering the threat on [c7] with one on [c2].} 11. Ne3 {A rather defensive and slightly passive choice.} Nf6 {[%cal Ge8g8] As so often in the Löwenthal, Black enjoys easy development and is now ready to castle.} 12. Bd3 {[%csl Re4]} Qh4 $5 {[%csl Ge1] The most aggressive square for the queen, angling to start a kingside attack at some point.} 13. O-O O-O {[%cal Ge5e4,Gc6e5,Gf8d8] Sensibly housing the king ahead of attempting anything active. As we'll see further in the first part of the course, Black is now ready to go ...[e4], advancing with tempo while facilitating ...[Ne5], either before or after ...[Rd8] as our activity fully offsets White's possession of the bishop-pair.} *

