1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. Nxd4 {White's main move, setting up the Open Sicilian.} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Our key Löwenthal central strike, refusing to allow the knight to settle on [d4].} 5. Nb5 {You'll face this critical move, eyeing the potential check on [d6], in the majority of your Löwenthal games, but especially at club level and online, the alternatives are sometimes seen.} a6 $5 {[%csl Gb5] 'Yes, go on then, we don't fear your check!' says Black, boldly kicking the knight again. This brings about the Löwenthal variation, whereas 5...[d6] would be a Kalashnikov.} 6. Nd6+ {[%csl Re8] You'll likely face this critical check in at least 90% of your Löwenthal games, although it's actually not quite compulsory.} Bxd6 {Naturally the knight had to go.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gg8f6,Gf6d6]} (7... Qf6 {(And this is another key move for us a solid alternative is 7...Qe7, activating our own queen, forcing White into a big decision with his, and angling for active development and a certain lead in the activity stakes after)} 8. Qxf6 Nxf6 {.}) 8. Qd1 {The main line and most common continuation, retreating the queen all the way back to avoid her being attacked or obstructing White's development.} Qg6 {[%csl Ge4,Gg2][%cal Gg6e4] An important move, not only attacking the e-pawn, but pressuring [g2] to make it hard for White to develop the kingside.} 9. Nc3 {Natural development as White may also think he has taken control of [d5] for good...} d5 $5 {[%csl Gc2,Ge4,Gg2][%cal Gd5d4] ...only for Black to gambit so. This ambitious break 9...[Nge7] is the alternative is a key cornerstone of our repertoire and good practical choice. With [e4] under fire and 10...[d4] threatened, White pretty much must accept the pawn, but how?} (9... d5 {The good news is that} 10. exd5 $2 Nd4 {is already very awkward for White, and if} 11. Bd3 {(to defend [c2])} Qxg2 {, and 10.Qxd5 Be6 also gives Black easy development and good compensation.}) 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical way to capture, threatening a fork.} Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gc6d4] Regaining the pawn with check and now ...[Nd4] may be an important follow-up, countering the threat on [c7] with one on [c2].} 11. Be2 $5 {[%csl Rg2]} (11. Be2 {A tricky try, as well as a move which sets a small trap. Yes,} Qxg2 12. Bf3 {then 13. [Nc7]+ would not be good news for Black.}) 11... Nd4 $1 {[%csl Gc2,Gd5,Gg2] Now, though, both [c2] and [g2], as well as the white knight are under pressure.} 12. Nc7+ {[%csl Re8]} Ke7 {[%cal Gd4c2,Ge4g2] The right square for the king, as we're happy to gambit the rook on [a8] to get in either 13...[Nxc2]+ or 13...[Qxg2].} 13. Nxa8 $2 {Critical, but also too greedy.} Qxg2 {[%cal Gg2h1] The right pawn to take as Black already enjoys something of a dream early scenario.} 14. Rf1 Bf5 {[%cal Gd4c2]} (14... Bf5 {With} 15. Bd3 {running into} Nf3+ 16. Ke2 Bg4 {, White lacks a good way to cover [c2], as we'll explore in a little more depth in Theory One.}) *

