[PlyCount "34"]
[GameId "2141525848470621"]

1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. Nxd4 {White's main move, setting up the Open Sicilian.} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Our key Löwenthal central strike, refusing to allow the knight to settle on [d4].} 5. Nb5 {You'll face this critical move, eyeing the potential check on [d6], in the majority of your Löwenthal games, but especially at club level and online, the alternatives are sometimes seen.} a6 $5 {[%csl Gb5] 'Yes, go on then, we don't fear your check!' says Black, boldly kicking the knight again. This brings about the Löwenthal variation, whereas 5...[d6] would be a Kalashnikov.} 6. Nd6+ {[%csl Re8] You'll likely face this critical check in at least 90% of your Löwenthal games, although it's actually not quite compulsory.} Bxd6 {Naturally the knight had to go.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gg8f6,Gf6d6]} (7... Qf6 {(And this is another key move for us a solid alternative is 7...Qe7, activating our own queen, forcing White into a big decision with his, and angling for active development and a certain lead in the activity stakes after)} 8. Qxf6 Nxf6 {.}) 8. Qd1 {The main line and most common continuation, retreating the queen all the way back to avoid her being attacked or obstructing White's development.} Qg6 {[%csl Ge4,Gg2][%cal Gg6e4] An important move, not only attacking the e-pawn, but pressuring [g2] to make it hard for White to develop the kingside.} 9. Nc3 {Natural development as White may also think he has taken control of [d5] for good...} d5 $5 {[%csl Gc2,Ge4,Gg2][%cal Gd5d4] ...only for Black to gambit so. This ambitious break 9...[Nge7] is the alternative is a key cornerstone of our repertoire and good practical choice. With [e4] under fire and 10...[d4] threatened, White pretty much must accept the pawn, but how?} (9... d5 {The good news is that} 10. exd5 $2 Nd4 {is already very awkward for White, and if} 11. Bd3 {(to defend [c2])} Qxg2 {, and 10.Qxd5 Be6 also gives Black easy development and good compensation.}) 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical way to capture, threatening a fork.} Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gc6d4] Regaining the pawn with check and now ...[Nd4] may be an important follow-up, countering the threat on [c7] with one on [c2].} 11. Be3 {[%cal Rd5c7] White's main move, renewing his threat.} Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c2,Ge4d5] A key counter knight leap, striking straight back against [c2].} 12. Nc7+ {Clearly the critical choice, as well as very much the main line.} Ke7 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Gd4c2]} (12... Ke7 {The right square and now} 13. Bd3 $2 Qxg2 {would leave Black doing very well, so here White has three traditional main moves and also one modern try.}) 13. Qd3 {[%csl Re4] White hurries to get the queens off and so reduce the size of any black initiative.} Nxc2+ {[%csl Ge1] The pawn was en prise, so might as well go.} 14. Kd2 {[%csl Rc2,Re4]} Qxd3+ {A necessary exchange, but the Löwenthal player should rarely mind an early queen exchange if it brings with it easy development and good activity.} 15. Bxd3 Nxe3 $1 {[%cal Ga8b8]} ({Just like in the 13.Nxa8, the right capture to make, whereas after} 15... Nxa1 $4 16. Nxa8 {Black's knight is stuck while White's will make it out.}) 16. Nxa8 Nd5 {[%csl Gb6,Gc7] Keeping our knight safe while aiming to trap its counterpart in the corner.} 17. Rac1 Ngf6 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Gh8d8,Gd5b4] Black has a pawn and decent activity for the exchange, which adds up to sufficient compensation. While White can save his knight, his position is likely the harder to play with Black all set to activate via ...[Rd8] and ...[Nb4], as we'll see further in both chapter 1c and Smirnov-Oleksienko, Vasylyshyn Memorial, Lvov 2007.} *

