1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. Nxd4 {White's main move, setting up the Open Sicilian.} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Our key Löwenthal central strike, refusing to allow the knight to settle on [d4].} 5. Nb5 {You'll face this critical move, eyeing the potential check on [d6], in the majority of your Löwenthal games, but especially at club level and online, the alternatives are sometimes seen.} a6 $5 {[%csl Gb5] 'Yes, go on then, we don't fear your check!' says Black, boldly kicking the knight again. This brings about the Löwenthal variation, whereas 5...[d6] would be a Kalashnikov.} 6. Nd6+ {[%csl Re8] You'll likely face this critical check in at least 90% of your Löwenthal games, although it's actually not quite compulsory.} Bxd6 {Naturally the knight had to go.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gg8f6,Gf6d6]} (7... Qf6 {(And this is another key move for us a solid alternative is 7...Qe7, activating our own queen, forcing White into a big decision with his, and angling for active development and a certain lead in the activity stakes after)} 8. Qxf6 Nxf6 {.}) 8. Qd1 {The main line and most common continuation, retreating the queen all the way back to avoid her being attacked or obstructing White's development.} Qg6 {[%csl Ge4,Gg2][%cal Gg6e4] An important move, not only attacking the e-pawn, but pressuring [g2] to make it hard for White to develop the kingside.} 9. Nc3 {Natural development as White may also think he has taken control of [d5] for good...} d5 $5 {[%csl Gc2,Ge4,Gg2][%cal Gd5d4] ...only for Black to gambit so. This ambitious break 9...[Nge7] is the alternative is a key cornerstone of our repertoire and good practical choice. With [e4] under fire and 10...[d4] threatened, White pretty much must accept the pawn, but how?} (9... d5 {The good news is that} 10. exd5 $2 Nd4 {is already very awkward for White, and if} 11. Bd3 {(to defend [c2])} Qxg2 {, and 10.Qxd5 Be6 also gives Black easy development and good compensation.}) 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical way to capture, threatening a fork.} Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gc6d4] Regaining the pawn with check and now ...[Nd4] may be an important follow-up, countering the threat on [c7] with one on [c2].} 11. Be3 {[%cal Rd5c7] White's main move, renewing his threat.} Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c2,Ge4d5] A key counter knight leap, striking straight back against [c2].} 12. Nc7+ {Clearly the critical choice, as well as very much the main line.} Ke7 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Gd4c2]} (12... Ke7 {The right square and now} 13. Bd3 $2 Qxg2 {would leave Black doing very well, so here White has three traditional main moves and also one modern try.}) 13. Rc1 {[%csl Ra8,Rc2] The old main line, simply securing [c2].} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4d1,Ga8d8] With the rook hanging on [a8], Black must play actively and this move pretty much forces White into an early queen exchange after all.} 14. Qd3 {[%csl Re4]} Qxd3 {[%csl Gc7] Black is again happy enough with the early exchange, especially considering the potentially offside position of the white knight.} 15. Bxd3 Rd8 {[%cal Gg8f6,Ge7d6] (We're now ready to go 16...Nf6 then trap the knight with 17...Rd7 16...Kd6 17.c3 Nc6 18.Bb6 would save it, so White must respond with a degree of precision to stay afloat.)} 16. h3 {[%csl Rg4] White's main move, if not completely forced, as we'll see in our coverage in chapter 1D.} Bh5 $1 {[%csl Gd1,Ge2][%cal Gh5g6] Preserving the bishop while maintaining control of [d1] and [e2] for now, as well as giving Black the option of depriving White of the bishop-pair after an exchange with ...[Bg6].} 17. f4 $1 {[%csl Re5,Rh5][%cal Rg2g4,Rf4f5] A critical advance, challenging on the dark squares while threatening to trap our bishop.} Kd6 $5 {[%cal Gd6c7] And this is a fearless response, counterattacking against the offside knight.} 18. Nxa6 {White tries to sell the trapped knight as dearly as possible.} bxa6 19. g4 {[%csl Rh5]} Bg6 {Preserving the bishop for a move and thereby preventing the position from becoming too open to favour White's diagonal-moving pieces.} 20. f5 Ne7 {[%csl Gh3,Gh8][%cal Ge7f5,Gh7g6]} (20... Ne7 {A chaotic middlegame has been reached, one where Black should have sufficient counter-chances, at least in practice. We'll explore things in some detail in chapter 1D, but note for now that Black is ready to go 21...Nexf5 and will meet} 21. fxg6 {with} hxg6 {, thereby obtaining a dynamic and secure pawn mass while opening up the h-file down to [h3].}) *

