1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. Nxd4 {White's main move, setting up the Open Sicilian.} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Our key Löwenthal central strike, refusing to allow the knight to settle on [d4].} 5. Nb5 {You'll face this critical move, eyeing the potential check on [d6], in the majority of your Löwenthal games, but especially at club level and online, the alternatives are sometimes seen.} a6 $5 {[%csl Gb5] 'Yes, go on then, we don't fear your check!' says Black, boldly kicking the knight again. This brings about the Löwenthal variation, whereas 5...[d6] would be a Kalashnikov.} 6. Nd6+ {[%csl Re8] You'll likely face this critical check in at least 90% of your Löwenthal games, although it's actually not quite compulsory.} Bxd6 {Naturally the knight had to go.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gg8f6,Gf6d6]} (7... Qf6 {(And this is another key move for us a solid alternative is 7...Qe7, activating our own queen, forcing White into a big decision with his, and angling for active development and a certain lead in the activity stakes after)} 8. Qxf6 Nxf6 {.}) 8. Qd1 {The main line and most common continuation, retreating the queen all the way back to avoid her being attacked or obstructing White's development.} Qg6 {[%csl Ge4,Gg2][%cal Gg6e4] An important move, not only attacking the e-pawn, but pressuring [g2] to make it hard for White to develop the kingside.} 9. Nc3 {Natural development as White may also think he has taken control of [d5] for good...} d5 $5 {[%csl Gc2,Ge4,Gg2][%cal Gd5d4] ...only for Black to gambit so. This ambitious break 9...[Nge7] is the alternative is a key cornerstone of our repertoire and good practical choice. With [e4] under fire and 10...[d4] threatened, White pretty much must accept the pawn, but how?} (9... d5 {The good news is that} 10. exd5 $2 Nd4 {is already very awkward for White, and if} 11. Bd3 {(to defend [c2])} Qxg2 {, and 10.Qxd5 Be6 also gives Black easy development and good compensation.}) 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical way to capture, threatening a fork.} Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gc6d4] Regaining the pawn with check and now ...[Nd4] may be an important follow-up, countering the threat on [c7] with one on [c2].} 11. Be3 {[%cal Rd5c7] White's main move, renewing his threat.} Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c2,Ge4d5] A key counter knight leap, striking straight back against [c2].} 12. Nc7+ {Clearly the critical choice, as well as very much the main line.} Ke7 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Gd4c2]} (12... Ke7 {The right square and now} 13. Bd3 $2 Qxg2 {would leave Black doing very well, so here White has three traditional main moves and also one modern try.}) 13. Be2 $5 (13. Be2 {A tricky modern try, endorsed by Anish Giri. It's yet to really take off in practice, but a theoretical opponent might prepare it just before a game. Here we actually have a choice, with} Qxg2 14. Rf1 Qc6 {(counterattacking against [c2] in true Löwenthal fashion usually leading to a middlegame where White has decent play for a pawn.)}) 13... Nxc2+ $5 {[%csl Ge1] A hard move to assess, as well as our main recommendation. In practice the resulting positions are simply extremely unclear and fun to play, objectively better though White would be in an all-grandmaster clash.} 14. Kf1 {[%cal Re3c5] Threatening a pretty nasty check on [c5].} Nxe3+ {[%csl Gd1,Gf1] Not for the first time in this repertoire, the bishop simply has to go.} 15. fxe3 Bh3 $5 {[%csl Gf1,Gg2,Gh1][%cal Ge4g2] We can easily imagine this move both discombobulating and disorientating an opponent not fully au fait with the line, known to theory though this little tactic is.} 16. Nd5+ {[%csl Re7]} Kf8 {Clearly the safest square for the king here.} 17. Bf3 {[%csl Re4] White sensibly prevents the big threat.} Qc4+ {[%csl Gf1] Continuing to force the pace.} 18. Kg1 Rd8 $1 {[%csl Gg1][%cal Ge5e4,Gc4h4]} (18... Rd8 {Objectively speaking, White is a bit better here, but a quick glance at the board should reveal chaos... chaos in which it's easy for White to make a false step. Indeed,} 19. gxh3 $2 e4 {would now work out quite well for Black and even after 19.Rc1 Qh4 20.gxh3 e4 we have plenty of counterplay and activity. This frankly crazy variation will be considered in much more detail later on.}) *

