1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. Nxd4 {White's main move, setting up the Open Sicilian.} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Our key Löwenthal central strike, refusing to allow the knight to settle on [d4].} 5. Nb5 {You'll face this critical move, eyeing the potential check on [d6], in the majority of your Löwenthal games, but especially at club level and online, the alternatives are sometimes seen.} a6 $5 {[%csl Gb5] 'Yes, go on then, we don't fear your check!' says Black, boldly kicking the knight again. This brings about the Löwenthal variation, whereas 5...[d6] would be a Kalashnikov.} 6. Nd6+ {[%csl Re8] You'll likely face this critical check in at least 90% of your Löwenthal games, although it's actually not quite compulsory.} Bxd6 {Naturally the knight had to go.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gg8f6,Gf6d6]} (7... Qf6 {(And this is another key move for us a solid alternative is 7...Qe7, activating our own queen, forcing White into a big decision with his, and angling for active development and a certain lead in the activity stakes after)} 8. Qxf6 Nxf6 {.}) 8. Qc7 ({Along with} 8. Qd1 {, White's most ambitious approach, keeping the queen as active inside the black camp as possible.}) 8... Nge7 {[%csl Gc2,Gc7][%cal Gd7d5] While 8. [Qd1] is well met by 8...[Qg6] and 8. [Qxf6] [Nxf6] is pretty forced, this is in general how we want to continue kingside development, facilitating castling while supporting the ...[d5] break.} (8... Nge7 {Note too how} 9. f3 $2 d5 {would already be pretty good for Black, especially as} 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would trap the errant white queen. White should also be very careful about allowing 9.c4? Nd4 .}) 9. Nc3 Nb4 $1 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5] A key move, tickling the weakest spot in the white camp while supporting the liberating ...[d5] break.} 10. Bd3 d5 {[%cal Gd5d4,Gb4d3,Ge8g8,Gc8e6] There aren't that many lines of the Sicilian where Black can free his game with ...[d5] as early as move 10. We now have ideas of a timely ...[d4] or exchange on [d3], as well as of just continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} 11. a3 {[%csl Rb4]} Nxd3+ {Naturally the bishop must go.} 12. cxd3 O-O $5 {[%cal Gf6g6]} (12... O-O {Offering a pawn sacrifice, since both} 13. exd5 Qg6 {and 13.Nxd5 Nxd5 14.exd5 Qg6 would offer easy and fairly dangerous counterplay.}) 13. O-O Be6 $5 {[%cal Gd5d4,Ge7g6] A further pawn sacrifice. White can take on [b7], but then we'll advance with ...[d4] and use our rooks to trouble the queen. Note too how then after ...[Ng6] Black may be quick to whip up a sudden attack on the kingside, where White rather lacks defenders. This will all be covered at the start of Theory Two.} *

