1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. Nxd4 {White's main move, setting up the Open Sicilian.} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Our key Löwenthal central strike, refusing to allow the knight to settle on [d4].} 5. Nb5 {You'll face this critical move, eyeing the potential check on [d6], in the majority of your Löwenthal games, but especially at club level and online, the alternatives are sometimes seen.} a6 $5 {[%csl Gb5] 'Yes, go on then, we don't fear your check!' says Black, boldly kicking the knight again. This brings about the Löwenthal variation, whereas 5...[d6] would be a Kalashnikov.} 6. Nd6+ {[%csl Re8] You'll likely face this critical check in at least 90% of your Löwenthal games, although it's actually not quite compulsory.} Bxd6 {Naturally the knight had to go.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gg8f6,Gf6d6]} (7... Qf6 {(And this is another key move for us a solid alternative is 7...Qe7, activating our own queen, forcing White into a big decision with his, and angling for active development and a certain lead in the activity stakes after)} 8. Qxf6 Nxf6 {.}) 8. Qxf6 ({White's second most popular move, hoping for an edge with the bishop-pair. The resulting play won't be as lively as after} 8. Qd1 Qg6 {, but Black's set-up should be pretty easy to handle.}) 8... Nxf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gd7d5] Attacking [e4] while supporting a potential ...[d5] break.} 9. Nc3 Nb4 {[%csl Gc2,Gf2][%cal Gb4c2] Ideas with an early ...[d5] don't fully equalise here, so instead we play as in the 8. [Qc7] lines by attacking the weakest spot in White's camp, [c2].} (9... Nb4 {White has three ways to defend the pawn, but} 10. Kd1 Ng4 {merely sees Black switching the focus of the attack and supplies a decent game, as we'll see at the start of Theory Three.}) 10. Bd3 {The most natural way of defending against the threat, if also a move which means White has to be happy to return the bishop-pair.} b5 $5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gd7d5] A radical advance and not Black's most common choice, but just a good move from what we can see. Black prepares to whisk the light-squared bishop to a fine role on [b7], from where it will help to force through ...[d5].} 11. Bg5 Bb7 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gb4d3]} (11... Bb7 {Now we're all set to break in the centre and while} 12. O-O-O {is possible, if White then meets} Nxd3+ {with} 13. Rxd3 {we will be able to steal a centre pawn through} Nxe4 {.}) 12. Bxf6 Nxd3+ $1 {A handy intermezzo, forcing White to recapture with the pawn, not a subsequent rook.} 13. cxd3 gxf6 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gd7d5,Ge8e7,Gb5b4] This dynamic position will be explored further in chapter 3c. The king should be safe enough on [e7] and Black's central control offsets the doubled pawns, with a temporary pawn sacrifice in ...[d5] now one possibility and, of course, ...[b4] then ...[d5] is another.} *

