1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. Nxd4 {White's main move, setting up the Open Sicilian.} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Our key Löwenthal central strike, refusing to allow the knight to settle on [d4].} 5. Nb5 {You'll face this critical move, eyeing the potential check on [d6], in the majority of your Löwenthal games, but especially at club level and online, the alternatives are sometimes seen.} a6 $5 {[%csl Gb5] 'Yes, go on then, we don't fear your check!' says Black, boldly kicking the knight again. This brings about the Löwenthal variation, whereas 5...[d6] would be a Kalashnikov.} 6. Nd6+ {[%csl Re8] You'll likely face this critical check in at least 90% of your Löwenthal games, although it's actually not quite compulsory.} Bxd6 {Naturally the knight had to go.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gg8f6,Gf6d6]} (7... Qf6 {(And this is another key move for us a solid alternative is 7...Qe7, activating our own queen, forcing White into a big decision with his, and angling for active development and a certain lead in the activity stakes after)} 8. Qxf6 Nxf6 {.}) 8. Qc5 {A rare and not especially good square for the queen.} d6 {[%cal Gd6c5,Gf6g6] Taking the chance to develop with tempo and now with 9...[Qg6] we may play for an early initiative.} 9. Qe3 Qg6 {[%csl Gg2] Tying White down to the defence of [g2].} 10. Nc3 Nge7 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gf7f5] We're already pretty actively placed, being ready to either leap forwards with ... [Nd4] or break with ...[f5], as we'll see further at the start of Theory Four.} *

