1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. Nxd4 {White's main move, setting up the Open Sicilian.} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Our key Löwenthal central strike, refusing to allow the knight to settle on [d4].} 5. Nb5 {You'll face this critical move, eyeing the potential check on [d6], in the majority of your Löwenthal games, but especially at club level and online, the alternatives are sometimes seen.} a6 $5 {[%csl Gb5] 'Yes, go on then, we don't fear your check!' says Black, boldly kicking the knight again. This brings about the Löwenthal variation, whereas 5...[d6] would be a Kalashnikov.} 6. Nd6+ {[%csl Re8] You'll likely face this critical check in at least 90% of your Löwenthal games, although it's actually not quite compulsory.} Bxd6 {Naturally the knight had to go.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gg8f6,Gf6d6]} (7... Qf6 {(And this is another key move for us a solid alternative is 7...Qe7, activating our own queen, forcing White into a big decision with his, and angling for active development and a certain lead in the activity stakes after)} 8. Qxf6 Nxf6 {.}) 8. Qd3 {This keeps [e4] covered, but the queen may be a little vulnerable here, not only to ...[Nb4], but after ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gb7b5]} (8... Nge7 {A much better approach than 8...Qg6 here. Black gets ready to break with ...d5, although in the event of} 9. c4 {we'll change tack and make a different strong gambit in the shape of} b5 $1 {.}) 9. Nc3 d5 $1 {[%cal Gc6b4]} (9... d5 {Another dangerous pawn sacrifice, looking to seize the initiative and go after c2 in the event of} 10. exd5 Nb4 {.}) 10. Nxd5 {[%csl Rf6]} Nxd5 (10... Nxd5 {The knight should go and now} 11. exd5 $2 Nd4 $1 {is already pretty awkward for White, and if} 12. Qd1 Qg6 {.}) 11. Qxd5 Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Ga8d8,Gf6g6,Gc6b4]} (11... Be6 {Black's lead in development supplies full compensation for the pawn. The a8-rook will irritate the white queen on the d-file or with} 12. Qc5 Rc8 {, a timely ...[Qg6] will pressure [e4] and [g2] once again, and ...[Nb4] may lead to the defence being overloaded on [c2]. In short, White must be pretty accurate here to maintain the balance, as chapter 4b will reveal.}) *

