1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. Nxd4 {White's main move, setting up the Open Sicilian.} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Our key Löwenthal central strike, refusing to allow the knight to settle on [d4].} 5. Nb5 {You'll face this critical move, eyeing the potential check on [d6], in the majority of your Löwenthal games, but especially at club level and online, the alternatives are sometimes seen.} a6 $5 {[%csl Gb5] 'Yes, go on then, we don't fear your check!' says Black, boldly kicking the knight again. This brings about the Löwenthal variation, whereas 5...[d6] would be a Kalashnikov.} 6. Nd6+ {[%csl Re8] You'll likely face this critical check in at least 90% of your Löwenthal games, although it's actually not quite compulsory.} Bxd6 {Naturally the knight had to go.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gg8f6,Gf6d6]} (7... Qf6 {(And this is another key move for us a solid alternative is 7...Qe7, activating our own queen, forcing White into a big decision with his, and angling for active development and a certain lead in the activity stakes after)} 8. Qxf6 Nxf6 {.}) 8. Qd2 {Perhaps a slightly strange-looking retreat, if also a positionally well justified choice: White wants to meet any ...[Qg6] with a quick [Qg5].} Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d6,Gc8e6]} (8... Nge7 {Sensible development. We may now castle or first go ...d6 and ...Be6, while} 9. Qg5 $6 d5 $1 {would seize the initiative.}) 9. Nc3 O-O {[%cal Gc6d4,Gb7b5,Gc6b4,Gd7d5]} (9... O-O {Making the king safe before looking to react to however White now sets up. Indeed, we'll cover a fair few moves here in chapter 4c, including} 10. Qg5 d5 $1 {again and 10.Bd3 Nb4 . Against other moves, Black may look to go ...[Nd4] and/or expand with ...[b5], with 10.b3!? b5 11.Bb2 Bb7 one fairly important line, looking to gambit the d-pawn for easy piece play.}) 10. Bc4 {Clamping down on [d5].} b5 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gb5b4,Gc8b7] Hassling the bishop, while giving Black ideas of not just ...[Bb7], but a timely ...[b4].} 11. Bb3 Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7] Continuing to hunt down the bishop, while getting ready to go ...[Bb7] then ...[b4]. Black enjoys decent counterplay here, with even the white kingside potentially vulnerable note the lack of defenders over there, as we'll see further in chapter 4c.} *

