1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. Nxd4 {White's main move, setting up the Open Sicilian.} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Our key Löwenthal central strike, refusing to allow the knight to settle on [d4].} 5. Nb5 {You'll face this critical move, eyeing the potential check on [d6], in the majority of your Löwenthal games, but especially at club level and online, the alternatives are sometimes seen.} a6 $5 {[%csl Gb5] 'Yes, go on then, we don't fear your check!' says Black, boldly kicking the knight again. This brings about the Löwenthal variation, whereas 5...[d6] would be a Kalashnikov.} 6. Nd6+ {[%csl Re8] You'll likely face this critical check in at least 90% of your Löwenthal games, although it's actually not quite compulsory.} Bxd6 {Naturally the knight had to go.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gg8f6,Gf6d6]} (7... Qf6 {(And this is another key move for us a solid alternative is 7...Qe7, activating our own queen, forcing White into a big decision with his, and angling for active development and a certain lead in the activity stakes after)} 8. Qxf6 Nxf6 {.}) 8. Qa3 $5 {Quite an aggressive choice, as White plays to control the d-file and would now like to go [Nc3] and [Be3] followed by [O-O-O] and [Bc5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5] Again, the right way to develop as we get ready to hit back with ...[d5], if allowed.} 9. Nc3 Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5]} (9... Rb8 {A key move, unpinning the a-pawn and so preparing to question the white queen's location with a quick ...b5. White can now change the structure, but Black's position remains relatively easy to handle after} 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. exd5 Ne7 {.}) 10. Be3 b5 {[%cal Gb5b4]} (10... b5 {With a certain threat and} 11. Ne2 d5 {would now get in the key pawn break after all.}) 11. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6]} Nxd5 {Once again, the knight must go.} 12. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} b4 $5 {[%cal Gc6e7,Gc6d4] Tickling the white queen. If she now moves to [b3] or [d3], Black will drop back with 13...[Ne7] then look to go ...[d6] and ...[O-O].} 13. Qa4 Nd4 $1 {[%csl Gc2,Gd5][%cal Gc8b7,Ge8g8] A change of approach with the white queen now slightly sidelined. Both [c2] and [d5] may become weak, and Black will finish development quickly with ...[Bb7] and ...[O-O], as we'll cover in chapter 4d.} *

