1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. Nxd4 {White's main move, setting up the Open Sicilian.} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Our key Löwenthal central strike, refusing to allow the knight to settle on [d4].} 5. Nb5 {You'll face this critical move, eyeing the potential check on [d6], in the majority of your Löwenthal games, but especially at club level and online, the alternatives are sometimes seen.} a6 $5 {[%csl Gb5] 'Yes, go on then, we don't fear your check!' says Black, boldly kicking the knight again. This brings about the Löwenthal variation, whereas 5...[d6] would be a Kalashnikov.} 6. N5a3 $6 {A strange location for the knight, even if White may plan to quickly regroup via [c4].} Nf6 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d5] Pressuring [e4] while supporting a key pawn break in ...[d5]. Black already enjoys a pretty comfortable game.} 7. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4] Continuing to compete hard for control of [d5] while renewing the threat to [e4].} 8. Bg5 {A fighting attempt to cut across Black's plans, but actually we can still break here.} d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd8d5,Gd5d4]} (8... d5 {Refusing to back down while fighting hard in return for the initiative and now} 9. exd5 Qxd5 {would unpin while leaving the white queenside under ongoing pressure.}) 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 {[%cal Gd5d4] The right way to recapture, activating the queen.} 10. exd5 Ne7 {[%csl Gb4,Gd5][%cal Ge5e4] White has won a pawn, but remains under pressure on the queenside. Indeed, Black is all set to go ...[e4] as well as pressure the pawn on [d5], and enjoys excellent compensation, as we'll see in chapter 5a.} *

