1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. Nxd4 {White's main move, setting up the Open Sicilian.} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Our key Löwenthal central strike, refusing to allow the knight to settle on [d4].} 5. Nb5 {You'll face this critical move, eyeing the potential check on [d6], in the majority of your Löwenthal games, but especially at club level and online, the alternatives are sometimes seen.} a6 $5 {[%csl Gb5] 'Yes, go on then, we don't fear your check!' says Black, boldly kicking the knight again. This brings about the Löwenthal variation, whereas 5...[d6] would be a Kalashnikov.} 6. N5c3 {A preferable retreat, if also far from a move to fear.} Bc5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gd8f6,Gd7d6] A fine diagonal for the bishop. Note too Black's early lead in development and if White now did something very slow, we might even be able to eye [f2] with 7...[Qf6], although most likely the plan is to develop the other bishop after ...[d6].} 7. Bc4 d6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gg8e7,Ge8g8] Facilitating ...[Be6] at some stage to challenge the bishop on [c4], while now we're all set to develop the kingside with ...[Nge7] and ...[O-O].} 8. O-O Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc5d4,Gh7h6] Black enjoys a comfortable game here, with ...[O-O] imminent, after which we may disrupt White's coordination a little with a timely ...[Bd4].} (8... Nge7 {We'll see that device and a model win by Black in the illustrative game Szikszai-Codirlasu, Eforie Nord 1998, while in chapter 5b we'll appreciate too that} 9. Bg5 h6 {quickly deals with the attempt to pin.}) *

