1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. Nxd4 {White's main move, setting up the Open Sicilian.} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Our key Löwenthal central strike, refusing to allow the knight to settle on [d4].} 5. Ne2 {The knight heads for [g3] or maybe [c3], but now we can develop the dark-squared bishop to a fine diagonal.} Bc5 {[%csl Gc5,Gf2][%cal Gd8b6]} (5... Bc5 {Already White must take care of f2 and} 6. Nbc3 $6 Qb6 {would be a little embarrassing for him.}) 6. Ng3 d6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gh7h5]} (6... d6 {Switching to sensible development, as we prepare ...Be6, although if White now does something slow, then it may be possible to fight for the initiative with} 7. Z0 h5 $5 {, and if} 8. Nxh5 Qh4 {.}) 7. Nc3 Be6 {[%csl Gf1][%cal Gg8e7,Gg8f6,Gd8h4] Ruling out [Bc4] from White ahead of developing the kingside. There are ideas of ...[Qh4], although we'd more prefer to go 8...[Nge7] or even ...[Nf6].} 8. Nd5 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6g4,Gd8f6,Gd8a5]} (8... Nf6 {Threatening 9...Ng4 and} 9. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {would be very nice for Black, while 9.Bg5 Qa5! is an important mechanism to unpin, as we'll see at the start of Theory Six.}) *

