1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. Nxd4 {White's main move, setting up the Open Sicilian.} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Our key Löwenthal central strike, refusing to allow the knight to settle on [d4].} 5. Nf5 (5. Nf5 {The most aggressive looking of the alternatives to 5.Nb5, if one which allows Black to go} d5 {or first support that break while looking for a dynamic game.}) 5... Nf6 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d5] Pressuring [e4] and only now wanting to hit back in the centre with 6...[d5].} 6. Nc3 d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5][%cal Gd5d4] Ever a key pawn break in the Sicilian and our early central pressure pretty much compels White into exchanges.} 7. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} Bxf5 {Not a bad way to develop the bishop.} 8. dxc6 bxc6 $5 {[%cal Ga8d8]} (8... bxc6 {Holding back on the potential queen exchange as} 9. Qxd8+ $6 Rxd8 {can only help Black due to our pressure against [c2].}) 9. Qf3 {[%csl Rc6,Rf5]} Qd7 {[%cal Ge5e4,Gf5c2,Gf8b4] Keeping everything covered. As we'll see further in chapter 6b, White can try to gambit [c2] here, but in any case Black is fine, with counterplay imminent and not just against that pawn, but through ...[Bb4] or even ...[e4].} *

