1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. Nxd4 {White's main move, setting up the Open Sicilian.} e5 {[%csl Gd4] Our key Löwenthal central strike, refusing to allow the knight to settle on [d4].} 5. Nf3 {A rather unpretentious, if not terrible retreat.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] Attacking [e4] once again, a pawn which White should defend.} 6. Bc4 $6 Nxe4 $1 (6... Nxe4 {Taking up the challenge and now even} 7. Qd5 $1 Qa5+ $1 {is very comfortable for Black, if also somewhat better for White than pursuing an aggressive looking path.}) 7. Bxf7+ $6 {[%csl Re8]} Kxf7 8. Qd5+ Ke8 {The king skips back and is actually quite safe here.} 9. Qxe4 d5 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ge5e4] Black already enjoys an excellent game thanks to the strong centre. We also have the bishop-pair and may be able to retain the initiative too after a quick ...[e4].} *

