1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. c3 $5 {[%cal Rc3d4]} ({As we'll see in Theory Seven there aren't many alternatives to} 4. Nxd4 {, bar really this, offering a transposition into the Morra Gambit d4 cxd4 c3 .}) 4... dxc3 {Correctly taking up the challenge.} 5. Nxc3 d6 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Ga7a6,Gg8f6] Freeing the light-squared bishop for action, although we should be careful not to rush to develop that piece, preferring first to make two useful moves in 6...[a6] and 7...[Nf6].} 6. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Re4e5]} a6 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gg8f6,Ge7e6]} ({It's very, very useful to take control of b5 so. This way we avoid being hit by} 6... Nf6 $2 7. e5 $1 {, and if} Nxe5 $2 8. Nxe5 dxe5 $2 9. Bxf7+ $1 {or 7...dxe5 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5! , while also sidestepping 6...Bg4? 7.Bxf7+! .}) (6... a6 {Only now do we want to go 7...Nf6 then ideally 8...Bg4, although in the event of} 7. e5 $5 {we'll change tack with} e6 $1 {to quickly shut down all White's fun.}) 7. O-O Nf6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gc8g4]} (7... Nf6 {Now everything is set for ...Bg4, such as with} 8. b4 Bg4 {, and 8.e5?! can be neutralised in fairly straightforward fashion with 8...dxe5 9.Qxd8+ Nxd8 .}) 8. Qe2 $6 {White's traditional choice and very standard Morra policy, if also one we should be pretty happy to see.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Ge2,Gf3,Gg4] A fairly awkward pin for White to deal with and now as well as continuing development with ...[e6], Black may be able to exploit the active bishop deployment with ...[Ne5].} 9. Rd1 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Re4e5] Lining up e4-e5 and hoping to win in style with 9...[Ne5]?? 10. [Nxe5].} e6 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Ge5][%cal Gf8e7,Gd8b8,Gd8c7,Gd8a5,Gg4f3] Prudently shutting down the gaze of the bishop on [c4] to give Black back control of [e5]. We're now set to continue development with ...[Be7], don't mind parting with the bishop-pair on [f3] and the queen can skip away from any potential problems by heading to [b8], [c7] or [a5].} 10. Bf4 $2 {Obvious, yet flawed.} Nh5 $1 {[%cal Gh5f4,Gc6e5] Allowing the bishop no respite as ideas involving ...[Ne5] quickly become rather unpleasant for White.} 11. Be3 Ne5 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gg4f3,Gd8h4]} (11... Ne5 {White is already in some trouble, with Black even ready to go} 12. Z0 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Qh4 $1 {, as we'll see further in chapter 7b.}) *

