1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5] The Open Sicilian.} cxd4 {A pretty essential exchange, as well as key component of the Löwenthal move order.} 4. c3 $5 {[%cal Rc3d4]} ({As we'll see in Theory Seven there aren't many alternatives to} 4. Nxd4 {, bar really this, offering a transposition into the Morra Gambit d4 cxd4 c3 .}) 4... dxc3 {Correctly taking up the challenge.} 5. Nxc3 d6 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Ga7a6,Gg8f6] Freeing the light-squared bishop for action, although we should be careful not to rush to develop that piece, preferring first to make two useful moves in 6...[a6] and 7...[Nf6].} 6. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Re4e5]} a6 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gg8f6,Ge7e6]} ({It's very, very useful to take control of b5 so. This way we avoid being hit by} 6... Nf6 $2 7. e5 $1 {, and if} Nxe5 $2 8. Nxe5 dxe5 $2 9. Bxf7+ $1 {or 7...dxe5 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5! , while also sidestepping 6...Bg4? 7.Bxf7+! .}) (6... a6 {Only now do we want to go 7...Nf6 then ideally 8...Bg4, although in the event of} 7. e5 $5 {we'll change tack with} e6 $1 {to quickly shut down all White's fun.}) 7. O-O Nf6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gc8g4]} (7... Nf6 {Now everything is set for ...Bg4, such as with} 8. b4 Bg4 {, and 8.e5?! can be neutralised in fairly straightforward fashion with 8...dxe5 9.Qxd8+ Nxd8 .}) 8. Bf4 Bg4 {[%csl Gd1,Gf3,Gg4][%cal Ge7e6]} (8... Bg4 {Again, we pin while provoking} 9. Qb3 {when} e6 {is an obvious and good response, and if} 10. Qxb7 $2 Na5 {.}) 9. h3 {[%csl Rg4]} Bxf3 10. Qxf3 e6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Our solid and standard approach, getting ready to go ...[Be7] then castle.} 11. Rfd1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Re4e5]} Qb8 $1 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] (Stepping off the d-file in thematic fashion. Once again, Black is very comfortable and will continue with 12...Be7 unless White permits 12.Qg3 Nh5? ) then 13...[O-O], even if that entails returning the extra pawn on [d6] to fully unravel, as we'll see further in chapter 7d.} *

