1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. Nc3 $5 {We'll examine this tricky move order last, in Theory Eight. White holds back on [d2]-[d4] and so aims to move order us away from the Löwenthal.} a6 $5 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Ge7e5,Gg8f6,Gd7d5,Ge7e6] A small surprise in return; ...[a6] is very rarely a bad move in the Sicilian, taking control of [b5] and enabling ...[b5] at some stage. Here we're also getting ready for 4.d4 when we want to hit back in Löwenthalesque style after all. (If instead White develops more slowly, we may continue with 4...Nf6 or 4.Bc4?! b5 ) followed by ...[d5] and/or ...[e6].} 4. g3 {Arguably the trickiest of White's alternatives to an Open Sicilian after all, as he prepares to fianchetto while keeping open the option of [d2]-[d4].} d6 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc8g4] A modest looking move, but a decent one as we fight for control of [d4] with a quick ...[Bg4].} (4... d6 {Now} 5. d4 Bg4 {would immediately pressure the d-pawn and} 6. d5 Nd4 {should be fine for Black.}) 5. Bg2 Bg4 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gg7g6] Pinning. It's worth giving up the bishop-pair to control [d4], a square we'll have even more control over once ...[g6] and ...[Bg7] has turned the dormant bishop on [f8] into a pretty powerful prelate.} 6. h3 {[%csl Rg4]} Bxf3 7. Bxf3 g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge7e6,Gg8e7,Ge8g8] The aforementioned fianchetto. With ...[Bg7], then ...[e6], ...[Nge7] and ...[O-O] on the way, Black should enjoy a comfortable form of set-up, one often seen too against the Closed Sicilian. We'll explore a little deeper in chapter 8b.} *

