1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Defence - an excellent, fighting response to 1. [e4] at all levels.} 2. Nf3 {In this course, we'll be focussing on how to react when White heads into main line Open Sicilian waters with this then 3. [d4].} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] By no means forced, of course, but sensible development and a key component of the Löwenthal variation, the line of the Open Sicilian with which we hope to confuse White. Already, Black is ready for a dark-square approach in the centre, aiming to control the [d4]- and [e5]-squares.} 3. Nc3 $5 {We'll examine this tricky move order last, in Theory Eight. White holds back on [d2]-[d4] and so aims to move order us away from the Löwenthal.} a6 $5 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Ge7e5,Gg8f6,Gd7d5,Ge7e6] A small surprise in return; ...[a6] is very rarely a bad move in the Sicilian, taking control of [b5] and enabling ...[b5] at some stage. Here we're also getting ready for 4.d4 when we want to hit back in Löwenthalesque style after all. (If instead White develops more slowly, we may continue with 4...Nf6 or 4.Bc4?! b5 ) followed by ...[d5] and/or ...[e6].} 4. d4 cxd4 {Naturally we exchange.} 5. Nxd4 e5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gf8c5] Löwenthal-like play, as well as possibly a surprise for White. The text is a little risky, but in practice has caused the majority of white players to respond relatively meekly.} (5... e5 {Note how both} 6. Nde2 {and 6.Nf3 can be well met by 6...Bc5 , bringing the bishop to an excellent post, while after 6.Nb3 Nf6 Black will bring the dark-squared bishop instead to [b4] or [e7]. There's also 6.Nxc6 when 6...dxc6 is a perhaps unexpected recapture, but after 7.Qxd8+ Kxd8 Black's control of [d5] offsets the inability to castle, as we'll also see in more detail in chapter 8c.}) 6. Nf5 {[%csl Rd6] Homing in on the weakened [d6]-square must be critical.} d6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gc8e6] Prudently avoiding a certain check, while getting ready to either go 7...Bxf5 8.exf5 Nge7 or 7...Be6 . The former approach is positionally a little risky, so is only really recommended if White does something slow here, which 7.Bc4 would not be and then 7...Be6 is very sensible, immediately and thematically challenging for control of the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} 7. Ne3 {Avoiding the potential exchange while clamping down on [d5] has been White's most common choice.} Nf6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gf8e7,Gg7g6,Gf8g7] The pressure against [e4] deters 8... [Ncd5] and now we're all set to go 8...[Be6] followed by ...[Be7] or even ...[g6] and ...[Bg7].} 8. Ned5 $5 {[%cal Rc1e3,Re3b6] White hints at a quick [Be3]-[b6], a dangerous policy.} Be7 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8] Preparing to quickly remove the king from being forked from [c7].} 9. Be3 O-O 10. Bb6 Qd7 {[%cal Gf6d5,Ge7d8]} (10... Qd7 {A slightly ungainly choice of square, but White's play has been pretty one-dimensional thus far. He likely can claim a small edge here, as we'll see in chapter 8c, but Black has avoided any early danger and is all set to untangle with} 11. Z0 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Bd8 $1 {followed by ...[Ne7].}) *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
