1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 $5 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to. Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Löwenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 $1 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. f3 {This doesn't help White's development, but also can hardly, of course, be a terrible move.} Nge7 {Calmly does it. Black prepares to castle while adding support to the ...[d5] and ...[f5] pawn breaks.} ({Note that here} 9... d5 $6 {isn't really an option:} 10. Qxd5 Be6 11. Qd2 $1 Rd8 {might offer decent activity for the pawn if White didn't have} 12. Qg5 {, forcing the queens off with a clear plus.}) 10. Be3 $6 d5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gd5d4] A strong temporary pawn sacrifice as Black wastes no time in putting the lead in development to good use.} 11. exd5 Nb4 {[%csl Gc2,Gg2][%cal Gb4c2,Gb4d5]} 12. Na3 {How else to defend [c2] with the light-squared bishop rather tied to the defence of [g2]?} Nbxd5 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gh8f8,Gf8d8,Gc8f5,Ga8c8,Gd5e3] The simplest and likely best recapture, as well as one which, of course, comes with tempo. Black is now ready to go ...[O-O] and ...[Rd8], as well as ...[Bf5] and ...[Rac8].} 13. Bc5 Qc6 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ge8e7,Gc6c5] (Continuing to hound the bishop and retain the initiative. It can exchange itself off on e7 then 14.Bxe7 Kxe7!? followed by ...[Rd8] is very much an option, but even then, White will be worse, with a hole on [e3] and the knight on [a3] slightly misplaced.)} *

