[GameId "2141525850055802"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to. Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Löwenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 $1 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. f3 {This doesn't help White's development, but also can hardly, of course, be a terrible move.} Nge7 {Calmly does it. Black prepares to castle while adding support to the ...[d5] and ...[f5] pawn breaks.} ({Note that here} 9... d5 $6 {isn't really an option:} 10. Qxd5 Be6 11. Qd2 $1 Rd8 {might offer decent activity for the pawn if White didn't have} 12. Qg5 {, forcing the queens off with a clear plus.}) 10. Nc3 O-O {[%cal Gd7d5,Gf7f5] (Calmly housing the king ahead of breaking with ...f5 or even ...d5 you may also wish to explore 10...Nd4!? followed by ...[d5] or 11.Be3 Qb6 , which quickly becomes rather sharp.)} 11. Be3 d5 $1 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gd5d4]} (11... d5 {A thematic and fairly strong pawn sacrifice, threatening ...d4 while intending to go after c2 if} 12. exd5 $6 Nb4 {.}) 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Rd8 $1 {[%cal Gd8d5,Gc8e6]} (13... Rd8 {The most accurate way to develop with gain of tempo, preventing the queen from tucking back in via d2 and now} 14. Qc4 Be6 15. Qe2 f5 $1 {most certainly left Black with the initiative in Bogdanovic-Minic, Bled 1963.}) 14. Qc5 Be6 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Ga8c8] Black enjoys full compensation for the pawn, with ...[Rac8] on the way and White some way from finding a safe spot for his king.} (14... Be6 {For example,} 15. c3 Rac8 {With the rather large threat of ...[Nd4].} 16. Qb6 Rd7 {Calmly defending [b7] while Black may well grab on [a2] should the white rook leave [a1].} 17. g4 {This was Desbiens-Nafii, Sainte-Foy-Tarentaise 2018, where Black might have asked the question on the kingside:} h5 $5 {((This aims to induce a further weakening in the shape of 18.h3 before going 18...Qf6. ) . )} 18. g5 Rcd8 {Black is now ready to seize the initiative with ...[f5] and may also cause trouble for the white queen with ... [Rd6]!?. The engines assess at their beloved '0.00', but White's position would surely be the harder to handle in practice.}) (14... Be6 15. Rd1 $5 Nd4 $5 {((Consistently going after c2 and a somewhat more pointed policy than the 15...Rxd1+ 16.Kxd1 Bxa2?! 17.b3 of Stepanov-Golubka, Tula 2010.))} 16. Bxd4 exd4 {Renewing the threat of ...[Rac8] at the cost of a second pawn.} 17. Rxd4 Rxd4 $1 18. Qxd4 Qg5 {A key follow-up to the exchange of rooks on [d4]. Black facilitates ...[Rd8] while keeping the queen in touch with [g2].} 19. Qd2 Qf6 {Black appears to have enough play for the two pawns, leading in development and even with ideas of ...[Bxa2], as well as the threats of ...[Qxb2] and ...[Rd8].}) *

