1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to. Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Löwenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 $1 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. f3 {This doesn't help White's development, but also can hardly, of course, be a terrible move.} Nge7 {Calmly does it. Black prepares to castle while adding support to the ...[d5] and ...[f5] pawn breaks.} ({Note that here} 9... d5 $6 {isn't really an option:} 10. Qxd5 Be6 11. Qd2 $1 Rd8 {might offer decent activity for the pawn if White didn't have} 12. Qg5 {, forcing the queens off with a clear plus.}) 10. c4 O-O {Housing the king and just compare the difference in development between the two sides! Black is ready to break with ...[f5] or even ...[Bf5], with an active, decent game.} 11. Be3 f5 $1 {[%cal Gf5e4]} (11... f5 {Threatening to take on e4 while hoping to induce} 12. exf5 $2 Nxf5 {when Black's initiative would become very serious indeed.}) 12. Nc3 fxe4 13. fxe4 b5 $5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gc6d4] The most ambitious choice, looking to enjoy a monstrous initiative after ...[Bb7] then ...[Nd4].} ({With White unable to castle kingside though, it should be said that the simple} 13... d6 {followed by ...[Be6] is also quite pleasant for Black.}) 14. cxb5 $2 axb5 {[%csl Ge4,Gg2][%cal Gb5b4] Threatening ...[b4] and if White now takes on [b5], he'll lose a pretty important pawn on [e4] or [g2] in return.} 15. Bxb5 Qxg2 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gg2h1,Gg2b2] This position was reached in Moreno Alberti-Ramos Guaz, Malpica 2011, where Black must have been fairly happy, attacking the rook on [h1] as well as the pawn on [b2]. With his king a concern, White surely must be clearly worse even if he now saves [b2].} 16. Qb3+ Kh8 {[%cal Gg2h1]} 17. O-O-O Nd4 $1 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Gd4b3] Ripping open further lines by pretty much forcing a destabilising exchange on [d4]. Black's active queen and somewhat safer king should add up to a clear advantage.} *

