1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to. Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Löwenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 $1 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Qxd5 {This is rather risky, since Black will now gain plenty of tempi against the queen.} Be6 {[%cal Ge6d5]} ({Probably best or at least the engines may have a point that after} 10... Nf6 11. Qd3 Be6 12. f3 $1 {Black, slightly surprisingly, doesn't have anything especially promising.}) 11. Qc5 $2 (11. Qc5 {This went unpunished after} Rd8 $2 {in Mohammad Fahad-Orantes Taboada, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2021, but here Black should very much be thinking about the potential weakness of [c2].}) 11... Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4c2]} (11... Nd4 {Threatening a sizeable fork and one which} 12. Nd5 $2 {wouldn't counter since after} Bxd5 13. exd5 {the black queen now supports} Nxc2+ {. As such, the engines indicate that White has nothing better than to miserably allow 12.Rb1 Nxc2+ .}) 12. Kd1 $2 Qg4+ $1 {[%csl Gd1,Gg2][%cal Ga8d8,Gg8f6]} (12... Qg4+ {A tricky check, continuing to angle to be able to go} 13. Be2 Qxg2 {. With ...[Rd8] and ...[Nf6] high on the agenda, Black is already doing pretty well.}) 13. f3 Nxf3 $1 {[%csl Gd1,Gh1][%cal Gf3d4] Simply threatening to return to [d4] and, of course, the knight is taboo due to the potential fork of the white king and rook.} 14. Be2 $2 Qxg2 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Ga8d8,Gg2h1] Attacking the rook and also threatening ...[Rd8]+. White is already pretty much lost.} *

