1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to. Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Löwenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 $1 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Qxd5 {This is rather risky, since Black will now gain plenty of tempi against the queen.} Be6 {[%cal Ge6d5]} ({Probably best or at least the engines may have a point that after} 10... Nf6 11. Qd3 Be6 12. f3 $1 {Black, slightly surprisingly, doesn't have anything especially promising.}) 11. Qd3 Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d3]} (11... Rd8 {Another key point behind preferring 10...Be6 to 10...Nf6 is revealed and now Black would regain the pawn with a comfortable position after} 12. Nd5 Bxd5 13. exd5 Nb4 $1 {.}) 12. Qg3 Nb4 $1 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gb4c2] Homing in on the weakest spot in White's camp, [c2].} 13. Bd3 Qxg3 {Slightly weakening White's structure ahead of regaining the pawn on [d3].} 14. hxg3 (14. hxg3 {Black now went in for} Rxd3 $5 15. cxd3 Nc2+ 16. Ke2 Nxa1 17. Be3 Ne7 18. Kd2 Nb3+ {(with rough equality and 0-1, 79 in Khrustalev-I.Kuzmin, Irkutsk 2015, and it's also possible to regain the pawn in a simpler fashion.)}) 14... Nxd3+ 15. cxd3 Rxd3 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge7c6,Gf7f6,Ge8f7] Black enjoys comfortable equality. In an ideal world, he'll get to fight for the initiative with ...[Ne7]-[c6], with ...[f6] also likely to prove a useful move, to shore up [e5] and create the option of ...[Kf7] as well as ...[O-O].} *

