1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to. Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Löwenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 $1 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. exd5 $2 Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4c2] (The right way to attack c2 White is OK after 10...Nb4? 11.Bd3! Nxd3+ 12.Qxd3 Qxg2 13.Qf1 , which isn't so easy to defend.)} (10... Nd4 {Indeed,} 11. Qd3 $2 Nxc2+ 12. Kd1 Qxd3+ 13. Bxd3 Nxa1 {(already saw a grandmaster netting material in Maltsevskaya-Plat, Internet blitz 2021.)}) 11. Bd3 $1 Qxg2 {[%cal Gg2h1,Gd4f3]} 12. Be4 {Once again, the only real way not to lose on the spot as White.} Qh3 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gc8g4] Material is level, but Black much the more active and clearly better, with ... [Bg4] on the way, as well as simply ...[Nf6].} 13. Qd3 Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4] Black need not fear an exchange of queens; a bishop will also do a pretty good job on [h3].} 14. Qxh3 $6 Bxh3 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gh3g2,Gd4c2]} (14... Bxh3 {Threatening to take on e4 then go ...Bg2 or ...Nxc2+, and} 15. Bd3 Bg2 {would now win material.}) 15. Kd1 Bg4+ {[%csl Gd1]} 16. Kd2 Rc8 {[%csl Gc2,Gd2][%cal Gf6e4,Gc8c3] The threats just keep on coming. Not only are ...[Nxe4]+ and ...[Rxc3] high on the agenda, but Black might also just go ...[O-O] and ...[Rfd8]. Indeed, it's likely no surprise that the engine assessment is already at '+3' for Black.} *

