1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to. Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Löwenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 $1 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. exd5 $2 Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4c2] (The right way to attack c2 White is OK after 10...Nb4? 11.Bd3! Nxd3+ 12.Qxd3 Qxg2 13.Qf1 , which isn't so easy to defend.)} (10... Nd4 {Indeed,} 11. Qd3 $2 Nxc2+ 12. Kd1 Qxd3+ 13. Bxd3 Nxa1 {(already saw a grandmaster netting material in Maltsevskaya-Plat, Internet blitz 2021.)}) 11. Bd3 $1 Qxg2 {[%cal Gg2h1,Gd4f3]} 12. Be4 {Once again, the only real way not to lose on the spot as White.} Qh3 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gc8g4] Material is level, but Black much the more active and clearly better, with ... [Bg4] on the way, as well as simply ...[Nf6].} 13. Be3 Bg4 {[%csl Gd1,Gf3] Developing with tempo while taking control of [f3].} 14. Qd3 (14. Qd3 {Now Black was a little hasty and even went on to lose after} Nf3+ 15. Bxf3 Bxf3 16. Rg1 {(in Karjakin-Rabiega, Internet blitz 2004, no less. A much better policy is to continue development while keeping the check in reserve.)}) 14... Nf6 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf6e4] Facilitating castling as well as taking on [e4], something which is well worth a pawn.} 15. Bxd4 exd4 $1 {[%cal Ge8c8] A far stronger choice than exchanging on [d3], as Richard realised way back in 2007 when sketching out a short Löwenthal repertoire for Black in the Everyman Chess book Dangerous Weapons: The Sicilian.} (15... exd4 {Now} 16. Qxd4 O-O-O {followed by ... [Rhe8] would leave Black with a huge initiative and the white king rather uncomfortable.}) 16. Ne2 Nxe4 $5 {This seems even stronger than castling long.} 17. Qxe4+ Kf8 {[%cal Ga8e8,Gg4f3] Now ...[Rae8] is a huge threat, as is ...[Bf3].} 18. Nf4 Qf3 {[%csl Ge4,Gh1]} 19. Qxf3 Bxf3 {[%csl Gd5,Ge1][%cal Ga8e8,Ge8e4,Gg7g5] Black is clearly better and will follow up with either ...[g5] or ...[Re8]+ then ...[Re4], causing further problems for the white king, as well as the highly vulnerable pawn on [d5].} *

