[PlyCount "36"]
[GameId "2141525850297472"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to. Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Löwenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 $1 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Ne3 {A solid choice, one which usefully overprotects [g2], although this slow approach shouldn't trouble Black.} Nf6 ({Developing the knight as actively as possible while getting ready to castle. There's also nothing wrong with} 11... Nge7 {if you prefer and Stockfish's suggestion of 11...Qg6!? might be explored too.}) 12. c3 $5 (12. c3 {White waits with Bd3 and now in practice Black has tended to go} O-O {when} 13. Bd3 Qh4 14. Nf5 Bxf5 15. Bxf5 Rad8 {pits Black's knights and central presence against White's bishops. Perhaps White can claim a nominal edge, but the black position is arguably the easier to play.}) 12... Qg6 $5 {[%cal Ge5e4,Gc8e6,Ga8d8] This queen retreat is a decent alternative for Black to castling and could really do with some OTB testing. The queen skips out of the way of the e-pawn, while Black is also ready to complete queenside development with ... [Be6] and ...[Rd8].} 13. Bd3 e4 $1 {Seizing space is the main point of Black's play.} 14. Bc2 O-O 15. O-O Be6 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gf8e8] Completing development while preparing to deploy the rooks to [d8] and [e8]. Black's position is also fairly harmonious, and there's no need to be overly concerned by the pin on the e-pawn.} 16. f3 $5 Rad8 {[%csl Gd1]} 17. Qe1 Rfe8 {[%cal Gc6e5,Gf6e4]} (17... Rfe8 {Black is now all set, if allowed, to seize the initiative with ...Ne5 and can safely get away with} 18. fxe4 Nxe4 {followed by ...[f5].}) 18. Qh4 {[%csl Re4]} Bc8 $1 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge5d3]} (18... Bc8 {Sensibly keeping everything secure. The knight on e3 may look good, but at some point White will need to move it to complete development. Meanwhile, Black is set to go ...Ne5-d3 or if} 19. f4 {then} Ne7 {would regroup in decent fashion.}) *

