1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to. Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Löwenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 $1 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Ne3 {A solid choice, one which usefully overprotects [g2], although this slow approach shouldn't trouble Black.} Nf6 ({Developing the knight as actively as possible while getting ready to castle. There's also nothing wrong with} 11... Nge7 {if you prefer and Stockfish's suggestion of 11...Qg6!? might be explored too.}) 12. Bd3 {[%csl Re4] Kicking the queen is certainly very natural.} Qh4 $1 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Ge5e4,Gc6e5] Continuing to make good, aggressive use of the queen. White might have the bishop-pair, but Black can certainly angle to turn his extra space into a kingside attack, not least if he can get ...[e4] and ...[Ne5] in.} 13. O-O {Calmly castling would appear to be White's best policy.} O-O {[%cal Ge5e4,Gf8d8]} ({Black follows suit, facilitates ...Rd8 and keeps ...e4 in reserve, thereby denying White the option of} 13... e4 14. Bc4 O-O 15. Qd6 {, which might be slightly annoying.}) (13... O-O {Now though} 14. Bc4 {can be well enough met by} Rd8 {or even 14...Ng4!? , angling for an attack.}) 14. f3 Rd8 {[%cal Gc6b4,Gc8e6,Gf6h5] Threatening ... [Nb4].. Black also has ideas of simply ...[Be6] and ...[Nh5], which begins to activate on the kingside; ...[g6] and ...[f5] may follow or just ...[Nf4].} 15. Qe1 {[%csl Rh4]} Qxe1 ({A simple approach, although if striving for maximum complexity you may well prefer} 15... Qd4 $5 {, with rough equality.}) 16. Rxe1 Be6 {[%cal Gc6b4] Completing development while renewing the threat of ...[Nb4].} 17. Bd2 (17. Bd2 {This was seen in Krzyzanowski-J.Baum, Polish Rapid Championship, Zgierz 2019, where} Rac8 {was one decent option, forcing the pace another.}) 17... e4 $1 {[%csl Gd2,Gd3]} 18. fxe4 Ne5 {[%cal Ge5d3]} (18... Ne5 {The bishop on d3 is pinned, meaning Black will either regain his pawn there with full equality, or see the same state of affairs occurring after multiple exchanges:} 19. Ba5 Nxd3 20. Bxd8 Nxe1 21. Bxf6 Nxc2 $1 22. Nxc2 gxf6 {The dust settles to leave an unbalanced but roughly level endgame, where in practice you might well slightly prefer to have the bishop if slightly inferior structure.}) *

