1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to. Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Löwenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 $1 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Ne3 {A solid choice, one which usefully overprotects [g2], although this slow approach shouldn't trouble Black.} Nf6 ({Developing the knight as actively as possible while getting ready to castle. There's also nothing wrong with} 11... Nge7 {if you prefer and Stockfish's suggestion of 11...Qg6!? might be explored too.}) 12. Bd3 {[%csl Re4] Kicking the queen is certainly very natural.} Qh4 $1 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Ge5e4,Gc6e5] Continuing to make good, aggressive use of the queen. White might have the bishop-pair, but Black can certainly angle to turn his extra space into a kingside attack, not least if he can get ...[e4] and ...[Ne5] in.} 13. O-O {Calmly castling would appear to be White's best policy.} O-O {[%cal Ge5e4,Gf8d8]} ({Black follows suit, facilitates ...Rd8 and keeps ...e4 in reserve, thereby denying White the option of} 13... e4 14. Bc4 O-O 15. Qd6 {, which might be slightly annoying.}) (13... O-O {Now though} 14. Bc4 {can be well enough met by} Rd8 {or even 14...Ng4!? , angling for an attack.}) 14. b3 Rd8 {[%csl Gd1,Gd3,Gd8][%cal Ge5e4] Thematically pinning and so threatening to win a piece.} 15. Qe1 e4 $1 {[%cal Ge4d3,Gc6d4,Gc6e5] (Driving the bishop backwards if 16.Bc4 b5 ,) ahead of activating the queen's knight via [d4] or [e5].} 16. Be2 Nd4 {[%csl Gc2,Ge2][%cal Gc8g4] Threatening to overload the defence with ...[Bg4].} 17. Bb2 (17. Bb2 {Here} Bg4 $6 18. Bxd4 $1 Rxd4 19. Rd1 {allowed White to seize the upper hand in Dvorak-Palliser, Street 2003, where Richard should have consistently removed the other bishop.}) 17... Nxe2+ $1 18. Qxe2 Nd5 {[%cal Gd5e3,Gc8e6,Gc8f5] Swapping off the strong knight on [e3] fully equalises. Black's bishop will emerge on [e6], [f5] or [g4] and there isn't any particularly good way for White to attack [g7].} (18... Nd5 {For example} 19. Rad1 Be6 {Black has no problem with an exchange on [d5] followed by dropping the bishop back to [c6].} 20. Qd2 Rac8 {Taking [c3] away from the white queen while introducing the threat of ...[Nc3].} 21. Qd4 f6 {Black has no problems whatsoever here and may either try to unbalance the position with ... [Nf4] or solidly preface that with ...[Rd7] and ...[Rcd8].}) *

