1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to. Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Löwenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 $1 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be2 $5 {[%cal Rd5c7]} (11. Be2 {White prepares to castle and hopes to win material after} Qxg2 $4 12. Bf3 Z0 {and} 13. Nc7+ {.}) 11... Nd4 $1 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Gd4c2,Ge4d5,Ge4g2] Black counters in the same style as after 11. [Be3], threatening ...[Qxd5] while also introducing the possibilities of ...[Qxg2] and ...[Nxc2]+, and, of course, White now won't be able to castle without dropping the bishop on [e2].} 12. Nc7+ Ke7 {The right square for the king, retaining control of some important squares on the d-file while dangling the rook on [a8] before White.} (12... Ke7 {Now the critical move is likely the calm} 13. Be3 $5 {, as we analyse via an 11.Be3 Nd4 12.Nc7+ Ke7 13.Be2 move order.}) 13. f3 {[%csl Re4]} Nxc2+ $1 {[%csl Ga1,Ge1]} ({The right pawn to take,} 13... Nxf3+ $2 14. Kf2 Nh4 15. Qd5 $1 {favouring White, as does 13...Qc6?! 14.c3! .}) 14. Kf2 {[%csl Re4]} Qc6 {[%csl Ga1,Gc7][%cal Gc6c5] Now White's knight and rook both hang, and there are also very much ideas of a check on [c5].} 15. Nxa8 ({This simply must be critical, especially as} 15. Bg5+ {can be repulsed by} f6 {.}) 15... Qc5+ 16. Kf1 Nf6 $5 {[%csl Ga1,Ga8,Gd1][%cal Gh8d8]} ({A new idea, threatening to cause serious problems for the white queen with ...Rd8. In all three over-the-board tests of this position, Black preferred} 16... Nxa1 {, but then} 17. b4 {, while still very murky, may favour White.}) 17. b4 $5 {[%csl Rc5]} Qc3 {[%csl Ga1][%cal Gh8d8]} (17... Qc3 {Renewing the threat of ...Rd8 while also preparing to annex the loose rook in the corner, as with} 18. Bd2 Qxa1 {.}) 18. Bd3 {[%csl Rc2]} (18. Bd3 {White aims to seize the initiative after} Nxa1 19. Be3 {, but Black doesn't have to allow that.}) 18... Nxb4 $1 {[%csl Ga1,Gd3] Now White won't be able to save both bishop and rook.} 19. Qd2 {[%csl Rb4]} Qxd2 20. Bxd2 Nxd3 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Gc8e6,Gf6d5] With two pawns for the exchange, the king centralised for the endgame and ...[Be6] set to complete development, Black enjoys full compensation for the exchange. There's even the idea of ...[Nd5], aiming to trap the knight's counterpart in the corner.} *

