1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to. Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Löwenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 $1 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be2 $5 {[%cal Rd5c7]} (11. Be2 {White prepares to castle and hopes to win material after} Qxg2 $4 12. Bf3 Z0 {and} 13. Nc7+ {.}) 11... Nd4 $1 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Gd4c2,Ge4d5,Ge4g2] Black counters in the same style as after 11. [Be3], threatening ...[Qxd5] while also introducing the possibilities of ...[Qxg2] and ...[Nxc2]+, and, of course, White now won't be able to castle without dropping the bishop on [e2].} 12. Nc7+ Ke7 {The right square for the king, retaining control of some important squares on the d-file while dangling the rook on [a8] before White.} (12... Ke7 {Now the critical move is likely the calm} 13. Be3 $5 {, as we analyse via an 11.Be3 Nd4 12.Nc7+ Ke7 13.Be2 move order.}) 13. f3 {[%csl Re4]} Nxc2+ $1 {[%csl Ga1,Ge1]} ({The right pawn to take,} 13... Nxf3+ $2 14. Kf2 Nh4 15. Qd5 $1 {favouring White, as does 13...Qc6?! 14.c3! .}) 14. Kf2 {[%csl Re4]} Qc6 {[%csl Ga1,Gc7][%cal Gc6c5] Now White's knight and rook both hang, and there are also very much ideas of a check on [c5].} 15. Nxa8 ({This simply must be critical, especially as} 15. Bg5+ {can be repulsed by} f6 {.}) 15... Qc5+ 16. Kf1 Nf6 $5 {[%csl Ga1,Ga8,Gd1][%cal Gh8d8]} ({A new idea, threatening to cause serious problems for the white queen with ...Rd8. In all three over-the-board tests of this position, Black preferred} 16... Nxa1 {, but then} 17. b4 {, while still very murky, may favour White.}) 17. Bg5 Rd8 {[%csl Gd1]} 18. Qc1 {[%csl Rc1,Rc2,Rc5]} Bf5 {[%csl Ga8,Gf1,Gh1][%cal Gh7h6,Gd8a8] A calm way of dealing with the pin. White is temporarily a rook up, but Black enjoys at least enough compensation, in large part because the white knight won't escape. Black's king is also arguably the safer, and he may even be threatening 19...h6 when 20.Bd2? could well walk into a powerful further sacrifice in the shape of 20...Rxd2! 21.Qxd2 Ne3+ . Note too that Black can deal well enough with any short-term tactics, as shown by 19.b4 Qd4! .} 19. a4 $5 {[%cal Ra1a3]} (19. a4 {White hopes to exploit the pin on the c-file to activate with advantage after} Rxa8 $2 20. Ra3 $1 {.}) 19... Qc6 $1 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gc2a1,Gd8a8,Gh7h6] Calmly making the queen safe to renew the threats of ...[Rxa8] and even ...[h6], while also placing ...[Nxa1] back on the agenda. As confirmed by the engines, the onus is on White to maintain the objective state of rough equality here.} *

