1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to. Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Löwenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 $1 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be2 $5 {[%cal Rd5c7]} (11. Be2 {White prepares to castle and hopes to win material after} Qxg2 $4 12. Bf3 Z0 {and} 13. Nc7+ {.}) 11... Nd4 $1 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Gd4c2,Ge4d5,Ge4g2] Black counters in the same style as after 11. [Be3], threatening ...[Qxd5] while also introducing the possibilities of ...[Qxg2] and ...[Nxc2]+, and, of course, White now won't be able to castle without dropping the bishop on [e2].} 12. Nc7+ Ke7 {The right square for the king, retaining control of some important squares on the d-file while dangling the rook on [a8] before White.} (12... Ke7 {Now the critical move is likely the calm} 13. Be3 $5 {, as we analyse via an 11.Be3 Nd4 12.Nc7+ Ke7 13.Be2 move order.}) 13. Kf1 {A calm move and also rather risky choice, although if White is precise he can avoid drifting into danger.} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Gc2,Ge2] Simply retaining the rook is arguably the trickiest line for White to face. Black is a pawn up, and so must now be quite happy just to exchange on [e2].} ({Instead,} 13... Nxe2 $5 14. Nxa8 Bh3 $1 15. gxh3 Nf6 $1 {gives Black enough play for the rook to force a draw, but no more than that.}) 14. Be3 Qc6 $1 {[%cal Gc6c7,Gd4e2]} ({A safe and sensible retreat, as well as a clear improvement over} 14... Qxc2 $2 {when} 15. Qxc2 Nxc2 16. Bc5+ $1 {gives White the initiative.}) 15. Bxd4 exd4 16. Qxd4 Qxc7 $1 {Black shouldn't be bluffed and should consistently take the knight. Yes, [g7] then [h8] will fall, but White's queen won't be able to make it out of the corner alive.} 17. Qxg7 Nf6 18. Qxh8 Bh3 $5 {[%csl Gf1,Gh8]} ({Striving for the maximum rather than force a draw with} 18... Bg4 19. Qg7 Bxe2+ 20. Kxe2 Qc4+ {. The text offers White only a choice between giving up the queen on [b8] or [g8].}) 19. Qg7 Rg8 {[%csl Gg2,Gg7]} (19... Rg8 {Clearly} 20. Qh6 $4 Bxg2+ {would now be pretty unwise, so the queen must go.}) 20. Qxg8 Nxg8 21. gxh3 Qxc2 {[%csl Gf1][%cal Gc2b2,Gg8f6,Gf6e4] This position isn't at all clear, even if it's '0.00' in engine speak of course!. With an active queen and also a knight ...[Nf6]-[e4] is very much a plan, we'd slightly prefer to take Black, and the white position does look the harder to coordinate.} *

