[%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be2 $5 {[%cal Rd5c7]} (11. Be2 {White prepares to castle and hopes to win material after} Qxg2 $4 12. Bf3 Z0 {and} 13. Nc7+ {.}) 11... Nd4 $1 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Gd4c2,Ge4d5,Ge4g2] Black counters in the same style as after 11. [Be3], threatening ...[Qxd5] while also introducing the possibilities of ...[Qxg2] and ...[Nxc2]+, and, of course, White now won't be able to castle without dropping the bishop on [e2].} 12. Nc7+ Ke7 {The right square for the king, retaining control of some important squares on the d-file while dangling the rook on [a8] before White.} (12... Ke7 {Now the critical move is likely the calm} 13. Be3 $5 {, as we analyse via an 11.Be3 Nd4 12.Nc7+ Ke7 13.Be2 move order.}) 13. c3 {This is another risky if objectively playable line which an opponent taken by surprise might stumble into.} Nc2+ {[%csl Ga1,Ge1][%cal Gc8f5]} (13... Nc2+ {Forking and now} 14. Kd2 $4 Bf5 {would be pretty terminal, and if} 15. Nxa8 Qf4# {.}) 14. Kf1 Nf6 {[%csl Gd1,Gd5][%cal Gh8d8] Ruling out [Nd5]+ while threatening to cause major discomfort with ...[Rd8].} 15. Bd3 (15. Bf3 Qc4+ 16. Be2 Qxc7 17. Qxc2 Be6 {⩱ followed by ...[Rhd8].}) 15... Rd8 $5 {[%csl Gd1,Gd3,Gd8]} ({A dangerous choice, although it should be said that} 15... Qc6 {is also very playable, and if} 16. Qxc2 {((Or 16.Nxa8 Nxa1 ))} Qxc7 {, pitting Black's extra central pawn against White's bishop-pair.}) 16. Qxc2 Rxd3 17. Nxa8 Bh3 $1 {The point of Black's play. The bishop is taboo and White must walk a tightrope to survive.} *

