[White "1A) 8.Qd1 Sidelines"]
[Black "8 Qd1 Qg6 9.Nc3 d5 10.Nxd5 with 11.Be2 \[Illustrative\] #5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "52"]
[GameId "2141525850596490"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to. Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Löwenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 $1 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and 0-0.} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5]. At this point Black has an important choice: 9...[d5]!? and 9...[Nge7], with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.} d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4] Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as 9...[Nge7] after which 10.Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence. The text threatens ... [d4], but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the [b1]-[h7] diagonal 10.exd5 [Nd4], or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7]. Note too that instead the rare 10.f3 [Nge7] would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 [Nge7] 10.Nc3 [d5] move order.} Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be2 $5 {[%cal Rd5c7] White prepares to castle and hopes to win material after 11... [Qxg2]?? 12.Bf3 and 13.Nc7+.} Nd4 $1 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Gd4c2,Ge4d5,Ge4g2] Black counters in the same style as after 11.Be3, threatening ...[Qxd5] while also introducing the possibilities of ...[Qxg2] and ...[Nxc2]+, and, of course, White now won't be able to castle without dropping the bishop on [e2].} 12. Nc7+ Ke7 {The right square for the king, retaining control of some important squares on the d-file while dangling the rook on [a8] before White. Now the critical move is likely the calm 13.Be3!?, as we analyse via an 11.Be3 [Nd4] 12.Nc7+ [Ke7] 13. [Be2] move order.} 13. c3 {This is another risky if objectively playable line which an opponent taken by surprise might stumble into.} Nc2+ {[%csl Ga1,Ge1][%cal Gc8f5]} (13... Nc2+ {Forking and now} 14. Kd2 $4 Bf5 {would be pretty terminal, and if} 15. Nxa8 Qf4# {.}) 14. Kf1 Nf6 {[%csl Gd1,Gd5][%cal Gh8d8] Ruling out [Nd5]+ while threatening to cause major discomfort with ...[Rd8].} 15. Bd3 (15. Bf3 Qc4+ 16. Be2 Qxc7 17. Qxc2 Be6 {⩱ followed by ...[Rhd8].}) 15... Rd8 $5 {[%csl Gd1,Gd3,Gd8]} ({A dangerous choice, although it should be said that} 15... Qc6 {is also very playable, and if} 16. Qxc2 {((Or 16.Nxa8 Nxa1 ))} Qxc7 {, pitting Black's extra central pawn against White's bishop-pair.}) 16. Qxc2 Rxd3 17. Nxa8 Bh3 $1 {The point of Black's play. The bishop is taboo and White must walk a tightrope to survive. Fleshing out the details.} 18. Rg1 (18. gxh3 $2 Qxh1+ 19. Ke2 Qf3+ $1 20. Ke1 Ne4 {Black is winning. ( The threat is 21.-- Rd1+! 22.Qxd1 Qxf2# and there just isn't a good defence. )} 21. Be3 Rxe3+ $1 22. fxe3 Qh1+ 23. Ke2 Qg2+ {White must either allow mate} ({Kd1} 23... Qf1+ {or lose the queen after}) 24. Kd3 Nc5+ {.}) 18... Ng4 $1 {[%csl Gf1][%cal Gg4h2]} 19. Bg5+ $1 ({The only move to stay on the board,} 19. Qe2 $2 {being mated in style by} Rd1+ $1 20. Qxd1 Nxh2# {.}) 19... f6 {[%cal Gg4h2]} 20. Qe2 $1 Nxh2+ 21. Ke1 Qf5 $1 {[%cal Gf6g5,Gh3g4]} (21... Qf5 {Retaining the queens. White is still a rook up, but the bishop on g5 hangs and} 22. Z0 Bg4 {is also a big threat, and if} 23. f3 Bxf3 $1 {.}) 22. Be3 Bg4 {[%csl Ge2]} (22... Bg4 {Continuing to hound the queen, while hoping for} 23. Qc2 $4 Rxe3+ $1 {.}) 23. f3 $1 Bxf3 $1 24. gxf3 Nxf3+ {[%csl Ge1]} 25. Kf1 $1 Nd2+ 26. Ke1 Nf3+ (26... Nf3+ {And the game will end with perpetual check unless White elects to fall for} 27. Kf2 $4 Nd4+ {.}) *

