1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to. Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Löwenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 $1 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be2 $5 {[%cal Rd5c7]} (11. Be2 {White prepares to castle and hopes to win material after} Qxg2 $4 12. Bf3 Z0 {and} 13. Nc7+ {.}) 11... Nd4 $1 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Gd4c2,Ge4d5,Ge4g2] Black counters in the same style as after 11. [Be3], threatening ...[Qxd5] while also introducing the possibilities of ...[Qxg2] and ...[Nxc2]+, and, of course, White now won't be able to castle without dropping the bishop on [e2].} 12. Nc7+ Ke7 {The right square for the king, retaining control of some important squares on the d-file while dangling the rook on [a8] before White.} (12... Ke7 {Now the critical move is likely the calm} 13. Be3 $5 {, as we analyse via an 11.Be3 Nd4 12.Nc7+ Ke7 13.Be2 move order.}) 13. O-O $2 {Covering [g2], but allowing Black a powerful shot.} Bh3 $3 {[%csl Gg1][%cal Ge4g2]} ({Threatening mate is a far, far stronger option than} 13... Qxe2 $2 14. Nxa8 {, after which White went on to win in Poddubnyi-Vlachos, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2024.}) (13... Bh3 {Now} 14. gxh3 Nxe2+ {would cost White the queen, so blocking the [h1]-[a8] diagonal is pretty much forced.}) 14. f3 Qxe2 {[%cal Ge2g2]} (14... Qxe2 {Renewing the threat of mate on g2 while hoping for} 15. gxh3 $2 Nxf3+ $1 {. Note too that 15.Nd5+ can simply be sidestepped by 15...Kf8 .}) 15. Qxe2 Nxe2+ {[%csl Gc1,Gg1]} 16. Kf2 Rc8 $1 {Saving the rook while activating it with tempo.} 17. Nd5+ Ke6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gh3g2,Gc8c2] Black is currently a piece ahead and just doing extremely well, with ...[Kxd5] a threat and ideas too of ...[Rxc2] or ...[Bxg2].} *

