[%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be2 $5 {[%cal Rd5c7]} (11. Be2 {White prepares to castle and hopes to win material after} Qxg2 $4 12. Bf3 Z0 {and} 13. Nc7+ {.}) 11... Nd4 $1 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Gd4c2,Ge4d5,Ge4g2] Black counters in the same style as after 11. [Be3], threatening ...[Qxd5] while also introducing the possibilities of ...[Qxg2] and ...[Nxc2]+, and, of course, White now won't be able to castle without dropping the bishop on [e2].} 12. Nc7+ Ke7 {The right square for the king, retaining control of some important squares on the d-file while dangling the rook on [a8] before White.} (12... Ke7 {Now the critical move is likely the calm} 13. Be3 $5 {, as we analyse via an 11.Be3 Nd4 12.Nc7+ Ke7 13.Be2 move order.}) 13. Nxa8 $2 {By far White's most common move in practice, but also overly greedy and a major mistake.} Qxg2 $1 {[%csl Ge1,Gh1]} ({The right pawn to take, whereas} 13... Nxc2+ $4 14. Kf1 Nxa1 15. Be3 {is winning for White, who will save his own knight while acquiring Black's.}) (13... Qxg2 {Note too that not only is 14...Qxh1+ a big threat, but that the horribly materialistic} 14. Kd2 $4 {would lose to} Nf6 {followed by ...[Ne4]+ or ...[Rd8].}) 14. Rf1 Bf5 {[%cal Gd4c2] Simply threatening to take on [c2], a square that White can't really cover.} 15. Qd2 $5 {[%cal Rd2b4]} Nxc2+ 16. Kd1 Nf6 $1 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gh8d8] Maintaining control of [b4] while threatening ...[Rd8].} 17. Qc3 Rd8+ 18. Bd2 (18. Bd2 {This was G.Orlov-Kruus, Kohtla Jarve 2005, where the strong American IM escaped and went on to win after} Qd5 $2 19. Nb6 {, but he really shouldn't have done.}) 18... Kf8 $1 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Gf8g8,Gf6e4]} (18... Kf8 {Black's king is now safe enough and 19...Ne4 a sizeable threat, while} 19. Qc7 {would be rebuffed by} Qd5 {.}) 19. Qxe5 Nd4 $1 {[%csl Ga8,Gd1,Gd2,Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gd4f3]} (19... Nd4 {An unexpected change of direction, but as confirmed by the engines, Black's attack should be decisive. The immediate threat is 20...Nf3,} 20. Qc7 Ne6 {defends everything while attacking the queen and renewing the threat of ...[Ne4], and 20.Qa5 b6! 21.Qxb6 Qxa8 should really be winning for Black.}) *

