[White "1B) 8.Qd1 with 13.Nxa8"]
[Black "8.Qd1 with 13.Nxa8 Nxc2+ 14.Kd2 Nxe3 15.Qf3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "34"]
[GameId "2141525851624596"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Lowenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Nxa8 $6 {White greedily snaffles the rook. Of course, this capture is a critical test of Black's bold approach, but it's also one the second player should be happy to see and Black has scored well from here.} Nxc2+ {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gc2e3] Discomforting the white king, if again a move not played with the intention of taking on [a1].} 14. Kd2 {[%cal Rd1c2]} Nxe3 $1 {[%csl Gd1]} ({An important bishop to remove, whereas after} 14... Nxa1 $2 15. Qc1 $1 Qb4+ 16. Kd1 {it's long been established that the black king is in somewhat more danger than the white one.}) 15. Qf3 $4 Qb4+ $1 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Gc8g4] Beginning to hunt down the enemy royal couple.} 16. Kxe3 Qd4+ {[%csl Ge3]} 17. Ke2 Bg4 {[%csl Ge2,Gf3,Gg4] Black wins the queen and the game.} *

