cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Nxa8 $6 {White greedily snaffles the rook. Of course, this capture is a critical test of Black's bold approach, but it's also one the second player should be happy to see and Black has scored well from here.} Nxc2+ {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gc2e3] Discomforting the white king, if again a move not played with the intention of taking on [a1].} 14. Kd2 {[%cal Rd1c2]} Nxe3 $1 {[%csl Gd1]} ({An important bishop to remove, whereas after} 14... Nxa1 $2 15. Qc1 $1 Qb4+ 16. Kd1 {it's long been established that the black king is in somewhat more danger than the white one.}) 15. Bd3 $6 {[%csl Re4]} Nxd1 $1 ({Black should be happy enough to exchange and in any case, this is a better choice than} 15... Nc4+ $6 16. Bxc4 Qxc4 17. Qb3 {.}) 16. Bxe4 Nxf2 {[%csl Ge4,Gh1] Forking.} 17. Rhe1 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gf2e4,Gh8d8] Not only is taking on [e4] a threat, but so once again is ...[Rd8]+. Black's initiative is sufficient to emerge with at least good play for the exchange.} (17... Nf6 {For example,} 18. Bc2 $1 Rd8+ 19. Ke2 {((A fairly essential move, since the knight on a8 would be in grave danger after 19.Kc1 Nd5!. ) . )} N2e4 20. Bxe4 Nxe4 {Threatening to check on [g4] then remove the knight.} 21. Ke3 $1 Nf6 22. Nb6 Be6 {With careful play, White has saved the knight, but with two central pawns for the exchange, Black may even be slightly for choice in the resulting ending. (18.Bf3? Rd8+! 19.Ke3 (( 19.Kc3 Be6 20.Nb6 Rd6 ['key': 'C', 'state': 'VCVV', 'val': 'Continuing to hassle the knight while getting ready to pin if', 'key': 'S', 'state': 'VCVV', 'val': '21.Nc4', 'key': 'S', 'state': 'VCVV', 'val': 'Rd3+', 'key': 'S', 'state': 'VCVV', 'val': '22.Kb4', 'key': 'S', 'state': 'VCVV', 'val': 'Rd4.', 'key': 'C', 'state': 'VCVV', 'val': '', 'key': 'C', 'state': 'VCVV', 'val': '.'] 21.Na4 e4 With ...[Nd5]+ on its way, Black's attack is worth far more than a rook. )) 19...N2g4+ Continuing to harry and aiming to get in a well-timed ...[e4]. 20.Bxg4 Nxg4+ 21.Ke2 Bf5 White's king and knight are exposed and Black will always be able to at least annex [h2], thereby acquiring a third pawn for the exchange. )}) *

