t ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Qd3 {[%csl Re4]} (13. Qd3 {White ignores the hanging rook, preferring to remove the queens while getting ready to seize a strong initiative in the event of} Qxd3 $2 14. Bxd3 Rb8 15. f4 {.}) 13... Nxc2+ {[%csl Ge3] This doesn't so much attack the rook on [a1] as prepare to remove the unopposed dark-squared bishop on [e3].} 14. Kd2 {[%csl Rc2,Re4] Naturally White would like to be able to recapture on [d3], if required, with the bishop from [f1].} Qxd3+ $1 ({Black must remove the queens so. Please don't become too ambitious and go} 14... Bf5 $4 {, which after} 15. Bc5+ Kf6 16. Qd6+ Be6 17. Bd3 {was already winning for White in Speelman-Bielczyk, Valetta 1980.}) 15. Bxd3 Nxe3 ({And this is the right piece to capture. After} 15... Nxa1 $4 16. Nxa8 {only one knight would be getting out of the corner, and it isn't Black's.}) 16. Nxa8 {Accepting what is essentially an exchange sacrifice must be critical.} Nd5 $1 {[%csl Ga8]} ({A key retreat, trapping the knight's counterpart in the corner. A combination of that and Black's extra pawn should ensure there's enough compensation for the exchange. Note too that these days,} 16... Nxg2 $2 {no longer seems as good:} 17. Rhc1 $1 {favours White after} Nh6 18. Rc7+ Kf6 19. Nb6 {and 17...Nf6 18.Rc7+ Kd6 19.Rac1 .}) 17. Rhe1 $2 Be6 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gh8a8]} (17... Be6 {Black simply threatens 18...Nf6 and 19...Rxa8. As such,} 18. Rxe5 Ngf6 {would pick up the white knight, and also note that one black knight can always replace the other on [d5] if needed.}) 18. Be4 Ngf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gf6d5]} 19. Bxd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Ga8] While White can pick off [e5], the knight on [a8] is lost and the resulting endgame will be superb for Black with two minor pieces against the rook.} *

