xc2+ {[%csl Ge3] This doesn't so much attack the rook on [a1] as prepare to remove the unopposed dark-squared bishop on [e3].} 14. Kd2 {[%csl Rc2,Re4] Naturally White would like to be able to recapture on [d3], if required, with the bishop from [f1].} Qxd3+ $1 ({Black must remove the queens so. Please don't become too ambitious and go} 14... Bf5 $4 {, which after} 15. Bc5+ Kf6 16. Qd6+ Be6 17. Bd3 {was already winning for White in Speelman-Bielczyk, Valetta 1980.}) 15. Bxd3 Nxe3 ({And this is the right piece to capture. After} 15... Nxa1 $4 16. Nxa8 {only one knight would be getting out of the corner, and it isn't Black's.}) 16. Nxa8 {Accepting what is essentially an exchange sacrifice must be critical.} Nd5 $1 {[%csl Ga8]} ({A key retreat, trapping the knight's counterpart in the corner. A combination of that and Black's extra pawn should ensure there's enough compensation for the exchange. Note too that these days,} 16... Nxg2 $2 {no longer seems as good:} 17. Rhc1 $1 {favours White after} Nh6 18. Rc7+ Kf6 19. Nb6 {and 17...Nf6 18.Rc7+ Kd6 19.Rac1 .}) 17. Rhc1 {[%cal Ra8c7]} ({This unsurprisingly leads to similar play to} 17. Rac1 {.}) 17... Ngf6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gh8d8] Ensuring that Black will continue to control the important [d5] point for a fair while and also preparing to seize the initiative with ...[Rd8].} 18. Nc7 {[%cal Rc7d5]} Nb4 $1 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gb4d3,Gh8d8] Best. Black continues to fight against the white knight's escape and also introduces ideas of simply ...[Nxd3], as well as of ...[Rd8].} ({Note too that with the other rook on c1, Black may consider} 18... Nf4 $6 {, but here it doesn't achieve very much at all after just} 19. Bf1 {.}) 19. Rc4 $5 {[%csl Rb4] Forcing the pace.} Nxd3 $1 {[%csl Gd2]} ({Exposing the white king and exchanging off the knight is the right way to go, since Black doesn't have quite enough play after} 19... Nc6 $6 20. Nxa6 $1 Be6 21. Rc3 {.}) 20. Kxd3 Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6]} ({Heading for c6 once again appears to be a better policy than} 20... Bf5+ 21. Ke3 {.}) 21. Rac1 Bc6 $1 ({Black has the tactics worked out, so is quite happy to provoke White to take on a6, although it should be mentioned that both} 21... Rd8 {and 21...Kd6 are also perfectly playable.}) 22. Nxa6 Rd8+ $5 {[%csl Gd3,Gf6][%cal Gc6b5]} (22... Rd8+ {This check offers White more chances to go wrong than the immediate 22...Bb5. Now} 23. Kc3 {can be met by} Nd5+ {and only then} 24. Kb3 Bb5 {, while 23.Ke3 Nd5 24.Ke4 can be met by 24...Nb4+ . White should definitely avoid 23.Kc2? Be4+ , so keeping the king on the problematic diagonal may actually be safest.}) 23. Ke2 Bb5 {[%csl Ga6,Gc4][%cal Gb5a6] Black will regain the exchange with full equality.} (23... Bb5 24. Nc7 Bxc4+ 25. Rxc4 {Here a draw was unsurprisingly agreed in Portych-Bohak, correspondence 2015, but over the board or in an online blitz game, Black might continue: targeting the white knight and advancing on the kingside are both decent plans. For example:} h5 $5 26. h4 {Preventing Black from annexing too much space.} Rd7 27. b4 Kd6 {Pretty much forcing the knight backwards.} 28. Nb5+ Ke6 29. Nc7+ Kf5 $5 {(A draw remains the most likely result we're very much still in '0.00' territory, but while White can advance on the queenside, Black can get in ...[g5] and in such positions it's far from unknown for White to make an obvious blunder:)} 30. Ke3 $4 Rxc7 $1 {The potential knight fork on [d5] will decide proceedings.}) *

