1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Lowenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Qd3 {[%csl Re4]} (13. Qd3 {White ignores the hanging rook, preferring to remove the queens while getting ready to seize a strong initiative in the event of} Qxd3 $2 14. Bxd3 Rb8 15. f4 {.}) 13... Nxc2+ {[%csl Ge3] This doesn't so much attack the rook on [a1] as prepare to remove the unopposed dark-squared bishop on [e3].} 14. Kd2 {[%csl Rc2,Re4] Naturally White would like to be able to recapture on [d3], if required, with the bishop from [f1].} Qxd3+ $1 ({Black must remove the queens so. Please don't become too ambitious and go} 14... Bf5 $4 {, which after} 15. Bc5+ Kf6 16. Qd6+ Be6 17. Bd3 {was already winning for White in Speelman-Bielczyk, Valetta 1980.}) 15. Bxd3 Nxe3 ({And this is the right piece to capture. After} 15... Nxa1 $4 16. Nxa8 {only one knight would be getting out of the corner, and it isn't Black's.}) 16. Nxa8 {Accepting what is essentially an exchange sacrifice must be critical.} Nd5 $1 {[%csl Ga8]} ({A key retreat, trapping the knight's counterpart in the corner. A combination of that and Black's extra pawn should ensure there's enough compensation for the exchange. Note too that these days,} 16... Nxg2 $2 {no longer seems as good:} 17. Rhc1 $1 {favours White after} Nh6 18. Rc7+ Kf6 19. Nb6 {and 17...Nf6 18.Rc7+ Kd6 19.Rac1 .}) 17. Rhc1 {[%cal Ra8c7]} ({This unsurprisingly leads to similar play to} 17. Rac1 {.}) 17... Ngf6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gh8d8] Ensuring that Black will continue to control the important [d5] point for a fair while and also preparing to seize the initiative with ...[Rd8].} 18. Nc7 {[%cal Rc7d5]} Nb4 $1 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gb4d3,Gh8d8] Best. Black continues to fight against the white knight's escape and also introduces ideas of simply ...[Nxd3], as well as of ...[Rd8].} ({Note too that with the other rook on c1, Black may consider} 18... Nf4 $6 {, but here it doesn't achieve very much at all after just} 19. Bf1 {.}) 19. Rc4 $5 {[%csl Rb4] Forcing the pace.} Nxd3 $1 {[%csl Gd2]} ({Exposing the white king and exchanging off the knight is the right way to go, since Black doesn't have quite enough play after} 19... Nc6 $6 20. Nxa6 $1 Be6 21. Rc3 {.}) 20. Kxd3 Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6]} ({Heading for c6 once again appears to be a better policy than} 20... Bf5+ 21. Ke3 {.}) 21. Rac1 Bc6 $1 ({Black has the tactics worked out, so is quite happy to provoke White to take on a6, although it should be mentioned that both} 21... Rd8 {and 21...Kd6 are also perfectly playable.}) 22. Rxc6 bxc6 {[%cal Gh8b8,Ga6a5]} (22... bxc6 {Now if} 23. Rxc6 {Black is in time to activate with} Rb8 {(attacking [b2])} 24. b3 Kd7 {followed by defending the a-pawn. Once again, the position is equal if not completely dead. Let's see an example.}) 23. Nxa6 Rd8+ {[%csl Gd3] Asking a question of the white king and hoping to either get to check next move or see it blocking the c-file on [c2].} 24. Ke2 $5 Kd6 $5 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gd8a8,Gf6d5]} ({(Looking for more ...Ra8 and ...Nd5 are both now very much ideas than simplification with)} 24... Ra8 25. Rxc6 Kd7 26. Rb6 Nd5 {when} 27. Nc5+ {and ½-½ was De Vassal-Aigner, correspondence 2007.}) 25. a4 Nd5 26. g3 f5 $1 {[%cal Ge5e4,Gd8d7,Gd7b7,Gd7a7] This left Black with ideas of ...[e4], as well as of ...[Rd7] then ...[Rb7] or ...[Ra7], and while Johansen-Carnstam, correspondence 2005, was drawn, at other time controls White might drift into trouble, be that down the b-file or if Black can get in ...[e4], ...[g5] and ...[f4].} *

