1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Lowenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Qd3 {[%csl Re4]} (13. Qd3 {White ignores the hanging rook, preferring to remove the queens while getting ready to seize a strong initiative in the event of} Qxd3 $2 14. Bxd3 Rb8 15. f4 {.}) 13... Nxc2+ {[%csl Ge3] This doesn't so much attack the rook on [a1] as prepare to remove the unopposed dark-squared bishop on [e3].} 14. Kd2 {[%csl Rc2,Re4] Naturally White would like to be able to recapture on [d3], if required, with the bishop from [f1].} Qxd3+ $1 ({Black must remove the queens so. Please don't become too ambitious and go} 14... Bf5 $4 {, which after} 15. Bc5+ Kf6 16. Qd6+ Be6 17. Bd3 {was already winning for White in Speelman-Bielczyk, Valetta 1980.}) 15. Bxd3 Nxe3 ({And this is the right piece to capture. After} 15... Nxa1 $4 16. Nxa8 {only one knight would be getting out of the corner, and it isn't Black's.}) 16. Nxa8 {Accepting what is essentially an exchange sacrifice must be critical.} Nd5 $1 {[%csl Ga8]} ({A key retreat, trapping the knight's counterpart in the corner. A combination of that and Black's extra pawn should ensure there's enough compensation for the exchange. Note too that these days,} 16... Nxg2 $2 {no longer seems as good:} 17. Rhc1 $1 {favours White after} Nh6 18. Rc7+ Kf6 19. Nb6 {and 17...Nf6 18.Rc7+ Kd6 19.Rac1 .}) 17. Rac1 {Trying to extricate the knight via [c7].} Ngf6 {[%csl Ga8,Gd2][%cal Gh8d8] Just like with the other rook on [c1], Black gets ready to win material after ...[Rd8].} 18. Rhd1 $2 {Centralisation is often a good plan, but here Black can also centralise and with somewhat more effect.} Kd6 $1 {[%csl Ga8,Gc7][%cal Gc8e6] The king fearlessly strolls forwards, taking control of the important [c7] point. It transpires that White can't really get anything going on the d-file, meaning that Black will win material after ...[Be6].} 19. Ke1 Be6 20. Nc7 $1 {[%cal Rc7e6]} Nxc7 $1 {[%cal Gc7d5] Picking up the stray knight while rightly refusing to fear the discovered check.} 21. Bxa6+ Ncd5 22. Bxb7 Rb8 {[%csl Gb2,Gb7,Gb8,Ge1][%cal Gf6d5] White must either now lose [b2] or consent to a sub-optimal exchange on [d5], after which Black was clearly for choice thanks to his well-centralised forces in Prandstetter-Nun, Trnava 1980.} *

