t ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Qd3 {[%csl Re4]} (13. Qd3 {White ignores the hanging rook, preferring to remove the queens while getting ready to seize a strong initiative in the event of} Qxd3 $2 14. Bxd3 Rb8 15. f4 {.}) 13... Nxc2+ {[%csl Ge3] This doesn't so much attack the rook on [a1] as prepare to remove the unopposed dark-squared bishop on [e3].} 14. Kd2 {[%csl Rc2,Re4] Naturally White would like to be able to recapture on [d3], if required, with the bishop from [f1].} Qxd3+ $1 ({Black must remove the queens so. Please don't become too ambitious and go} 14... Bf5 $4 {, which after} 15. Bc5+ Kf6 16. Qd6+ Be6 17. Bd3 {was already winning for White in Speelman-Bielczyk, Valetta 1980.}) 15. Bxd3 Nxe3 ({And this is the right piece to capture. After} 15... Nxa1 $4 16. Nxa8 {only one knight would be getting out of the corner, and it isn't Black's.}) 16. Nxa8 {Accepting what is essentially an exchange sacrifice must be critical.} Nd5 $1 {[%csl Ga8]} ({A key retreat, trapping the knight's counterpart in the corner. A combination of that and Black's extra pawn should ensure there's enough compensation for the exchange. Note too that these days,} 16... Nxg2 $2 {no longer seems as good:} 17. Rhc1 $1 {favours White after} Nh6 18. Rc7+ Kf6 19. Nb6 {and 17...Nf6 18.Rc7+ Kd6 19.Rac1 .}) 17. Rac1 {Trying to extricate the knight via [c7].} Ngf6 {[%csl Ga8,Gd2][%cal Gh8d8] Just like with the other rook on [c1], Black gets ready to win material after ...[Rd8].} 18. Nc7 $1 {The knight should try to make it out whilst it can.} Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gb4a2,Gh8d8]} (18... Nb4 {Consistent with our approach against Rhc1, and do note that now} 19. Rc4 Nxd3 20. Kxd3 Bd7 21. Rhc1 Bc6 {would transpose to a position we analysed via that other move order.}) ({Here, with the rook still on h1, Black can also consider} 18... Nf4 $5 {, but we're quite happy with the text move, threatening ...[Rd8] while also giving Black ideas of ... [Nxa2] and ...[Nxd3].}) 19. Bc4 $6 {This may look active, but is actually more of a pseudo-active move.} Kd6 $1 {[%cal Gd6c7] With its counterpart on the d-file, Black's king can stroll forwards and do so with a definite threat.} 20. Bxf7 Bd7 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gb4c6] This time the idea isn't so much ...[Bc6], as ...[Nc6] to trap and win the white knight.} 21. Rhd1 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gd6c7]} 22. Nxa6 bxa6 23. Ke1+ Ke7 {[%cal Ge7f7,Gh8b8,Gc6d4,Gb8b6] Taking stock, we find White with a rook and pawn for the knight-pair, which shouldn't be quite enough here. The rooks are on open files, but currently fully contained by the black pieces, and Black not only threatens ...[Kxf7], but is ready to go ...[Rb8] targeting [b2] then ....[Rb6]. That will cover everything, enabling Black to start to activate the extra minor pieces, perhaps beginning with ...[Nd4].} *

