t ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Qd3 {[%csl Re4]} (13. Qd3 {White ignores the hanging rook, preferring to remove the queens while getting ready to seize a strong initiative in the event of} Qxd3 $2 14. Bxd3 Rb8 15. f4 {.}) 13... Nxc2+ {[%csl Ge3] This doesn't so much attack the rook on [a1] as prepare to remove the unopposed dark-squared bishop on [e3].} 14. Kd2 {[%csl Rc2,Re4] Naturally White would like to be able to recapture on [d3], if required, with the bishop from [f1].} Qxd3+ $1 ({Black must remove the queens so. Please don't become too ambitious and go} 14... Bf5 $4 {, which after} 15. Bc5+ Kf6 16. Qd6+ Be6 17. Bd3 {was already winning for White in Speelman-Bielczyk, Valetta 1980.}) 15. Bxd3 Nxe3 ({And this is the right piece to capture. After} 15... Nxa1 $4 16. Nxa8 {only one knight would be getting out of the corner, and it isn't Black's.}) 16. Nxa8 {Accepting what is essentially an exchange sacrifice must be critical.} Nd5 $1 {[%csl Ga8]} ({A key retreat, trapping the knight's counterpart in the corner. A combination of that and Black's extra pawn should ensure there's enough compensation for the exchange. Note too that these days,} 16... Nxg2 $2 {no longer seems as good:} 17. Rhc1 $1 {favours White after} Nh6 18. Rc7+ Kf6 19. Nb6 {and 17...Nf6 18.Rc7+ Kd6 19.Rac1 .}) 17. Rac1 {Trying to extricate the knight via [c7].} Ngf6 {[%csl Ga8,Gd2][%cal Gh8d8] Just like with the other rook on [c1], Black gets ready to win material after ...[Rd8].} 18. Nc7 $1 {The knight should try to make it out whilst it can.} Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gb4a2,Gh8d8]} (18... Nb4 {Consistent with our approach against Rhc1, and do note that now} 19. Rc4 Nxd3 20. Kxd3 Bd7 21. Rhc1 Bc6 {would transpose to a position we analysed via that other move order.}) ({Here, with the rook still on h1, Black can also consider} 18... Nf4 $5 {, but we're quite happy with the text move, threatening ...[Rd8] while also giving Black ideas of ... [Nxa2] and ...[Nxd3].}) 19. Bb1 $5 {Keeping the c-file unobstructed, while making the bishop and a-pawn safe.} Kd6 $5 ({The engines of 2024 quite like this old suggestion of Richard's, although it should be said that Black can also secure reasonable counterplay with the less provocative} 19... Rd8+ 20. Ke2 Nc6 21. Rhd1 Nd4+ {. The text move threatens ...[Nc6] and also ...[Bd7], so White really needs to react - down the d-file.}) 20. Rhd1 Nc6 {[%cal Gd6c7] Compelling the knight to return to the corner.} 21. Na8 {[%cal Ra8b6]} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4d1,Gh8a8]} ({With} 21... Be6 {running into} 22. Nb6 {to free the knight, Black should prefer to create a double-attack. White's reply is pretty much forced.}) 22. f3 Rxa8 $1 {Black elects to see his knight activated, and this looks like a stronger policy than exchanging on [f3].} 23. fxg4 Nxg4 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gg4h2,Gc6d4] Black has two good pawns for the exchange and is all set to activate with ...[Nd4] and ...[h5] making ...[Nxh2] into a threat. Meanwhile White lacks a good discovered check and surely can't claim any advantage in this position, one which we'll return to in the illustrative game Smirnov-Oleksienko, Vasylyshyn Memorial, Lvov 2007.} *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1C) 8.Qd1 with 13.Qd3"]
[Black "8.Qd1 with 13.Qd3 Nxc2+ 14.Kd2 Qxd3+ 15.Bxd3 #12"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "50"]
[GameId "2141525853242543"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Lowenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Qd3 {[%csl Re4]} (13. Qd3 {White ignores the hanging rook, preferring to remove the queens while getting ready to seize a strong initiative in the event of} Qxd3 $2 14. Bxd3 Rb8 15. f4 {.}) 13... Nxc2+ {[%csl Ge3] This doesn't so much attack the rook on [a1] as prepare to remove the unopposed dark-squared bishop on [e3].} 14. Kd2 {[%csl Rc2,Re4] Naturally White would like to be able to recapture on [d3], if required, with the bishop from [f1].} Qxd3+ $1 ({Black must remove the queens so. Please don't become too ambitious and go} 14... Bf5 $4 {, which after} 15. Bc5+ Kf6 16. Qd6+ Be6 17. Bd3 {was already winning for White in Speelman-Bielczyk, Valetta 1980.}) 15. Bxd3 Nxe3 ({And this is the right piece to capture. After} 15... Nxa1 $4 16. Nxa8 {only one knight would be getting out of the corner, and it isn't Black's.}) 16. Nxa8 {Accepting what is essentially an exchange sacrifice must be critical.} Nd5 $1 {[%csl Ga8]} ({A key retreat, trapping the knight's counterpart in the corner. A combination of that and Black's extra pawn should ensure there's enough compensation for the exchange. Note too that these days,} 16... Nxg2 $2 {no longer seems as good:} 17. Rhc1 $1 {favours White after} Nh6 18. Rc7+ Kf6 19. Nb6 {and 17...Nf6 18.Rc7+ Kd6 19.Rac1 .}) 17. Rac1 {Trying to extricate the knight via [c7].} Ngf6 {[%csl Ga8,Gd2][%cal Gh8d8] Just like with the other rook on [c1], Black gets ready to win material after ...[Rd8].} 18. Nc7 $1 {The knight should try to make it out whilst it can.} Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gb4a2,Gh8d8]} (18... Nb4 {Consistent with our approach against Rhc1, and do note that now} 19. Rc4 Nxd3 20. Kxd3 Bd7 21. Rhc1 Bc6 {would transpose to a position we analysed via that other move order.}) ({Here, with the rook still on h1, Black can also consider} 18... Nf4 $5 {, but we're quite happy with the text move, threatening ...[Rd8] while also giving Black ideas of ... [Nxa2] and ...[Nxd3].}) 19. a3 {[%cal Ra3b4] In practice White has usually elected to force the pace.} Nxd3 $5 {[%csl Gc7,Gd2][%cal Gc8d7,Gd7c6]} ({(This simple exchange once again sets the most problems for White the king is now exposed and ...Bd7-c6 very much an idea, although it should be said that Black is also fine, if you prefer, after)} 19... Nc6 20. Nxa6 Nd4 21. Nc5 b6 {, followed by regaining the exchange via ...[Nb3]+, which should lead to a draw.}) 20. Kxd3 Bd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7c6,Gh8c8,Gh8d8,Ge7d6] This paves the way for ...[Bc6], while enabling the rook to go to [c8] as well as [d8]. There's even an immediate threat in the piece-winning ...[Kd6] followed by ... [Bc6] or ...[Rc8].} 21. Rc5 Rd8 $5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd7c6]} ({Angling for more than} 21... Bc6 22. Rxc6 bxc6 23. Nxa6 {. Black gets ready to play ...[Bc6] with check and, of course, the e-pawn is taboo .}) {Rxe5?? Kd6} 22. Ke2 Bc6 {[%csl Gc7,Gg2][%cal Ge7d6]} (22... Bc6 {Eyeing g2 while threatening ...Kd6 and now} 23. Rxc6 bxc6 24. Nxa6 Nd5 {would lead to a familiar type of scenario, where Black will look to quickly expand in the centre through ...[f5] and ...[e4], or even cause trouble with ... [Nf4]+.}) 23. Nxa6 Nd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5f4] Once again, the trickiest try, threatening ...[Nf4]+, a check which it's far from easy for White to meet, hence why he needs to either find the text or return the exchange on [c6].} 24. g3 $1 Nc3+ $1 {[%csl Ge2,Gh1] Exploiting the suddenly loose piece on [h1] to regain the exchange.} 25. Rxc3 Bxh1 {[%cal Ge7e6]} (25... Bxh1 {An unbalanced if '0.00' endgame has arisen. White can save the knight, but after} 26. Nc5 Bc6 {or 26.Nb4 Ke6 (there's always 27.f3 e4 , if needed, to save the bishop, Black has everything under control and will look to advance in the centre and gradually exploit having the more long-range minor piece.)}) *

