1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Lowenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Rc1 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Rc2c3] White's main move and the one which traditionally you would expect from a theoretically-inclined opponent.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4d1]} ({With the rook on a8 still hanging and c2-c3 also now a sizeable threat, Black absolutely must force the pace. In contrast,} 13... Rb8 $2 14. c3 Bg4 15. Qd2 $1 {badly fails to cut the mustard.}) 14. Qd3 {[%csl Ra8,Re4] Invariably played as White offers a queen exchange, hoping to then rescue the knight and begin to exploit having the bishop-pair.} Qxd3 {As the rook still hangs, this is a second pretty much forced move for Black in a row.} 15. cxd3 $6 {This is likely to be the choice of an opponent worried about their knight, although after...} Rd8 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd8d4,Ge7d6] ...The Knight actually isn't going anywhere. Not only has Black taken [d5] under control, but the rook can recapture on [d4] in the event of any rather misguided exchange there from White, and there's an actual threat: ...[Kd6] and only then ...[Rc8].} 16. h3 {[%csl Rg4]} Bf5 $5 {[%cal Ge7d6]} ({A provocative idea. If you'd like to be a little more solid then} 16... Bd7 17. Nd5+ Kd6 {can be recommended, followed by 18...[Bc6] with equality.}) 17. g4 {We've followed Fedorowicz-Arnason, New York 1980, where Black was a little too ambitious by dropping back to [g6].} Bd7 $1 {[%cal Ge7d6] Renewing the idea of ...[Kd6].} 18. Bg2 Kd6 {[%cal Gd7c6,Gg8e7,Ge5d4] Now Black is all set to complete development with 19...[Ne7], then round up the white knight after 20...[Rc8] or even 20...[Bc6].} (18... Kd6 {There's also absolutely nothing to fear in} 19. Bxd4 exd4 20. Nd5 Bc6 {, so perhaps White would be greedy.}) 19. Bxb7 $5 Rb8 {[%csl Gb2,Gb7] Black will regain the pawn on [b2], thereby remaining active enough in an unclear if likely roughly level scenario. That is, unless White becomes too greedy.} 20. Bxa6 $2 Bc6 {[%cal Gd6c7,Gc6h1]} (20... Bc6 {All of a sudden White is in serious trouble and must seemingly find} 21. f4 $1 {to avoid losing pretty much immediately. However, after} Kxc7 22. fxe5 Nf3+ {Black maintains a large advantage.}) *

