cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Rc1 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Rc2c3] White's main move and the one which traditionally you would expect from a theoretically-inclined opponent.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4d1]} ({With the rook on a8 still hanging and c2-c3 also now a sizeable threat, Black absolutely must force the pace. In contrast,} 13... Rb8 $2 14. c3 Bg4 15. Qd2 $1 {badly fails to cut the mustard.}) 14. Qd3 {[%csl Ra8,Re4] Invariably played as White offers a queen exchange, hoping to then rescue the knight and begin to exploit having the bishop-pair.} Qxd3 {As the rook still hangs, this is a second pretty much forced move for Black in a row.} 15. Bxd3 $1 {White realises that the advanced knight can't be rounded up.} Rd8 {[%csl Gc7,Gd5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd8d7]} (15... Rd8 {Once again the right square for the rook, keeping the white knight stuck on c7. Black isn't now quite threatening} 16. Z0 Kd6 {due to} 17. c3 {, and if} Nc6 18. Bb6 {, but 16...Nf6 (will complete development, while threatening to trap the knight with 17...[Rd7] the rook on [h8] now covers [a8].)}) 16. f3 ({This is an inferior version of} 16. h3 {, since now any subsequent [f3]-[f4] will cost a tempo and leave White without control of [g4], unless [h2]-[h3] is played after all.}) 16... Bh5 $1 {[%cal Ge7d6]} ({The best retreat, whereas} 16... Bc8 {would allow White a fairly pleasant choice of} 17. f4 {and 17.Kf2 followed by [Rhd1], both of which should lead to an edge. Placing the bishop on [h5] also makes ...[Kd6] a definite threat and note too how 17.c3? Nxf3+! would now not be at all wise for White.}) 17. Be4 $5 Nf6 $1 {[%csl Gb7,Gd5][%cal Ge7d6,Gd8d7] Black's simplest choice, regaining control of [d5] and so threatening ...[Kd6] or ...[Rd7] after all.} ({It should be said that} 17... f5 $2 {sees the tactics working in White's favour after} 18. Bxb7 Rd7 19. Nd5+ {, but 17...Kd6!? is quite playable, and if 18.Bxd4 exd4 19.Nd5 f5 20.Nf4 fxe4 21.Nxh5 with rough equality.}) ({Of course, after} 17... Nf6 {the b-pawn is taboo Bxb7?? Rd7 , so White is likely to try to clear the d-file.}) 18. c3 {[%csl Rd4]} Nxe4 (18... Nxe4 {Depriving White of the bishop-pair, while hoping to land a small tactic in the event of} 19. fxe4 $6 Nc2+ {.}) 19. cxd4 $1 (19. fxe4 $6 Nc2+ $1 {Of course, the knight can't be touched due to the potentially loose rook on [h1].} 20. Kf2 Nxe3 21. Kxe3 f5 $5 {although it should be said that after the calmer 21...[Kd6] Black was eventually able to make use of having the superior minor piece in the rating upset that was Alexikov-Matviychuk, Alushta 2007.}) {This highly aggressive move fights against both the white knight and king and enables Black to meet Nd5+ with Ke6 ,} 19... exd4 {[%cal Gd4e3] The position remains sharp, but with Black calling the shots and White the side having to play accurately to maintain the balance.} 20. Bf4 {This position has still only had the one recorded over-the-board test, Tomkins-B.Ferguson, Seattle 1984.} g5 $1 {[%cal Gg5f4]} ({This idea from Markland and Harding's 1982 book Sicilian: Lines with e5 pre-dates and improves over the} 20... Nf6 21. Kd2 {of that game. Black keeps the threats going.}) 21. fxe4 gxf4 {With equality according to Harding and Markland, a view which shouldn't be too hard to appreciate. Black has some handy trumps and has avoided allowing White an initiative down the e-file, but the position may now fizzle out.} (21... gxf4 {A likely sequence runs} 22. Nd5+ Kd6 {((Sensible, although 22...Rxd5!? 23.exd5 Bg6 , relying on the passed d-pawn, would definitely be a try if you really wanted to unbalance things.))} 23. Nxf4 Bg6 24. Nxg6 hxg6 {Black will be quick to pressure [e4] with ...[Rh4] and/or ...[Rde8] and may even get in ...[f5], hoping that the [d4]-pawn will prove its worth one day in the endgame. With care, White can defend and justify the engines' '0.00' assessment, but in practice Black certainly couldn't complain.}) *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1D) 8.Qd1 with 13.Rc1"]
[Black "8.Qd1 with 13.Rc1 Bg4 14.Qd3 #3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "42"]
[GameId "2141525853496501"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Lowenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Rc1 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Rc2c3] White's main move and the one which traditionally you would expect from a theoretically-inclined opponent.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4d1]} ({With the rook on a8 still hanging and c2-c3 also now a sizeable threat, Black absolutely must force the pace. In contrast,} 13... Rb8 $2 14. c3 Bg4 15. Qd2 $1 {badly fails to cut the mustard.}) 14. Qd3 {[%csl Ra8,Re4] Invariably played as White offers a queen exchange, hoping to then rescue the knight and begin to exploit having the bishop-pair.} Qxd3 {As the rook still hangs, this is a second pretty much forced move for Black in a row.} 15. Bxd3 $1 {White realises that the advanced knight can't be rounded up.} Rd8 {[%csl Gc7,Gd5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd8d7]} (15... Rd8 {Once again the right square for the rook, keeping the white knight stuck on c7. Black isn't now quite threatening} 16. Z0 Kd6 {due to} 17. c3 {, and if} Nc6 18. Bb6 {, but 16...Nf6 (will complete development, while threatening to trap the knight with 17...[Rd7] the rook on [h8] now covers [a8].)}) 16. f3 ({This is an inferior version of} 16. h3 {, since now any subsequent [f3]-[f4] will cost a tempo and leave White without control of [g4], unless [h2]-[h3] is played after all.}) 16... Bh5 $1 {[%cal Ge7d6]} ({The best retreat, whereas} 16... Bc8 {would allow White a fairly pleasant choice of} 17. f4 {and 17.Kf2 followed by [Rhd1], both of which should lead to an edge. Placing the bishop on [h5] also makes ...[Kd6] a definite threat and note too how 17.c3? Nxf3+! would now not be at all wise for White.}) 17. Kf2 {[%cal Rc2c3] Now that ...[Nxf3]+ won't come with check, [c2]-[c3] is a definite threat.} Nf6 $1 {[%cal Ge7d6,Gd8d7]} ({Development counts. Black gets ready to go ...Kd6 or ...Rd7 and this is a somewhat superior option to} 17... Kd6 $2 18. c3 {when the rook on [c1] turns out not to be too badly placed after all.}) 18. Rcd1 Rd7 {[%cal Gd7c7]} 19. Rhe1 $1 {[%csl Rd4] A typically cunning and tactical engine defence.} Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c7] Even here Black cannot be unhappy and deploys the final piece to try and win the white knight after all.} 20. Bxd4 Rxd4 21. c3 {[%csl Rd4]} Rdd8 {[%csl Gc7]} (21... Rdd8 {Now} 22. g4 $2 {runs into} Nxg4+ $1 23. fxg4 Bxg4 {when Black will win material, while even White's best option and the resulting unbalanced endgame should not be feared.}) (21... Rdd8 {For example,} 22. Nxa6 bxa6 23. Rxe5+ Kd6 $1 {((Bringing the king over to help fight against the white pawns and now Black will even meet 24.Ra5 with 24...Kc7 , looking to then cause trouble down the d-file.))} 24. Ree1 $5 Kc7 25. Bxa6 Rxd1 {Liquidating so is the simplest way to maintain control.} 26. Rxd1 Ra8 27. Bc4 Ne4+ $1 {Exploiting the pin to reroute the knight to [d6]. White has three good pawns for the piece and the engines declare their beloved '0.00', but in practice it should be easier for Black to cause problems with the extra piece than it will be for White to safely advance the pawns.}) *

