l Gg4d1]} ({With the rook on a8 still hanging and c2-c3 also now a sizeable threat, Black absolutely must force the pace. In contrast,} 13... Rb8 $2 14. c3 Bg4 15. Qd2 $1 {badly fails to cut the mustard.}) 14. Qd3 {[%csl Ra8,Re4] Invariably played as White offers a queen exchange, hoping to then rescue the knight and begin to exploit having the bishop-pair.} Qxd3 {As the rook still hangs, this is a second pretty much forced move for Black in a row.} 15. Bxd3 $1 {White realises that the advanced knight can't be rounded up.} Rd8 {[%csl Gc7,Gd5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd8d7]} (15... Rd8 {Once again the right square for the rook, keeping the white knight stuck on c7. Black isn't now quite threatening} 16. Z0 Kd6 {due to} 17. c3 {, and if} Nc6 18. Bb6 {, but 16...Nf6 (will complete development, while threatening to trap the knight with 17...[Rd7] the rook on [h8] now covers [a8].)}) 16. f3 ({This is an inferior version of} 16. h3 {, since now any subsequent [f3]-[f4] will cost a tempo and leave White without control of [g4], unless [h2]-[h3] is played after all.}) 16... Bh5 $1 {[%cal Ge7d6]} ({The best retreat, whereas} 16... Bc8 {would allow White a fairly pleasant choice of} 17. f4 {and 17.Kf2 followed by [Rhd1], both of which should lead to an edge. Placing the bishop on [h5] also makes ...[Kd6] a definite threat and note too how 17.c3? Nxf3+! would now not be at all wise for White.}) 17. Kf2 {[%cal Rc2c3] Now that ...[Nxf3]+ won't come with check, [c2]-[c3] is a definite threat.} Nf6 $1 {[%cal Ge7d6,Gd8d7]} ({Development counts. Black gets ready to go ...Kd6 or ...Rd7 and this is a somewhat superior option to} 17... Kd6 $2 18. c3 {when the rook on [c1] turns out not to be too badly placed after all.}) 18. Rhd1 $6 {A little risky.} Rd7 {[%cal Gd7c7] Trapping the knight.} 19. c3 {[%csl Rd4]} Nxf3 $1 {[%cal Gd7c7,Gf3h2,Gf6g4] Selling the black knight as dearly as possible.} 20. Bc5+ Kd8 (20... Kd8 {Now} 21. gxf3 Kxc7 {would just leave Black a pawn up, but better that for White than