l Gg4d1]} ({With the rook on a8 still hanging and c2-c3 also now a sizeable threat, Black absolutely must force the pace. In contrast,} 13... Rb8 $2 14. c3 Bg4 15. Qd2 $1 {badly fails to cut the mustard.}) 14. Qd3 {[%csl Ra8,Re4] Invariably played as White offers a queen exchange, hoping to then rescue the knight and begin to exploit having the bishop-pair.} Qxd3 {As the rook still hangs, this is a second pretty much forced move for Black in a row.} 15. Bxd3 $1 {White realises that the advanced knight can't be rounded up.} Rd8 {[%csl Gc7,Gd5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd8d7]} (15... Rd8 {Once again the right square for the rook, keeping the white knight stuck on c7. Black isn't now quite threatening} 16. Z0 Kd6 {due to} 17. c3 {, and if} Nc6 18. Bb6 {, but 16...Nf6 (will complete development, while threatening to trap the knight with 17...[Rd7] the rook on [h8] now covers [a8].)}) 16. f3 ({This is an inferior version of} 16. h3 {, since now any subsequent [f3]-[f4] will cost a tempo and leave White without control of [g4], unless [h2]-[h3] is played after all.}) 16... Bh5 $1 {[%cal Ge7d6]} ({The best retreat, whereas} 16... Bc8 {would allow White a fairly pleasant choice of} 17. f4 {and 17.Kf2 followed by [Rhd1], both of which should lead to an edge. Placing the bishop on [h5] also makes ...[Kd6] a definite threat and note too how 17.c3? Nxf3+! would now not be at all wise for White.}) 17. Bc4 {[%cal Gc7d5]} Nf6 $5 {[%cal Ge7d6]} ({(Striving for the maximum and threatening ...Kd6. A safe and fractionally superior according to the engines alternative is)} 17... Kd6 18. Nd5 Ne7 19. Nxe7 Kxe7 {when Black is very solidly placed, while also ready to go both ...[Bg6] and ...[b5].}) 18. c3 {[%csl Rd4]} Nxf3+ $1 {A fairly standard motif, the knights sacrifices itself as dearly as possible.} 19. gxf3 Kd6 {[%cal Gd6c7,Gd6c6]} (19... Kd6 {With a simple threat and note too how now} 20. Bb6 $6 {would be met by} Kc6 21. Ba5 b6 {to regain the piece after all.}) 20. Nxa6 $1 {White imitates Black and gives up the piece in the most disruptive way.} bxa6 {[%cal Gh5f3,Gf6d5] Talk about a messy position, and with queens off the board! Black is fairly happy to trade [a6] for [f3] and as well as 21...[Bxf3], 21...[Nd5] may well be a useful resource.} 21. Rg1 Bxf3 22. Rxg7 Nd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e3,Gf7f5,Gf3d5] (Staying active and counterattacking against the bishop on e3. Now the f-pawn may advance and 23.Bxd5 Bxd5 would, of course, save it, and all three results look very possible. That's at least certainly the case over-the-board, while from here a high-level email game, Badolati-Salcedo Mederos, correspondence 2008, landed up as a draw.)} *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1D) 8.Qd1 with 13.Rc1"]
[Black "8.Qd1 with 13.Rc1 Bg4 14.Qd3 #6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "34"]
[GameId "2141525853611192"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Lowenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Rc1 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Rc2c3] White's main move and the one which traditionally you would expect from a theoretically-inclined opponent.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4d1]} ({With the rook on a8 still hanging and c2-c3 also now a sizeable threat, Black absolutely must force the pace. In contrast,} 13... Rb8 $2 14. c3 Bg4 15. Qd2 $1 {badly fails to cut the mustard.}) 14. Qd3 {[%csl Ra8,Re4] Invariably played as White offers a queen exchange, hoping to then rescue the knight and begin to exploit having the bishop-pair.} Qxd3 {As the rook still hangs, this is a second pretty much forced move for Black in a row.} 15. Bxd3 $1 {White realises that the advanced knight can't be rounded up.} Rd8 {[%csl Gc7,Gd5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd8d7]} (15... Rd8 {Once again the right square for the rook, keeping the white knight stuck on c7. Black isn't now quite threatening} 16. Z0 Kd6 {due to} 17. c3 {, and if} Nc6 18. Bb6 {, but 16...Nf6 (will complete development, while threatening to trap the knight with 17...[Rd7] the rook on [h8] now covers [a8].)}) 16. Be4 $2 {[%cal Rc7d5]} Nf6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gf6e4] Attacking the bishop while taking control of [d5] already leaves White in some trouble.} 17. Bxb7 $2 (17. Bg5 Kd6 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Nd5 f5 {would be very good for Black.}) 17... Rd7 {[%cal Gd7c7,Gd7b7] The skewer nets a whole piece.} *

