l Gg4d1]} ({With the rook on a8 still hanging and c2-c3 also now a sizeable threat, Black absolutely must force the pace. In contrast,} 13... Rb8 $2 14. c3 Bg4 15. Qd2 $1 {badly fails to cut the mustard.}) 14. Qd3 {[%csl Ra8,Re4] Invariably played as White offers a queen exchange, hoping to then rescue the knight and begin to exploit having the bishop-pair.} Qxd3 {As the rook still hangs, this is a second pretty much forced move for Black in a row.} 15. Bxd3 $1 {White realises that the advanced knight can't be rounded up.} Rd8 {[%csl Gc7,Gd5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd8d7]} (15... Rd8 {Once again the right square for the rook, keeping the white knight stuck on c7. Black isn't now quite threatening} 16. Z0 Kd6 {due to} 17. c3 {, and if} Nc6 18. Bb6 {, but 16...Nf6 (will complete development, while threatening to trap the knight with 17...[Rd7] the rook on [h8] now covers [a8].)}) 16. c4 (16. c4 {A better way for White than 16.Be4 of taking control of d5, while trying to lure Black into} Nf3+ $2 17. gxf3 Bxf3 {. The problem is that} 18. Nd5+ $1 Rxd5 19. cxd5 Bxh1 20. Rc7+ {gives White far too strong an initiative.}) 16... Nf6 {[%csl Gd5] Black typically fights for the key [d5] point.} 17. Bg5 Be6 $1 {[%cal Gd4f3,Gd8d7] A simple approach, continuing to cover d5 ( 17...Kd6!? 18.Bxf6 gxf6 19.Nd5 Be6 may also be OK, but the tempting 17...Nf3+?! 18.gxf3 Bxf3 doesn't seem completely convincing after 19.Nd5+ Rxd5 20.cxd5 Bxh1 21.Rc7+ ) . Black now threatens ... [Nf3]+, as well as ...[Rd7].} 18. Be4 Rd7 $1 {[%cal Gd4e6,Gd7c7] This doesn't win a piece, but is one of two good ways ( 18...h6!? is the other to force a fairly favourable transformation of the position. There are two important points.)} 19. Nxe6 Nxe6 {[%csl Ge4,Gg5]} (19... Nxe6 {The point and now} 20. Bh4 $4 g5 {would win a piece, so White's reply is fairly forced.}) 20. Bxf6+ Kxf6 {[%cal Gd7d4]} ({Simple chess, keeping the structure intact, although} 20... gxf6 21. O-O Rd2 {also seemed fine in Khachian-Zelcic, Cannes 1996.}) (20... Kxf6 {Black now threatens} 21. Z0 Rd4 {, and if} 22. Bxb7 $2 Nc5 {, threatening the bishop and also ...[Nd3]+. Note too that 21.Bd5? can be easily rebuffed by 21...Nf4 .}) 21. O-O b6 $5 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gh8d8,Gh8c8] Black doesn't need to rush to liquidate pawns on the queenside. Now ...[Rhd8] or ...[Rc8] will follow and Black should be happy to exchange at least one pair of rooks, looking to probe with the knight and/or on the queenside, while also enjoying the more active king.} *

