1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Lowenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Rc1 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Rc2c3] White's main move and the one which traditionally you would expect from a theoretically-inclined opponent.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4d1]} ({With the rook on a8 still hanging and c2-c3 also now a sizeable threat, Black absolutely must force the pace. In contrast,} 13... Rb8 $2 14. c3 Bg4 15. Qd2 $1 {badly fails to cut the mustard.}) 14. Qd3 {[%csl Ra8,Re4] Invariably played as White offers a queen exchange, hoping to then rescue the knight and begin to exploit having the bishop-pair.} Qxd3 {As the rook still hangs, this is a second pretty much forced move for Black in a row.} 15. Bxd3 $1 {White realises that the advanced knight can't be rounded up.} Rd8 {[%csl Gc7,Gd5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd8d7]} (15... Rd8 {Once again the right square for the rook, keeping the white knight stuck on c7. Black isn't now quite threatening} 16. Z0 Kd6 {due to} 17. c3 {, and if} Nc6 18. Bb6 {, but 16...Nf6 (will complete development, while threatening to trap the knight with 17...[Rd7] the rook on [h8] now covers [a8].)}) 16. f4 {This may look a little dangerous, but Black has a good reply, one well worth remembering.} Kd6 $1 {[%cal Gd6c7]} (16... Kd6 {Attacking the knight without delay and, of course,} 17. fxe5+ $2 Kxc7 {would just cost White a piece, as the rook on [d8] defends the knight on [d4].}) (16... Kd6 {But what about} 17. c3 {you might wonder? Well, the good news is that there are downsides to [f2]-[f4], two even.}) 17. c3 Nc6 $5 {[%cal Gd6c7]} ({Black's most uncompromising choice, continuing to go after the white knight. The safer option of} 17... Nf5 {(also takes advantage of a downside to [f2]-[f4] the now loose bishop on [e3], and after)} 18. Bxf5 Bxf5 19. Nd5 $5 Nf6 {the position is likely to liquidate down to a roughly level opposite-coloured bishop scenario.}) 18. Bb6 {A fairly forced move unless White just wants to lose a piece, but now the pawn on [f4] is hanging.} exf4 19. O-O Nf6 $1 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Gc6e5]} (19... Nf6 {Development counts and is somewhat more important than trying to defend the extra pawn on f4. Black now threatens 20...Ne5, hitting the bishop on d3 and facilitating the piece-winning ...Kc6, while the control of d1 is pretty useful and something which} 20. h3 Bh5 {would retain.}) (19... Nf6 {Note too that} 20. Rxf4 $6 Ke5 {(would force White to give up the exchange the bishop on [d3] also hangs for some but probably not quite enough compensation.)}) 20. c4 {[%cal Rc7d5] This prepared to extricate the knight and seize the initiative with 21. [Nd5] in Yankovsky-Collins, Berkeley 2011.} (20. c4 {There was nothing then wrong with the strong Irish IM's choice of} Ne5 {, but Black might also have continued in a pretty aggressive vein.}) 20... Nb4 $5 {[%csl Ga2][%cal Gb4d3,Gd6c6]} (20... Nb4 {Hitting the bishop as well as the a-pawn, while also clearing the way for ...Kc6. Now} 21. Bb1 Kc6 22. Ba5 {(( 22.c5 Rd4! would defend the extra pawn on [d4]. ))} Nd3 23. Bxd3 Rxd3 {seems fine for Black, something which is also the case if White, in turn, is more ambitious.}) 21. c5+ $5 Kc6 {[%cal Gd8d4,Gb4d3]} 22. Bc4 Rd4 $5 {[%csl Gc7,Gf4][%cal Gb4d3,Gh8c8] The position is quite sharp, but to us and the engines the black king seems safe enough. They indicate that White should be OK, but with [f4] now covered and Black threatening both ...[Rc8] and ...[Nd3], we would certainly prefer to be in the second player's shoes.} *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
