l Gg4d1]} ({With the rook on a8 still hanging and c2-c3 also now a sizeable threat, Black absolutely must force the pace. In contrast,} 13... Rb8 $2 14. c3 Bg4 15. Qd2 $1 {badly fails to cut the mustard.}) 14. Qd3 {[%csl Ra8,Re4] Invariably played as White offers a queen exchange, hoping to then rescue the knight and begin to exploit having the bishop-pair.} Qxd3 {As the rook still hangs, this is a second pretty much forced move for Black in a row.} 15. Bxd3 $1 {White realises that the advanced knight can't be rounded up.} Rd8 {[%csl Gc7,Gd5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd8d7]} (15... Rd8 {Once again the right square for the rook, keeping the white knight stuck on c7. Black isn't now quite threatening} 16. Z0 Kd6 {due to} 17. c3 {, and if} Nc6 18. Bb6 {, but 16...Nf6 (will complete development, while threatening to trap the knight with 17...[Rd7] the rook on [h8] now covers [a8].)}) 16. h3 {[%csl Rg4] White's best and most common move, forcing the black bishop to make a big decision.} Bh5 $1 {[%cal Gg8f6,Ge7d6] The best square for the bishop, maintaining control of [e2] and [d1].} ({Over the years Richard has spent a fair amount of time looking at} 16... Bc8 $6 {, which is tricky, but objectively} 17. f4 $1 Kd6 $6 18. Na8 $1 {should just be very good for White. The text move leaves Black set to complete development with 17...[Nf6], as well as most certainly still with ideas of a timely ...[Kd6].}) 17. O-O $6 Kd6 $1 {[%cal Gd6c7] An alert move. Once again, Black is now in a position to exploit the downside to [c2]-[c3].} 18. c3 Nf3+ $1 {This is it, shredding White's structure.} 19. gxf3 Kxc7 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Gd8d3,Gg8f6,Gg8e7,Gf7f5] With ...[Rxd3] threatened, [f3] also weak and Black all set to complete development with either ...[Nf6] or ...[Ne7] and ...[f5], White was surely at least slightly worse in Goumas-Migot, Heraklion 2017.} *

