l Gg4d1]} ({With the rook on a8 still hanging and c2-c3 also now a sizeable threat, Black absolutely must force the pace. In contrast,} 13... Rb8 $2 14. c3 Bg4 15. Qd2 $1 {badly fails to cut the mustard.}) 14. Qd3 {[%csl Ra8,Re4] Invariably played as White offers a queen exchange, hoping to then rescue the knight and begin to exploit having the bishop-pair.} Qxd3 {As the rook still hangs, this is a second pretty much forced move for Black in a row.} 15. Bxd3 $1 {White realises that the advanced knight can't be rounded up.} Rd8 {[%csl Gc7,Gd5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd8d7]} (15... Rd8 {Once again the right square for the rook, keeping the white knight stuck on c7. Black isn't now quite threatening} 16. Z0 Kd6 {due to} 17. c3 {, and if} Nc6 18. Bb6 {, but 16...Nf6 (will complete development, while threatening to trap the knight with 17...[Rd7] the rook on [h8] now covers [a8].)}) 16. h3 {[%csl Rg4] White's best and most common move, forcing the black bishop to make a big decision.} Bh5 $1 {[%cal Gg8f6,Ge7d6] The best square for the bishop, maintaining control of [e2] and [d1].} ({Over the years Richard has spent a fair amount of time looking at} 16... Bc8 $6 {, which is tricky, but objectively} 17. f4 $1 Kd6 $6 18. Na8 $1 {should just be very good for White. The text move leaves Black set to complete development with 17...[Nf6], as well as most certainly still with ideas of a timely ...[Kd6].}) 17. Be4 $2 Nf6 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ge7d6] (Going after the bishop and also the knight on c7 ...Kd6 is threatened and 18.Bxb7? Rd7 would win a piece.)} 18. Bg5 Kd6 $1 {[%cal Gd6c7] Forcing the pace. White can save the knight, but Black should welcome the upcoming dynamism granted by the doubled f-pawns.} 19. Bxf6 gxf6 {[%cal Gd6c7]} 20. Nd5 f5 {[%cal Gf5e4] Already putting the Sveshnikov style pawns to good use, and now White has only one good way not to lose a piece.} 21. Nf6 $1 Bg6 $1 {[%cal Gf5e4,Gd6e6] Maintaining a key piece, while threatening both ...[Ke6] and ...[fxe4].} 22. Bxb7 $1 {Fearless play from White and, again, the only move not to lose a piece.} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gb8b7,Gb8b2]} ({Instead,} 22... Ke6 $2 23. c3 {wouldn't actually be too clear, but now Black will either get to take on [b7] or [b2]. Meanwhile the knight on [f6] remains in some trouble and Black went on to convert this clearly better position in Semenov-Taksrud, correspondence 1988.}) *

