l Gg4d1]} ({With the rook on a8 still hanging and c2-c3 also now a sizeable threat, Black absolutely must force the pace. In contrast,} 13... Rb8 $2 14. c3 Bg4 15. Qd2 $1 {badly fails to cut the mustard.}) 14. Qd3 {[%csl Ra8,Re4] Invariably played as White offers a queen exchange, hoping to then rescue the knight and begin to exploit having the bishop-pair.} Qxd3 {As the rook still hangs, this is a second pretty much forced move for Black in a row.} 15. Bxd3 $1 {White realises that the advanced knight can't be rounded up.} Rd8 {[%csl Gc7,Gd5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd8d7]} (15... Rd8 {Once again the right square for the rook, keeping the white knight stuck on c7. Black isn't now quite threatening} 16. Z0 Kd6 {due to} 17. c3 {, and if} Nc6 18. Bb6 {, but 16...Nf6 (will complete development, while threatening to trap the knight with 17...[Rd7] the rook on [h8] now covers [a8].)}) 16. h3 {[%csl Rg4] White's best and most common move, forcing the black bishop to make a big decision.} Bh5 $1 {[%cal Gg8f6,Ge7d6] The best square for the bishop, maintaining control of [e2] and [d1].} ({Over the years Richard has spent a fair amount of time looking at} 16... Bc8 $6 {, which is tricky, but objectively} 17. f4 $1 Kd6 $6 18. Na8 $1 {should just be very good for White. The text move leaves Black set to complete development with 17...[Nf6], as well as most certainly still with ideas of a timely ...[Kd6].}) 17. c4 $6 Nf6 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd4f3]} ({Straightforward and fairly strong. Black takes control of d5 and only now wants to go ...Nf3+, in contrast to} 17... Nf3+ $6 {, which isn't clear at all after the fearless} 18. Ke2 $1 {.}) (17... Nf6 {Here the engines already wonder if ditching a whole pawn with} 18. Nd5+ $5 Nxd5 19. cxd5 Rxd5 {might not be White's best defensive try, which speaks volumes and also feels like something Black cannot be unhappy with} ({Rc7+} 19... Rd7 {keeps control.})) 18. g4 $5 Bg6 {[%csl Gd3]} 19. Bxg6 hxg6 {[%cal Gd8c8,Gf6g4] Threatening ...[Rc8], as well as ...[Nxg4].} 20. g5 Ne4 {[%cal Ge4c5,Gd4f5] Black's knights begin to weave their magic. Already ... [Nc5] may cause White trouble on [d3] and there's also ...[Nf5], calmly going after the weak pawn on [g5].} 21. Nd5+ {This check was tried in Bessenyei-Forgo, correspondence 1991, where the black king went to [d7], but it might also have advanced:} Ke6 $1 {[%csl Gg5,Gh8][%cal Ge4g5]} (21... Ke6 {Whether or not White goes in for} 22. Bxd4 exd4 {, Black is surely clearly for choice.}) (21... Ke6 {Observe not only how weak g5 is, but that ...Nxg5 is already a threat and that} 22. h4 {would run into} Rxh4 $1 {.}) *

