l Gg4d1]} ({With the rook on a8 still hanging and c2-c3 also now a sizeable threat, Black absolutely must force the pace. In contrast,} 13... Rb8 $2 14. c3 Bg4 15. Qd2 $1 {badly fails to cut the mustard.}) 14. Qd3 {[%csl Ra8,Re4] Invariably played as White offers a queen exchange, hoping to then rescue the knight and begin to exploit having the bishop-pair.} Qxd3 {As the rook still hangs, this is a second pretty much forced move for Black in a row.} 15. Bxd3 $1 {White realises that the advanced knight can't be rounded up.} Rd8 {[%csl Gc7,Gd5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd8d7]} (15... Rd8 {Once again the right square for the rook, keeping the white knight stuck on c7. Black isn't now quite threatening} 16. Z0 Kd6 {due to} 17. c3 {, and if} Nc6 18. Bb6 {, but 16...Nf6 (will complete development, while threatening to trap the knight with 17...[Rd7] the rook on [h8] now covers [a8].)}) 16. h3 {[%csl Rg4] White's best and most common move, forcing the black bishop to make a big decision.} Bh5 $1 {[%cal Gg8f6,Ge7d6] The best square for the bishop, maintaining control of [e2] and [d1].} ({Over the years Richard has spent a fair amount of time looking at} 16... Bc8 $6 {, which is tricky, but objectively} 17. f4 $1 Kd6 $6 18. Na8 $1 {should just be very good for White. The text move leaves Black set to complete development with 17...[Nf6], as well as most certainly still with ideas of a timely ...[Kd6].}) 17. f4 $1 {[%csl Re7,Rh5][%cal Rf4e5,Rg2g4] White's main move, undermining [e5] and rather going after the bishop on [h5]. Other moves even risk leaving White worse.} Kd6 $5 {[%cal Gd6c7] Black's most uncompromising choice, one ignored by top theoreticians John Nunn and Joe Gallagher way back in 1995 when they recommended 13. [Rc1] for White in the seminal work Beating the Sicilian 3.} ({The text is both more punchy and stronger than} 17... f6 $6 {when} 18. g4 Bf7 $5 {(( 18...Bg6 19.f5 Bf7 20.c3 is just very good for White))} 19. O-O $5 {appears to turn out somewhat in White's favour after} Kd6 20. Nxa6 bxa6 21. fxe5+ {.}) ({It should be said though that the text move isn't forced, with} 17... exf4 18. Bxf4 Bg6 {a solid and fairly dependable alternative.}) 18. Nxa6 {Selling the knight as dearly as possible has been White's usual choice and is a fairly important one.} bxa6 19. g4 Bg6 {[%cal Gg6d3] A second fairly forced move. Black is currently a piece ahead, but clearly White is set to regain it after entombing the bishop on [g6].} 20. f5 ({Regaining the piece. Note too that White can also go} 20. Bxd4 exd4 21. f5 {when we'll see} Ne7 {by transposition and a 20.f5 Ne7 21.Bxd4 exd4 move order.}) 20... Ne7 {[%cal Gg6f5,Ge7f5]} ({Forcing the pace is Black's simplest and arguably best move. Black has often gone in for} 20... Bxf5 $6 21. gxf5 Ne7 {, but then White has the initiative after} 22. Rd1 $1 {.}) ({It should be said that there's also} 20... Nf6 {, although then} 21. c3 $5 {may slightly favour White and, in any case, after much analysis we prefer the text move, threatening 21... [Nexf5].}) 21. fxg6 $5 {(This is likely a more critical more order or at least it pretty much forces Black to recapture with the h-pawn there's no great follow-up for Black after 21...Nxg6? 22.c3 ) .} hxg6 {[%csl Gh8][%cal Gd8b8,Ga6a5,Ge7d5] Involving the only unmoved piece. Black may now head forwards on the queenside after ...[Rb8] and/or ...[a5], as well as ...[Nd5].} 22. c3 Nd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e3] Black continues as actively as possible, trusting in the fine, centralised knight to offset White's upcoming extra pawn on [d4].} 23. Bxd4 exd4 24. cxd4 Rb8 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gd5b4] Threatening to remove a fairly important pawn on [b2].} 25. b3 (25. b3 {From here, White eventually ground out a win after} Nf4 $6 26. Kd2 $1 {in Reis-Salcedo Mederos, correspondence 2008, where there was no need to yet activate the knight.}) 25... Rbe8+ $1 {[%csl Ge1,Gh3][%cal Ge8e3] Tickling the white king and preparing to invade on [e3]. White can try to swap [h3] for [a6], but in any case Black will retain sufficient activity for the pawn.} (25... Rbe8+ {For example,} 26. Kd2 Re3 27. Bxa6 Ra8 $1 {It's also possible to chop on [h3], but this is an arguably simpler course.} 28. Bc4 Rxa2+ {Pretty much forcing White's next.} 29. Rc2 Rxc2+ {And a fairly forced response.} 30. Kxc2 f6 {Black's active pieces fully offset White's extra pawn.} 31. h4 Re4 {would now regain it, and in any case Black is all set to finally involve with ...[Nf4] or even ...[Nb4].}) *

