1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Lowenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Rc1 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Rc2c3] White's main move and the one which traditionally you would expect from a theoretically-inclined opponent.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4d1]} ({With the rook on a8 still hanging and c2-c3 also now a sizeable threat, Black absolutely must force the pace. In contrast,} 13... Rb8 $2 14. c3 Bg4 15. Qd2 $1 {badly fails to cut the mustard.}) 14. Qd3 {[%csl Ra8,Re4] Invariably played as White offers a queen exchange, hoping to then rescue the knight and begin to exploit having the bishop-pair.} Qxd3 {As the rook still hangs, this is a second pretty much forced move for Black in a row.} 15. Bxd3 $1 {White realises that the advanced knight can't be rounded up.} Rd8 {[%csl Gc7,Gd5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd8d7]} (15... Rd8 {Once again the right square for the rook, keeping the white knight stuck on c7. Black isn't now quite threatening} 16. Z0 Kd6 {due to} 17. c3 {, and if} Nc6 18. Bb6 {, but 16...Nf6 (will complete development, while threatening to trap the knight with 17...[Rd7] the rook on [h8] now covers [a8].)}) 16. h3 {[%csl Rg4] White's best and most common move, forcing the black bishop to make a big decision.} Bh5 $1 {[%cal Gg8f6,Ge7d6] The best square for the bishop, maintaining control of [e2] and [d1].} ({Over the years Richard has spent a fair amount of time looking at} 16... Bc8 $6 {, which is tricky, but objectively} 17. f4 $1 Kd6 $6 18. Na8 $1 {should just be very good for White. The text move leaves Black set to complete development with 17...[Nf6], as well as most certainly still with ideas of a timely ...[Kd6].}) 17. f4 $1 {[%csl Re7,Rh5][%cal Rf4e5,Rg2g4] White's main move, undermining [e5] and rather going after the bishop on [h5]. Other moves even risk leaving White worse.} Kd6 $5 {[%cal Gd6c7] Black's most uncompromising choice, one ignored by top theoreticians John Nunn and Joe Gallagher way back in 1995 when they recommended 13. [Rc1] for White in the seminal work Beating the Sicilian 3.} ({The text is both more punchy and stronger than} 17... f6 $6 {when} 18. g4 Bf7 $5 {(( 18...Bg6 19.f5 Bf7 20.c3 is just very good for White))} 19. O-O $5 {appears to turn out somewhat in White's favour after} Kd6 20. Nxa6 bxa6 21. fxe5+ {.}) ({It should be said though that the text move isn't forced, with} 17... exf4 18. Bxf4 Bg6 {a solid and fairly dependable alternative.}) 18. Nxa6 {Selling the knight as dearly as possible has been White's usual choice and is a fairly important one.} bxa6 19. g4 Bg6 {[%cal Gg6d3] A second fairly forced move. Black is currently a piece ahead, but clearly White is set to regain it after entombing the bishop on [g6].} 20. f5 ({Regaining the piece. Note too that White can also go} 20. Bxd4 exd4 21. f5 {when we'll see} Ne7 {by transposition and a 20.f5 Ne7 21.Bxd4 exd4 move order.}) 20... Ne7 {[%cal Gg6f5,Ge7f5]} ({Forcing the pace is Black's simplest and arguably best move. Black has often gone in for} 20... Bxf5 $6 21. gxf5 Ne7 {, but then White has the initiative after} 22. Rd1 $1 {.}) ({It should be said that there's also} 20... Nf6 {, although then} 21. c3 $5 {may slightly favour White and, in any case, after much analysis we prefer the text move, threatening 21... [Nexf5].}) 21. fxg6 $5 {(This is likely a more critical more order or at least it pretty much forces Black to recapture with the h-pawn there's no great follow-up for Black after 21...Nxg6? 22.c3 ) .} hxg6 {[%csl Gh8][%cal Gd8b8,Ga6a5,Ge7d5] Involving the only unmoved piece. Black may now head forwards on the queenside after ...[Rb8] and/or ...[a5], as well as ...[Nd5].} 22. Bxa6 {Bravely snatching this pawn must be critical.} Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8b2] (A better square than a8 here, since Black will now regain a pawn on b2 or a2 or even c2 if 23.Rb1? Nxc2+ ) .} 23. b3 Ra8 {[%csl Ga2,Ga6] The main point behind the little shuffle via [b8] is revealed.} 24. Bc4 Rxa2 {[%cal Ge7d5,Gd4c2] Not for the first time, we find the black knights pretty actively placed: [c2] is en prise and ...[Nd5] imminent.} 25. Bxd4 exd4 {[%cal Ge7d5]} 26. Bxf7 Nd5 $1 {A further pawn sacrifice, but we believe that Black's activity supplies sufficient counterplay and compensation. White's rooks are both pretty tied down and Black may increase the pressure not only with ...[Ne3], ...[Nf4] or ...[Nb4], but both ...[g5] and ...[Rc8].} (26... Nd5 27. Bxd5 Kxd5 28. Kd2 Rc8 {The engines display '0.00', largely because ...[Rc3] followed by ...[Rxb3] is imminent.}) (26... Nd5 {For example} 27. Bxg6 Nf4 28. Bf7 d3 $5 {(The pawn is clearly taboo due to the resulting knight fork and meanwhile Black is all set to pick off [h3] and/or [c2], leaving a draw looking very likely it's again '0. 00' in engine speak.)}) *

