} Kd6 20. Nxa6 bxa6 21. fxe5+ {.}) ({It should be said though that the text move isn't forced, with} 17... exf4 18. Bxf4 Bg6 {a solid and fairly dependable alternative.}) 18. Nxa6 {Selling the knight as dearly as possible has been White's usual choice and is a fairly important one.} bxa6 19. g4 Bg6 {[%cal Gg6d3] A second fairly forced move. Black is currently a piece ahead, but clearly White is set to regain it after entombing the bishop on [g6].} 20. f5 ({Regaining the piece. Note too that White can also go} 20. Bxd4 exd4 21. f5 {when we'll see} Ne7 {by transposition and a 20.f5 Ne7 21.Bxd4 exd4 move order.}) 20... Ne7 {[%cal Gg6f5,Ge7f5]} ({Forcing the pace is Black's simplest and arguably best move. Black has often gone in for} 20... Bxf5 $6 21. gxf5 Ne7 {, but then White has the initiative after} 22. Rd1 $1 {.}) ({It should be said that there's also} 20... Nf6 {, although then} 21. c3 $5 {may slightly favour White and, in any case, after much analysis we prefer the text move, threatening 21... [Nexf5].}) 21. Bxd4 exd4 {[%cal Ge7d5] With White able to desperado the bishop on [e5], there's nothing better than this simple recapture, after which Black may look to activate with ...[Nd5].} 22. fxg6 {Probably the most challenging move order.} Nxg6 {[%cal Gh8e8,Gh7h5,Gg6e5,Gg6f4,Gd6c5]} ({By no means the only recapture, but a simpler one than} 22... hxg6 {, which is though very much playable too and should be closely compared with our coverage of 21.fxg6 hxg6 , to which it may even transpose.}) ({After} 22... Nxg6 {Black is now ready to activate the knight via [f4] or [e5] and also has ideas of both ...[Rhe8] and ...[h5]. Note too that there's usually ...[Kc5] if needed to defend the d-pawn and that Black can hardly object to gaining pressure down the h-file after} 23. Bxg6 hxg6 {. Of course, the critical test must be if White annexes the en prise a-pawn.}) 23. Bxa6 $5 Ra8 {[%csl Ga2,Ga6] Attacking the bishop and looking to regain the pawn on [a2].} 24. Bc4 {[%csl Ra2]} Ne5 {[%csl Ga2,Gc4] Continuing to activate with gain of tempo.} 25. Bb3 h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5g4,Ge5f3] Black continues the active stance and while he is currently a pawn down, his activity fully makes up for it. The simple threat is ...[hxg4] and 26 [g5] runs into 26...[Nf3]+, while '0.00' is the ever-helpful engine view.} (25... h5 {For example,} 26. gxh5 Rxh5 {((Simply preparing to double rooks on the h-file and now 27.Kf2 Rah8 28.Kg2 leaves Black with at least 28...Rg5+. ) . )} 27. a4 $5 Kc5 {By no means the only decent move, but using the king to keep tabs on the a-pawn makes good sense.} 28. Ra1 Rah8 {There are some tempting alternatives involving trying to start some play against the white king, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with regaining the pawn so.} 29. a5 Rxh3 30. Rxh3 Rxh3 {Recreating the big threat on [h1].} 31. Kf2 f6 {This secures the knight on its fine central square. The rook can now shoot back via [h8] to [a8] and Black may also contemplate a timely ...[g5]. While the most likely result is a draw, it's far from implausible that Black will get to round up the a-pawn or create some serious threats as the kingside pawns advance.}) *

