l Gg4d1]} ({With the rook on a8 still hanging and c2-c3 also now a sizeable threat, Black absolutely must force the pace. In contrast,} 13... Rb8 $2 14. c3 Bg4 15. Qd2 $1 {badly fails to cut the mustard.}) 14. Qd3 {[%csl Ra8,Re4] Invariably played as White offers a queen exchange, hoping to then rescue the knight and begin to exploit having the bishop-pair.} Qxd3 {As the rook still hangs, this is a second pretty much forced move for Black in a row.} 15. Bxd3 $1 {White realises that the advanced knight can't be rounded up.} Rd8 {[%csl Gc7,Gd5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd8d7]} (15... Rd8 {Once again the right square for the rook, keeping the white knight stuck on c7. Black isn't now quite threatening} 16. Z0 Kd6 {due to} 17. c3 {, and if} Nc6 18. Bb6 {, but 16...Nf6 (will complete development, while threatening to trap the knight with 17...[Rd7] the rook on [h8] now covers [a8].)}) 16. h3 {[%csl Rg4] White's best and most common move, forcing the black bishop to make a big decision.} Bh5 $1 {[%cal Gg8f6,Ge7d6] The best square for the bishop, maintaining control of [e2] and [d1].} ({Over the years Richard has spent a fair amount of time looking at} 16... Bc8 $6 {, which is tricky, but objectively} 17. f4 $1 Kd6 $6 18. Na8 $1 {should just be very good for White. The text move leaves Black set to complete development with 17...[Nf6], as well as most certainly still with ideas of a timely ...[Kd6].}) 17. f4 $1 {[%csl Re7,Rh5][%cal Rf4e5,Rg2g4] White's main move, undermining [e5] and rather going after the bishop on [h5]. Other moves even risk leaving White worse.} exf4 18. Bxf4 Bg6 {[%cal Gg6d3,Gf7f6,Ge7f7,Gg8e7] The aforementioned solid option, one we figured we should perhaps supply some brief coverage of for those days when you're not up to plunging the board into chaos with 17...[Kd6]!?. Black threatens to destroy White's structure with an exchange on [d3], after which a plan of ...[f6], ...[Kf7] and ...[Ne7] might well continue to leave the white knight stranded on [c7].} 19. Bxg6 hxg6 {[%csl Gh8][%cal Gg8f6] And so the rook on [h8] becomes a factor without having had to move, while Black is all set to complete development with ...[Nf6], or even ...[f5] and ...[Nf6] to obtain an outpost on [e4].} 20. Kf2 $5 {[%cal Rh1e1]} Nf6 {[%cal Ge7d7,Gd7c6] Black should swiftly complete development here and may now look to run the king to safety via [d7] and [c6] not [c8] as then [Na8] may be irritating.} 21. Rhe1+ Kd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7c6,Gh8h4] Black is now ready to step off the open d-file with ...[Kc6], as well as activate with ...[Rh4], and this move was recommended by Richard back in Dangerous Weapons: The Sicilian, and has now had a test.} 22. c4 Rh4 $1 {[%csl Gf4,Gf6][%cal Gh4f4]} (22... Rh4 {Attacking the bishop while angling for} 23. Bg3 $4 Ne4+ {or 23.Bh2 Ng4+!? .}) 23. Be5 {[%cal Rc1d1]} Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gd7c8,Gc6e5] With the bishop on [e5] under fire, Black was able to retreat the king to [a8] and had fully equalised in Kermer-Stefanov, correspondence 2015.} *

