1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Lowenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Be2 $1 {This tricky counter-gambit was unknown back in 2006 when Richard first analysed the Löwenthal for his and John Emms book, Dangerous Weapons: The Sicilian. Three games played before that have turned up, but it took for Anish Giri to recommend the line last year in Lifetime Repertoires: Giri's 1. [e4] − Part 3, for it to become slightly trendy with well booked-up white players. It is still to fully catch on, if growing in popularity the position after 12...Ke7 occurred just 11 times on TWIC in 2023, with 13.Rc1 seen in six of those games and 13.Be2 in the other five. While it's hard to imagine an unprepared opponent wishing to gambit their g-pawn so, Black should very much be ready for this line and, at the time of writing, it's arguably the critical test of the main line Lowenthal with 9...[d5].As such, we'll cover not the usual one, but both defensive options for Black. One grabs a pawn then looks to defend; the other is riskier in the eyes of the engines and objectively good for White after much precision, while simply looking very unclear to human eyes.} Nxc2+ $6 {[%csl Ga1,Ge1,Ge3] Yes, this assessment is an objective one; from a practical perspective, especially at lower levels, the move arguably deserves to be denoted '!?', since White must now play pretty accurately to maintain the advantage. Perhaps even '!??!' or '?!!?' would be best! This is definitely the critical test of 13. [Be2] and has been Black's main choice in the limited practice with the line - it certainly forces white players to really know their stuff.} 14. Kf1 {[%csl Re7][%cal Re3c5]} (14. Kf1 {The rook on a1 is most certainly taboo here. Black cannot allow} Nxa1 15. Bc5+ Kf6 16. Ne8+ {, with a deadly initiative for White.}) 14... Nxe3+ $1 {[%csl Gd1,Gf1]} 15. fxe3 {[%csl Ra8,Re7]} (15. fxe3 {Here Black has a few moves, of which saving the rook with} Rb8 {is the safest try and after} 16. Qb3 $1 Be6 $1 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Rc1 {(White has promising play for the pawn '+1' in engine speak, unclear and messy too though the position looks to the human eye, with neither king especially happy. Black also has a more dramatic option.)}) 15... Bh3 $5 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Ga8d8] A hard move to assess: objectively we should again perhaps write '?!', but also '?!!?' might be the most accurate. It's certainly the move that you'd like to work, and might especially be a good try at blitz or bullet. Of course, an opponent with time to react is more likely to find the only sequence to keep White's nose clearly in front, although staying on that correct but narrow path is not so easy, as we'll now see.} 16. Nd5+ $1 Kf8 17. Bf3 {[%csl Rh3]} Qc4+ (17... Qc4+ {With the bishop hanging on h3, Black must keep forcing the pace, and now} 18. Kf2 $2 Qh4+ 19. g3 Qg5 20. Qb3 g6 $1 21. Qxb7 {(Kotturi-O.Belov, correspondence 2009)} Rd8 {leaves Black with the safer king and somewhat for choice. White can do better than that, though.}) 18. Kg1 $1 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Rd5b6]} Rd8 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Gf3][%cal Ge5e4] Introducing a powerful idea in the shape of ...[e4].} 19. gxh3 $2 e4 {[%csl Gd5,Gf3] Revealing Black's main idea, and the piece will now be won back.} 20. Rc1 Qxd5 21. Qxd5 Rxd5 {[%cal Gd5b5,Gd5d2] In this roughly level position, the rook is bound for [b5] or more likely [d2], and it transpires that Black doesn't need to fear a pin on the back rank.} 22. Rc8+ Ke7 23. Bxe4 Rd2 {[%csl Gg1,Gh1] Keeping White's own pieces bottled up.} 24. Kf1 {We've followed an over-the-board encounter, Garrido Outon-Orantes Taboada, Roquetas de Mar 2021, where White was rated 2379 and Black 2286, which should demonstrate that 13. [Be2] is far from a forced win for White in practice, +'0.8' or whatever though the engines may proclaim. Here Black elected to give up the exchange for some if perhaps not quite enough compensation after 24...[Nf6]!?. That's clearly a tempting, if also unnecessary, course of action.} b5 $1 25. Rg1 g6 {[%cal Gd2d8,Gg8f6] The material count is level and the engines display '0. 00', which isn't such a surprise when you consider that Black is about to go ...[Rd8] then ...[Nf6].} *

