most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Be2 $1 {This tricky counter-gambit was unknown back in 2006 when Richard first analysed the Löwenthal for his and John Emms book, Dangerous Weapons: The Sicilian. Three games played before that have turned up, but it took for Anish Giri to recommend the line last year in Lifetime Repertoires: Giri's 1. [e4] − Part 3, for it to become slightly trendy with well booked-up white players. It is still to fully catch on, if growing in popularity the position after 12...Ke7 occurred just 11 times on TWIC in 2023, with 13.Rc1 seen in six of those games and 13.Be2 in the other five. While it's hard to imagine an unprepared opponent wishing to gambit their g-pawn so, Black should very much be ready for this line and, at the time of writing, it's arguably the critical test of the main line Lowenthal with 9...[d5].As such, we'll cover not the usual one, but both defensive options for Black. One grabs a pawn then looks to defend; the other is riskier in the eyes of the engines and objectively good for White after much precision, while simply looking very unclear to human eyes.} Nxc2+ $6 {[%csl Ga1,Ge1,Ge3] Yes, this assessment is an objective one; from a practical perspective, especially at lower levels, the move arguably deserves to be denoted '!?', since White must now play pretty accurately to maintain the advantage. Perhaps even '!??!' or '?!!?' would be best! This is definitely the critical test of 13. [Be2] and has been Black's main choice in the limited practice with the line - it certainly forces white players to really know their stuff.} 14. Kf1 {[%csl Re7][%cal Re3c5]} (14. Kf1 {The rook on a1 is most certainly taboo here. Black cannot allow} Nxa1 15. Bc5+ Kf6 16. Ne8+ {, with a deadly initiative for White.}) 14... Nxe3+ $1 {[%csl Gd1,Gf1]} 15. fxe3 {[%csl Ra8,Re7]} (15. fxe3 {Here Black has a few moves, of which saving the rook with} Rb8 {is the safest try and after} 16. Qb3 $1 Be6 $1 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Rc1 {(White has promising play for the pawn '+1' in engine speak, unclear and messy too though the position looks to the human eye, with neither king especially happy. Black also has a more dramatic option.)}) 15... Bh3 $5 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Ga8d8] A hard move to assess: objectively we should again perhaps write '?!', but also '?!!?' might be the most accurate. It's certainly the move that you'd like to work, and might especially be a good try at blitz or bullet. Of course, an opponent with time to react is more likely to find the only sequence to keep White's nose clearly in front, although staying on that correct but narrow path is not so easy, as we'll now see.} 16. Nd5+ $1 Kf8 17. Bf3 {[%csl Rh3]} Qc4+ (17... Qc4+ {With the bishop hanging on h3, Black must keep forcing the pace, and now} 18. Kf2 $2 Qh4+ 19. g3 Qg5 20. Qb3 g6 $1 21. Qxb7 {(Kotturi-O.Belov, correspondence 2009)} Rd8 {leaves Black with the safer king and somewhat for choice. White can do better than that, though.}) 18. Kg1 $1 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Rd5b6]} Rd8 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Gf3][%cal Ge5e4] Introducing a powerful idea in the shape of ...[e4].} 19. Rc1 $1 {[%csl Rc4]} Qh4 {[%csl Ge4]} (19... Qh4 {Maintaining control of the key e4-square. Here} 20. Qb3 $6 Be6 {(pinning)} 21. Qd1 $2 Bh3 $2 {saw a draw agreed in I.Dias-Hervada Serrano, Maia 2024, but simply 21...e4 22.g3 Qg5 would have won. This is not such an easy line for White to play, even when well prepared.}) 20. gxh3 e4 {[%cal Ge4f3,Gg8f6] Now if the bishop moves, Black will regain the piece with a very promising game after ...[Nf6] there's always a handy check on [g5] or even [e1].} 21. Qd4 $1 {[%csl Re4,Rh4] 'Powerful' writes Giri, quite reasonably. Black's reply might also be described as powerful.} Qg5+ $1 22. Kf2 $1 ({Further precision, whereas Black was fine and later drew after} 22. Bg4 Qxd5 23. Qxd5 Rxd5 24. Rc8+ Ke7 {(followed by ...[Rd2] and/or ...[Rd8] in another pretty decent level 2493 vs 2443 test, Brodsky-Posthuma, Grand Rapids 2023.)}) 22... exf3 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gg5g2,Gg8e7] This bold response is our best suggestion for what you should do here, i.e. if you opt for the 13...[Nc2]+ and 15...[Bh3] line, and your opponent knows all the theory.} ({It attempts to improve over} 22... Qxd5 23. Qxd5 Rxd5 24. Rc8+ Ke7 25. Bxe4 {when the combination of the back-rank pin and vulnerable queenside left Black in some trouble in Khanin-Lauda, St. Petersburg 2012.}) 23. Rhg1 $1 {[%csl Rg5,Rg7]} (23. Rhg1 {Naturally, White should cover g2 while counterattacking down the g-file and possibly hoping for} Qh6 $4 24. Qc5+ {with a quick win.}) 23... Qxd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5d4]} 24. Qxg7+ Ke7 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gd5d2,Gd5a5,Gd8d2,Gg8f6]} (24... Ke7 {Black is ready to check on d2 and note that} 25. Rgd1 Qa5 $1 {would now maintain the rough equilibrium, and if} 26. Qxh8 Rd2+ {when White must exchange rooks to avoid being mated.}) (24... Ke7 {Observe too that} 25. Qxh8 $2 Nf6 {is already winning for Black, since it will quickly be mate after} 26. Qg7 $2 Ne4+ {. As such, there's yet again only one way for White to maintain the advantage.}) 25. Rc7+ $1 Kd6 $5 {[%cal Gd6c7] Continuing in uncompromising fashion. If White now takes the rook in the corner, Black will calmly remove the one on [c7] and win.} 26. Rxf7 $1 {[%csl Rd6,Gf2,Rh8] Once again, the only move, and a brave one at that, which preserves a clear or even any advantage for White according to the engines, but look at the board! Were you ever to reach this position in a game, could we really say with both kings so exposed that anything other than that all three results are possible?} Qd2+ $1 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gf3f2]} (26... Qd2+ {Hoping to favourably distract with} 27. Kg3 $2 f2 $1 {, while forcing the white king up the board.}) 27. Kxf3 Qd5+ {[%csl Gf3]} (27... Qd5+ {Continuing to hound the white king and now if} 28. e4 {Black can force perpetual check with} Qd2 {, while 28.Kf2 can be fairly well met by 28...Ne7 . And surely only a silicon, not human form would feel confident about advancing the white king here?}) 28. Kf4 $5 {[%csl Rh8]} Ne7 $1 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gd5f7] (Lacking a good check if 28...Qc4+? 29.e4 , Black absolutely must catch up in development so while saving the rook in the corner. There's now even a threat of ) 29...Qxf7+! 30.Qxf7 Rhf8 , (and White has only one way not to land up in big trouble.We'd be amazed if this position ever occurs in your game, unless you're playing correspondence that is, and it's surely high time that we called a halt to the memorisation you may also have been happy to stop that after, say, 22...[exf3].)} *

