have turned up, but it took for Anish Giri to recommend the line last year in Lifetime Repertoires: Giri's 1. [e4] − Part 3, for it to become slightly trendy with well booked-up white players. It is still to fully catch on, if growing in popularity the position after 12...Ke7 occurred just 11 times on TWIC in 2023, with 13.Rc1 seen in six of those games and 13.Be2 in the other five. While it's hard to imagine an unprepared opponent wishing to gambit their g-pawn so, Black should very much be ready for this line and, at the time of writing, it's arguably the critical test of the main line Lowenthal with 9...[d5].As such, we'll cover not the usual one, but both defensive options for Black. One grabs a pawn then looks to defend; the other is riskier in the eyes of the engines and objectively good for White after much precision, while simply looking very unclear to human eyes.} Nxc2+ $6 {[%csl Ga1,Ge1,Ge3] Yes, this assessment is an objective one; from a practical perspective, especially at lower levels, the move arguably deserves to be denoted '!?', since White must now play pretty accurately to maintain the advantage. Perhaps even '!??!' or '?!!?' would be best! This is definitely the critical test of 13. [Be2] and has been Black's main choice in the limited practice with the line - it certainly forces white players to really know their stuff.} 14. Kf1 {[%csl Re7][%cal Re3c5]} (14. Kf1 {The rook on a1 is most certainly taboo here. Black cannot allow} Nxa1 15. Bc5+ Kf6 16. Ne8+ {, with a deadly initiative for White.}) 14... Nxe3+ $1 {[%csl Gd1,Gf1]} 15. fxe3 {[%csl Ra8,Re7]} (15. fxe3 {Here Black has a few moves, of which saving the rook with} Rb8 {is the safest try and after} 16. Qb3 $1 Be6 $1 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Rc1 {(White has promising play for the pawn '+1' in engine speak, unclear and messy too though the position looks to the human eye, with neither king especially happy. Black also has a more dramatic option.)}) 15... Bh3 $5 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Ga8d8] A hard move to