5 Rxd5 24. Rc8+ Ke7 25. Bxe4 {when the combination of the back-rank pin and vulnerable queenside left Black in some trouble in Khanin-Lauda, St. Petersburg 2012.}) 23. Rhg1 $1 {[%csl Rg5,Rg7]} (23. Rhg1 {Naturally, White should cover g2 while counterattacking down the g-file and possibly hoping for} Qh6 $4 24. Qc5+ {with a quick win.}) 23... Qxd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5d4]} 24. Qxg7+ Ke7 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gd5d2,Gd5a5,Gd8d2,Gg8f6]} (24... Ke7 {Black is ready to check on d2 and note that} 25. Rgd1 Qa5 $1 {would now maintain the rough equilibrium, and if} 26. Qxh8 Rd2+ {when White must exchange rooks to avoid being mated.}) (24... Ke7 {Observe too that} 25. Qxh8 $2 Nf6 {is already winning for Black, since it will quickly be mate after} 26. Qg7 $2 Ne4+ {. As such, there's yet again only one way for White to maintain the advantage.}) 25. Rc7+ $1 Kd6 $5 {[%cal Gd6c7] Continuing in uncompromising fashion. If White now takes the rook in the corner, Black will calmly remove the one on [c7] and win.} 26. Rxf7 $1 {[%csl Rd6,Gf2,Rh8] Once again, the only move, and a brave one at that, which preserves a clear or even any advantage for White according to the engines, but look at the board! Were you ever to reach this position in a game, could we really say with both kings so exposed that anything other than that all three results are possible?} Qd2+ $1 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gf3f2]} (26... Qd2+ {Hoping to favourably distract with} 27. Kg3 $2 f2 $1 {, while forcing the white king up the board.}) 27. Kxf3 Qd5+ {[%csl Gf3]} (27... Qd5+ {Continuing to hound the white king and now if} 28. e4 {Black can force perpetual check with} Qd2 {, while 28.Kf2 can be fairly well met by 28...Ne7 . And surely only a silicon, not human form would feel confident about advancing the white king here?}) 28. Kf4 $5 {[%csl Rh8]} Ne7 $1 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gd5f7] (Lacking a good check if 28...Qc4+? 29.e4 , Black absolutely must catch up in development so while saving the rook in the corner. There's now even a threat of ) 29...Qxf7+! 30.Qxf7 Rhf8 , (and White has only one way not to land up in big trouble.We'd be amazed if this position ever occurs in your game, unless you're playing correspondence that is, and it's surely high time that we called a halt to the memorisation you may also have been happy to stop that after, say, 22...[exf3].)} 29. Qf6+ $1 {[%csl Rd6,Re7]} Qe6 {[%csl Gf6]} ({A more challenging course of action than the attempt to run with} 29... Kc7 30. Qxe7+ Kb6 {.}) 30. Rd1+ {[%csl Rd6,Re6]} Nd5+ {Calmly blocking the check and now White must find a third only move in a row.} 31. Rxd5+ $1 {[%csl Rd6,Re6]} Kxd5 32. Qd4+ {And a fourth, as well as the point where Anish Giri understandably halted his analysis on Lifetime Repertoires: Giri's 1. [e4] − Part 3, liking White.} Kc6 {Taking stock, we find Black with an exposed king, but also an extra rook. Care must be taken not to allow [Qxb7]+ to force mate, and once again in a human encounter, it's not hard to imagine this position fizzling out to a draw.} 33. Qc3+ Kb6 {[%cal Gb6a7] Not forced, but attempting to hide on [a7] makes sense and in any case the same position is set to arise after some further checks.} 34. Qb4+ $1 {[%csl Rb6,Rb7]} Kc6 $1 {Clearly an only move and now White can either keep checking or take some pawns:} 35. Qxb7+ Kd6 $1 {Here so that there won't be any [Rc7]+. The position may look scary, but there are only two attacking pieces, and White's own king isn't exactly completely happy. If White is after more than a half-point, at some stage, he needs the black king on [d5] when [Rf5]+ will be possible.} 36. Qxa6+ Kd5 37. Qb5+ Kd6 38. Qb6+ Kd5 {Continuing to dodge the checks, and now White might crown this perfect play by winning the black queen... except that it may not win the game.} 39. Rf5+ $1 Qxf5+ $1 40. Kxf5 Rdf8+ {[%csl Gb6,Gf5] It's vital to drive the white king offside.} 41. Kg5 Rhg8+ {[%csl Gg5]} 42. Kh4 Ke4 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Ge4f3,Gg8g6] We're on move 42 so should really end our analysis here. Stockfish proclaims at '+1.6', but seems uncertain that White can win, and so are we. Black simply wants to go ...[Kf3], then attack the white king, most simply with ...[Rg6]. Perhaps in a TCEC the effective engine world championship encounter, White would find a way to win in 100+ moves, but between two humans, our money would definitely be on a draw.} *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1E) 8.Qd1 with 13.Be2"]
[Black "8.Qd1 with 13.Be2 Nxc2+ 14.Kf1 \[Alternative 13...Qxg2\] #4"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "46"]
[GameId "2141525854835916"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key Lowenthal tabiya, and firstly we'll focus on White's most important option.} 8. Qd1 {The main line and quite an ambitious choice. White retreats his queen away from being further harried and keeps control of the [d5]-square, but falls further behind in terms of development.} Qg6 {A key follow-up for Black, attacking [e4] and also preventing White from easily completing kingside development with [Bc4] and [O-O].} 9. Nc3 {This is the only really serious move at White's disposal, defending [e4] and aiming to cause trouble with a future [Nd5].} (9. Nc3 {At this point, Black has an important choice:} d5 $5 {and 9...Nge7 , with the sharper and practically very tricky former our recommendation in this course.}) 9... d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Be2 $1 {This tricky counter-gambit was unknown back in 2006 when Richard first analysed the Löwenthal for his and John Emms book, Dangerous Weapons: The Sicilian. Three games played before that have turned up, but it took for Anish Giri to recommend the line last year in Lifetime Repertoires: Giri's 1. [e4] − Part 3, for it to become slightly trendy with well booked-up white players. It is still to fully catch on, if growing in popularity the position after 12...Ke7 occurred just 11 times on TWIC in 2023, with 13.Rc1 seen in six of those games and 13.Be2 in the other five. While it's hard to imagine an unprepared opponent wishing to gambit their g-pawn so, Black should very much be ready for this line and, at the time of writing, it's arguably the critical test of the main line Lowenthal with 9...[d5].As such, we'll cover not the usual one, but both defensive options for Black. One grabs a pawn then looks to defend; the other is riskier in the eyes of the engines and objectively good for White after much precision, while simply looking very unclear to human eyes.} Qxg2 $5 {[%cal Gg2h1] Snaffling the gambitted pawn is also a pretty critical test of White's strategy and may even carry some surprise value, having been seen somewhat less often thus far in praxis.} 14. Rf1 {[%cal Re3d4,Rc7a8] White now threatens to take twice on [d4], as well as grab the hanging rook, but fortunately for Black, help is at hand.} Qc6 $1 {[%csl Gc2,Gc7] Hitting not just the knight but [c2].} 15. Nxa8 $6 Nxc2+ {[%csl Ra1,Re1,Re3] Our favourite manoeuvre, attacking not just the king and rook in the corner, but also the bishop on [e3]. In response, White must either give up the queen for insufficient compensation or move the king.} 16. Kd2 Bf5 $1 {[%cal Gc6d5,Gg8f6,Gh8d8]} ({A key follow-up and much better policy than} 16... Nxa1 $2 {when White has a few tricky responses, including} 17. b4 $1 {. The text move threatens not just 17...[Qd5]+, but especially 17...[Nf6] followed by a devastating 18...[Rd8]+. White has only one real defence.}) 17. Bf3 $1 {[%csl Rc6]} Qb5 $1 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gg8f6,Gb5a5]} (17... Qb5 {Keeping the queen as active as possible and not e4?? Qxc2 , and now ...[Qb4]+ is very much an idea, or if} 18. Nc7 Qa5+ {, as well as ...[Nf6] and ...[Rd8]+.}) 18. Qe2 $1 {More precise defence and now Black has nothing better than to check, drive the king back and then take the hanging rook.} Qb4+ $1 {[%csl Ga1,Gd2]} 19. Kc1 Nxa1 {[%csl Gh8][%cal Gg8f6] Now all is set for ...[Nf6] and the inclusion of the rook on [h8] into the attack. White has only one disruptive way to prevent that:} 20. Bg5+ $5 {[%csl Re5]} (20. Bg5+ {The point is, of course,} Nf6 $2 21. Qxe5+ {.}) 20... Kf8 $1 {[%cal Gb4c5,Ga1c2] Hiding from the checks and preparing to release the knight via ...[Qc5]+ and ...[Nc2].} 21. Bd2 $1 {[%csl Rb4]} Qa4 {[%cal Ga4c2,Ga4a2] With two big threats, one especially big one. White's reply is forced.} 22. Qd1 $1 {[%csl Ra2]} Qc4+ $5 {[%csl Gc1]} ({Black absolutely must avoid} 22... Qxa2 $4 23. Bb4+ {with mate next move. The text continues in our favourite fighting and provocative style, although it should be said that 22...Qc2+ 23.Qxc2 Nxc2 is also possible if you prefer a quieter game.}) 23. Bc3 Ke7 {[%csl Ra1,Ga8,Gc1,Re7,Gh8][%cal Gg8f6,Gf6d7,Gf7f6,Gg8h6] The position is pretty unclear, but at least Black has two extra pawns and is all set to complete development with ... [Nf6]. Neither king nor cornered knight is overly happy, but we wouldn't mind taking Black in this '0.00' scenario with ...[Nf6]-[d7] one possibility to cover [e5], ...[f6] and ...[Nh6] another.} *

