][%cal Gd5d4]} ({Black's most ambitious move, as well as one which has been almost as popular in practice as} 9... Nge7 {after which Be3 seems fairly pleasant for White on the latest evidence.}) {The text threatens ...d4, but is essentially a pawn sacrifice, aiming to either rip open the b1-h7 diagonal ( 10.exd5 Nd4 ,) or to seize the initiative while White loses time taking on [d5] with a piece.} 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5c7] The critical main line. White abandons [e4], but threatens a big check on [c7].} ({Note too that instead the rare} 10. f3 Nge7 {would take us back to a position we saw via a 9.f3 Nge7 10.Nc3 O-O move order.}) 10... Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Naturally Black removes the pawn which White has left en prise and now there are three ways to deal with the check.} 11. Be3 {The main line and a move played in 64% of the games to have reached this position on the Mega Database 2024. White keeps everything secure and renews the threat to check on [c7].} Nd4 {A key follow-up to the forcing play initiated by 9...[d5]. Black threatens both 12... [Qxd5] and 12...[Nxc2]+.} 12. Nc7+ {A critical check, as well as White's invariable choice.} Ke7 {Another pretty much only move and a key one to remember, as the king avoids stepping on to the d-file or obstructing the path of the rook on [h8]. Black dangles the rook on [a8] before White and we've reached quite a critical tabiya. In practice a well-prepared black player should expect to do fairly well, since White has a number of pitfalls to avoid and has often been caught out of book, although it must be admitted that objectively Black is unable to equalise if White is very precise and really knows his stuff, beginning with the fairly recent discovery of 13. [Be2]!?.} (12... Ke7 {Here we will consider:} 13. Nxa8 {, 13.Qd3 , 13.Rc1 and 13.Be2 . We should also briefly mention 13.Bd3 .}) 13. Be2 $1 {This tricky counter-gambit was unknown back in 2006 when Richard first analysed the Löwenthal for his and John Emms book, Dangerous Weapons: The Sicilian. Three games played before that have turned up, but it took for Anish Giri to recommend the line last year in Lifetime Repertoires: Giri's 1. [e4] − Part 3, for it to become slightly trendy with well booked-up white players. It is still to fully catch on, if growing in popularity the position after 12...Ke7 occurred just 11 times on TWIC in 2023, with 13.Rc1 seen in six of those games and 13.Be2 in the other five. While it's hard to imagine an unprepared opponent wishing to gambit their g-pawn so, Black should very much be ready for this line and, at the time of writing, it's arguably the critical test of the main line Lowenthal with 9...[d5].As such, we'll cover not the usual one, but both defensive options for Black. One grabs a pawn then looks to defend; the other is riskier in the eyes of the engines and objectively good for White after much precision, while simply looking very unclear to human eyes.} Qxg2 $5 {[%cal Gg2h1] Snaffling the gambitted pawn is also a pretty critical test of White's strategy and may even carry some surprise value, having been seen somewhat less often thus far in praxis.} 14. Rf1 {[%cal Re3d4,Rc7a8] White now threatens to take twice on [d4], as well as grab the hanging rook, but fortunately for Black, help is at hand.} Qc6 $1 {[%csl Gc2,Gc7] Hitting not just the knight but [c2].} 15. c3 $1 {[%csl Ra8,Rd4] This effectively works out as a pawn sacrifice and gives Black much less fun if the rook is bagged.} Qxc7 ({Pocketing the dangerous knight ahead of, looking to defend the king while maintaining the extra pawn. Risk takers may also wish to consider, especially at a faster time control,} 15... Nxe2 $6 16. Nxa8 Nf4 {when the position looks pretty unclear, although after the accurate} 17. Bxf4 $1 exf4 18. Qb3 $1 {White should emerge with a clear advantage.}) 16. cxd4 {'We have got strong bishops and Black's king is a lot more vulnerable. Black has to be very accurate not to lose immediately and is in trouble even with the best play' writes Giri. While we're happy to accept that objectively White should have more than enough for the pawn, matters don't seem all doom and gloom for Black, especially after our next two moves, prioritising queenside development.} Be6 $1 {[%cal Ga8d8] (The only move tested in practice thus far, catching up in development and freeing a path for ...Rd8 the alternative would be to try and erect some sort of blockade after 16...Ke8!? 17.dxe5 Ne7 18.f4 Qa5+ ) .} 17. dxe5 Rd8 {[%csl Gd1,Ge5] Both White's queen and e-pawn hang and there's only one move to maintain the advantage in the view of the engines.} 18. Qa4 $1 {[%cal Rf2f4]} Qxe5 {Staying a pawn ahead before White can get in [f2]-[f4]. Black would now like to unravel with ...[f6], ... [Kf7] and ...[Ne7], and we've reached another position which doesn't look at all clear to us, one where we really do feel that anything could happen in practice, even if the engines may again assess at almost '+1'.} (18... Qxe5 {They likely like White's bishop-pair and slightly safer king, and while this position may not be about to occur in a world championship match, it doesn't seem at all unplayable. For example,} 19. Rg1 $1 {Pressuring [g7] to take ...[f6] off the agenda is fairly necessary if White wishes to fight for the advantage.} Kf8 {Trying to hide the king and also freeing [e7] for the knight. Once again, we're told that White only has one route to be better.} 20. Qb4+ Ne7 {((Now Black is all set to go ...f6 or ... Rd7, and might even be threatening to snatch the loose pawn on h2, not least after 21.Qxb7 Nd5! 22.Rd1 Qxh2 , which is just very unclear - or '0.00' if you prefer.))} 21. Bf4 $1 Qf5 {Keeping the queen safe and continuing to prevent White from being able to castle long. ((The alternative would be 21...Qd4!? 22.Qxd4 Rxd4 23.Be5 Nf5! , giving up the exchange to unravel, with some but probably not quite enough compensation for it.))} 22. Bd6 Rd7 {Calmly defending the knight while getting ready to unpin with 23...[Ke8]. ((The position still doesn't look overly clear, obvious though White's compensation is, but 23.Rc1 Ke8 24.Rg3 Qd5 is assessed at just over '+1' by Stockfish. )) That didn't though happen in the only test of the position thus far.} 23. O-O-O Ke8 24. Rge1 Nc6 {White is apparently still better, but Black has a threat, as well as a fairly active queen of his own. The immediate plan is to run away with ... [Kd8]-[c8] then develop the rook from [h8], with all three results still looking possible to us, while in the 2522 versus 2430 clash, Van Assche-De Vassal, correspondence 2012, Black went on to hold a pawn-down ending.}) *

