1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. c4 $2 {This also restrains ...[d5], but constructing a Maroczy Bind so is far too ambitious with White so far behind in development. Black has now scored well in practice with 9...[Qg6], but there's something even better.} Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4c2]} (9... Nd4 {With a certain threat, one which isn't so easy for White to meet in view of} 10. Bd3 Qg6 $1 {, keeping up the pressure on the light squares.}) 10. Bd3 $6 (10. Bd3 {This tempted Black into} Nf3+ $2 {in Susovic-Miskovic, Stobrec 2004, which may look tempting, but after} 11. gxf3 $1 Qxf3 12. Rg1 Qxd3 13. Nc3 {White's grip and dark-square initiative would give him far too much for the pawn. As such, Black should counter in a slightly less dramatic fashion on the light squares.}) 10... Qg6 $1 {[%csl Gd3,Gg6][%cal Gg6g2,Gd7d5] Threatening [g2] and the potential pin on the [b1]-[h7] diagonal means that Black is also set to break with ...[d5].} 11. O-O d5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gc8h3]} (11... d5 {All of a sudden ...Bh3 is a large threat, as well as ...Nf3+ and the engines think that White must find} 12. f3 $5 {to restrict Black to only a clear advantage after} dxc4 13. Qxc4 Bh3 14. Rf2 Nxf3+ {, winning a pawn.}) 12. cxd5 $2 Bh3 {[%csl Gg1][%cal Gg6g2] Rarely a bad first move for a bishop, threatening mate in one into the bargain.} 13. g3 Nf3+ {[%csl Gg1]} 14. Kh1 Qh5 {[%csl Gh1][%cal Gh3g4,Gh3f1,Gh5h2]} ({Flicking in} 14... Rc8 $5 15. Qxb7 {before going} Qh5 {is also very strong. In either case, Black threatens not only to take on [f1], but also just to go ...[Bg4], both of which will threaten mate.}) 15. d6 {[%csl Re8][%cal Rc7e7] White gets in his own mate threat, but it's easily sidestepped.} Nc6 {[%csl Gh1,Gh5][%cal Gh3f1]} (15... Nc6 {White may have an active queen, but is completely lost. There's just no good way to deal with the threat of 16...Bxf1 as} 16. Rd1 $2 Nfd4 $1 {would be an immediate game-ender on the light squares.}) 16. d7+ $5 {Desperation.} Bxd7 {[%cal Gh5h2]} 17. h4 Qg4 {[%cal Gg4h3]} (17... Qg4 {The black queen gets in after all and in view of} 18. Kg2 Nxh4+ {, White should really resign.}) *

