1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. c4 $2 {This also restrains ...[d5], but constructing a Maroczy Bind so is far too ambitious with White so far behind in development. Black has now scored well in practice with 9...[Qg6], but there's something even better.} Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4c2]} (9... Nd4 {With a certain threat, one which isn't so easy for White to meet in view of} 10. Bd3 Qg6 $1 {, keeping up the pressure on the light squares.}) 10. Bd3 $6 (10. Bd3 {This tempted Black into} Nf3+ $2 {in Susovic-Miskovic, Stobrec 2004, which may look tempting, but after} 11. gxf3 $1 Qxf3 12. Rg1 Qxd3 13. Nc3 {White's grip and dark-square initiative would give him far too much for the pawn. As such, Black should counter in a slightly less dramatic fashion on the light squares.}) 10... Qg6 $1 {[%csl Gd3,Gg6][%cal Gg6g2,Gd7d5] Threatening [g2] and the potential pin on the [b1]-[h7] diagonal means that Black is also set to break with ...[d5].} 11. Kf1 $5 d5 $1 {[%csl Gc1,Gc7,Gc8,Gf1][%cal Gd5e4,Gd5c4] White might have prevented ...[Qxg2], but that doesn't mean Black need be denied the other big idea in the position, and now there's a very nice refutation of 12.cxd5?. Take your time and have a look for it if this is a new position to you...} (11... d5 {The answer is} 12. cxd5 $2 Bh3 $1 13. gxh3 Rc8 {when the X-ray down the c-file means Black will regain the piece with plenty of interest. Instead, 12.Nc3 dxc4 13.Bxc4 Be6 would leave Black quickly completing development and all set to enjoy the safer king position with a pleasant edge, so perhaps White might get greedy.}) 12. Qxe5 Ndc6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gc6b4,Ge8g8] A powerful retreat, kicking the queen away while facilitating not just castling, but ideas of a quick raid with ...[Nb4].} 13. Qg3 Nb4 {[%csl Gd3,Gg3]} (13... Nb4 {Threatening to take on g3 then d3 and, of course,} 14. Be2 $2 {would run into} Nc2 {.}) 14. Qxg6 Nxg6 {[%cal Gb4d3]} 15. Ke2 dxc4 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gb4c2,Gb4d3] White can't save the bishop and prevent ...[Nc2], meaning that Black will win the exchange for clearly insufficient compensation.} *

