1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. c4 $2 {This also restrains ...[d5], but constructing a Maroczy Bind so is far too ambitious with White so far behind in development. Black has now scored well in practice with 9...[Qg6], but there's something even better.} Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4c2]} (9... Nd4 {With a certain threat, one which isn't so easy for White to meet in view of} 10. Bd3 Qg6 $1 {, keeping up the pressure on the light squares.}) 10. Na3 {Not an ideal square for the knight, but probably the best way of covering [c2].} d6 $5 (10... d6 {A modest little move, but also a good one: Black simply wants to take control after ...Nec6 and ...O-O, while} 11. c5 $2 dxc5 12. Qxc5 Be6 {would only open the c-file for Black's benefit.}) 11. Be3 Nec6 {[%cal Gc6d4] Enabling Black to maintain a powerfully-placed knight on [d4] should White ever exchange.} 12. O-O-O ({Easy to criticise, but it's far from easy for White to develop the bishop from f1, with} 12. Bd3 $6 {running into} Nb4 {, and if} 13. Bb1 $6 Qg6 {with a serious-looking initiative for Black.}) 12... O-O {[%csl Gc1,Gc7][%cal Gc8e6,Gb7b5] Black's king is the safer and it may now be possible to gambit the d-pawn for open lines and a strong initiative after ...[Be6]. There are also very much ideas of ...[b5], looking to cause trouble for both the white king and the white queen.} 13. Nc2 (13. Nc2 {Here Black couldn't resist} b5 $5 {and went on to win in Knight-Mi.White, Hastings 2008/09, but there's something even stronger here.}) 13... Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gg4d1]} (13... Bg4 {Black wants to force the rook to a slightly strange square before breaking with ...b5 and would be clearly for choice after, for instance} 14. Rd2 b5 $1 {. We're also setting a small trap.}) 14. f3 $2 {[%csl Rg4]} Bxf3 $1 {[%cal Gf3d1]} (14... Bxf3 {Hitting the rook and} 15. Nxd4 exd4 {wouldn't now help White.}) 15. gxf3 Nxc2 {[%cal Gc2e3,Gf6f3] Continuing to force the pace.} 16. Kxc2 Qxf3 {[%cal Gf3e3,Gf3h1] The double attack on [e3] and [h1] means that Black will regain the piece with a significant advantage.} *

