1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Bd2 $6 {Rather modest, as White prioritises trying to prevent ...[Nb4].} d5 (9... d5 {The key break and don't forget that now} 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would leave the white queen red-faced.}) 10. Nc3 $1 (10. Nc3 {White angles for} d4 11. Nd5 $1 {and so Black went 10...Be6 in Wegener-Packroff, German League 2006, but it's also possible to sacrifice a pawn.}) 10... O-O $1 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gf6g6]} (10... O-O {Sensibly housing the king, which means that Black is ready to go} 11. Z0 dxe4 {, and if} 12. Nxe4 Qg6 {.}) 11. exd5 Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c2]} (11... Nd4 {An ambitious approach, there’s also absolutely nothing wrong with regaining the pawn with 11…Nb4} 12. Bd3 Nxd5 {.}) 12. Bd3 Bf5 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf5d3] Black enjoys promising play for a pawn he may well shortly regain. As well as the threat to remove the defender of [c2], …Rfc8 may well cause something of a headache for the white queen stranded on the queenside. White will need to play accurately to maintain the rough balance.} *

