1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Bd2 $6 {Rather modest, as White prioritises trying to prevent ...[Nb4].} d5 (9... d5 {The key break and don't forget that now} 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would leave the white queen red-faced.}) 10. Nc3 $1 (10. Nc3 {White angles for} d4 11. Nd5 $1 {and so Black went 10...Be6 in Wegener-Packroff, German League 2006, but it's also possible to sacrifice a pawn.}) 10... O-O $1 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gf6g6] Sensibly housing the king, which means that Black is ready to go 11...dxe4 , and if 12.Nxe4 Qg6 .} 11. Nxd5 $2 {This does force a pair of knights off, but also leaves White rather vulnerable down the c-file.} Nxd5 12. exd5 Nd4 {[%csl Gc2,Gc7,Ge1][%cal Gc8f5]} (12... Nd4 {The point of Black's play. Now 13...Bf5 is a big threat and, of course,} 13. c3 $2 Nc2+ {wouldn't help White, and neither would 13.O-O-O? Bf5 when a massacre would be brewing down the c-file.}) 13. Bd3 e4 $1 (13... e4 {A powerful pawn sacrifice and refutation of White's play. Now White has nothing better than grovelling in a horrible position after} 14. c3 exd3 15. cxd4 Re8+ $1 16. Be3 Qxd4 17. O-O Qxd5 {when the extra pawn on [d3] is a big one. The problem is that the e-pawn is poisoned.}) 14. Bxe4 $2 Re8 {[%csl Ge1,Ge4,Ge8][%cal Ge8e4] Black is simply winning a piece as the bishop can't really be defended.} 15. f3 $2 Nxf3+ $1 {[%csl Gd2,Ge1,Ge4]} 16. gxf3 $2 Qxf3 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Ge8e4,Gf3h1] It's all over bar the shouting, with perhaps the only surprise being that the engines indicate White can survive for 14 more moves before being mated.} *

