1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Na4 $5 {[%cal Rc1d2,Ra4b6] A more ambitious try, threatening [Bd2] then [Nb6].} b5 $1 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gb5a4]} (10... b5 {Forcing the pace while being happy to lure the knight forwards. Black might now meet} 11. Bd2 {with} Nec6 {, although we should point out that 11...Nbc6!? would also be absolutely fine, and if 12.Nb6?? Ra7! or 12.Nc3 O-O .}) 11. Nb6 $6 {[%csl Ra8] Continuing the ambitious policy.} Nxc2+ $1 {[%csl Ga1,Ge1]} 12. Kd1 $2 Qxf2 $1 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gc2a1,Ge8g8]} ({Cutting out any Be3 resources is even stronger than} 12... Nxa1 {, which has long been known to be pretty promising for Black.}) 13. Nxa8 Nxa1 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Gf2d4,Ge8g8,Gd7d5] Black now threatens 14...[Qd4]+, as well as 14...[O-O] followed by ...[d5]. The knight on [a1] might be stuck for now, but remains a useful attacking presence and in any case, the key feature of the position is the exposed white king.} 14. Qc3 {[%cal Ra8c7]} O-O {[%cal Gc8b7,Gd7d5] Wisely housing the king ahead of going ...[Bb7] and/or ...[d5].} 15. Be3 Qh4 {[%csl Ga8,Gd1][%cal Gc8b7] With 16...[Bb7] on the way, Black was simply doing extremely well in Biryukov-Sanzhaev, Saratov 2015, where White remained badly hampered by the misplaced king on [d1].} *

