1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Na4 $5 {[%cal Rc1d2,Ra4b6] A more ambitious try, threatening [Bd2] then [Nb6].} b5 $1 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gb5a4]} (10... b5 {Forcing the pace while being happy to lure the knight forwards. Black might now meet} 11. Bd2 {with} Nec6 {, although we should point out that 11...Nbc6!? would also be absolutely fine, and if 12.Nb6?? Ra7! or 12.Nc3 O-O .}) 11. a3 (11. a3 {A safe choice and one which would lead to rough equality after} Nxc2+ 12. Qxc2 bxa4 13. Qxa4 O-O {when Black will get in ...[d5]. That's more than acceptable for Black, but we'd also be tempted here to set a small trap.}) 11... Nbc6 $5 (11... Nbc6 {The point is that again} 12. Nb6 $4 {fails to} Ra7 $1 {when it's the white queen being trapped.}) 12. Nc3 O-O {[%csl Gc7][%cal Ga8b8,Gb8b7,Gc6d4] (Sensibly housing the king and now 13...Nd4 is one idea, 13...Rb8 very much another, simply threatening to round up the errant white queen with ...Rb7 the immediate 12...Rb8? would fail to 13.Nd5! ) .} 13. Be3 $1 {[%cal Re3c5] This threatened to assist the white queen and take over the dark squares with [Bc5] in Bures-Eschholz, Pardubice 2012.} d6 $1 {[%csl Gc5,Gc7][%cal Gc8e6,Gf8d8,Gf6g6] Cutting out [Bc5] ideas. Black may now follow up with ...[Qg6] or sacrifice the d-pawn for easy play with ...[Be6], and ...[Rd8] is very much an idea too, supporting ...[d5] while threatening ...[Rd7]; [Qb6] [Rb8].} 14. O-O-O Rd8 $1 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gd8d7,Ga8b8]} (14... Rd8 {Threatening} 15. Z0 Rd7 16. Qb6 Rb8 $1 {(( 16...Rb7? would be much less effective due to 17.Nd5 ))} 17. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 18. Qxc6 Nxe3 19. fxe3 Qd8 {with a fairly big advantage for Black, due to the superior structure and much safer king. As such, White really needs to take up the challenge here.}) 15. Nd5 $1 {[%csl Rc6,Rd8,Re7,Rf6]} Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5e3]} (15... Nxd5 {A fairly obligatory exchange and now} 16. Qxc6 $2 Nxe3 {would counter-attack against the rook on [d1] and leave Black doing well.}) 16. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} Nd4 {[%cal Gc8f5,Ga8c8,Gd4f5]} (16... Nd4 {Suddenly ...Bf5 then ...Rac8 is a big threat and Black also has ideas of a timely ...Nf5, not least in the event of} 17. Qb6 Nf5 {. In short, there's enough counterplay against [c2] to maintain the balance, and that's assuming White is accurate here.}) (16... Nd4 {For example,} 17. Bxd4 exd4 18. Qb6 Bf5 {Covering the rook on [d8], and preparing to go after the white king with ... [Rac8]. (( 18...Qxf2?? 19.Qxd8# would not be wise))} 19. Qxd4 Qg6 {((A fine square for the queen, attacking c2 while also getting ready to play down not only the c-file, but also the e-file in the event of 20.c3 Re8. ) . )} 20. Bd3 Bxd3 {Exchanging on Black's terms and if White now recaptures with a piece then 21...Qxg2 will regain the pawn with a decent position for Black.} 21. cxd3 $5 {((White hopes for 21...Qxg2?? 22.Rhg1 , but Black can do much better than blunder the game away.))} a5 $1 {Black is now ready to blow open lines with ...[b4]. The active queen and safer king position fully offset White's extra doubled pawn.}) (16... Nd4 17. Rxd4 $5 {This actually isn't ridiculous due to the hanging rook on [d8].} exd4 18. Bxd4 Qg5+ 19. Be3 Qf6 {Black renews the threat of ...[Bf5] and there isn't a good way for either side to avoid the repetition with} 20. Bd4 Qg5+ 21. Be3 Qf6 {, etc.}) *

