1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. Bd2 $5 (11. Bd2 {White facilitates long castling, but mainly plays against the knight on b4 and angles for} d4 12. Na4 $1 {when} Qc6 13. Qxc6+ Nexc6 14. Nb6 {(would give him a slightly improved version of Line 2B 11. [O-O] [d4]. That position is still playable for Black, but it's also very possible to maintain flexibility.)}) 11... O-O $5 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gb4d3]} (11... O-O {Making the king safe. Black is now ready to complete development with ...Be6, would very much welcome long castling from White and can now meet} 12. Na4 $6 {with simply} Nxd3+ 13. cxd3 Be6 $1 {, gambiting a pawn for easy and decent counterplay down the b-, c- and d-files.}) 12. O-O {[%cal Rf2f4] A prudent choice, as well as one which allows White to fight for the initiative with [f2]-[f4].} Be6 $5 ({Completing development while dangling the b-pawn before White. With White lining up f2-f4, please don't close the position with} 12... d4 $2 13. Na4 {, but as well as the text move, Black might exchange on [d3] or even check out the engines' calm suggestion of 12...Re8!? , overprotecting and awaiting events.}) 13. Qxb7 Rab8 {[%csl Gb2,Gb7]} (13... Rab8 {With tempo and Black will now gain another one if White goes in for} 14. Qc7 Rfc8 {.}) 14. Qa7 Nxd3 {[%csl Gb2]} ({Simple and decent chess, although if you revel in complexity, you may also wish to explore} 14... Nec6 $5 15. Qc5 Rfc8 {.}) 15. cxd3 Rxb2 {[%cal Gb2d2,Gb2c2] Regaining the pawn with equality. Indeed, due to Black's superior activity, only with a crafty retreat do the engines feel White can maintain equality.} 16. Bc1 $1 Rc2 {[%csl Gc3]} 17. Ba3 {[%csl Re7]} Re8 {[%cal Gc2c3] Everything is defended and Black absolutely fine, whether a pair of rooks now comes off on [c1] or White prefers a different way to hoover.} 18. Bxe7 {[%csl Rf6,Rg8]} Qxe7 $1 {Necessary, of course, and any pawn which White can now gain will but be a temporary gain.} (18... Qxe7 {For example,} 19. Qxe7 Rxe7 20. Nxd5 Bxd5 21. exd5 h5 $5 {Seizing as much space as possible, while avoiding any back-rank issues and freeing a path into the game for the king via [h7] and [g6]. The rook on [c2] is clearly very active and can always move to [d2]. Moreover, with ...[Rd7] next up, it's likely White who will have to be the more precise to head this rook endgame into drawish territory.}) *

