1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. Bd2 $5 (11. Bd2 {White facilitates long castling, but mainly plays against the knight on b4 and angles for} d4 12. Na4 $1 {when} Qc6 13. Qxc6+ Nexc6 14. Nb6 {(would give him a slightly improved version of Line 2B 11. [O-O] [d4]. That position is still playable for Black, but it's also very possible to maintain flexibility.)}) 11... O-O $5 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gb4d3]} (11... O-O {Making the king safe. Black is now ready to complete development with ...Be6, would very much welcome long castling from White and can now meet} 12. Na4 $6 {with simply} Nxd3+ 13. cxd3 Be6 $1 {, gambiting a pawn for easy and decent counterplay down the b-, c- and d-files.}) 12. O-O {[%cal Rf2f4] A prudent choice, as well as one which allows White to fight for the initiative with [f2]-[f4].} Be6 $5 ({Completing development while dangling the b-pawn before White. With White lining up f2-f4, please don't close the position with} 12... d4 $2 13. Na4 {, but as well as the text move, Black might exchange on [d3] or even check out the engines' calm suggestion of 12...Re8!? , overprotecting and awaiting events.}) 13. f4 $5 {[%csl Re5] It feels critical for White to elect to fighting for the initiative so.} Nxd3 {Sooner or later, it makes sense to deprive White of the bishop-pair, especially as the position opens up.} 14. cxd3 {[%csl Re5,Re7,Rf6]} (14. cxd3 {This position was reached in Folk-Lacina, Czech League 2014, where} exf4 $4 15. e5 Qh4 16. Rxf4 Qg5 {was something of a disaster for Black}) {h4 would have won a piece. Instead, Black should prefer to counter against White's own queen.} 14... Rfc8 $1 {[%cal Gc8c7,Ga8b8,Gb8b2,Gc8c2,Gd5d4]} (14... Rfc8 {Kicking the queen away as Black angles to get a rook active on the seventh rank, be it after} 15. Qxb7 Rab8 {and 16...[Rxb2] or 15.Qxe5 Qxe5 16.fxe5 d4! and 17...[Rc2]. Another important point is 15.Qd6 exf4 16.e5 Nf5! , which is why the engines prefer something a little more sneaky as White, although even then Black should be fine.}) 15. Qb6 $5 dxe4 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gc8d8]} ({Arguably simplest, although} 15... d4 {should also be fine. With the text move, Black avoids any dark-square issues and even gets ready to activate with tempo in the event of dxe4 Rd8 .}) 16. Nxe4 $5 {[%csl Rf6]} Qg6 {Clearly the safest spot for the queen. Black can follow up with ...[Bd5] or even ...[Nd5], with ...[Rc2] very much an idea too.} 17. fxe5 Bd5 $1 {[%cal Gg6b6,Gd5e4]} (17... Bd5 {This pawn sacrifice is the star point of Black's play. We threaten to take on e4 and, of course,} 18. Nd6 $4 Qxg2# {would not spell good news for White.}) 18. Qxg6 Nxg6 {[%cal Gg6e5,Gc8e8,Gc8c2]} (18... Nxg6 {Black gets ready to take on e5 and can always go ...Re8, especially in the event of} 19. Bc3 Bxe4 20. dxe4 Re8 {, if not ...[Rc2]. In any case, we should be fine with active pieces, the unopposed light-squared bishop and easy central targets.}) (18... Nxg6 {For example,} 19. Nc3 Be6 {Calmly done. (( Black attacks e5 and would enjoy full positional compensation for the pawn after, say, 20.Rae1 Rd8 21.Re3 Rac8 , which explains why White might prefer to push in the centre.))} 20. d4 Rc4 $1 {Further precision. ((In true hypermodern fashion, Black lures the white centre forwards as after 21.d5 Bd7 the [e5]-pawn would be very weak - there's always ...[Re8] if needed.) 21. [Be3] [Ne7]! Improving the worst-placed piece. After ...[Rac8] then ...[Nd5] Black's light-square blockade and control should supply full compensation for the pawn, with a draw starting to look quite likely. )}) *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2A) 8.Qc7 Sidelines"]
[Black "8.Qc7 with 9.Nc3 Nb4 10.Bd3 and 11.f4 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "40"]
[GameId "2141525855323353"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. f4 $5 {[%csl Ge1,Re5] Full marks to White for aggression, but this does also expose his king somewhat.} Nxd3+ {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gf6h4]} ({Depriving White of the bishop-pair before checking, although it's also possible to begin with} 11... Qh4+ $5 12. g3 Qh3 {and even 11...d4 is OK here, as well as having been Black's most common choice in practice, in view of 12.Na4 Qh4+! .}) 12. cxd3 Qh4+ $1 {[%csl Ge1] An old idea of Richard's from ChessPublishing, forcing White to either make a sub-optimal king move or weaken his kingside.} 13. g3 Qh3 {[%csl Ge1,Gh1][%cal Gh3g2]} (13... Qh3 {Threatening to pretty much win on the spot with} 14. Z0 Qg2 15. Rf1 Bh3 {.}) 14. Kf2 $6 Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gd5d4,Ga8c8] Activating the bishop whilst Black can. Now ...[d4] followed by ...[Rc8] is very much a threat, and Black is also all set to attack the white king after ...[Ng6] and ...[O-O]. The [b7]-pawn is a price very much worth paying for such activity.} 15. exd5 $2 ({Even after} 15. Qxb7 Rd8 {Black has a strong initiative and excellent compensation. One threat is…d4, another …Bc8, kicking the queen while preparing both a timely opening of the centre and to complete mobilisation with …Rd7 and …O-O.}) 15... Ng6 (15... Ng6 {Simply facilitating castling and now if} 16. Qd6 Rd8 17. Qc5 Rc8 18. Qd6 {then} f6 $1 {followed by ... [Kf7] and ...[Rhd8] would also leave Black doing extremely well.}) 16. Qxb7 O-O {Just compare the two kings! Meanwhile Black is all set to blow open lines with ...[exf4].} 17. d6 (17. d6 {Black did win quickly here after} exf4 {in Van der Leest-Sadallah, Hoogeveen 2007, but only because White missed a chance to minimise the damage with} 18. Qg2 $1 {. In any case, there's something even stronger. Can you spot it? Answer on the next line, as Daniel King would say in one of his 'How Good Is Your Chess?' articles!}) 17... Nxf4 {A crushing blow, threatening to take on [d3] and so pretty much forcing White to accept the sacrifice.} 18. gxf4 exf4 {[%cal Ga8e8]} ({This calm move is the star follow-up and much stronger than} 18... Qh4+ 19. Kg1 {.}) {Now 19...Qh4+ is a big threat, and if 20.Kg1 Qe1+ 21.Kg2 f3+ . Black is also all set to bolster the attack with ...[Rae8] and the engines simply can't see a defence for White, in part because taking on [f4] has a certain downside.} 19. Bxf4 Rab8 {The point. Black gets ready to take on [b2] then hunt down the white king.} 20. Qe4 (20. Qe4 {Hoping for} Rxb2+ $6 21. Ke1 {, but Black has even better than that.}) 20... Rfe8 {[%csl Ge4,Gf2][%cal Gb8b2] Calmly inviting the final piece to the party, as Yasser Seirawan might say. White can't save both queen and king, and is hopelessly lost.} *

