1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. f4 $5 {[%csl Ge1,Re5] Full marks to White for aggression, but this does also expose his king somewhat.} Nxd3+ {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gf6h4]} ({Depriving White of the bishop-pair before checking, although it's also possible to begin with} 11... Qh4+ $5 12. g3 Qh3 {and even 11...d4 is OK here, as well as having been Black's most common choice in practice, in view of 12.Na4 Qh4+! .}) 12. cxd3 Qh4+ $1 {[%csl Ge1] An old idea of Richard's from ChessPublishing, forcing White to either make a sub-optimal king move or weaken his kingside.} 13. g3 Qh3 {[%csl Ge1,Gh1][%cal Gh3g2]} (13... Qh3 {Threatening to pretty much win on the spot with} 14. Z0 Qg2 15. Rf1 Bh3 {.}) 14. f5 $1 {Wisely shutting down the bishop on [c8], albeit at the cost of having to allow ...[Qg2].} Qg2 {[%csl Gh1] Having said 'A', Black might as well say 'B' and invade with the queen.} 15. Rf1 f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg2h2,Gc8d7] Sensibly securing [e5] and so threatening ...[Qxh2], as well as just to continue development with ...[Bd7] and ...[Rc8]. That pretty much compels White to force the pace, and there are now two important lines, in both of which Black is fine.} 16. Rf2 $5 {[%csl Rg2]} Qg1+ (16... Qg1+ {White can't repeat here as} 17. Rf1 $2 Qxh2 {would leave Black doing well, but after...}) 17. Ke2 $1 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Ra1b1,Rc1e3,Rc3d5] ...Black must be careful as [Nxd5] is now a threat, as is 18. [Rb1] followed by [Be3].} Bxf5 $1 {Threatening a big check on [g4] and this piece sacrifice fully saves Black.} 18. exf5 Nc6 $1 {A key follow-up, one which leaves White without an especially great way of preventing the big threat of 19...[Nd4]+.} 19. Be3 $1 {[%csl Rg1]} Qxa1 20. Qxg7 {[%csl Rh8]} O-O-O {Completing development whilst saving the rook in the corner. A dispirited opponent might even resign here, but actually White has a resource, one good enough to force a draw.} 21. Nxd5 $1 {[%csl Rc8,Rh8][%cal Rg7c7]} Kb8 $1 ({Wisely running away. Unfortunately for Black,} 21... Qxb2+ $2 22. Kf3 {would not help matters.}) 22. Qc7+ Ka8 {[%cal Gd8d5,Ga8a7,Ga7a8] Black isn't getting mated, but by alternating his knight between [b6] and [c8] White is able to force perpetual check.} *

