 to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. f4 $5 {[%csl Ge1,Re5] Full marks to White for aggression, but this does also expose his king somewhat.} Nxd3+ {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gf6h4]} ({Depriving White of the bishop-pair before checking, although it's also possible to begin with} 11... Qh4+ $5 12. g3 Qh3 {and even 11...d4 is OK here, as well as having been Black's most common choice in practice, in view of 12.Na4 Qh4+! .}) 12. cxd3 Qh4+ $1 {[%csl Ge1] An old idea of Richard's from ChessPublishing, forcing White to either make a sub-optimal king move or weaken his kingside.} 13. g3 Qh3 {[%csl Ge1,Gh1][%cal Gh3g2]} (13... Qh3 {Threatening to pretty much win on the spot with} 14. Z0 Qg2 15. Rf1 Bh3 {.}) 14. f5 $1 {Wisely shutting down the bishop on [c8], albeit at the cost of having to allow ...[Qg2].} Qg2 {[%csl Gh1] Having said 'A', Black might as well say 'B' and invade with the queen.} 15. Rf1 f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg2h2,Gc8d7] Sensibly securing [e5] and so threatening ...[Qxh2], as well as just to continue development with ...[Bd7] and ...[Rc8]. That pretty much compels White to force the pace, and there are now two important lines, in both of which Black is fine.} 16. Nxd5 {[%csl Re8][%cal Rc7e7] The obvious try.} Nxd5 17. Qxg7 {[%csl Rd5,Rh8] The double-attack may look scary, but White's own king is far from being entirely happy.} Nb4 $1 {[%csl Ge1,Gf1][%cal Gb4d3]} 18. Qxh8+ Ke7 (18... Ke7 {Renewing the threat of} 19. Z0 Nxd3+ 20. Kd1 Qxf1+ {. In view of his undeveloped queenside, White has nothing better than to force perpetual check, and not with 19.Qxh7+? Kd6 , but rather 19. [Qg7]+.}) 19. Qg7+ $1 Ke8 20. Qg8+ Ke7 {[%csl Gf6] Ensuring that [f6] won't fall with tempo. Neither side can really avoid the draw.} *

