1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. h4 $5 {Another very aggressive advance and one Black surely shouldn't fear.} h6 $1 (11... h6 {We like this modest advance, simply preventing Bg5. The pawn on h4 will now look a little strange if White castles, and it's also hard to believe that the insertion of h2-h4 and ...h6 gives him an improved version of Line 2A in the event of} 12. exd5 Nexd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 {. As such, a creative and bold opponent might prefer to continue in the style of our previous line.}) 12. f4 $5 {[%csl Re5] As played in Mogirzan-Nunez, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, and, of course, the ...[Qh4]+ ideas we used against the immediate 11. [f4] are no longer applicable.} d4 $5 {[%cal Gd4c3,Ge7c6]} (12... d4 {Black's most ambitious approach, and he will surely now be able to gain sufficient counterplay after} 13. Ne2 Nec6 {or 13.fxe5?! Qg6 .}) 13. Na4 $5 {[%cal Ra4b6]} Bg4 $1 (13... Bg4 {The point of Black's play, exploiting the downside to 11.h4 and preparing to meet} 14. Nb6 {with} Rd8 {. Now 14.Qxb7 Nxd3+ 15.cxd3 O-O would leave Black with the safer king and promising play for a pawn, while 14.Qxe5? Qxe5 15.fxe5 Rc8! is another important point and leaves Black doing pretty well. As such, White might prefer the other capture.}) 14. fxe5 Qg6 $5 {[%cal Ga8c8]} ({Angling for more than the far-from-silly} 14... Qc6 {would and now} 15. Nb6 Rd8 {(again keeps everything under control, while even allowing Black to castle if [Qxe7] then ...[Qxb6] will be on. There are two other important lines.)}) 15. Qxb7 $4 {[%csl Ra8,Rb4]} Nxd3+ {[%csl Ge1] A simple way of dealing with the double attack, and it's Black's next, which is the stunner.} 16. cxd3 Bc8 $3 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gg6g2] Olé! All of sudden White appears to be lost, despite being able to go a rook ahead.} 17. Qxa8 Qxg2 {[%cal Gg2h1]} 18. Rf1 O-O {[%csl Ga8,Ge1][%cal Gc8h3,Gc8g4] White is a rook and pawn up, but completely unable to deal with the major threats of 19...[Bh3] and 19...[Bg4], since there's just not enough time to bring his queen to safety.} (18... O-O {For example,} 19. Qa7 Nc6 {And why not activate with tempo. Black might even now be able to make good use of ...[Nxe5].} 20. Qc5 Bg4 21. Rf2 Qh1+ {Of course, it will be mate on [d1] if the king now moves.} 22. Rf1 Qxh4+ 23. Rf2 {Another rather forced move.} Qh1+ 24. Rf1 Qg2 $1 {Renewing the mate threat and, no, Black is not after a draw.} 25. Rf2 Qg1+ 26. Rf1 Qg3+ $1 {Forcing the rook to move once again.} 27. Rf2 Nxe5 {Black's initiative is just far too strong, with the threats of 28...[Nxd3]+ and 28...[Nf3]+ completely ruinous.}) *

