1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. a3 {[%csl Rb4] White's third most common move, simply seeking to end the queenside tension straightaway.} Nxd3+ {Naturally, Black removes the bishop ahead of looking to castle and complete development.} 12. cxd3 (12. cxd3 {Here Black has often been happy to go} d4 {, but why allow White chances for an edge after} 13. Na4 $1 {when the d-pawn isn't really attacked?}) 12... O-O $5 {[%cal Gc8e6]} (12... O-O {Rapid development is Black's watchword. Now ...Be6 may follow or even ...Qg6, while} 13. Nxd5 $6 Nxd5 14. exd5 {can be well enough met by} Qg6 {or even 14...Rd8 .}) 13. exd5 {Accepting the pawn this way is a little risky, but also a fairly critical test of Black's gambit approach.} Qg6 $1 {[%csl Gd3,Ge7,Gg2][%cal Gg6g2]} (13... Qg6 {Hitting d3, as well as g2, and now it's not impossible to imagine a lowly-rated opponent allowing Black a decisive early advantage after} 14. O-O $4 Bh3 {. Yes, the knight on [e7] is hanging, but it shouldn't be too hard to appreciate that 14.Qxe7?? Qxg2 15.Rf1 Bh3 would also be most unwise for White.}) 14. Qxe5 Qxg2 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gg2h1,Gc8h3]} 15. Qe4 $1 {The point of White's play.} Bh3 $1 {[%cal Ga8d8,Ge7d5,Gf8e8,Gh3g2,Gf7f5] And we reveal the point of our play, being ready to recapture on [g2] in the event of a queen exchange, thereby forking the rook and [d5]-pawn.} (15... Bh3 {Meanwhile ...Rfe8 or just ...Rad8 and ...Nxd5 is on the way, while} 16. Be3 {could even be met by} f5 {.}) 16. Qxg2 Bxg2 17. Rg1 {[%csl Rg2]} Bf3 $5 ({Sidestepping any issues with} 17... Bxd5 18. Bh6 $1 {. Now 18.Bh6?! can be met by 18...Nf5 and, likewise, 18.d6 Nf5 will see Black regaining the pawn with an edge. Meanwhile ...[Rad8] and ...[Rfe8] are imminent and Black is at least equal.}) *

