1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. a3 {[%csl Rb4] White's third most common move, simply seeking to end the queenside tension straightaway.} Nxd3+ {Naturally, Black removes the bishop ahead of looking to castle and complete development.} 12. cxd3 (12. cxd3 {Here Black has often been happy to go} d4 {, but why allow White chances for an edge after} 13. Na4 $1 {when the d-pawn isn't really attacked?}) 12... O-O $5 {[%cal Gc8e6]} (12... O-O {Rapid development is Black's watchword. Now ...Be6 may follow or even ...Qg6, while} 13. Nxd5 $6 Nxd5 14. exd5 {can be well enough met by} Qg6 {or even 14...Rd8 .}) 13. O-O Be6 $1 {[%csl Gd5]} ({Continuing to retain the tension, whereas} 13... d4 $6 14. Na4 $1 Be6 15. Nb6 Rab8 16. f4 $1 {(gave White the initiative in a battle of Lowenthal experts, Snape-P.Richmond, Daventry rapid 2014.)}) {The text move secures d5 and only now may Black consider 14...d4 when 15.Na4 Rac8! 16.Qxb7 Ng6 would supply a strong initiative for the pawn, with ...[Rc2] imminent and White also vulnerable on the kingside.} 14. exd5 Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5c7,Ge6d5]} 15. Qxb7 Rfd8 {[%csl Gd3,Gg1][%cal Gf6g6,Gd5c3,Ge6d5]} (15... Rfd8 {Black is a pawn down, but has full compensation for it, with ...Qg6 next up and d3 highly vulnerable. White can avoid a trade of knights, but also has no advantage after} 16. Ne4 Qg6 {when 17...[Bh3] may well be a threat.}) 16. Nxd5 $6 Bxd5 {[%csl Gb7]} 17. Qb4 Qg6 {[%cal Gg6g2]} (17... Qg6 {Threatening mate and now} 18. g3 $2 Qf5 {would be most unwise for White, in view of} 19. f3 Bxf3 $1 {.}) 18. f3 $1 Bc6 {[%cal Gd8d3] With 19...[Rxd3] next up, the initiative clearly belongs to Black and the presence of opposite-coloured bishops can only assist the attacker. That clearly isn't White who will have to defend accurately to draw.} *

