[GameId "2141525855823073"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. a3 {[%csl Rb4] White's third most common move, simply seeking to end the queenside tension straightaway.} Nxd3+ {Naturally, Black removes the bishop ahead of looking to castle and complete development.} 12. cxd3 (12. cxd3 {Here Black has often been happy to go} d4 {, but why allow White chances for an edge after} 13. Na4 $1 {when the d-pawn isn't really attacked?}) 12... O-O $5 {[%cal Gc8e6]} (12... O-O {Rapid development is Black's watchword. Now ...Be6 may follow or even ...Qg6, while} 13. Nxd5 $6 Nxd5 14. exd5 {can be well enough met by} Qg6 {or even 14...Rd8 .}) 13. O-O Be6 $1 {[%csl Gd5]} ({Continuing to retain the tension, whereas} 13... d4 $6 14. Na4 $1 Be6 15. Nb6 Rab8 16. f4 $1 {(gave White the initiative in a battle of Lowenthal experts, Snape-P.Richmond, Daventry rapid 2014.)}) {The text move secures d5 and only now may Black consider 14...d4 when 15.Na4 Rac8! 16.Qxb7 Ng6 would supply a strong initiative for the pawn, with ...[Rc2] imminent and White also vulnerable on the kingside.} 14. Bd2 $2 d4 $1 {Forcing the pace with [Na4] no longer an issue now that the bishop has escaped from [c8].} 15. Na4 {[%cal Ra4b6]} Rac8 $1 {A powerful pawn sacrifice, activating the rook before White can get in [Nb6].} 16. Qxb7 Ng6 {[%csl Gf4]} (16... Ng6 {Black now controls f4, meaning that} 17. f4 $5 {can just be met by} exf4 {. Meanwhile 17...[Rc2] is imminent, as is ...[Nh4] and already the engines think that Black is just doing pretty well due to the imminent kingside attack.}) 17. Bb4 $2 ({A} 17. Rac1 $2 Nh4 $1 {Threatening 18...[Qg6] and already there's just no good defence for White.} 18. Rxc8 Bxc8 $1 19. Qb6 Nf3+ $1 {A graphic illustration of White's difficulties. ((It will quickly be mate after 20.gxf3 Qxf3 and 21...Bh3 , and neither does moving the king especially help.))} 20. Kh1 Qh4 $1 {((Preparing to force mate on h2 or after 21.h3 Bxh3!. ) . )} 21. gxf3 Qh3 $1 {The light-square attack will force mate after all.}) ({B} 17. f4 $5 {This desperate advance is the best defence the engines can find.} exf4 {Now Black may go ...[Qg5] after all.} 18. Qb4 h6 $1 {The engines love this little move, which avoids any back rank issues, and it's certainly hard to find a good reply for White. If he takes the pressure off [f4], ...[Nh4] or just ...[Ne5] may well be rather unpleasant, and meanwhile Black will go 19...Rc2 or even 19...Rb8!? 20.Qa5 Rb5! 21.Qxa6 Rh5! , with a very strong attack after ...[Qh4]. For example: 19.Rab1 (( 19.Rac1 Rxc1! ['key': 'C', 'state': 'VVV', 'val': 'Well-timed as if now', 'key': 'S', 'state': 'VVV', 'val': '20.Rxc1?', 'key': 'C', 'state': 'VVV', 'val': 'then', 'key': 'S', 'state': 'VVV', 'val': '20...Nh4', 'key': 'C', 'state': 'VVV', 'val': 'will leave White in huge trouble on the kingside.'] 20.Bxc1 Rc8 Black is doing very well, with much the safer king and ...[Rc2] one idea, ...[Bg4]-[e2] another.)) 19...Rb8! 20.Qa5 Rb5! Continuing to active with tempo. 21.Qxa6 Rh5 ((And now 22...Qh4 is a big threat and White would also be facing a huge attack after 22.Be1 Qg5. ) . ) 22.Qd6 Rd8 Involving the final piece with gain of tempo. 23.Qc7 Rc8 24.Qd6 Rc2! All Black's pieces are attacking and we can easily let the [f4]-pawn go. 25.Bxf4 Nh4 White is completely busted with [g2] en prise and Black always having ...[Qg6] in reserve if needed.}) 17... Qg5 $1 {[%cal Gg6f4,Ge6h3,Gg6h4] A superb spot for the queen, one which leaves Black threatening not just ...[Bh3], but both ...[Nh4] and ...[Nf4] which would also attack [d3]. Already we're at '+4' for Black in engine speak.} 18. Bxf8 $2 Nh4 {[%csl Gg1][%cal Gg5g2]} 19. g3 Nf3+ {[%csl Gg1][%cal Gg5g4,Gg5h5]} (19... Nf3+ {White is going to be mated, be it after} 20. Kh1 Qh5 {or...}) 20. Kg2 Qg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4h3]} 21. h3 Qxh3+ 22. Kxf3 Bg4# *

