 to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. a3 {[%csl Rb4] White's third most common move, simply seeking to end the queenside tension straightaway.} Nxd3+ {Naturally, Black removes the bishop ahead of looking to castle and complete development.} 12. cxd3 (12. cxd3 {Here Black has often been happy to go} d4 {, but why allow White chances for an edge after} 13. Na4 $1 {when the d-pawn isn't really attacked?}) 12... O-O $5 {[%cal Gc8e6]} (12... O-O {Rapid development is Black's watchword. Now ...Be6 may follow or even ...Qg6, while} 13. Nxd5 $6 Nxd5 14. exd5 {can be well enough met by} Qg6 {or even 14...Rd8 .}) 13. O-O Be6 $1 {[%csl Gd5]} ({Continuing to retain the tension, whereas} 13... d4 $6 14. Na4 $1 Be6 15. Nb6 Rab8 16. f4 $1 {(gave White the initiative in a battle of Lowenthal experts, Snape-P.Richmond, Daventry rapid 2014.)}) {The text move secures d5 and only now may Black consider 14...d4 when 15.Na4 Rac8! 16.Qxb7 Ng6 would supply a strong initiative for the pawn, with ...[Rc2] imminent and White also vulnerable on the kingside.} 14. f4 $5 {[%csl Re5] A radical response, counterattacking against [e5].} exf4 {[%cal Gf6d4,Ge7g6]} (14... exf4 {Simple chess, as Black gets ready to meet} 15. Bxf4 {with} Qd4+ {then ...[Ng6].}) (14... d4 $5 {is also possible and should be tried if you really have to win.}) 15. e5 $5 {[%csl Re7]} Qh4 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Ge7g6] Keeping the knight defended while getting ready to activate with ...[Ng6].} 16. Rxf4 {[%csl Rh4]} Qe1+ $1 17. Rf1 Qh4 (17... Qh4 {With Black threatening 18...Qd4+ and also having such moves as ...d4 and ...Nf5 available, it's not a total surprise the engines indicate White should settle for a repetition here with} 18. Rf4 $1 Qe1+ 19. Rf1 {, etc.}) *

