 to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. a3 {[%csl Rb4] White's third most common move, simply seeking to end the queenside tension straightaway.} Nxd3+ {Naturally, Black removes the bishop ahead of looking to castle and complete development.} 12. cxd3 (12. cxd3 {Here Black has often been happy to go} d4 {, but why allow White chances for an edge after} 13. Na4 $1 {when the d-pawn isn't really attacked?}) 12... O-O $5 {[%cal Gc8e6]} (12... O-O {Rapid development is Black's watchword. Now ...Be6 may follow or even ...Qg6, while} 13. Nxd5 $6 Nxd5 14. exd5 {can be well enough met by} Qg6 {or even 14...Rd8 .}) 13. O-O Be6 $1 {[%csl Gd5]} ({Continuing to retain the tension, whereas} 13... d4 $6 14. Na4 $1 Be6 15. Nb6 Rab8 16. f4 $1 {(gave White the initiative in a battle of Lowenthal experts, Snape-P.Richmond, Daventry rapid 2014.)}) {The text move secures d5 and only now may Black consider 14...d4 when 15.Na4 Rac8! 16.Qxb7 Ng6 would supply a strong initiative for the pawn, with ...[Rc2] imminent and White also vulnerable on the kingside.} 14. Qxb7 {Swiping the pawn so must be fairly critical.} d4 $1 {[%cal Gf6g6,Gd4c3,Gf8b8,Gb8c8,Gc8c2]} (14... d4 {(Forcing the pace. Black's play on both flanks White's king can easily find itself quite vulnerable after ...Qg6 supplies full compensation for the pawn, and we will be able to activate with tempo, such as by)} 15. Ne2 Rfb8 $1 16. Qc7 Rc8 {, looking to invade next on [c2]. Seemingly better that for White though than still trying to activate the knight via the rim.}) 15. Na4 $2 Rac8 $1 {[%cal Gc8c2]} (15... Rac8 {Probably the best of a few tempting options. Black activates the rook and pretty much takes} 16. f4 $2 {off the table in view of} Qg6 {.}) 16. Nb6 {[%cal Rb6d7]} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Ga6,Gb7]} (16... Rb8 {A change of approach to avoid Nd7 and to set a certain trap. Yes,} 17. Qxa6 $4 Bc8 $1 {would be an unexpected change of direction and neat retreat to material.}) 17. Qc7 Bh3 $1 {[%csl Gg1][%cal Gb8b6,Gf6g6] The dual threats of 18...[Rxb6] and 18...[Qg6] ensure that Black is somewhat for choice, with a powerful kingside attack brewing.} (17... Bh3 {For example,} 18. gxh3 Rxb6 {((The threat is 19.-- Rc8 20.Qd7 Qf3!. ) . )} 19. f4 $1 Ng6 $1 {((Threatening to go 20...Rc6 then 21...exf4 and 20.fxe5? Qe6 would only serve to help Black's attack.))} 20. f5 Rc6 21. Qa5 Rc2 $1 {The knight on [g6] is clearly taboo and meanwhile, Black is set to increase the pressure with ...[Nh4] and ... [Rfc8], leaving us with superb and much more than enough play for the pawn.}) *

