1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. exd5 {White's simplest and second most popular choice ( 11.O-O is even more popular and the subject of the next chapter, eliminating any notion of ...[d4] once and for all.)} (11. Nxd5 {A less forcing move order.} Nexd5 12. exd5 Nxd5 ({Play has transposed to our main line exd5 Nexd5} 12... Nxd5 {Nxd5})) {. ( 12...Nxd3+!? White's move order gives Black this additional option, declining to regain the pawn, but weakening White's structure and light squares somewhat. 13.cxd3 O-O 14.O-O Rd8 This ensured that Black would regain the pawn and was absolutely fine for him in Kerek-Bako, Hungarian League 1995, and similar sentiments also appear here to Nigel Povah's old recommendation of 14...Bf5!? . )} 11... Nexd5 {[%cal Gd5c7,Gb4d3]} ({Regaining the pawn with tempo and not allowing it to very dangerously live with} 11... Nxd3+ $2 12. cxd3 O-O $2 13. d6 {.}) 12. Nxd5 {Pretty much forced if White wants to avoid any structural damage on [d3].} Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5c7] Clearly White will have to move the queen, after which he does have the bishop-pair, but Black shouldn't have too much to fear. Richard has often defended this position at blitz and Black's nicely centralised knight is a good piece, while after ... [Be6] development is almost complete.} 13. Qa5 $5 {[%csl Rd5]} ({A slightly more sneaky policy than} 13. Qc5 {. White attacks the knight and has also spied the pin on the a-file, meaning that [Bb5]+ is possible.}) 13... Be6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge8g8]} ({Black shouldn't fear the check and should calmly continue development so. In the cold light of 2024 it transpires that another old idea of Nigel Povah's, namely} 13... Ne7 $5 14. Bb5+ axb5 $2 15. Qxa8 Qg6 {fails to} 16. O-O O-O 17. Qa3 {, although here 14...[Nc6]!? is not totally ridiculous.}) 14. Bb5+ Kf8 $1 {[%cal Gf6d8,Gh7h6,Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Gf8g8,Gg8h7]} (14... Kf8 {The right square for the king. In some lines Black will be able to castle by hand, and we are now set to challenge White's pieces with 15...Qd8, as well as ready to meet} 15. Qa3+ $6 {with} Qe7 {.}) 15. O-O (15. Bd3 Qd8 16. Qd2 $5 Qc7 {A decent square for the queen. Black can now look to go ...[Rd8], as well as activate with ...[Nf4].} 17. b3 Rd8 {Introducing ideas of ...[e4], as well as of ...[Nf4].} 18. O-O {!} f6 $1 {((Keeping everything tight as there's no good follow-up to 18...e4? 19.Bxe4. ) . )} 19. Qe2 Kf7 20. c4 {(Here a draw was agreed in a fairly high-level correspondence encounter 2463 vs 2514, Drugda-Koegler, ICCF email 2007. Black is absolutely fine after)} Ne7 {or even 20...Nc3!? 21.Qc2 Qd6 22.Bxh7 e4! ((Trapping the bishop unless White wants to fall for 23.Bxe4?? Qxh2# . )) 23.Qxc3 Rxh7 24.Qg3 Qd7 Black's kingside pressure offers enough compensation for the pawn.}) 15... Qd8 $1 {[%csl Ga5,Gb5] The aforementioned retreat, one which appears to be almost a clean equaliser.} 16. Qa3+ Qe7 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gf8e7,Gf7f6,Ge7a3]} (16... Qe7 {Continuing to offer the trade of queens and if White now tries to maintain the tension with} 17. b3 {, Black can simply free a different square for the king with} f6 {. In any case, Black is absolutely fine here.}) (16... Qe7 {For example,} 17. Qxe7+ Kxe7 18. Bd3 f5 $5 {Beginning to seize as much space as possible. (( 18...Nb4 19.Be4 Bd5 is also absolutely fine, although after 20.Bd2! opposite-coloured bishops would occur.))} 19. Bd2 Kf6 $5 {Black continues the kingside policy and will likely follow up with ...[g5]. A move on the other flank in ...[Rac8] could well prove useful too, while we're aiming to provoke} 20. c4 Nf4 $1 21. Bxf4 exf4 {when Black's king is much the more active and White slightly vulnerable on the d-file and [c4]. ( 19...e4?! 20.Be2 Rac8 21.c4! (This isn't so good for Black and gave White a definite edge after 22. [b3] next, with his unopposed dark-squared bishop beginning to look a little annoying in A.Jackson-S.Ledger, British League 4NCL 2005.))}) *

