[GameId "2141525856097510"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. exd5 {White's simplest and second most popular choice ( 11.O-O is even more popular and the subject of the next chapter, eliminating any notion of ...[d4] once and for all.)} (11. Nxd5 {A less forcing move order.} Nexd5 12. exd5 Nxd5 ({Play has transposed to our main line exd5 Nexd5} 12... Nxd5 {Nxd5})) {. ( 12...Nxd3+!? White's move order gives Black this additional option, declining to regain the pawn, but weakening White's structure and light squares somewhat. 13.cxd3 O-O 14.O-O Rd8 This ensured that Black would regain the pawn and was absolutely fine for him in Kerek-Bako, Hungarian League 1995, and similar sentiments also appear here to Nigel Povah's old recommendation of 14...Bf5!? . )} 11... Nexd5 {[%cal Gd5c7,Gb4d3]} ({Regaining the pawn with tempo and not allowing it to very dangerously live with} 11... Nxd3+ $2 12. cxd3 O-O $2 13. d6 {.}) 12. Nxd5 {Pretty much forced if White wants to avoid any structural damage on [d3].} Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5c7] Clearly White will have to move the queen, after which he does have the bishop-pair, but Black shouldn't have too much to fear. Richard has often defended this position at blitz and Black's nicely centralised knight is a good piece, while after ... [Be6] development is almost complete.} 13. Qc5 {[%csl Rd5,Re8] White's most common choice, attacking the knight while preventing Black from castling.} Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8] Naturally Black develops the final minor piece and gets ready to go ...[Rc8].} 14. O-O Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c5,Gf6e7] There's no reason not to deploy the rook with tempo before challenging the white queen with ...[Qe7].} 15. Qd6 {[%csl Re5] Hoping that [e5] can be targeted, but Black isn't going to allow the queen to stay on [d6].} Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d6,Gf6e7] Continuing to attack the white queen before dropping its black counterpart back to [e7].} 16. Qa3 Qe7 {[%cal Ge7a3,Gd5b4,Ge8e7]} (16... Qe7 {Black hopes to mash up the white queenside pawns or perhaps to get in a timely ...Nb4. Now} 17. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {would connect the rooks whilst keeping the knight well centralised, and we'll return to this position in the illustrative game Schramm-Tomczak, German League 1995.}) 17. Qa4+ $5 Bd7 {[%csl Ga4]} ({The obvious way to block, although if you're playing for a win and wanting to keep pieces on, it should be said that there isn't too much wrong with} 17... Rd7 $5 18. Bd2 f6 $1 {and ...[Kf7], if not here 18...O-O? 19.Qe4! when White would win a pawn.}) 18. Qe4 {[%csl Rd5]} Nb4 {[%cal Gd7c6,Gb4d3] (Forcing the pace the other way of doing so, 18...Bc6 19.Re1 Nb4 , is OK too,) as Black goes after the bishop on [d3] while clearing a path for ...[Bc6].} 19. Qxb7 {The proof of the pudding must lie in the eating, although here the queen doesn't do too much unlike if the black rook was still on [c8], and we're able to force exchanges on our terms.} Nxd3 20. cxd3 Bb5 $1 {[%csl Gb7,Gd3] Going straight after the weakling on [d3].} 21. Qxe7+ Kxe7 22. Re1 {[%csl Re5]} Kf6 {[%csl Gd3] Black will regain the pawn on [d3], with full equality.} *

