 to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. exd5 {White's simplest and second most popular choice ( 11.O-O is even more popular and the subject of the next chapter, eliminating any notion of ...[d4] once and for all.)} (11. Nxd5 {A less forcing move order.} Nexd5 12. exd5 Nxd5 ({Play has transposed to our main line exd5 Nexd5} 12... Nxd5 {Nxd5})) {. ( 12...Nxd3+!? White's move order gives Black this additional option, declining to regain the pawn, but weakening White's structure and light squares somewhat. 13.cxd3 O-O 14.O-O Rd8 This ensured that Black would regain the pawn and was absolutely fine for him in Kerek-Bako, Hungarian League 1995, and similar sentiments also appear here to Nigel Povah's old recommendation of 14...Bf5!? . )} 11... Nexd5 {[%cal Gd5c7,Gb4d3]} ({Regaining the pawn with tempo and not allowing it to very dangerously live with} 11... Nxd3+ $2 12. cxd3 O-O $2 13. d6 {.}) 12. Nxd5 {Pretty much forced if White wants to avoid any structural damage on [d3].} Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5c7] Clearly White will have to move the queen, after which he does have the bishop-pair, but Black shouldn't have too much to fear. Richard has often defended this position at blitz and Black's nicely centralised knight is a good piece, while after ... [Be6] development is almost complete.} 13. Qc5 {[%csl Rd5,Re8] White's most common choice, attacking the knight while preventing Black from castling.} Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8] Naturally Black develops the final minor piece and gets ready to go ...[Rc8].} 14. O-O Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c5,Gf6e7] There's no reason not to deploy the rook with tempo before challenging the white queen with ...[Qe7].} 15. Qa3 {The most challenging square for White to place the queen.} Qe7 {[%cal Ge7a3,Gd5b4,Ge8g8] Once again, preparing the way for not just ...[Qxa3] or ...[Nb4], but to safely castle kingside.} 16. Qa4+ $5 {A slightly more tricky try, aiming to discombobulate.} Bd7 {Just like after 15.Qd6 Rd8 16.Qa3 Qe7 17.Qa4+ , Black shouldn't fear making this obvious block, although it should be said that 16...[Rc6]!? is also playable if you wanted to avoid what now follows.} 17. Qe4 $1 (17. Qe4 {The point of White's play and now} Bc6 18. Re1 {was slightly annoying for Black in Garcia Canio-Dickl, Catalan League 2008.}) 17... Nb4 $1 {This is yet to receive an over-the-board test, but playing just as we would with the rook on [d8], looks like the best policy for Black.} 18. Qxb7 Nxd3 {Removing a potentially powerful bishop while again creating a target on [d3].} 19. cxd3 O-O $5 ({With the rook on d8, we would, of course, have gone} 19... Bb5 {, but here we instead sacrifice a second pawn.}) {Having castled, Black is now ready to go 20...Qe6 ( 19...Qe6 20.Qb4 is slightly annoying, hence sacrificing a6 ,) then ...[Bb5], with a firm light-square blockade. As such, White might well accept the offer.} 20. Qxa6 Rc6 $1 {[%csl Ga6,Gd3,Gg2][%cal Gc6g6] This rook lift is the main point of the second pawn sacrifice. The rook will swing over to [g6] and with targets on [g2] and [d3], the engines indicate that Black should have enough for the two pawns. That may initially seem surprising, but White's queenside pawns aren't going anywhere fast and the presence of opposite-coloured bishops usually helps the side with the initiative, which is Black.} *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2B) 8.Qc7 with 11.exd5"]
[Black "8.Qc7 with 11.exd5 Nexd5 12.Nxd5 \[Illustrative\]"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "60"]
[GameId "2141525856228585"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. exd5 {White's simplest and second most popular choice ( 11.O-O is even more popular and the subject of the next chapter, eliminating any notion of ...[d4] once and for all.)} (11. Nxd5 {A less forcing move order.} Nexd5 12. exd5 Nxd5 ({Play has transposed to our main line exd5 Nexd5} 12... Nxd5 {Nxd5})) {. ( 12...Nxd3+!? White's move order gives Black this additional option, declining to regain the pawn, but weakening White's structure and light squares somewhat. 13.cxd3 O-O 14.O-O Rd8 This ensured that Black would regain the pawn and was absolutely fine for him in Kerek-Bako, Hungarian League 1995, and similar sentiments also appear here to Nigel Povah's old recommendation of 14...Bf5!? . )} 11... Nexd5 {[%cal Gd5c7,Gb4d3]} ({Regaining the pawn with tempo and not allowing it to very dangerously live with} 11... Nxd3+ $2 12. cxd3 O-O $2 13. d6 {.}) 12. Nxd5 {Pretty much forced if White wants to avoid any structural damage on [d3].} Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5c7] Clearly White will have to move the queen, after which he does have the bishop-pair, but Black shouldn't have too much to fear. Richard has often defended this position at blitz and Black's nicely centralised knight is a good piece, while after ... [Be6] development is almost complete.} 13. Qc5 {[%csl Rd5,Re8] White's most common choice, attacking the knight while preventing Black from castling.} Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8] Naturally Black develops the final minor piece and gets ready to go ...[Rc8].} 14. O-O Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c5,Gf6e7] There's no reason not to deploy the rook with tempo before challenging the white queen with ...[Qe7].} 15. Qa3 {The most challenging square for White to place the queen.} Qe7 {[%cal Ge7a3,Gd5b4,Ge8g8] Once again, preparing the way for not just ...[Qxa3] or ...[Nb4], but to safely castle kingside.} 16. Qa4+ $5 {A slightly more tricky try, aiming to discombobulate.} Bd7 {Just like after 15.Qd6 Rd8 16.Qa3 Qe7 17.Qa4+ , Black shouldn't fear making this obvious block, although it should be said that 16...[Rc6]!? is also playable if you wanted to avoid what now follows.} 17. Qe4 $1 (17. Qe4 {The point of White's play and now} Bc6 18. Re1 {was slightly annoying for Black in Garcia Canio-Dickl, Catalan League 2008.}) 17... Nb4 $1 {This is yet to receive an over-the-board test, but playing just as we would with the rook on [d8], looks like the best policy for Black.} 18. Qxb7 Nxd3 {Removing a potentially powerful bishop while again creating a target on [d3].} 19. cxd3 O-O $5 ({With the rook on d8, we would, of course, have gone} 19... Bb5 {, but here we instead sacrifice a second pawn.}) {Having castled, Black is now ready to go 20...Qe6 ( 19...Qe6 20.Qb4 is slightly annoying, hence sacrificing a6 ,) then ...[Bb5], with a firm light-square blockade. As such, White might well accept the offer.} 20. Qxa6 Rc6 $1 {[%csl Ga6,Gd3,Gg2][%cal Gc6g6] This rook lift is the main point of the second pawn sacrifice. The rook will swing over to [g6] and with targets on [g2] and [d3], the engines indicate that Black should have enough for the two pawns. That may initially seem surprising, but White's queenside pawns aren't going anywhere fast and the presence of opposite-coloured bishops usually helps the side with the initiative, which is Black.Let's see an example.} 21. Qa5 Rg6 {[%cal Gd7h3,Gd7c6] Threatening to win the exchange with ...[Bh3], as well as go ...[Bc6].} 22. f3 Bc6 $1 {[%csl Gb2,Gd3,Gf3][%cal Ge7b7,Gf8d8] Still the best square for the bishop. Black may now increase the pressure on the kingside with ...Qb7 ( 23.Bd2 Qb7 would immediately regain a pawn,) or build up against the weakling on [d3], beginning with ...[Rd8].} 23. Qc3 Qb7 {[%cal Gc6f3]} 24. Kh1 Rc8 {[%cal Gc6f3]} (24... Rc8 {Renewing a certain threat and now the engines indicate that White hasn't anything better than} 25. Qb3 {when} Qxb3 26. axb3 Rd6 {would regain one pawn and be pretty drawish.}) 25. Qe1 f5 $1 {Black retains the initiative and dangerous compensation, which is no surprise if you compare the difference in terms of activity and coordination between the two sides' forces. Now ...[e4] is threatened, blowing open the long diagonal, and taking the [e5]-pawn would be a risky business:} 26. Qxe5 $2 Re8 $1 27. Qxf5 Re2 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Gg6g2,Ge2g2]} (27... Re2 {(Black is four pawns down!, but there's no good way to defend g2 in view of)} 28. Rg1 $2 Bxf3 $1 {.}) 28. Bg5 $1 {Seemingly the only real defence.} (28. Bf4 $2 Rexg2 29. Bg3 Rxb2 {It's now only two pawns and ...[Rf6] or ...[Rb5] will follow.}) 28... Bd7 {[%csl Gf5,Gg5]} 29. Qf4 h6 {[%csl Gg5] In view of a certain tactic, Black is winning material and will emerge with the upper hand.} 30. Bh4 Rg4 $1 {[%csl Gf4,Gh4] The bishop will fall.} *

