1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. exd5 {White's simplest and second most popular choice ( 11.O-O is even more popular and the subject of the next chapter, eliminating any notion of ...[d4] once and for all.)} (11. Nxd5 {A less forcing move order.} Nexd5 12. exd5 Nxd5 ({Play has transposed to our main line exd5 Nexd5} 12... Nxd5 {Nxd5})) {. ( 12...Nxd3+!? White's move order gives Black this additional option, declining to regain the pawn, but weakening White's structure and light squares somewhat. 13.cxd3 O-O 14.O-O Rd8 This ensured that Black would regain the pawn and was absolutely fine for him in Kerek-Bako, Hungarian League 1995, and similar sentiments also appear here to Nigel Povah's old recommendation of 14...Bf5!? . )} 11... Nexd5 {[%cal Gd5c7,Gb4d3]} ({Regaining the pawn with tempo and not allowing it to very dangerously live with} 11... Nxd3+ $2 12. cxd3 O-O $2 13. d6 {.}) 12. Nxd5 {Pretty much forced if White wants to avoid any structural damage on [d3].} Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5c7] Clearly White will have to move the queen, after which he does have the bishop-pair, but Black shouldn't have too much to fear. Richard has often defended this position at blitz and Black's nicely centralised knight is a good piece, while after ... [Be6] development is almost complete.} 13. Qc5 {[%csl Rd5,Re8] White's most common choice, attacking the knight while preventing Black from castling.} Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8] Naturally Black develops the final minor piece and gets ready to go ...[Rc8].} 14. O-O Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c5,Gf6e7] There's no reason not to deploy the rook with tempo before challenging the white queen with ...[Qe7].} 15. Qa3 {The most challenging square for White to place the queen.} Qe7 {[%cal Ge7a3,Gd5b4,Ge8g8] Once again, preparing the way for not just ...[Qxa3] or ...[Nb4], but to safely castle kingside.} 16. Qxe7+ {A simple approach, but Black's well-centralised forces will comfortably offset White's two bishops.} Kxe7 {[%cal Gd5b4] Just like with the rook on [d8] not [c8], this should be a fairly comfortable set-up for Black, with the centralised knight and good coordination.} 17. Bd2 {[%csl Rb4] Wisely cutting out the possibility of ...[Nb4].} Rhd8 {[%cal Gd5f4,Gf7f5] Centralising the final piece. Black may now look to expand with ...[f5] Bg5+ can always be met by ...[Nf6], or press forwards with ...[Nf4].} 18. Rae1 {[%csl Re5]} (18. Rae1 {Attacking e5 and hoping to seize the initiative in the event of} Kf6 $6 19. f4 $1 {.}) 18... Nf4 $1 {[%csl Gd8][%cal Gf4d3] (Unbalancing the pawn structure the alternative for White is to allow Black full equality with 19.Rxe5 Nxd3 20.cxd3 Rxd3 , by counterattacking down the d-file.)} 19. Bxf4 exf4 20. Re4 {[%csl Rf4]} g5 $1 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Ge7f6,Gb7b5,Gc8c5] This was very comfortable for Black in Grabarczyk-Pedzich, Polish Championship, Sopot 1997. If White is careless, his restricted kingside might become a problem and meanwhile he isn't getting anywhere on the queenside, while Black may improve the pieces with such moves as ...[Rc5], ...[b5] and ...[Kf6].} *

