{Black is nominally for choice with the more active pieces, but White should be able to hold the rook ending after Rd4+ or b4 Rxa2 Rd7 , without too much difficulty.} 1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. exd5 {White's simplest and second most popular choice ( 11.O-O is even more popular and the subject of the next chapter, eliminating any notion of ...[d4] once and for all.)} (11. Nxd5 {A less forcing move order.} Nexd5 12. exd5 Nxd5 ({Play has transposed to our main line exd5 Nexd5} 12... Nxd5 {Nxd5})) {. ( 12...Nxd3+!? White's move order gives Black this additional option, declining to regain the pawn, but weakening White's structure and light squares somewhat. 13.cxd3 O-O 14.O-O Rd8 This ensured that Black would regain the pawn and was absolutely fine for him in Kerek-Bako, Hungarian League 1995, and similar sentiments also appear here to Nigel Povah's old recommendation of 14...Bf5!? . )} 11... Nexd5 {[%cal Gd5c7,Gb4d3]} ({Regaining the pawn with tempo and not allowing it to very dangerously live with} 11... Nxd3+ $2 12. cxd3 O-O $2 13. d6 {.}) 12. Nxd5 {Pretty much forced if White wants to avoid any structural damage on [d3].} Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5c7] Clearly White will have to move the queen, after which he does have the bishop-pair, but Black shouldn't have too much to fear. Richard has often defended this position at blitz and Black's nicely centralised knight is a good piece, while after ... [Be6] development is almost complete.} 13. Qc5 {[%csl Rd5,Re8] White's most common choice, attacking the knight while preventing Black from castling.} Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8] Naturally Black develops the final minor piece and gets ready to go ...[Rc8].} 14. O-O Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c5,Gf6e7] There's no reason not to deploy the rook with tempo before challenging the white queen with ...[Qe7].} 15. Qa3 {The most challenging square for White to place the queen.} Qe7 {[%cal Ge7a3,Gd5b4,Ge8g8] Once again, preparing the way for not just ...[Qxa3] or ...[Nb4], but to safely castle kingside.} 16. Qxe7+ {A simple approach, but Black's well-centralised forces will comfortably offset White's two bishops.} Kxe7 {[%cal Gd5b4] Just like with the rook on [d8] not [c8], this should be a fairly comfortable set-up for Black, with the centralised knight and good coordination.} 17. Bd2 {[%csl Rb4] Wisely cutting out the possibility of ...[Nb4].} Rhd8 {[%cal Gd5f4,Gf7f5] Centralising the final piece. Black may now look to expand with ...[f5] Bg5+ can always be met by ...[Nf6], or press forwards with ...[Nf4].} 18. Rfe1 {[%csl Re5]} Kf6 $5 {[%cal Ge6f5]} ({Being so well centralised, Black elects to play for more than the full equality again offered by} 18... Nf4 {. The plan now is to deprive White of the bishop-pair while weakening the defence of [c2] with ...[Bf5].}) 19. Rad1 Bf5 {[%cal Gf5d3,Gc8c2] Threatening to exchange on [d3], then invade on [c2]. Already it's clear that White needs to be the more accurate to maintain equality.} (19... Bf5 {A For example,} 20. Bxf5 $2 Kxf5 21. c3 f6 {It does no harm to secure [e5] so and, as such, take any ideas of [g2]-[g4] off the table. Black is now ready to expand with all of ... [b5], ...[h5] and ...[g5], and just where is White's play?} 22. f3 b5 23. Kf2 {((We've followed the game Gasimov-Orantes Taboada, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2021, where Black began to regroup with 23...Nb6 , but there was no need to move the knight from the centre just yet.))} h5 $1 {Ruling out any notion of [g2]-[g4], while seizing space and, yes, this advance might also have been made on the previous turn. If White now tries to sit, Black will begin to exert definite pressure on the kingside after ...[g5]-[g4] and already Black is clearly for choice, having all the space and all the play.} 24. Be3 $6 b4 $1 {Much stronger than exchanging on [e3] as the minority attack lands with some effect on the queenside.} 25. cxb4 Nxb4 {The threats of ...[Nd3]+ and ...[Nxa2] ensure that Black will win a clear pawn.}) (19... Bf5 {B} 20. Bg5+ $1 {This neat tactic is the only real way to maintain full equality for White.} Kxg5 21. Rxe5 {The point.} g6 {Black must defend the attacked bishop.} 22. Bxf5 gxf5 23. h4+ $1 {Creating some luft for the white king to avoid any back-rank issues before recouping the piece.} Kg4 24. Rdxd5 Rxd5 25. Rxd5 Rxc2) *

