1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. O-O {White's most common choice, maintaining the tension.} d4 {[%cal Gd4c3]} ({As} 11... O-O 12. f4 {is a bit annoying, Black should take up the challenge, seizing space and asking an immediate question of the knight on [c3].}) 12. Ne2 (12. Ne2 {In practice, this retreat has been almost as common as the trip to the rim with the knight. Here Black has three fully playable continuations,} Nxd3 13. cxd3 O-O {, 12...Nec6!? and our recommendation, castling.}) 12... O-O {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gc8e6,Ge7c6,Gc8g4] Preserving the tension while getting ready to continue development with ...[Nec6] and ... [Be6]. Note how Black doesn't rush to exchange on [d3] as the knight is quite useful on [b4] for instance, in some lines [a2] may hang after ...[Be6], and has often been known to lead White to spend a tempo challenging it. Another important concept is that of meeting White's main pawn break, [f2]-[f4], with ... [Bg4], challenging the knight on [e2].} 13. Bd2 {[%csl Rb4]} Nxd3 14. cxd3 Bg4 $5 {[%cal Gg4e2,Gf8c8] Activating the bishop without delay, to both free [c8] for a rook and set a small trap.} 15. f3 $1 {[%csl Rb7,Rg4]} Rfc8 $1 ({A somewhat more active choice than} 15... Bc8 {, dangling the b-pawn before White and hoping to be able to retreat the bishop to [d7].}) 16. Qa5 {[%csl Rg4] An attempt to avoid an early draw, if also a retreat which shouldn't especially trouble Black.} Bd7 {[%cal Gd7b5,Ge7c6] The right retreat, preparing to bring the bishop round to [b5] to target the backwards pawn on [d3].} (16... Bd7 {Here} 17. f4 {was tried in V.Onischuk-Grekh, Lvov 2009, where} Nc6 {would have been sensible, and if} 18. Qd5 ({and not} 18. fxe5 $4 Qxf1+ $1) 18... Qe6 {, with rough equality.White has also been known to try [Rac1].}) 17. Rac1 Bb5 {[%csl Gd3] A consistent approach, one which forces White into a slightly miserable retreat.} 18. Qa3 (18. Qa3 {Here} Rxc1 19. Rxc1 Nc6 {was completely fine for Black in Rosen-Danielmeier, German League 2006, and Black might also try for more.}) 18... Ng6 $5 {[%cal Gf6e6] Retaining the tension, while challenging for control of [f4]. If White now plays slowly, Black may go ...[Qe6] followed by attempting to trade all the rooks and be left in control of the c-file, while we're also hoping to tempt White forwards.} 19. f4 $6 Qe7 $1 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Ge7a3] A strong retreat and now an exchange of queens would leave White in trouble on [d3] and clearly worse.} 20. Bb4 {[%csl Re7]} Qh4 {[%csl Ga3,Gb5,Gh4][%cal Gh4g4,Gg6f4] A fine, active spot for the queen. Black is ready to go ...[Nxf4] or probe with ...[Qg4] and definitely enjoys a small but pleasant advantage, in part simply due to having the more active queen.} *

