 to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. O-O {White's most common choice, maintaining the tension.} d4 {[%cal Gd4c3]} ({As} 11... O-O 12. f4 {is a bit annoying, Black should take up the challenge, seizing space and asking an immediate question of the knight on [c3].}) 12. Ne2 (12. Ne2 {In practice, this retreat has been almost as common as the trip to the rim with the knight. Here Black has three fully playable continuations,} Nxd3 13. cxd3 O-O {, 12...Nec6!? and our recommendation, castling.}) 12... O-O {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gc8e6,Ge7c6,Gc8g4] Preserving the tension while getting ready to continue development with ...[Nec6] and ... [Be6]. Note how Black doesn't rush to exchange on [d3] as the knight is quite useful on [b4] for instance, in some lines [a2] may hang after ...[Be6], and has often been known to lead White to spend a tempo challenging it. Another important concept is that of meeting White's main pawn break, [f2]-[f4], with ... [Bg4], challenging the knight on [e2].} 13. Bd2 {[%csl Rb4]} Nxd3 14. cxd3 Bg4 $5 {[%cal Gg4e2,Gf8c8] Activating the bishop without delay, to both free [c8] for a rook and set a small trap.} 15. f3 $1 {[%csl Rb7,Rg4]} Rfc8 $1 ({A somewhat more active choice than} 15... Bc8 {, dangling the b-pawn before White and hoping to be able to retreat the bishop to [d7].}) 16. Qxb7 {Now play is likely to end in an early handshake.} Rab8 ({Forcing the issue, although if you were desperate to win,} 16... Be6 $5 {followed by} 17. Z0 Rcb8 {might be considered.}) 17. Qa7 {[%csl Rg4]} Ra8 {With the bishop hanging, Black doesn't have anything better than to force a repetition, one which the white queen can scarcely escape either.} *

