1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. O-O {White's most common choice, maintaining the tension.} d4 {[%cal Gd4c3]} ({As} 11... O-O 12. f4 {is a bit annoying, Black should take up the challenge, seizing space and asking an immediate question of the knight on [c3].}) 12. Ne2 (12. Ne2 {In practice, this retreat has been almost as common as the trip to the rim with the knight. Here Black has three fully playable continuations,} Nxd3 13. cxd3 O-O {, 12...Nec6!? and our recommendation, castling.}) 12... O-O {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gc8e6,Ge7c6,Gc8g4] Preserving the tension while getting ready to continue development with ...[Nec6] and ... [Be6]. Note how Black doesn't rush to exchange on [d3] as the knight is quite useful on [b4] for instance, in some lines [a2] may hang after ...[Be6], and has often been known to lead White to spend a tempo challenging it. Another important concept is that of meeting White's main pawn break, [f2]-[f4], with ... [Bg4], challenging the knight on [e2].} 13. f4 {[%csl Re5] White usually can't resist carrying out his thematic break without delay.} Bg4 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gg4e2] Our standard response to [f2]-[f4] and a good one here again, threatening to take on [d3] then [e2].} 14. fxe5 {[%csl Rf6]} Qc6 $1 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gb4d3,Gg4e2] The star follow-up and one which ensures Black retains sufficient control of proceedings, whether White now elects to exchange queens or minor pieces.} 15. Qxc6 Nexc6 {[%csl Gd3,Ge2][%cal Gc6e5] Recapturing this way to keep up the pressure against the pieces on [d3] and [e2], pressure which will only be amplified once Black has regained the pawn with ...[Nxe5].} 16. Nf4 {White sensibly overprotects [d3].} Nxe5 17. Bd2 {[%csl Rb4]} Nbxd3 {Not forced, but yet again it makes sense to deprive White of the bishop-pair.} 18. cxd3 Rac8 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gg4d7,Gd7b5,Gf7f5] With control of the c-file and ...[Bd7] set to follow, Black had absolutely no reason to complain in Nisipeanu-G.Horvath, Eger 1995. Note how ...Bd7 will not only prepare to increase the pressure against d3 with ...Bb5, but also facilitate a potential break in the shape of ...f5 ( 18...f5? 19.h3 would be a bit annoying.)} *

