[Round "?"]
[White "2C) 8.Qc7 with 11.O-O"]
[Black "8.Qc7 with 11.O-O d4 12.Ne2 O-O 13.f4 #3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "38"]
[GameId "2141525856535794"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. O-O {White's most common choice, maintaining the tension.} d4 {[%cal Gd4c3]} ({As} 11... O-O 12. f4 {is a bit annoying, Black should take up the challenge, seizing space and asking an immediate question of the knight on [c3].}) 12. Ne2 (12. Ne2 {In practice, this retreat has been almost as common as the trip to the rim with the knight. Here Black has three fully playable continuations,} Nxd3 13. cxd3 O-O {, 12...Nec6!? and our recommendation, castling.}) 12... O-O {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gc8e6,Ge7c6,Gc8g4] Preserving the tension while getting ready to continue development with ...[Nec6] and ... [Be6]. Note how Black doesn't rush to exchange on [d3] as the knight is quite useful on [b4] for instance, in some lines [a2] may hang after ...[Be6], and has often been known to lead White to spend a tempo challenging it. Another important concept is that of meeting White's main pawn break, [f2]-[f4], with ... [Bg4], challenging the knight on [e2].} 13. f4 {[%csl Re5] White usually can't resist carrying out his thematic break without delay.} Bg4 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gg4e2] Our standard response to [f2]-[f4] and a good one here again, threatening to take on [d3] then [e2].} 14. fxe5 {[%csl Rf6]} Qc6 $1 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gb4d3,Gg4e2] The star follow-up and one which ensures Black retains sufficient control of proceedings, whether White now elects to exchange queens or minor pieces.} 15. Qxe7 {This can at least be considered critical.} Nxd3 {Clearly the bishop must go and now Black can hope that White, as has sometimes been the case in practice, grows too ambitious.} 16. Ng3 Rae8 $1 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Ge8e7,Gd3e5,Gc6c2]} (16... Rae8 {This rook, to keep f7 secure. Now White hasn't anything better than} 17. Qg5 {when Black is very comfortable after} Nxe5 {then ...[f6], although in practice White has often preferred a different square.}) 17. Qd6 $6 Qxc2 $1 {[%csl Gb2,Ge5]} (17... Qxc2 {The right pawn to take with e5 so weak, and now the engines indicate that White must find the radical} 18. Bg5 $5 {to only be slightly worse after} Nxe5 {or even 18...Qxb2 .}) 18. Qxd4 $6 Be2 $1 {[%cal Ge2f1] Exploiting White's back-rank difficulties to force a favourable exchange.} 19. Nxe2 Qxe2 {[%csl Gb2,Gd3,Ge2,Ge5][%cal Ge8d8] White might have been a pawn up, but was also in a pretty unpleasant position in Kindermann-Kallai, Budapest 1985. Black's queen and knight team could hardly be better placed and not only is the [e5]-pawn not long for this world, but [b2] is also quite vulnerable and ...[Rd8] on the way to activate the rooks.} *

