1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. O-O {White's most common choice, maintaining the tension.} d4 {[%cal Gd4c3]} ({As} 11... O-O 12. f4 {is a bit annoying, Black should take up the challenge, seizing space and asking an immediate question of the knight on [c3].}) 12. Na4 $1 {[%cal Ra4b6] The critical line, threatening to land the knight on [b6].} Qc6 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,Gc7] An essential resource to hold Black's position together. Note too how thanks to the pressure against [c2], the bishop on [d3] isn't going anywhere, so Black need not rush with the exchange on [d3] and give White an open c-file to try and exploit.} 13. Qa5 $5 {[%csl Rb4]} Nxd3 {With the knight now hanging the exchange on [d3] makes perfect sense.} 14. cxd3 Qb5 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Ga5]} ({A new idea to counter the rare 13.Qa5. Black has usually gone} 14... b5 15. Nb6 Rb8 {(( 15...Qc7 16.Bd2 Rb8 17.Nc4! is a bit annoying)) But here if White finds} 16. Nxc8 Rxc8 17. Bg5 $1 {followed by [Rac1] he does obtain a nagging pull. Black should be able to defend and does remain pretty solid, but there doesn't seem to be any need to allow the line.}) 15. Qxb5+ axb5 {[%csl Ga4]} (15... axb5 {Forcing the knight to move after all and now} 16. Nc5 $2 b6 17. Nb3 Be6 {would already be pretty good for Black, so White should head forwards.}) 16. Nb6 {[%csl Ra8]} Ra6 {[%cal Ga6b6]} 17. Nxc8 Nxc8 {[%csl Ga2,Ga6,Gb5][%cal Ge8d7,Gc8b6,Gb6a4,Gh8c8] The b-pawns might be doubled, but they are scarcely a weakness here, and even give Black some useful pressure down the a-file. Left alone, we would go ...[Nb6] and ...[Kd7], likely followed by ...[Rc8] and ...[Na4], so White would be advised to aim for some play of his own.} 18. f4 $1 {[%csl Re5]} Kd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7e6] As calm as you like and a move which demonstrates that Black is fully equal with the king en route for [e6].} (18... Kd7 {For example,} 19. fxe5 Ke6 20. Bf4 Ne7 {Black isn't in a rush to regain the pawn; it makes sense to first activate the rook on [h8], to [c8] or [a8]. The engines proclaim '0.00' and White is half a pawn up, but to our eyes, Black's position is the easier to play and White must play accurately to obtain some play of his own.} 21. Rfc1 Nc6 {( Closing the c-file, although Black would also be fine after challenging for it with 21...[Rc8]. )} 22. Rc5 $1 b4 23. Rb5 Rha8 $1 {White has done well to activate the rook, but Black is still completely equal thanks to the pressure down the half-open a-file.} 24. Rxb7 Rxa2 25. Rxa2 Rxa2 {With both his b- and d-pawns pretty vulnerable here, White would be well advised to aim for a repetition:} 26. Rb6 $1 Kd7 27. Rb7+ Ke8 $5 {Trying to keep the game alive.} 28. Rc7 Nd8 {The knight will find another good square on [e6].} 29. Bc1 Ne6 {We're still in '0.00' territory, but with ideas of ...[b3] and ...[Ra1], as well as ...[Kd7] or . ..Ra5 and ...[Rxe5], Black could certainly play on in this unbalanced but roughly level endgame.}) *

