1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. O-O {White's most common choice, maintaining the tension.} d4 {[%cal Gd4c3]} ({As} 11... O-O 12. f4 {is a bit annoying, Black should take up the challenge, seizing space and asking an immediate question of the knight on [c3].}) 12. Na4 $1 {[%cal Ra4b6] The critical line, threatening to land the knight on [b6].} Qc6 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,Gc7] An essential resource to hold Black's position together. Note too how thanks to the pressure against [c2], the bishop on [d3] isn't going anywhere, so Black need not rush with the exchange on [d3] and give White an open c-file to try and exploit.} 13. Qa5 $5 {[%csl Rb4]} Nxd3 {With the knight now hanging the exchange on [d3] makes perfect sense.} 14. cxd3 Qb5 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Ga5]} ({A new idea to counter the rare 13.Qa5. Black has usually gone} 14... b5 15. Nb6 Rb8 {(( 15...Qc7 16.Bd2 Rb8 17.Nc4! is a bit annoying)) But here if White finds} 16. Nxc8 Rxc8 17. Bg5 $1 {followed by [Rac1] he does obtain a nagging pull. Black should be able to defend and does remain pretty solid, but there doesn't seem to be any need to allow the line.}) 15. Bd2 {Preserving the tension.} Be6 {[%cal Ga6b5,Gb5d3,Ge7c6]} (15... Be6 {Black likewise maintains the status quo. With the minor pieces developed, ...Qxd3 may at some stage become a possibility and} 16. Qxb5+ axb5 {is again not to be feared, and if} 17. Nc5 Bc8 $1 {to retain an important piece followed by ...[b6].}) {Finally, with the bishop now in play, Black is all set to force the pace with 16...Nc6 as then 17.Qxb5 axb5 18.Nb6 wouldn't lead anywhere after 18...Ra6 .} 16. Nc5 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Rc5e6]} Bc8 $5 {[%cal Gb7b6] Not forced, but it makes sense to keep everything covered while threatening ... [b6].} 17. Na4 Be6 {[%cal Ge7c6] Offering a repetition, one which we can see White accepting.} 18. Nc5 (18. Rfc1 $5 {((An attempt to complicate. White angles for 18...Qxd3 19.Rc7 , which looks a little risky for Black.))} Nc6 {((Forcing the queens off as 19.Qc7?? Qxa4 would hardly be wise for White.)) ((Black might also consider the solid-looking 18...Qxa5 19.Bxa5 Nc6 ))} 19. Qxb5 axb5 20. Nb6 $5 Ra6 $1 {((Forcing the pace and hoping one day to double rooks on the a-file, rather than allow White to press down that file after 20...Rxa2?! 21.Rxa2 Bxa2 22.Ra1. ) . )} 21. Nd5 Kd7 22. Rc5 $1 b6 $1 {The best way to give up the pawn.} 23. Rxb5 Rb8 {Black has definite positional compensation for the pawn. The main idea is 24...[Na7] to drive the rook away, after which White might find himself coming under pressure on [d5] or [a2].} 24. Nb4 Nxb4 {((Simple chess, although 24...Ra5!? is also fine.))} 25. Bxb4 Rc8 {Black's active pieces fully offset White's extra pawn and already 26...[Rxa2] is a threat to exploit the back rank.}) 18... b6 $5 {[%csl Ga5,Gc5] A definite winning try, unbalancing the structure to the maximum.} 19. Qxb5+ axb5 20. Nxe6 fxe6 {[%csl Ga8][%cal Ge8d7] Black's structure is a little ugly, but again the half-open a-file is useful and ...[Kd7] on the way to connect the rooks.} 21. Rfc1 Kd7 {[%cal Ge7c6,Gh8c8,Gc6a5] Black seems to be fine here. One good plan is ...[Nc6], ...[Rfc8] and ...[Na5] to activate the pieces, another ...[Rfc8] and if [Rxc8] [Nxc8] followed by the potential knight manoeuvre ...[Nd6]-[b7]-[c5].} *

