1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. O-O {White's most common choice, maintaining the tension.} d4 {[%cal Gd4c3]} ({As} 11... O-O 12. f4 {is a bit annoying, Black should take up the challenge, seizing space and asking an immediate question of the knight on [c3].}) 12. Na4 $1 {[%cal Ra4b6] The critical line, threatening to land the knight on [b6].} Qc6 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,Gc7] An essential resource to hold Black's position together. Note too how thanks to the pressure against [c2], the bishop on [d3] isn't going anywhere, so Black need not rush with the exchange on [d3] and give White an open c-file to try and exploit.} 13. Qxc6+ {Invariably played with the knight on [a4] hanging, if not actually forced.} Nexc6 {[%csl Gb4] The right way to recapture, keeping the other knight actively placed on [b4].} 14. Bd2 {White calmly completes development.} Be6 $5 {[%cal Ge6a2]} (14... Be6 {Cheekily threatening to swipe the a-pawn with 15...Bxa2 and no longer will} 15. Nb6 {now be an issue. Black might then transpose to our main line with} Rb8 {, but there's absolutely no reason not to place the rook instead on a more active square with 15...Rd8 .}) 15. f4 $5 {[%cal Ra4b6,Rf4f5]} (15. f4 {This menaces Nb6 followed by f4-f5 and also sets a small trap:} Bxa2 $2 16. Nb6 Rd8 17. Rxa2 $1 Nxa2 18. Nd5 {traps the knight on [a2] to leave White clearly for choice.}) 15... exf4 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A simple approach, with d4 secure here, as well as one which avoids coming under a bit of pressure after} 15... f6 16. Nc5 {.}) 16. Bxf4 O-O {[%cal Gb4d3,Gf7f5] Housing the king and we may now look to obtain a bit of pressure of our own after an exchange on [d3] then ...[f5].} 17. Nc5 Bc8 $5 {[%cal Ga6a5,Gb4d3,Ga5a4,Gb7b6] This retreat isn't forced, but does rather ask White: well, just what are you up to and what really is the knight on [c5] doing? Black may now exchange on [d3] and should also look to seize some useful space with ...[a5], angling to follow up with ...[a4] and ...[b6].} 18. a3 {[%csl Rb4]} Nxd3 19. cxd3 {[%cal Rb2b4]} a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gb7b6,Gf7f6,Gf7f5,Gc6e5] Ruling out [b2]-[b4] for now. Admittedly, White must be nominally for choice here, but Black is extremely solid and seems comfortable enough: one idea is, of course, a cramping ...[a4], which may even be followed up by the ...[f5] break. Meanwhile, a timely ...[b6] will evict the white knight and Black can even consider ...[f6] and ...[Ne5], which will either pressure [d3] or leave Black well-placed in the centre in the event of a [Bxe5] [fxe5] exchange.} *

