0. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. O-O {White's most common choice, maintaining the tension.} d4 {[%cal Gd4c3]} ({As} 11... O-O 12. f4 {is a bit annoying, Black should take up the challenge, seizing space and asking an immediate question of the knight on [c3].}) 12. Na4 $1 {[%cal Ra4b6] The critical line, threatening to land the knight on [b6].} Qc6 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,Gc7] An essential resource to hold Black's position together. Note too how thanks to the pressure against [c2], the bishop on [d3] isn't going anywhere, so Black need not rush with the exchange on [d3] and give White an open c-file to try and exploit.} 13. Qxc6+ {Invariably played with the knight on [a4] hanging, if not actually forced.} Nexc6 {[%csl Gb4] The right way to recapture, keeping the other knight actively placed on [b4].} 14. Bd2 {White calmly completes development.} Be6 $5 {[%cal Ge6a2]} (14... Be6 {Cheekily threatening to swipe the a-pawn with 15...Bxa2 and no longer will} 15. Nb6 {now be an issue. Black might then transpose to our main line with} Rb8 {, but there's absolutely no reason not to place the rook instead on a more active square with 15...Rd8 .}) 15. a3 {[%csl Rb4]} Nxd3 16. cxd3 b5 $1 {[%cal Gb5a4,Ge8e7,Ga4c5,Gh8c8]} (16... b5 {This may seem a little surprising; why force the knight off the rim? Well, now White can no longer take control of the c-file with Nb6 and Rac1 and here} 17. Nb6 {can be dealt with comfortably enough by} Rb8 18. Nd5 Kd7 {. Black also gets ready to contest the c-file with ...[Ke7] and ...[Rhc8].}) 17. Nc5 Ke7 {[%cal Gh8c8]} 18. Rac1 Rhc8 {[%cal Ga6a5,Gf7f6] Completing the mini-plan. Black may now stabilise the centre with ...[f6], which possibly also hints at kingside expansion in the not-too-distant future, or consider expanding on the queenside with ...[a5].} 19. Rc2 Nd8 $1 {[%cal Ge6d7,Gd8e6] An important retreat to note as Black avoids becoming uncomfortably pinned down the c-file and can now regroup with ...[Bd7] and ...[Ne6]. There shouldn't be anything to fear here.} 20. Rfc1 Bd7 21. f4 $5 {[%csl Re5]} exf4 $1 ({The d4-pawn actually isn't so weak, and this exchange is preferable to allowing} 21... f6 22. fxe5 fxe5 23. Be1 $1 {when White could begin to press after [Bg3].}) 22. Bxf4 {We've followed Zude-Medvedovski, Hessen 2019, where it's hard to understand why Black returned the knight to [c6].} Ne6 {[%csl Gc5,Gf4] Preparing mass exchanges on [c5] if allowed.} 23. Bg3 (23. Nxe6 Kxe6 $1 {The right way to recapture, keeping the white bishop away from [d4] and preparing to either to exchange all the rooks or just one pair then seek counterplay with ...[b4] and ...[Bb5].}) 23... Nxc5 {By no means forced, but heading straight for a pure opposite-coloured bishop endgame is the simplest way to draw.} 24. Rxc5 Rxc5 25. Rxc5 Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c5,Gc8c2,Gc8c1] Hoovering off the final pair of rooks unless White wants to allow Black too much activity down the c-file.} (25... f6 $5 26. Bf2 b4 {Here too Black should be active enough to draw comfortably, with ...[Bb5] on the way.}) 26. Rxc8 Bxc8 27. Be5 {[%csl Rd4,Rg7] This may seem a little scary. Isn't Black losing a pawn? Well, yes, and perhaps even two, but here there's a handy little move.} b4 $1 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd7b5,Gb4a3] Black simply prepares to go ... [Bd7]-[b5] and White's advantage will now only be symbolic.} 28. axb4 Bd7 29. Kf2 {The only real critical try.} Bb5 30. Ke2 {[%csl Rd4,Rg7]} g6 31. Bxd4 Ke6 {[%cal Gf7f5] White has two extra pawns, but the one on [b2] isn't going anywhere and neither really is the d-pawn. Black will break with ...[f5] and should hold comfortably; indeed, it's notable that the engines assess at just '0.11'.} *

