1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. O-O {White's most common choice, maintaining the tension.} d4 {[%cal Gd4c3]} ({As} 11... O-O 12. f4 {is a bit annoying, Black should take up the challenge, seizing space and asking an immediate question of the knight on [c3].}) 12. Na4 $1 {[%cal Ra4b6] The critical line, threatening to land the knight on [b6].} Qc6 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,Gc7] An essential resource to hold Black's position together. Note too how thanks to the pressure against [c2], the bishop on [d3] isn't going anywhere, so Black need not rush with the exchange on [d3] and give White an open c-file to try and exploit.} 13. Qxc6+ {Invariably played with the knight on [a4] hanging, if not actually forced.} Nexc6 {[%csl Gb4] The right way to recapture, keeping the other knight actively placed on [b4].} 14. Nb6 {[%csl Ra8] Invariably played, if not actually forced.} Rb8 {Unsurprisingly a fairly forced move.} 15. f4 $5 {[%cal Rf4e5]} (15. f4 {(This is the other move which is sometimes seen here, one supported by John Nunn himself in that old classic, Nunn's Chess Openings NCO, and, of course,)} exf4 $4 16. Bxf4 {is definitely not an option for Black here.}) 15... f6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gc6e5] Safest, simplest and best, shoring up the defence of [e5] and avoiding any issues on the [h2]-[b8] diagonal.} (15... f6 {We'll now see in the illustrative game Zawadzka-Heidrich, German League 2011, that} 16. f5 {isn't to be feared and even allows Black the option of} Kd8 $5 {.}) 16. fxe5 Nxe5 $1 {[%cal Gb4d3,Ge5d3]} ({Despite our last move, this is the right way to recapture, avoiding the scary situation that} 16... fxe5 17. Bc4 $5 {can quickly become. Black is now ready to take twice on [d3], so White should probably pin.}) 17. Bf4 Be6 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gb8d8,Gd8d6] Calmly developing the final minor piece. Black is now ready to unpin then make good use of the rook with ...[Rd8]-[d6] and doesn't seem to have any real problems.} 18. Bxe5 fxe5 19. a3 {[%csl Rb4]} Nc6 {[%cal Gh8f8,Ge8e7] With ...[Rf8] and ...[Ke7] on the way, Black enjoyed comfortable equality in Willemsma-Duijker, Vlissingen 2012.} *

