1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. O-O {White's most common choice, maintaining the tension.} d4 {[%cal Gd4c3]} ({As} 11... O-O 12. f4 {is a bit annoying, Black should take up the challenge, seizing space and asking an immediate question of the knight on [c3].}) 12. Na4 $1 {[%cal Ra4b6] The critical line, threatening to land the knight on [b6].} Qc6 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,Gc7] An essential resource to hold Black's position together. Note too how thanks to the pressure against [c2], the bishop on [d3] isn't going anywhere, so Black need not rush with the exchange on [d3] and give White an open c-file to try and exploit.} 13. Qxc6+ {Invariably played with the knight on [a4] hanging, if not actually forced.} Nexc6 {[%csl Gb4] The right way to recapture, keeping the other knight actively placed on [b4].} 14. Nb6 {[%csl Ra8] Invariably played, if not actually forced.} Rb8 {Unsurprisingly a fairly forced move.} 15. Nxc8 {A rather modest continuation.} Rxc8 16. Bd2 Nxd3 {By no means forced, but a simple and decent choice, one which ensures White will never cause any problems on the light squares in the middlegame, and we should perhaps note that here a draw was agreed in Arnason-Sosonko, Reykjavik 1980.} 17. cxd3 Kd7 {[%csl Gc8,Gd3][%cal Gc8c7,Gh8c8,Gc6d8,Gd8e6,Ge6c5] Activating the king while placing it in contact with both [c8] and the queenside in general. Black may continue by doubling rooks with ...[Rc7] and ...[Rhc8] here, but we are actually threatening to carry out a powerful regrouping: 18...[Nd8]! to clear the c-file, after which ...[Ne6] will bring the knight to a fine square ...[Nc5] has led to the [d3]-pawn dropping off in a few of Richard's blitz games in this line.} 18. f4 $6 {White tries to break out, but this only actually serves to help Black.} exf4 $1 19. Bxf4 Ke6 {[%cal Gc6b4,Gf7f6,Gg7g5,Gh7h5] A fine spot for the king. Black may now consider active ideas involving ...[Nb4], as well as ...[f6] followed by expansion with ...[g5] and/or ...[h5]. The engines feel confident that White is only a touch worse, but with his bishop struggling for a good role and also required currently to prevent ...[Ne5], Black's position seems somewhat the easier to handle to us.} *

