1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rb1c3,Rc1e3,Re1c1] An aggressive square for the white queen. Left alone, White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3] and [O-O-O], after which the weakness of [d6] may well prove a major headache for Black. As such, we should once again aim for a quick ...[d5].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (8... Nge7 {Best, as well as a thematic way of supporting d5 instead, Qg6?! Nc3 d5? exd5 Nb4 Qxe5+ would already be superb for White. Note too Black's not insubstantial lead in development and how, say,} 9. Be2 $6 d5 10. exd5 $4 Nxd5 {would already trap the white queen.}) 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5] Invariably played to restrain ...[d5] - for now.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5]} ({A key counter for Black, striking against c2 while offering further support to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. O-O {White's most common choice, maintaining the tension.} d4 {[%cal Gd4c3]} ({As} 11... O-O 12. f4 {is a bit annoying, Black should take up the challenge, seizing space and asking an immediate question of the knight on [c3].}) 12. Na4 $1 {[%cal Ra4b6] The critical line, threatening to land the knight on [b6].} Qc6 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,Gc7] An essential resource to hold Black's position together. Note too how thanks to the pressure against [c2], the bishop on [d3] isn't going anywhere, so Black need not rush with the exchange on [d3] and give White an open c-file to try and exploit.} 13. Qxc6+ {Invariably played with the knight on [a4] hanging, if not actually forced.} Nexc6 {[%csl Gb4] The right way to recapture, keeping the other knight actively placed on [b4].} 14. Nb6 {[%csl Ra8] Invariably played, if not actually forced.} Rb8 {Unsurprisingly a fairly forced move.} 15. Bd2 {By some margin White's most common move, simply completing development.} Be6 {[%cal Ge6a2,Gb8d8,Ge8g8] Maintaining the tension as there's still no rush to exchange on [d3], thereby opening up the c-file for White. Black can now even consider stealing a pawn with ...[Bxa2], as well as such sensible moves as ...[Rd8] and ...[O-O].} 16. f4 $5 {[%cal Rf4e5,Rf4f5] Upping the ante and forcing Black to be alert.} Nxd3 {A simple solution, if not an especially common choice.} (16... f6 17. a3 Nxd3 18. cxd3 {((This is how Black has tended to defend in practice, but here some care is required: neither 18...O-O? 19.f5! nor 18...Kd8? 19.a4! is at all satisfactory.)) Indeed, only through radical means can Black come close to equality.} f5 $1 {Countering in the centre just in the nick of time, despite the loss of a tempo with the f-pawn - compare with our line after 16... [Nxd3] 17. [cxd3].}) 17. cxd3 f5 $1 {A vigorous and essential reaction. We obtain some central pressure of our own and takes ideas of [f4]-[f5] off the table for good. Now we're all set to castle and White temporarily going a pawn to the good need not be feared.} 18. exf5 Bxf5 19. fxe5 {[%csl Rf5]} O-O $1 {[%cal Gf5d3,Gc6e5,Gb8e8]} ({A key move to remember. Rather than allow White to seize the initiative with} 19... Bxd3 20. Rf3 {, Black instead makes the king safe and brings the final piece into play. Note too how all of ... [Bxd3], ...[Nxe5] and ...[Rae8] are now set to follow, meaning that White will do extremely well to maintain the extra pawn.}) (19... O-O {For example,} 20. Rae1 Be6 $5 {((Fighting against the white knight and e-pawn. It's possible to allow 20...Bxd3 21.Rxf8+ Rxf8 22.e6 , but there's actually no need to when Black can solidly blockade whilst countering against [a2].))} 21. a3 Rxf1+ {((A timely trade as now 22.Kxf1 Rf8+ 23.Kg1 Rf5 would regain the pawn without delay.))} 22. Rxf1 Re8 {The e5-pawn is falling and Black can meet either} 23. Re1 {or 23.Bf4 with 23...Bf5 . As such, it was no surprise that a draw was shortly agreed in Bohak-Paulik, correspondence 2009.}) *

