 to ...d5. You may have wondered about} 9... d5 $2 {, but please don't play it!} 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Ne4 $1 {is pretty much a refutation.}) 10. Bd3 {White invariably covers [c2] so in sensible fashion.} d5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5d4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Getting in the ideal break. Black now has ideas of ... [d4] and/or a timely exchange on [d3], as well of simply continuing development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} (10... d5 {There are now two main options for White:} 11. exd5 {and 11.O-O . In practice, a surprisingly large number of alternatives have also been seen on the odd occasion. Note that of these 11.Nxd5 usually just transposes into Line 2A after 11...Nbxd5 12.exd5 Nxd5 .}) 11. O-O {White's most common choice, maintaining the tension.} d4 {[%cal Gd4c3]} ({As} 11... O-O 12. f4 {is a bit annoying, Black should take up the challenge, seizing space and asking an immediate question of the knight on [c3].}) 12. Na4 $1 {[%cal Ra4b6] The critical line, threatening to land the knight on [b6].} Qc6 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,Gc7] An essential resource to hold Black's position together. Note too how thanks to the pressure against [c2], the bishop on [d3] isn't going anywhere, so Black need not rush with the exchange on [d3] and give White an open c-file to try and exploit.} 13. Qxc6+ {Invariably played with the knight on [a4] hanging, if not actually forced.} Nexc6 {[%csl Gb4] The right way to recapture, keeping the other knight actively placed on [b4].} 14. Nb6 {[%csl Ra8] Invariably played, if not actually forced.} Rb8 {Unsurprisingly a fairly forced move.} 15. Bd2 {By some margin White's most common move, simply completing development.} Be6 {[%cal Ge6a2,Gb8d8,Ge8g8] Maintaining the tension as there's still no rush to exchange on [d3], thereby opening up the c-file for White. Black can now even consider stealing a pawn with ...[Bxa2], as well as such sensible moves as ...[Rd8] and ...[O-O].} 16. a3 {[%csl Rb4] White has tended to preserve the a-pawn and force the situation on the queenside so.} Nxd3 17. cxd3 O-O {[%cal Gf7f6,Gf7f5]} ({Whilst we can't advocate} 17... Kd8 $2 {on account of} 18. a4 $1 Kc7 19. a5 ({when the black king actually isn't so happy, there's absolutely nothing wrong with housing the king here f6!? is also playable, and if} 19. f4 f5 $1 {, again.})) {Black may continue with the solid ...[f6] and ...[Rf7], or fight back in more active vein with ...[f5].} 18. a4 $1 {Emanuel Berg's try looks like a fairly critical test, or at least it forces Black to be more solid than we might perhaps like.} f6 $1 {[%cal Gf8f7,Gc6a7,Ga7c8] Modest and probably best. Black retains a very solid set-up and is now set to go ...[Rf7] and/or ...[Na7]-[c8] to deal with the annoyingly placed white knight.} ({Note too that here} 18... f5 {isn't quite so good as after 18. [b4], on account of} 19. f3 fxe4 20. dxe4 $1 {when} Ne7 $6 {would now run into} 21. Bb4 $1 {.}) 19. Rfc1 Rf7 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gc6a7,Ga7c8,Gb8e8,Gc6b8,Gb8d7] Keeping White out of [c7] so that Black can either go ...[Na7]-[c8] or ...[Re8], ... [Nb8] and ...[Nd7].} ({Interestingly, the engines very slightly prefer something slightly more ambitious:} 19... g5 $5 {, seizing space, followed by ...[Na7]-[c8] after all or even ...[h5].}) 20. f3 {We've followed E.Berg-Heidrich, German League 2002, in which the strong Swedish GM went on to grind out a win, but Black would have been OK had he got on with challenging the annoying knight on [b6].} Na7 $1 {[%cal Ga7c8] Heading straight for [c8] should promise Black full equality.} *

