 Nxd3 17. cxd3 O-O {[%cal Gf7f6,Gf7f5]} ({Whilst we can't advocate} 17... Kd8 $2 {on account of} 18. a4 $1 Kc7 19. a5 ({when the black king actually isn't so happy, there's absolutely nothing wrong with housing the king here f6!? is also playable, and if} 19. f4 f5 $1 {, again.})) {Black may continue with the solid ...[f6] and ...[Rf7], or fight back in more active vein with ...[f5].} 18. a4 $1 {Emanuel Berg's try looks like a fairly critical test, or at least it forces Black to be more solid than we might perhaps like.} f6 $1 {[%cal Gf8f7,Gc6a7,Ga7c8] Modest and probably best. Black retains a very solid set-up and is now set to go ...[Rf7] and/or ...[Na7]-[c8] to deal with the annoyingly placed white knight.} ({Note too that here} 18... f5 {isn't quite so good as after 18. [b4], on account of} 19. f3 fxe4 20. dxe4 $1 {when} Ne7 $6 {would now run into} 21. Bb4 $1 {.}) 19. Rfc1 Rf7 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gc6a7,Ga7c8,Gb8e8,Gc6b8,Gb8d7] Keeping White out of [c7] so that Black can either go ...[Na7]-[c8] or ...[Re8], ... [Nb8] and ...[Nd7].} ({Interestingly, the engines very slightly prefer something slightly more ambitious:} 19... g5 $5 {, seizing space, followed by ...[Na7]-[c8] after all or even ...[h5].}) 20. f3 {We've followed E.Berg-Heidrich, German League 2002, in which the strong Swedish GM went on to grind out a win, but Black would have been OK had he got on with challenging the annoying knight on [b6]. Illustrative} Na7 $1 {[%cal Ga7c8] Heading straight for [c8] should promise Black full equality. Let's see an example.} 21. Rc5 Nc8 {[%csl Gb6]} 22. a5 (22. Nd5 $6 {It's not unknown for White to overpress in this structure.} b6 $1 23. Rc4 Bxd5 24. exd5 Rd7 {With ...[Rxd5] or even ...[Ne7] imminent, White will have to scramble for counterplay and to try to draw.}) 22... Nxb6 23. axb6 Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c5]} (23... Rc8 {Preparing to liquidate and} 24. Rxc8+ Bxc8 25. Rc1 Be6 {is certainly nothing to fear.}) 24. Rac1 {[%csl Rc8]} Rxc5 25. Rxc5 Rf8 $1 {[%cal Gf8c8] Angling to exchange off the remaining rooks.} 26. Rc7 Rf7 {If the white rook retreats, we can return ours to [f8] and meanwhile we are ready to exchange: there's no reason with such a bishop on [e6] to fear a passed pawn on [c7].} 27. f4 Rxc7 28. bxc7 b6 {[%cal Gg8f7,Gf7e7,Ge7d7,Ge6c8] Keeping White's bishop out of [a5]. Black is now ready to go ...[Kf7], ...[Ke7] and then ...[Kd7], and White has absolutely nothing here.} 29. Bb4 Kf7 30. Bd6 {[%csl Re5]} exf4 31. Bxf4 Ke7 {[%csl Ga6,Gb6,Ge6][%cal Ge7d7] With 32...[Kd7] next up, it should be fully clear that Black is in no danger whatsoever. Indeed, in practice, frustrated white players can even lose such endgames, either by allowing Black to advance the outside majority too far or by failing to spot after ...[Kd7] that ...[Bb3]-[c2] is on.} *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
