1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qxf6 {White's second most common option after 8. [Qd1], one likely to be played by opponents unfamiliar with the Löwenthal or ones who like to grind away, their aim here being to gradually exploit White's bishop-pair.} Nxf6 {[%csl Gc6,Rd5,Rd6,Gf6][%cal Gf6e4] Unsurprisingly, the right recapture. White might have the bishop-pair, and currently we could perhaps point to [d5] and [d6] as potential holes, but Black's set-up is actually quite a comfortable one. In this variation, we're unlikely to be subject to any sort of theoretical duel - unlike after 8. [Qd1], say - and Black's lead in development is most certainly not to be underestimated.} 9. f3 $6 d5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e4] It's only move 9 and already Black has got in the thematic break and, as so often in the Sicilian, here achieving ...[d5] already leaves Black fractionally for choice.} 10. Bg5 {[%cal Rg5f6] White threatens to win a pawn, but Black should not mind him returning the bishop-pair.} dxe4 {Pretty much forcing White to exchange on [f6] unless he just wants to be a pawn down.} 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. fxe4 Be6 {[%cal Gc6b4,Ga8d8,Gf6f5,Gh8g8,Ge8e7]} (12... Be6 {This completed minor piece development to leave Black comfortably placed in Cvetanovic-Marcetic, Vrnjacka Banja 2012, where he was threatening to take control with} 13. Z0 Nb4 14. Na3 Rd8 {. The other rook may be developed to [g8] and there will always be a timely ...[f5] to activate in the centre and undouble the pawns, while the king should be safe and well enough placed on [e7].}) *

