1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qxf6 {White's second most common option after 8. [Qd1], one likely to be played by opponents unfamiliar with the Löwenthal or ones who like to grind away, their aim here being to gradually exploit White's bishop-pair.} Nxf6 {[%csl Gc6,Rd5,Rd6,Gf6][%cal Gf6e4] Unsurprisingly, the right recapture. White might have the bishop-pair, and currently we could perhaps point to [d5] and [d6] as potential holes, but Black's set-up is actually quite a comfortable one. In this variation, we're unlikely to be subject to any sort of theoretical duel - unlike after 8. [Qd1], say - and Black's lead in development is most certainly not to be underestimated.} 9. f3 $6 d5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e4] It's only move 9 and already Black has got in the thematic break and, as so often in the Sicilian, here achieving ...[d5] already leaves Black fractionally for choice.} 10. exd5 Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5b4,Gc6d4]} ({A simple recapture. There's no need to get fancy with} 10... Nb4 {or 10...Nd4 when such an easy move is available; now 11...[Ndb4] is actually a threat, followed by 12...[Nd4] if needed.}) {marked as clickable, but I made it trainable as it is very popular} 11. Bd2 Bf5 {[%cal Gf5c2]} (11... Bf5 {Developing with tempo and once again reminding White that c2 is the softest spot in his camp. Black also gets ready to seize the initiative with} 12. c3 e4 $1 {, and if} 13. fxe4 Bxe4 {followed by ...[O-O-O].}) 12. Na3 (12. Na3 {Here} Ndb4 13. c3 Nd3+ 14. Bxd3 Bxd3 {was very comfortable for Black in Votava-Heidrich, German League 2001, if also very solid for White. As such, Black might prefer to retain the tension.}) 12... O-O $5 {[%csl Gf1][%cal Gf8e8,Ge5e4] The king is safer here than on [c8] and Black would now like to either go ...[Rfe8] and ...[e4] to seize the initiative in the centre or ...[Rfd8] and ...[b5] to leave the white knight looking a little silly on [a3]. Note too White's slight lack of a great and safe square for his light-squared bishop.} 13. O-O-O $5 Rfd8 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Gb7b5,Gc6d4,Ga8c8] With such moves as ...[b5], ...[Rac8] and ...[Nd4] imminent, it's clear that only one king is in danger, White's.} *

