1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qxf6 {White's second most common option after 8. [Qd1], one likely to be played by opponents unfamiliar with the Löwenthal or ones who like to grind away, their aim here being to gradually exploit White's bishop-pair.} Nxf6 {[%csl Gc6,Rd5,Rd6,Gf6][%cal Gf6e4] Unsurprisingly, the right recapture. White might have the bishop-pair, and currently we could perhaps point to [d5] and [d6] as potential holes, but Black's set-up is actually quite a comfortable one. In this variation, we're unlikely to be subject to any sort of theoretical duel - unlike after 8. [Qd1], say - and Black's lead in development is most certainly not to be underestimated.} 9. f3 $6 d5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e4] It's only move 9 and already Black has got in the thematic break and, as so often in the Sicilian, here achieving ...[d5] already leaves Black fractionally for choice.} 10. exd5 Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5b4,Gc6d4]} ({A simple recapture. There's no need to get fancy with} 10... Nb4 {or 10...Nd4 when such an easy move is available; now 11...[Ndb4] is actually a threat, followed by 12...[Nd4] if needed.}) 11. c3 Be6 {[%cal Ge8c8,Ge8g8,Gf7f5] Now that White has made a further non-developing move in [c2]-[c3], there's no need to place the bishop on [f5], not that 11...[Bf5] can exactly be terrible. Instead, the text move can be followed up by either ...[O-O-O] or ...[O-O] and ...[f5].} 12. Na3 Rd8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Gf7f5,Ge8g8] Reacting to White's plans, involving the rook and ensuring that after [Nc4] a check on [d6] won't be an issue.} ({Black also sidesteps the outwardly tempting} 12... b5 {when} 13. c4 $1 Ndb4 14. Kf2 {actually isn't so clear. Instead, we wait for 13.Nc4 to go 13...b5 and may now castle kingside or even look to quickly seize space, be that with ...[f5] or even ... [h5]-[h4].}) 13. Bd2 (13. Bd2 {Here} O-O {was very comfortable for Black in Tomescu-Bonaccorsi, Taormina 2002, and there's also an intriguing idea from Stockfish.}) 13... h5 $5 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gf7f6,Ge8f7] Black simply threatens to annex more space with ...[h4] when after ...[f6] and ...[Kf7], our set-up would be a pleasant one, as well as leave White under potential pressure on both flanks.} 14. h4 {The obvious response.} Nf4 $1 {Immediately exploiting the weakened white kingside. Black can now consider castling then checking on [d3], as well as even ideas of ...[Ne7]-[f5]. Probably White should though sit tight and suffer, not exchange.} 15. Bxf4 $6 exf4 {[%csl Ge1,Ge3][%cal Gh8h6,Gc6e7,Ge7f5,Ge7d5] Black might have doubled pawns, but this is a fairly horrible scenario for White. His king and knight are far from well placed, unlike the black rooks and, yes, ...[Rh6] is going to neatly bring the second one into the fray. Factor in to the weakness of [e3] and that ...[Ne7]-[f5] or ...[Nd5] is imminent, and it's no surprise that the engines already consider Black to be clearly for choice.} *

