1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qxf6 {White's second most common option after 8. [Qd1], one likely to be played by opponents unfamiliar with the Löwenthal or ones who like to grind away, their aim here being to gradually exploit White's bishop-pair.} Nxf6 {[%csl Gc6,Rd5,Rd6,Gf6][%cal Gf6e4] Unsurprisingly, the right recapture. White might have the bishop-pair, and currently we could perhaps point to [d5] and [d6] as potential holes, but Black's set-up is actually quite a comfortable one. In this variation, we're unlikely to be subject to any sort of theoretical duel - unlike after 8. [Qd1], say - and Black's lead in development is most certainly not to be underestimated.} 9. Bd3 ({Compared with} 9. f3 d5 {, this at least develops a piece. Now 9...Nb4 10.Nc3 would transpose into Chapter 3c, but Black can do even better than that.}) 9... d5 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gc6b4]} (9... d5 {Wasting no time getting in the central break. Already e4 is under fire, with Black also having ideas of ...Nb4, as well as of meeting} 10. Nc3 {with} d4 {.}) 10. exd5 Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5b4,Gc8e6,Ge8c8,Ge8g8] A calm recapture. Now 11...[Ndb4] is very much an idea, looking to weaken White's structure, while Black can quickly complete development with ...[Be6] followed by ...[O-O] or even ...[O-O-O].} 11. c3 {Prudently keeping Black out of [b4], albeit at the cost of a slight weakening.} Be6 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gf7f5,Ge8g8] Ever a good spot for the bishop, as well as a move which enables Black to either go ... [O-O-O] or ...[f5] and ...[O-O].} 12. O-O (12. O-O {Here} O-O {was absolutely fine for the famous East German player and Lowenthal aficionado in Kupfer-Baumbach, Warsaw 1989, but it's also possible to be a little more adventurous.}) 12... Nf4 $5 {[%cal Gf4d3,Ge8c8] An idea we've already seen, one which comes with tempo and may well be followed by quickly castling long.} 13. Bxf4 exf4 (13... exf4 {It's actually not so easy for White to complete development here:} 14. Nd2 $4 O-O-O {would, of course, not be wise and 14.Na3 O-O-O is also very pleasant for Black, thanks to the pressure down the d-file and even against [a2].}) 14. Be4 O-O-O {[%csl Gb1,Gd8][%cal Gh8e8,Ge6d5,Gc6e5] With such a fine bishop on [e6], Black most certainly doesn't fear an exchange on [c6] and plays against the knight on [b1] and for the potential entry square on [d2]. Now ...[Ne5] may follow or even a kingside expansion, although the simplest and arguably the best plan is just ...[O-O-O] followed by ...[Bd5].} *

