1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qxf6 {White's second most common option after 8. [Qd1], one likely to be played by opponents unfamiliar with the Löwenthal or ones who like to grind away, their aim here being to gradually exploit White's bishop-pair.} Nxf6 {[%csl Gc6,Rd5,Rd6,Gf6][%cal Gf6e4] Unsurprisingly, the right recapture. White might have the bishop-pair, and currently we could perhaps point to [d5] and [d6] as potential holes, but Black's set-up is actually quite a comfortable one. In this variation, we're unlikely to be subject to any sort of theoretical duel - unlike after 8. [Qd1], say - and Black's lead in development is most certainly not to be underestimated.} 9. Nc3 {White's main option by some margin, developing while defending the pawn on [e4]. The alternatives are not completely unknown in practice though, if also moves which Black should welcome.} Nb4 {[%csl Ga1,Gd5,Ge1][%cal Gb4c2] We borrow an idea from the 8.Qc7 lines, quickly striking against the weakest spot in the white camp, c2. Black also increases control over d5 and while the immediate 9...d5 is playable, after 10.exd5 Nb4 11.Bd3 theory has long considered White to have a nagging edge.} ({After} 9... Nb4 {we reach something of a tabiya, one where White has two main moves:} 10. Kd2 {and 10.Bd3 . Of these, the more natural latter line is seen roughly twice as often as the former. We should also mention that there's one other way White might defend [d1].}) 10. Kd1 Ng4 {[%csl Gc2,Gd1,Gf2,Gh1][%cal Gg4f2] This is why white players tend to prefer 10. [Kd2] to 10. [Kd1]. In order to keep control of both [c2] and [f2], White must consent to some structural damage.} 11. Be3 {[%cal Re3b6]} Nxe3+ {Exchanging before the bishop can make its way to the sanctuary of [b6].} 12. fxe3 d6 {[%cal Gc8e6]} (12... d6 {There's no rush to castle in this line. Instead, Black gets ready to go ...Be6 and} 13. Bc4 Be6 14. Bxe6 $6 fxe6 {followed by ...[Ke7] would leave us with good central control.}) 13. a3 {[%csl Rb4] White tends to drive the knight backwards so.} Nc6 14. Bc4 Be6 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf7e6,Ga8c8]} (14... Be6 {Thematically challenging for control of a key diagonal. Now} 15. Bxe6 $6 fxe6 {would again be rather pleasant for Black and keep White out of [d5] and in any case ...[Rc8] is on the way.}) 15. Bd5 Rc8 16. Kd2 (16. Kd2 {Here Black exchanged with} Bxd5 {in Bacallao Alonso-Gonzalez Mesa, Matanzas 2008, where} 17. Nxd5 {would have maintained the rough balance. It's also possible as Black to retain the tension.}) 16... Ke7 $5 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Gc6a5,Gc8c7,Gf7e6,Gb7b5] Black enjoys comfortable equality and may look to the flanks to expand, be it with ...[h5]-[h5] or ...[Rc7] in conjunction with ...[Na5] then ...[b5].} *

