1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qxf6 {White's second most common option after 8. [Qd1], one likely to be played by opponents unfamiliar with the Löwenthal or ones who like to grind away, their aim here being to gradually exploit White's bishop-pair.} Nxf6 {Unsurprisingly, the right recapture. White might have the bishop-pair, and currently we could perhaps point to [d5] and [d6] as potential holes, but Black's set-up is actually quite a comfortable one. In this variation, we're unlikely to be subject to any sort of theoretical duel - unlike after 8. [Qd1], say - and Black's lead in development is most certainly not to be underestimated.} 9. Nc3 {White's main option by some margin, developing while defending the pawn on [e4]. The alternatives are not completely unknown in practice though, if also moves which Black should welcome.} Nb4 {We borrow an idea from the 8.Qc7 lines, quickly striking against the weakest spot in the white camp, c2. Black also increases control over d5 and while the immediate 9...d5 is playable, after 10.exd5 Nb4 11.Bd3 theory has long considered White to have a nagging edge.} ({After} 9... Nb4 {we reach something of a tabiya, one where White has two main moves:} 10. Kd2 {and 10.Bd3 . Of these, the more natural latter line is seen roughly twice as often as the former. We should also mention that there's one other way White might defend [d1].}) 10. Kd2 {White calmly defends [c2] and aims to hang on to the bishop-pair.} d6 $1 {[%cal Gc8e6]} ({(This may appear modest, but is also best. There's no rush to castle as Black the king is hardly badly placed in the centre for now, so we prepare ...Be6, while refusing to open the position to White's advantage with)} 10... d5 $6 {(( 10...Ng4? now leads nowhere after 11.f3. ) . )} 11. a3 d4 {(what else?)} 12. axb4 dxc3+ 13. Ke3 $1 {.}) 11. b3 $5 (11. b3 {White aims to keep the king on d2 and develop the dark-squared bishop via b2 or even a3, not least in the event of} O-O 12. Ba3 $1 {.}) 11... Be6 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Ge8c8,Gd6d5] Thematic development and now we are ready to go after the white king with ...[O-O-O] and ...[d5] if allowed.} 12. Ba3 {[%csl Rb4]} a5 $5 {[%csl Ga8][%cal Ga5b4,Ge8e7,Gh8d8,Gd6d5]} ({An interesting change of approach, not that there's anything wrong with} 12... Nc6 {when we'll see} 13. f3 {((And not 13.Bxd6?? O-O-O ))} O-O-O {via a 12.f3 O-O-O 13.Ba3 Nc6 move order.}) (12... a5 {The text keeps the a3-f8 diagonal closed, and Black would be delighted to see} 13. Bxb4 $2 axb4 {when suddenly the [e4]-pawn may well fall. In any case, the king should be quite happy on [e7], after which ...[Rfd8] and, ideally, ...[d5] will follow.}) 13. Re1 $5 {White shores up [e4] and hopes that his potential pressure against [e5] will deter Black from breaking with ...[d5].} Rc8 $1 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Ge8g8,Gh8f8,Gf8d8]} ({After White's last move, this seems more accurate than} 13... Ke7 {when} 14. Nb5 {followed by 15. [c3] would be slightly annoying. Instead, Black obtains some pressure down the c-file} (14. Bxb4 $6 axb4 15. Nb5 {Ke7 is nothing to fear, while getting ready to go [O-O] then [Rfd8].})) 14. Bb2 (14. Bb2 {Here Black settled for} Ke7 {in Kevlishvili-Duijker, Wijk aan Zee 2015, and it might be fractionally more accurate to castle.}) 14... O-O $5 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Gd6d5] Black is finally all set to quickly break with ...[d5] and seize the initiative.} 15. a3 {[%csl Rb4]} Nc6 16. Kc1 Nd4 $1 {[%csl Gb3,Gc2][%cal Gc8c6,Gf8c8] Exerting some useful pressure against [c2] and potentially [b3]. With ...[Rc6] and ...[Rfc8] on the way, Black has at least the easier position to play.} *

