1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qxf6 {White's second most common option after 8. [Qd1], one likely to be played by opponents unfamiliar with the Löwenthal or ones who like to grind away, their aim here being to gradually exploit White's bishop-pair.} Nxf6 {Unsurprisingly, the right recapture. White might have the bishop-pair, and currently we could perhaps point to [d5] and [d6] as potential holes, but Black's set-up is actually quite a comfortable one. In this variation, we're unlikely to be subject to any sort of theoretical duel - unlike after 8. [Qd1], say - and Black's lead in development is most certainly not to be underestimated.} 9. Nc3 {White's main option by some margin, developing while defending the pawn on [e4]. The alternatives are not completely unknown in practice though, if also moves which Black should welcome.} Nb4 {We borrow an idea from the 8.Qc7 lines, quickly striking against the weakest spot in the white camp, c2. Black also increases control over d5 and while the immediate 9...d5 is playable, after 10.exd5 Nb4 11.Bd3 theory has long considered White to have a nagging edge.} ({After} 9... Nb4 {we reach something of a tabiya, one where White has two main moves:} 10. Kd2 {and 10.Bd3 . Of these, the more natural latter line is seen roughly twice as often as the former. We should also mention that there's one other way White might defend [d1].}) 10. Kd2 {White calmly defends [c2] and aims to hang on to the bishop-pair.} d6 $1 {[%cal Gc8e6]} ({(This may appear modest, but is also best. There's no rush to castle as Black the king is hardly badly placed in the centre for now, so we prepare ...Be6, while refusing to open the position to White's advantage with)} 10... d5 $6 {(( 10...Ng4? now leads nowhere after 11.f3. ) . )} 11. a3 d4 {(what else?)} 12. axb4 dxc3+ 13. Ke3 $1 {.}) 11. b3 $5 (11. b3 {White aims to keep the king on d2 and develop the dark-squared bishop via b2 or even a3, not least in the event of} O-O 12. Ba3 $1 {.}) 11... Be6 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Ge8c8,Gd6d5] Thematic development and now we are ready to go after the white king with ...[O-O-O] and ...[d5] if allowed.} 12. f3 {White shores up the centre before committing the dark-squared bishop.} O-O-O {[%csl Gc8,Gd2][%cal Gd6d5] One king is fairly safe here and one king certainly won't be if Black now gets in a quick ...[d5].} 13. Ba3 {[%csl Rb4]} Nc6 {[%cal Gd6d5]} ({Simply does it, although even here a definite case might also be made for} 13... a5 $5 {.}) 14. Bd3 (14. Rd1 d5 {((Wasting no time on getting in the key break, although 14...b5!? 15.Bb2 and only then 15...d5 might also be considered.))} 15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Rxd5+ {The right way to recapture, preparing to exchange a pair of rooks, then swing the final piece from [h8] into play.} 17. Kc1 Rxd1+ 18. Kxd1 Bf5 $1 {(With ...[Rd8] + and ...[Nd4] on the way, Black's activity and superior coordination offset White's bishop-pair and all the all-GM clash C.Balogh-Plat, Czech League 2019, was later drawn.)}) 14... d5 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gf6d5]} ({Simple chess, although if you prefer to maintain the tension, both} 14... d5 {and 14...h5!? , a space-gaining idea of the Russian IM Alexander Anoshkin, are also fully viable. After the text move, Black is ready to take on [e4] and 15.exd5 Nxd5 16.Nxd5 Rxd5 followed by ...[Bf5] and/or ...[Nd4] would leave us with sufficient activity.}) 15. Rad1 dxe4 {Slightly damaging White's structure as the bishop on [d3] is, of course, pinned.} 16. Nxe4 Nxe4+ 17. fxe4 h5 $5 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gd8d7,Gh8h6,Gh6g6,Gh6f6,Gf7f6,Gh8d8,Ga6a5,Gc6b4] This seized some useful space as White remained up too little and Black completely OK in Jenni-Martinovic, Dresden 2007. Black would like to seize some further space with ...[h4], after which we might lift the rook on [h8] into play via [h6], directing it toward [g6] or even [f6]. Another possibility is just to sit tight with ...[f6], ...[Rd7] and ...[Rhd8], while it may even prove possible to fight on the queenside after all with the slightly retrograde ...[a5] and ...[Nb4].} *

