1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qxf6 {White's second most common option after 8. [Qd1], one likely to be played by opponents unfamiliar with the Löwenthal or ones who like to grind away, their aim here being to gradually exploit White's bishop-pair.} Nxf6 {Unsurprisingly, the right recapture. White might have the bishop-pair, and currently we could perhaps point to [d5] and [d6] as potential holes, but Black's set-up is actually quite a comfortable one. In this variation, we're unlikely to be subject to any sort of theoretical duel - unlike after 8. [Qd1], say - and Black's lead in development is most certainly not to be underestimated.} 9. Nc3 {White's main option by some margin, developing while defending the pawn on [e4]. The alternatives are not completely unknown in practice though, if also moves which Black should welcome.} Nb4 {We borrow an idea from the 8.Qc7 lines, quickly striking against the weakest spot in the white camp, c2. Black also increases control over d5 and while the immediate 9...d5 is playable, after 10.exd5 Nb4 11.Bd3 theory has long considered White to have a nagging edge.} ({After} 9... Nb4 {we reach something of a tabiya, one where White has two main moves:} 10. Kd2 {and 10.Bd3 . Of these, the more natural latter line is seen roughly twice as often as the former. We should also mention that there's one other way White might defend [d1].}) 10. Kd2 {White calmly defends [c2] and aims to hang on to the bishop-pair.} d6 $1 {[%cal Gc8e6]} ({(This may appear modest, but is also best. There's no rush to castle as Black the king is hardly badly placed in the centre for now, so we prepare ...Be6, while refusing to open the position to White's advantage with)} 10... d5 $6 {(( 10...Ng4? now leads nowhere after 11.f3. ) . )} 11. a3 d4 {(what else?)} 12. axb4 dxc3+ 13. Ke3 $1 {.}) 11. a3 {[%csl Rb4] White tends to drive the knight back without delay.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga8c8,Ga8d8,Ge8c8] Naturally, the knight drops back and now Black is all set to go ...[Be6] followed by ...[Rc8] or ....[O-O-O].} 12. Ke1 {White frees the dark-squared bishop for operations.} Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gd6d5]} ({Swift and thematic development, although if you don't like the resulting kingside situation, you may wish to begin with} 12... h6 {, which echoes the prophylactic 10...[h6] that some black players like to meet 10. [Bd3] with. After 12...Be6 , Black is ready to go 13...[Rc8] or even 13...[d5] if allowed.}) 13. Be3 Ne7 $1 {[%cal Gd6d5]} ({A notable manoeuvre, adding even more weight to the ...d5 break and so denying White the nominal edge he might be able to claim after} 13... d5 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Rd1 {. We'll now see an instructive grind from Black after 14. [Bd3] [d5] in the illustrative game Zuriel-Nemcova, Tromsø Women's Olympiad 2014.}) 14. f3 Rc8 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gd6d5] Black adds even more weight to the ...[d5] break by hoping that the [c2]-pawn may find itself vulnerable after exchanges on [d5].} 15. Bd3 d5 {Finally it's time for the key break.} 16. exd5 Nfxd5 {[%cal Gd5e3,Gd5c3,Ge7d5] Threatening structural ruin on [c3], as well as the bishop on [e3], and don't forget that thanks to 13...[Ne7], Black is now able to recapture on [d5] with a knight.} 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5e3]} 18. Bd2 (18. Bd2 {(White continues to defend well. Black now stood comfortably don't forget that White can no longer castle after)} O-O {(in Zinchenko-Oleksienko, Alushta 2007, going on to win this all-grandmaster encounter 0-1, 42, and here there's an arguably even simpler way to play.)}) 18... Ne7 $5 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Ge6f5,Gf7f6,Ge8f7] Black plays to deprive White of the bishop-pair with ...[Bf5]. White can attack [e5] with [Bc3], but we're quite happy to go ...[f6] in any case, after which ...[Kf7] will enable the final piece to swing into play from [h8] unless that is Black prefers to play for kingside expansion with ...[h5] and perhaps even ...[g5].} *

