1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qxf6 {White's second most common option after 8. [Qd1], one likely to be played by opponents unfamiliar with the Löwenthal or ones who like to grind away, their aim here being to gradually exploit White's bishop-pair.} Nxf6 {Unsurprisingly, the right recapture. White might have the bishop-pair, and currently we could perhaps point to [d5] and [d6] as potential holes, but Black's set-up is actually quite a comfortable one. In this variation, we're unlikely to be subject to any sort of theoretical duel - unlike after 8. [Qd1], say - and Black's lead in development is most certainly not to be underestimated.} 9. Nc3 {White's main option by some margin, developing while defending the pawn on [e4]. The alternatives are not completely unknown in practice though, if also moves which Black should welcome.} Nb4 {We borrow an idea from the 8.Qc7 lines, quickly striking against the weakest spot in the white camp, c2. Black also increases control over d5 and while the immediate 9...d5 is playable, after 10.exd5 Nb4 11.Bd3 theory has long considered White to have a nagging edge.} ({After} 9... Nb4 {we reach something of a tabiya, one where White has two main moves:} 10. Kd2 {and 10.Bd3 . Of these, the more natural latter line is seen roughly twice as often as the former. We should also mention that there's one other way White might defend [d1].}) 10. Kd2 {White calmly defends [c2] and aims to hang on to the bishop-pair.} d6 $1 {[%cal Gc8e6]} ({(This may appear modest, but is also best. There's no rush to castle as Black the king is hardly badly placed in the centre for now, so we prepare ...Be6, while refusing to open the position to White's advantage with)} 10... d5 $6 {(( 10...Ng4? now leads nowhere after 11.f3. ) . )} 11. a3 d4 {(what else?)} 12. axb4 dxc3+ 13. Ke3 $1 {.}) 11. a3 {[%csl Rb4] White tends to drive the knight back without delay.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga8c8,Ga8d8,Ge8c8] Naturally, the knight drops back and now Black is all set to go ...[Be6] followed by ...[Rc8] or ....[O-O-O].} 12. Ke1 {White frees the dark-squared bishop for operations.} Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gd6d5]} ({Swift and thematic development, although if you don't like the resulting kingside situation, you may wish to begin with} 12... h6 {, which echoes the prophylactic 10...[h6] that some black players like to meet 10. [Bd3] with. After 12...Be6 , Black is ready to go 13...[Rc8] or even 13...[d5] if allowed.}) 13. f3 (13. f3 {White makes a semi-useful move and may still follow up with Be3 or Bg5. While} Ne7 {makes less sense when there isn't a bishop on [e3], it's hard to believe that 13...d5 can be too bad, and if 14.exd5 Nxd5 15.Nxd5 Bxd5 16.Bd3 O-O followed by ...[f5]. Black can also first make a useful move.}) 13... Rc8 $5 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gd6d5,Gc6d4,Ge6c4]} (13... Rc8 {Improving the rook while waiting for} 14. Be3 {to go} Ne7 {. Meanwhile, with the rook well placed on the c-file, Black is now all set to go ...[d5] or even first obtain some pressure with another plan worth noting, 14...Nd4 , and if 15.Bd3 then 15...Bc4 .}) 14. Kf2 (14. Kf2 {This was seen in Zinchenko-Van Zutphen, Paleochora 2011, where} Ke7 $5 15. Be3 Na5 {revealed yet another way for Black to obtain counterplay. A simpler plan was also very much still possible though.}) 14... Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c2] Pretty much forcing White's next.} 15. Bd3 Bc4 {[%cal Gc4d3,Gd4b3] And now White must reckon with Black following up the exchange on [d3] by sinking the knight into [b3], a policy which would echo one of White's favourite motifs in the 8. [Qc7] lines.} 16. Be3 {[%cal Re3d4]} Bxd3 17. cxd3 Nd7 $5 {[%cal Gd7c5]} ({With the bishop away from c1,} 17... Nb3 {wouldn't achieve so much. Black might though claim full equality with 17...Nc2 , with the text move, a slightly more double-edged try for more.}) 18. Bxd4 exd4 {[%cal Gd4c3]} 19. Ne2 Nc5 {[%cal Gc5d3,Gc5b3] The position is equal, but not completely dead. Black would like to take on [d3] with check, after which [b2] might be grabbed, although even more of an immediate threat is 20... [Nb3] followed by 21...[Rc2].} *

