1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qxf6 {White's second most common option after 8. [Qd1], one likely to be played by opponents unfamiliar with the Löwenthal or ones who like to grind away, their aim here being to gradually exploit White's bishop-pair.} Nxf6 {Unsurprisingly, the right recapture. White might have the bishop-pair, and currently we could perhaps point to [d5] and [d6] as potential holes, but Black's set-up is actually quite a comfortable one. In this variation, we're unlikely to be subject to any sort of theoretical duel - unlike after 8. [Qd1], say - and Black's lead in development is most certainly not to be underestimated.} 9. Nc3 {White's main option by some margin, developing while defending the pawn on [e4]. The alternatives are not completely unknown in practice though, if also moves which Black should welcome.} Nb4 {We borrow an idea from the 8.Qc7 lines, quickly striking against the weakest spot in the white camp, c2. Black also increases control over d5 and while the immediate 9...d5 is playable, after 10.exd5 Nb4 11.Bd3 theory has long considered White to have a nagging edge.} ({After} 9... Nb4 {we reach something of a tabiya, one where White has two main moves:} 10. Kd2 {and 10.Bd3 . Of these, the more natural latter line is seen roughly twice as often as the former. We should also mention that there's one other way White might defend [d1].}) 10. Kd2 {White calmly defends [c2] and aims to hang on to the bishop-pair.} d6 $1 {[%cal Gc8e6]} ({(This may appear modest, but is also best. There's no rush to castle as Black the king is hardly badly placed in the centre for now, so we prepare ...Be6, while refusing to open the position to White's advantage with)} 10... d5 $6 {(( 10...Ng4? now leads nowhere after 11.f3. ) . )} 11. a3 d4 {(what else?)} 12. axb4 dxc3+ 13. Ke3 $1 {.}) 11. a3 {[%csl Rb4] White tends to drive the knight back without delay.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga8c8,Ga8d8,Ge8c8] Naturally, the knight drops back and now Black is all set to go ...[Be6] followed by ...[Rc8] or ....[O-O-O].} 12. Ke1 {White frees the dark-squared bishop for operations.} Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gd6d5]} ({Swift and thematic development, although if you don't like the resulting kingside situation, you may wish to begin with} 12... h6 {, which echoes the prophylactic 10...[h6] that some black players like to meet 10. [Bd3] with. After 12...Be6 , Black is ready to go 13...[Rc8] or even 13...[d5] if allowed.}) 13. Bg5 {This must be critical, preventing ...[d5] and trying to break up Black's structure.} (13. Bd3 Rc8 {Once again, Black calmly improves the rook before deciding whether or not to break in the centre.} 14. f3 h5 $5 {((By no means definitely best, but certainly an instructive idea to note, simply seizing space on the kingside. As well as 14...d5 , both 14...Ke7 and 14...Na5 also look reasonable for Black.))} 15. Be3 Ne7 {Only heading here now that White has a bishop on [e3] which the ...[d5] break then a ...[Nxd5] recapture can target.} 16. Rd1 d5 17. exd5 Nexd5 18. Bd2 h4 {While White was still very solid, Black too was comfortable and ready to look for a bit of play on the kingside with ... [Nf4] in Figlio-Zeihen, correspondence 2003.}) 13... h6 $5 ({A provocative choice and one of a few good options for Black. Both} 13... Ke7 {and 13...Rc8 also look fine, but there's no reason whatsoever to fear doubled f-pawns.}) 14. Bxf6 gxf6 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gf6f5,Ga8c8,Gh8g8] Black is already set to undouble the pawns whilst activating the pieces with ...[f5]. There are very much ideas too of ... [Nd4], especially in response to [Rd1], and the rooks should find useful enough posts on [c8] and [g8].} 15. Bd3 Rc8 {[%cal Gh8g8] Unfortunately for White he can't castle here and ...[Rg8] is coming. He should though prefer to sit tight rather than allow Black to favourably transform the position.} 16. Nd5 $5 Bxd5 $1 17. exd5 Nd4 $5 {[%cal Gh8g8,Gf6f5,Ge8e7] A more active square for the knight than [e7] and it can always jump into [b3] in the event of [c2]-[c3]. Black is also ready to go ...[Rg8] and ...[f5], beginning to roll the Sveshnikov-like central majority, while the king should be pretty well placed on [e7] or even [f6].} *

