1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qxf6 {White's second most common option after 8. [Qd1], one likely to be played by opponents unfamiliar with the Löwenthal or ones who like to grind away, their aim here being to gradually exploit White's bishop-pair.} Nxf6 {Unsurprisingly, the right recapture. White might have the bishop-pair, and currently we could perhaps point to [d5] and [d6] as potential holes, but Black's set-up is actually quite a comfortable one. In this variation, we're unlikely to be subject to any sort of theoretical duel - unlike after 8. [Qd1], say - and Black's lead in development is most certainly not to be underestimated.} 9. Nc3 {White's main option by some margin, developing while defending the pawn on [e4]. The alternatives are not completely unknown in practice though, if also moves which Black should welcome.} Nb4 {We borrow an idea from the 8.Qc7 lines, quickly striking against the weakest spot in the white camp, c2. Black also increases control over d5 and while the immediate 9...d5 is playable, after 10.exd5 Nb4 11.Bd3 theory has long considered White to have a nagging edge.} ({After} 9... Nb4 {we reach something of a tabiya, one where White has two main moves:} 10. Kd2 {and 10.Bd3 . Of these, the more natural latter line is seen roughly twice as often as the former. We should also mention that there's one other way White might defend [d1].}) 10. Kd2 {White calmly defends [c2] and aims to hang on to the bishop-pair.} d6 $1 {[%cal Gc8e6]} ({(This may appear modest, but is also best. There's no rush to castle as Black the king is hardly badly placed in the centre for now, so we prepare ...Be6, while refusing to open the position to White's advantage with)} 10... d5 $6 {(( 10...Ng4? now leads nowhere after 11.f3. ) . )} 11. a3 d4 {(what else?)} 12. axb4 dxc3+ 13. Ke3 $1 {.}) 11. a3 {[%csl Rb4] White tends to drive the knight back without delay.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga8c8,Ga8d8,Ge8c8] Naturally, the knight drops back and now Black is all set to go ...[Be6] followed by ...[Rc8] or ....[O-O-O].} 12. Nd5 $5 {[%cal Rd5c7]} (12. Nd5 {A radical try. White has only one piece developed and moves it again, but does threaten Nc7+. We really wanted to make} Nxe4+ $6 13. Ke3 Nf6 14. Nc7+ Ke7 15. Nxa8 Nd4 {work, but eventually had to give up after} 16. Bd3 Ng4+ 17. Kd2 Nxf2 18. Kc3 $3 {. Thankfully, Black has a simpler and decent option available.}) 12... Nxd5 ({Forcing the pace, although if you don't mind dynamic, Sveshnikov type play,} 12... Rb8 $5 {might be considered, and if} 13. Nxf6+ gxf6 {followed by ...[f5].}) 13. exd5 Nd4 $1 {[%csl Gb3] Exploiting one downside to 11. [a3] to head forwards, as now White won't find it too easy to arrange [c2]-[c3], while Black will quickly be quite actively placed after 14...[Bf5].} 14. Bd3 Bf5 {[%cal Gf5d3,Ga8c8] Consistent, as well as an approach which prepares to rid White of the fabled bishop-pair.} 15. Bxf5 Nxf5 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gb7b5,Ge8d7] With ...[Rc8] on the way, as well as such moves as ...[Kd7] and ...[b5], Black is comfortably placed.} 16. Kd3 b5 17. a4 $6 Kd7 $1 {[%cal Gf5e7,Ga6b5,Gh8a8] Exchanges on [b5] and [a8] can only help Black to activate his pieces here, and in any case White was already in a bit of trouble, with 18...[Ne7] a definite threat in Skorchenko-Anoshkin, Belorechensk 2007.} *

