1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qxf6 {White's second most common option after 8. [Qd1], one likely to be played by opponents unfamiliar with the Löwenthal or ones who like to grind away, their aim here being to gradually exploit White's bishop-pair.} Nxf6 {Unsurprisingly, the right recapture. White might have the bishop-pair, and currently we could perhaps point to [d5] and [d6] as potential holes, but Black's set-up is actually quite a comfortable one. In this variation, we're unlikely to be subject to any sort of theoretical duel - unlike after 8. [Qd1], say - and Black's lead in development is most certainly not to be underestimated.} 9. Nc3 {White's main option by some margin, developing while defending the pawn on [e4]. The alternatives are not completely unknown in practice though, if also moves which Black should welcome.} Nb4 {We borrow an idea from the 8.Qc7 lines, quickly striking against the weakest spot in the white camp, c2. Black also increases control over d5 and while the immediate 9...d5 is playable, after 10.exd5 Nb4 11.Bd3 theory has long considered White to have a nagging edge.} ({After} 9... Nb4 {we reach something of a tabiya, one where White has two main moves:} 10. Kd2 {and 10.Bd3 . Of these, the more natural latter line is seen roughly twice as often as the former. We should also mention that there's one other way White might defend [d1].}) 10. Kd2 {White calmly defends [c2] and aims to hang on to the bishop-pair.} d6 $1 {[%cal Gc8e6]} ({(This may appear modest, but is also best. There's no rush to castle as Black the king is hardly badly placed in the centre for now, so we prepare ...Be6, while refusing to open the position to White's advantage with)} 10... d5 $6 {(( 10...Ng4? now leads nowhere after 11.f3. ) . )} 11. a3 d4 {(what else?)} 12. axb4 dxc3+ 13. Ke3 $1 {.}) 11. a3 {[%csl Rb4] White tends to drive the knight back without delay.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga8c8,Ga8d8,Ge8c8] Naturally, the knight drops back and now Black is all set to go ...[Be6] followed by ...[Rc8] or ....[O-O-O].} 12. Bd3 {One of White's two main moves, the other being to drop the king back.} (12. Bc4 Be6 {((Ever a good response to White deploying his light-squared bishop so. Black would be pretty comfortable after 13.Bxe6 fxe6 or 13.Ba2 Nd4 , but better that for White than being too ambitious.))} 13. Nd5 $2 Nxe4+ 14. Ke3 Bxd5 15. Bxd5 Nf6 {Black was simply a pawn up and went on to win in Vivas Zamora-D.Popov, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2020.}) 12... Be6 {Thematically continuing development and now in practice White has tended to await events.} 13. Rd1 b5 $5 {[%cal Ge8e7,Gh8c8] A new idea, but with White's queenside looking a little congested, seizing space on that side of the board is definitely tempting. Black is now likely to keep the queen's rook on [a8] and swing the king's rook over to [c8] after ...[Ke7].} 14. Ke1 Ke7 15. Be3 {Possible now that Black doesn't have a slightly tricky ... [Ne7] available in response.} Rhc8 {[%cal Gc6a5,Ga5c4,Ga8b8,Gf6d7,Gd7c5,Gd7b6] This is a comfortable type of Sicilian for Black. Going ...[Na5]-[c4] should secure decent counterplay and ...[Nd7] is also an idea, heading for [c5] or even [b6] after ...[Rab8].} *

