1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qxf6 {White's second most common option after 8. [Qd1], one likely to be played by opponents unfamiliar with the Löwenthal or ones who like to grind away, their aim here being to gradually exploit White's bishop-pair.} Nxf6 {Unsurprisingly, the right recapture. White might have the bishop-pair, and currently we could perhaps point to [d5] and [d6] as potential holes, but Black's set-up is actually quite a comfortable one. In this variation, we're unlikely to be subject to any sort of theoretical duel - unlike after 8. [Qd1], say - and Black's lead in development is most certainly not to be underestimated.} 9. Nc3 {White's main option by some margin, developing while defending the pawn on [e4]. The alternatives are not completely unknown in practice though, if also moves which Black should welcome.} Nb4 {We borrow an idea from the 8.Qc7 lines, quickly striking against the weakest spot in the white camp, c2. Black also increases control over d5 and while the immediate 9...d5 is playable, after 10.exd5 Nb4 11.Bd3 theory has long considered White to have a nagging edge.} ({After} 9... Nb4 {we reach something of a tabiya, one where White has two main moves:} 10. Kd2 {and 10.Bd3 . Of these, the more natural latter line is seen roughly twice as often as the former. We should also mention that there's one other way White might defend [d1].}) 10. Bd3 {[%cal Rc1g5] Natural development from White, who thereby preserves castling options and is happy to return the bishop-pair to catch up in development. Here the battle for control of the [d5]-square will be especially important, with White set to stake an immediate stake to superiority there after [Bg5].} b5 $5 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gc8b7] A fairly rare choice, but seemingly also the best move on the latest evidence. Black frees [b7] for the light-squared bishop and so gets ready to break with ...[d5].} ({The immediate} 10... d5 {leaves Black struggling to equalise after} 11. exd5 Nfxd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bd2 {or here if 11...Nxd3+ 12.cxd3 b5!? 13.Bg5! .}) ({As such, Richard has long quite liked to go} 10... h6 {here as Black, preventing [Bg5], but the rare} 11. b3 $1 {then [Ba3] is a slightly annoying response. However, if you liked the 10. [Kd2] [d6] variations, then 10...d6 is also possible in response to 10. [Bd3], and if 11.Bg5 Be6 12.Bxf6 gxf6 with dynamic play and reasonable counter-chances for Black.}) 11. Be3 {[%cal Re3c5,Re1c1]} (11. Be3 {This has a couple of aggressive ideas in mind, namely O-O-O and Bc5, and after} Nxd3+ 12. cxd3 O-O {(( 12...d5!? ))} 13. Bc5 {White had an edge in Czegledi-Fodre, Hungarian League 2000.}) 11... Bb7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (11... Bb7 {Simply supporting ...d5 so now} 12. Bc5 {can be met by} Nxd3+ 13. cxd3 d5 {.}) 12. O-O-O Nxd3+ {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d5] A timely exchange with ...[d5] on the way and [e4] also looking just a little loose.} 13. cxd3 d5 {[%cal Gd5d4,Ga8c8] Black has completely equalised. Indeed, with such moves as ...[d4] and ...[Rc8] on the way, the onus is only really on White to maintain the balance.} 14. d4 $5 {[%csl Re5]} dxe4 {[%cal Gf6g4] A simple solution as the knight will be quite happy to visit the other half of the board and [g4].} 15. dxe5 Ng4 {[%cal Gg4e5,Gg4e3,Ge8g8] With such activity and ...[O-O] set to supply the safer king, Black can be pretty happy with the outcome of the opening.} *

