known in practice though, if also moves which Black should welcome.} Nb4 {We borrow an idea from the 8.Qc7 lines, quickly striking against the weakest spot in the white camp, c2. Black also increases control over d5 and while the immediate 9...d5 is playable, after 10.exd5 Nb4 11.Bd3 theory has long considered White to have a nagging edge.} ({After} 9... Nb4 {we reach something of a tabiya, one where White has two main moves:} 10. Kd2 {and 10.Bd3 . Of these, the more natural latter line is seen roughly twice as often as the former. We should also mention that there's one other way White might defend [d1].}) 10. Bd3 {[%cal Rc1g5] Natural development from White, who thereby preserves castling options and is happy to return the bishop-pair to catch up in development. Here the battle for control of the [d5]-square will be especially important, with White set to stake an immediate stake to superiority there after [Bg5].} b5 $5 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gc8b7] A fairly rare choice, but seemingly also the best move on the latest evidence. Black frees [b7] for the light-squared bishop and so gets ready to break with ...[d5].} ({The immediate} 10... d5 {leaves Black struggling to equalise after} 11. exd5 Nfxd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bd2 {or here if 11...Nxd3+ 12.cxd3 b5!? 13.Bg5! .}) ({As such, Richard has long quite liked to go} 10... h6 {here as Black, preventing [Bg5], but the rare} 11. b3 $1 {then [Ba3] is a slightly annoying response. However, if you liked the 10. [Kd2] [d6] variations, then 10...d6 is also possible in response to 10. [Bd3], and if 11.Bg5 Be6 12.Bxf6 gxf6 with dynamic play and reasonable counter-chances for Black.}) 11. Bg5 {White logically continues the battle for control of [d5], although in the limited practice with 10...[b5], a number of alternatives have also been tried.} Bb7 {[%cal Gd7d5] Consistent and best. There's no rush to exchange on [d3] and Black is now ready to break with ...[d5].} 12. O-O-O {This would be good, but for the fact that Black can exchange on [d3] with check.} Nxd3+ 13. Rxd3 $5 Nxe4 {[%cal Ge4g5]} ({Helping ourselves to the en prise pawn.} 13... Bxe4 $5 {is likewise a decent choice and after} 14. Nxe4 $5 Nxe4 15. Be3 {White has enough for the pawn, but no more than that.}) 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 {[%cal Ge4d3]} 15. Re3 {[%csl Re4] This was tried in Maltsevskaya-Orantes Taboada, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2021, where dropping the bishop back to [e6] would have been the easiest way to maintain full equality.} Bd5 {A very safe policy ditto 15...[Bf5].} 16. Rxe5+ {[%csl Rd5,Re8]} Be6 {[%cal Gf7f6,Ge8f7,Gh8c8] Black is rock-solid here and completely equal. We'll likely follow up with ...[f6] and ...[Kf7], then look to obtain some queenside play, beginning with ...[Rhc8].} *

