known in practice though, if also moves which Black should welcome.} Nb4 {We borrow an idea from the 8.Qc7 lines, quickly striking against the weakest spot in the white camp, c2. Black also increases control over d5 and while the immediate 9...d5 is playable, after 10.exd5 Nb4 11.Bd3 theory has long considered White to have a nagging edge.} ({After} 9... Nb4 {we reach something of a tabiya, one where White has two main moves:} 10. Kd2 {and 10.Bd3 . Of these, the more natural latter line is seen roughly twice as often as the former. We should also mention that there's one other way White might defend [d1].}) 10. Bd3 {[%cal Rc1g5] Natural development from White, who thereby preserves castling options and is happy to return the bishop-pair to catch up in development. Here the battle for control of the [d5]-square will be especially important, with White set to stake an immediate stake to superiority there after [Bg5].} b5 $5 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gc8b7] A fairly rare choice, but seemingly also the best move on the latest evidence. Black frees [b7] for the light-squared bishop and so gets ready to break with ...[d5].} ({The immediate} 10... d5 {leaves Black struggling to equalise after} 11. exd5 Nfxd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bd2 {or here if 11...Nxd3+ 12.cxd3 b5!? 13.Bg5! .}) ({As such, Richard has long quite liked to go} 10... h6 {here as Black, preventing [Bg5], but the rare} 11. b3 $1 {then [Ba3] is a slightly annoying response. However, if you liked the 10. [Kd2] [d6] variations, then 10...d6 is also possible in response to 10. [Bd3], and if 11.Bg5 Be6 12.Bxf6 gxf6 with dynamic play and reasonable counter-chances for Black.}) 11. Bg5 {White logically continues the battle for control of [d5], although in the limited practice with 10...[b5], a number of alternatives have also been tried.} Bb7 {[%cal Gd7d5] Consistent and best. There's no rush to exchange on [d3] and Black is now ready to break with ...[d5].} 12. f4 $5 {[%csl Re5] Another aggressive try, if also one Black is well placed to counter.} Ng4 $1 {[%cal Gg4e5,Gf7f6,Gg4e3] The knight covers e5 and Black has a threat here: 13...f6 (to kick the bishop to a much worse square) 14.Bh4 Ne3 , forking [c2] and [g2]. Meanwhile, 13.f5 can be well enough met by 13...f6 .} 13. fxe5 Nxe5 {[%csl Gd3] Maintaining the material balance while introducing a certain threat on [d3].} 14. O-O-O Rc8 {[%csl Gc3,Gc8]} (14... Rc8 {Ever a fine spot for the rook in these lines, as well as a move which here rather ties down the white knight to staying on c3 and now while} 15. Be2 {would retain the bishop-pair, it would also run into} Bxe4 $1 {.}) 15. Kb1 Nbxd3 {It makes sense to exchange off White's light-squared bishop before Black looks to counter on the light squares.} 16. cxd3 O-O {[%cal Gb5b4,Gf7f5]} (16... O-O {Black enjoyed comfortable equality here in Havelka-Pisk, Czech League 2024. Both the ...f5 and ...b4 breaks are high on the agenda and} 17. Be7 Rfe8 {is nothing to fear.}) *

