1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qxf6 {White's second most common option after 8. [Qd1], one likely to be played by opponents unfamiliar with the Löwenthal or ones who like to grind away, their aim here being to gradually exploit White's bishop-pair.} Nxf6 {Unsurprisingly, the right recapture. White might have the bishop-pair, and currently we could perhaps point to [d5] and [d6] as potential holes, but Black's set-up is actually quite a comfortable one. In this variation, we're unlikely to be subject to any sort of theoretical duel - unlike after 8. [Qd1], say - and Black's lead in development is most certainly not to be underestimated.} 9. Nc3 {White's main option by some margin, developing while defending the pawn on [e4]. The alternatives are not completely unknown in practice though, if also moves which Black should welcome.} Nb4 {We borrow an idea from the 8.Qc7 lines, quickly striking against the weakest spot in the white camp, c2. Black also increases control over d5 and while the immediate 9...d5 is playable, after 10.exd5 Nb4 11.Bd3 theory has long considered White to have a nagging edge.} ({After} 9... Nb4 {we reach something of a tabiya, one where White has two main moves:} 10. Kd2 {and 10.Bd3 . Of these, the more natural latter line is seen roughly twice as often as the former. We should also mention that there's one other way White might defend [d1].}) 10. Bd3 {[%cal Rc1g5] Natural development from White, who thereby preserves castling options and is happy to return the bishop-pair to catch up in development. Here the battle for control of the [d5]-square will be especially important, with White set to stake an immediate stake to superiority there after [Bg5].} b5 $5 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gc8b7] A fairly rare choice, but seemingly also the best move on the latest evidence. Black frees [b7] for the light-squared bishop and so gets ready to break with ...[d5].} ({The immediate} 10... d5 {leaves Black struggling to equalise after} 11. exd5 Nfxd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bd2 {or here if 11...Nxd3+ 12.cxd3 b5!? 13.Bg5! .}) ({As such, Richard has long quite liked to go} 10... h6 {here as Black, preventing [Bg5], but the rare} 11. b3 $1 {then [Ba3] is a slightly annoying response. However, if you liked the 10. [Kd2] [d6] variations, then 10...d6 is also possible in response to 10. [Bd3], and if 11.Bg5 Be6 12.Bxf6 gxf6 with dynamic play and reasonable counter-chances for Black.}) 11. Bg5 {White logically continues the battle for control of [d5], although in the limited practice with 10...[b5], a number of alternatives have also been tried.} Bb7 {[%cal Gd7d5] Consistent and best. There's no rush to exchange on [d3] and Black is now ready to break with ...[d5].} 12. Bxf6 {Doubling the pawns so must be a critical try.} Nxd3+ $1 {[%csl Ge1]} ({A useful intermezzo, making White recapture with the pawn, whereas} 12... gxf6 $6 13. O-O-O {would facilitate recapturing with the rook.}) 13. cxd3 gxf6 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gb5b4,Gd7d5,Gf6f5,Ge8e7,Gh8g8,Ga8c8] We do have doubled pawns here, but all of the ...[b4], ...[d5] and ...[f5] advances are high on the agenda and Black's activity should fully offset White's slightly superior structure. The king may come to [e7] and the rooks to [c8] and [g8], although in the immediate future Black's focus is likely to be on disrupting the white knight with 14...[b4].} 14. f3 $5 (14. f3 {A crafty little move and now} b4 15. Nd1 $1 d5 {(this break no longer comes with tempo against [e4])} 16. Ne3 {homed in on Black's weaknesses and favoured White in Spyropoulos-Papidakis, Nikaia 2023. We must do better than that.}) 14... d5 $1 {[%cal Gb7d5,Ge8e7,Ge7d6,Ga8c8]} (14... d5 {Not for the first time we see Black happy to provoke} 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 {when} Ke7 {followed by ...[Rac8] and ...[Kd6] should comfortably regain the pawn. As such, White might try to retain the tension.}) 15. Rc1 Ke7 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gh8d8] (Black too can retain the tension. ...Rac8 will follow, and perhaps even ...Rfd8, all the while as we enjoy full equality if you're really keen to play for a win, we should advise that you may prefer 15...d4!? 16.Ne2 Rc8 , angling to keep the game alive in an unbalanced rook and bishop against rook and knight endgame.)} *

