known in practice though, if also moves which Black should welcome.} Nb4 {We borrow an idea from the 8.Qc7 lines, quickly striking against the weakest spot in the white camp, c2. Black also increases control over d5 and while the immediate 9...d5 is playable, after 10.exd5 Nb4 11.Bd3 theory has long considered White to have a nagging edge.} ({After} 9... Nb4 {we reach something of a tabiya, one where White has two main moves:} 10. Kd2 {and 10.Bd3 . Of these, the more natural latter line is seen roughly twice as often as the former. We should also mention that there's one other way White might defend [d1].}) 10. Bd3 {[%cal Rc1g5] Natural development from White, who thereby preserves castling options and is happy to return the bishop-pair to catch up in development. Here the battle for control of the [d5]-square will be especially important, with White set to stake an immediate stake to superiority there after [Bg5].} b5 $5 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gc8b7] A fairly rare choice, but seemingly also the best move on the latest evidence. Black frees [b7] for the light-squared bishop and so gets ready to break with ...[d5].} ({The immediate} 10... d5 {leaves Black struggling to equalise after} 11. exd5 Nfxd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bd2 {or here if 11...Nxd3+ 12.cxd3 b5!? 13.Bg5! .}) ({As such, Richard has long quite liked to go} 10... h6 {here as Black, preventing [Bg5], but the rare} 11. b3 $1 {then [Ba3] is a slightly annoying response. However, if you liked the 10. [Kd2] [d6] variations, then 10...d6 is also possible in response to 10. [Bd3], and if 11.Bg5 Be6 12.Bxf6 gxf6 with dynamic play and reasonable counter-chances for Black.}) 11. Bg5 {White logically continues the battle for control of [d5], although in the limited practice with 10...[b5], a number of alternatives have also been tried.} Bb7 {[%cal Gd7d5] Consistent and best. There's no rush to exchange on [d3] and Black is now ready to break with ...[d5].} 12. Bxf6 {Doubling the pawns so must be a critical try.} Nxd3+ $1 {[%csl Ge1]} ({A useful intermezzo, making White recapture with the pawn, whereas} 12... gxf6 $6 13. O-O-O {would facilitate recapturing with the rook.}) 13. cxd3 gxf6 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gb5b4,Gd7d5,Gf6f5,Ge8e7,Gh8g8,Ga8c8] We do have doubled pawns here, but all of the ...[b4], ...[d5] and ...[f5] advances are high on the agenda and Black's activity should fully offset White's slightly superior structure. The king may come to [e7] and the rooks to [c8] and [g8], although in the immediate future Black's focus is likely to be on disrupting the white knight with 14...[b4].} 14. f3 $5 (14. f3 {A crafty little move and now} b4 15. Nd1 $1 d5 {(this break no longer comes with tempo against [e4])} 16. Ne3 {homed in on Black's weaknesses and favoured White in Spyropoulos-Papidakis, Nikaia 2023. We must do better than that.}) 14... d5 $1 {[%cal Gb7d5,Ge8e7,Ge7d6,Ga8c8]} (14... d5 {Not for the first time we see Black happy to provoke} 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 {when} Ke7 {followed by ...[Rac8] and ...[Kd6] should comfortably regain the pawn. As such, White might try to retain the tension.}) 15. Rc1 {Illustrative} Ke7 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gh8d8] (Black too can retain the tension. ...Rac8 will follow, and perhaps even ...Rfd8, all the while as we enjoy full equality if you're really keen to play for a win, we should advise that you may prefer 15...d4!? 16.Ne2 Rc8 , angling to keep the game alive in an unbalanced rook and bishop against rook and knight endgame.)} 16. Nxd5+ {[%csl Re7]} Bxd5 17. exd5 Rac8 {[%cal Ge7d6]} (17... Rac8 {Simply preparing to regain the pawn with 18...Kd6 and then ...Kxd5, and clearly} 18. Rc6 {is nothing to fear here in view of} Rxc6 19. dxc6 Rc8 {.}) 18. Kd2 Kd6 {[%cal Gd6d5,Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Gf6f5] With not only ...[Kxd5] on the agenda, but useful expansion through ... [h5]-[h4] and ...[f5], the onus is on White to find some counterplay and maintain the balance, and hoovering is not necessarily the answer.} 19. Rxc8 Rxc8 20. Rc1 $5 {A risky choice.} Rxc1 21. Kxc1 f5 $1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gf5f4,Gd6d5] Aiming to cramp with ...[f4]. After carefully checking things, we discovered that the pawn ending should be a draw, but with the less active king and an isolated d-pawn, it's again White who must be the more accurate to hold it.} *

