1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc5 ({We've dealt with White's three main options in our key tabiya and must now examine the remaining queen retreats. All three lines have their own characteristics and while they shouldn't be feared, Black must treat them with respect and understand what sort of set-up to aim for.Here we'll focus on} 8. Qd3 {, 8.Qd2 and 8.Qa3 . There is one other square available, but the queen rather floats in mid-air on the very odd occasion that it is placed on [c5].}) 8... d6 {[%csl Gc5,Gc8] Freeing the bishop to enter the game with gain of tempo.} 9. Qc3 $6 Qg6 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gg2] Eyeing e4 and g2, while exploiting White's inability to be able to go 10. [Nc3] or 10. [Bd3].} 10. f3 Nge7 {[%cal Gf7f5] Already a quick ...[f5] looms to exploit Black's not insignificant lead in development.} 11. Qd2 $5 {[%cal Rd2g5] This at least tried to remove the queens with [Qg5], even if it also left White with an inferior version of 8. [Qd2] in D.Burgess-Senior, British Rapidplay Championship, Bradford 2023.} f5 $1 {[%cal Gf5e4,Ge8g8] Pressuring [e4] while also getting ready to open the f-file, which should leave Black with a pretty attractive position once he's castled.We're also able to dodge a queen exchange here, be it with ...[h6] or ...[Qf7].} 12. Qg5 Qf7 $1 13. Nc3 O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Gf5e4,Gc6b4]} (13... O-O {Black threatens to blow open the centre with} 14. Z0 fxe4 {, and if} 15. Nxe4 d5 {. Black is already doing pretty well, with ideas too of ...[b5], as well as the good, old ...[Nb4].}) *

