1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc5 ({We've dealt with White's three main options in our key tabiya and must now examine the remaining queen retreats. All three lines have their own characteristics and while they shouldn't be feared, Black must treat them with respect and understand what sort of set-up to aim for.Here we'll focus on} 8. Qd3 {, 8.Qd2 and 8.Qa3 . There is one other square available, but the queen rather floats in mid-air on the very odd occasion that it is placed on [c5].}) 8... d6 {[%csl Gc5,Gc8] Freeing the bishop to enter the game with gain of tempo.} 9. Qe3 {At least this keeps the queen centralised.} Qg6 {[%csl Gf1,Gg2] Angling to keep the bishop on [f1] tied to the defence of [g2].} 10. Nc3 (10. c3 $6 Nf6 {Attacking [e4] while supporting ...[d5]; good classical chess, although a definite case might also be made for 10...[f5]!?.} 11. f3 d5 12. exd5 Nxd5 {Not for the first time in the Löwenthal we find Black with a healthy lead in development and White would be advised here to try to remove the queens.} 13. Qg5 {Black now exchanged on [g5] in Rosenzweig-Zisman, Jerusalem 2013, where it was also possible to retain the tension.} Be6 $5 14. Qxg6 hxg6 {The half-open h-file is fairly useful for Black, who will castle long then look to go forwards, be that with ...[Nf4], ...[f5] and ...[e4], or even ...[Nce7]-[f5].}) 10... Nge7 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gd6d5]} ({A more flexible scheme of development than} 10... Nf6 {. Black keeps the f-pawn free for action, although with the knight on [e7], we're now ready to seize the initiative with Nd4 , and if} 11. Bd3 d5 {.}) 11. Bd2 (11. Bd2 {White prepares to meet} Nd4 {with} 12. O-O-O {, but that leap is by no means Black's only idea in this structure.}) 11... f5 $5 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gb7b5,Gf5e4]} (11... f5 {Upping the ante. Black will now be attacking c2 if} 12. exf5 $2 Bxf5 {and meanwhile is ready to exchange on [e4] or perhaps even expand in further aggressive fashion with ...[b5].}) 12. O-O-O fxe4 {[%cal Gd6d5]} 13. Nxe4 {Regaining the pawn ( 13.Bc4 Be6 is also slightly better for Black, but now we're able to expand in the centre.)} d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4]} 14. Ng3 O-O {[%csl Gc1,Gd5,Ge5][%cal Gg6d6,Gc8e6,Ge7f5] Black enjoys a fine centre indeed, as well as a small edge. The queen can zoom over to [d6] if attacked, while ...[Be6] will complete development. We may then look to attack on the queenside or free the pieces and play right across the board after ...[Nf5].} *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
