1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd3 {A slightly unwieldy square for the queen, since now a quick ...[d5] may expose her to attack, such as with [exd5] [Bf5], and she is also vulnerable to a well-timed ...[Nb4] raid. On the plus side, White covers [e4] and gets ready to complete kingside development with [Be2] and [O-O], while now ...[Qg6] may be able to be met by [Qg3].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Developing and supporting ...d5.} 8... Qg6 $6 {achieves little here after} 9. Nc3 {, but the immediate 8...d5!? is possible, when 9.exd5 Bf5 10.Qg3 Nb4 11.Na3 may work out a little better for White.}) {d5? Nxd5 leaves the white queen usefully defending [e4]} 9. c4 $5 {[%csl Rd5] Erecting a Maroczy Bind and giving White full control of [d5], but all his pieces, bar the queen, are still at home. As such, Black is quite justified in trying to hit back immediately.} b5 $1 {Offering a pawn to blow open the position ( 9...Nd4 10.Nc3 d6 is a calmer, decent enough alternative, one which White shouldn't accept.)} 10. Be3 $5 {Sensible development from White, who may now tuck the queen back into a more secure post on [d2].} bxc4 {[%cal Gc4d3]} (10... bxc4 {Black continues to strive to open the position and would be happy to see} 11. Qxc4 O-O {followed by ...[d5] and/or ...[Rb8].}) 11. Qd2 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Rf1c4]} (11. Qd2 {Unfortunately, it seems that} d5 $5 12. exd5 Nd4 13. Bxc4 {doesn't give Black quite enough for a pawn here, so slightly more modest development is the order of the day.}) 11... d6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gf6g6] Preparing to cover the extra pawn on [c4] with ...[Be6] and ...[Qg6] is also likely to be an idea in this line.} 12. Bxc4 Be6 {[%cal Ge8g8,Ge6c4,Gf7f5,Gd6d5]} (12... Be6 {Challenging for control of the a2-g8 diagonal in thematic fashion, although here Black will meet} 13. Bxe6 {with} Qxe6 {to retain the pawn on [d6]. Black is now set to castle and then either go ...[Rfd8] to break with ...[d5] or look to get in ...[f5], depending on what White does with his light-squared bishop.}) *

