1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd3 {A slightly unwieldy square for the queen, since now a quick ...[d5] may expose her to attack, such as with [exd5] [Bf5], and she is also vulnerable to a well-timed ...[Nb4] raid. On the plus side, White covers [e4] and gets ready to complete kingside development with [Be2] and [O-O], while now ...[Qg6] may be able to be met by [Qg3].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Developing and supporting ...d5.} 8... Qg6 $6 {achieves little here after} 9. Nc3 {, but the immediate 8...d5!? is possible, when 9.exd5 Bf5 10.Qg3 Nb4 11.Na3 may work out a little better for White.}) {d5? Nxd5 leaves the white queen usefully defending [e4]} 9. c4 $5 {[%csl Rd5] Erecting a Maroczy Bind and giving White full control of [d5], but all his pieces, bar the queen, are still at home. As such, Black is quite justified in trying to hit back immediately.} b5 $1 {Offering a pawn to blow open the position ( 9...Nd4 10.Nc3 d6 is a calmer, decent enough alternative, one which White shouldn't accept.)} 10. cxb5 $6 {[%csl Rc6]} axb5 {Now [Nc3] will always run into ...[b4] and Black is all set to castle then break with ...[d5], but better that for White than now grabbing the pawn.} 11. Qxb5 $2 Nd4 {[%cal Gd4b5,Gd4c2] Already introducing some quite big threats with the knight.} 12. Qd3 d5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e4,Ge8g8,Gc8a6] We've already a huge initiative it's even '+3' in engine speak, with ...[O-O] and ...[dxe4] one idea to rip open lines, ...[Ba6] another.} *

