1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd3 {A slightly unwieldy square for the queen, since now a quick ...[d5] may expose her to attack, such as with [exd5] [Bf5], and she is also vulnerable to a well-timed ...[Nb4] raid. On the plus side, White covers [e4] and gets ready to complete kingside development with [Be2] and [O-O], while now ...[Qg6] may be able to be met by [Qg3].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Developing and supporting ...d5.} 8... Qg6 $6 {achieves little here after} 9. Nc3 {, but the immediate 8...d5!? is possible, when 9.exd5 Bf5 10.Qg3 Nb4 11.Na3 may work out a little better for White.}) {d5? Nxd5 leaves the white queen usefully defending [e4]} 9. g3 $2 {White tries to develop the light-squared bishop via a fianchetto, but there's simply no time for such a policy here.} d5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e4]} (9... d5 {Already} 10. exd5 $2 Bf5 {followed by ...[Nd4] would be superb for Black, as would be 10.Bg2 dxe4 11.Bxe4 Bg4 then ...[Rd8].}) 10. Nc3 Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5e4]} (10... Nb4 {Refusing to let White settle, and there just isn't a great square for his queen here. The engines give a slight nod to} 11. Qd1 {, but after} dxe4 {Black is clearly for choice and already much more than that after} 12. Nxe4 $2 Qc6 {.}) 11. Qe2 $2 d4 $1 {[%cal Gd4c3] It was already quite the massacre in Nguyen-Reutsky, Moscow 2006, where retreating the knight would scarcely have helped White.} 12. Nb1 Nec6 {[%cal Gd4d3,Gc8g4,Gc6d4] A combination of ...[d3], ...[Nd4] and, if needed, ...[Bg4] is going to clean White up. Talk about a total failure of development.} *

