1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd3 {A slightly unwieldy square for the queen, since now a quick ...[d5] may expose her to attack, such as with [exd5] [Bf5], and she is also vulnerable to a well-timed ...[Nb4] raid. On the plus side, White covers [e4] and gets ready to complete kingside development with [Be2] and [O-O], while now ...[Qg6] may be able to be met by [Qg3].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Developing and supporting ...d5.} 8... Qg6 $6 {achieves little here after} 9. Nc3 {, but the immediate 8...d5!? is possible, when 9.exd5 Bf5 10.Qg3 Nb4 11.Na3 may work out a little better for White.}) {d5? Nxd5 leaves the white queen usefully defending [e4]} 9. Nc3 {White tends to develop in this way and should be wary of falling too far behind in development.} d5 $1 {[%cal Gf6g6,Gd5d4]} ({It's high time to get on with the key break and annoy the white queen. Slightly strangely,} 9... O-O {has been more common in practice, but then} 10. Be3 d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Bf5 13. Qd2 {favours White. Instead, after the text move Black is ready to increase the pressure with ...[Qg6] or advance through ...[d4], so White pretty much has to accept the gambit.}) 10. exd5 $5 {A risky choice, if also one chosen by a young Nodirbek Abdusattorov and when he was already rated over 2600, so we must take this line seriously.} Nb4 {[%csl Gc2,Gd3,Gd5]} (10... Nb4 {Black wastes no time in pressuring d5 and c2, as well as the white queen, and now, for example,} 11. Qd2 $6 Qg6 {would already leave White under pressure, and worse.}) 11. Qe4 $1 {[%csl Rb4] Correctly counter-attacking against the knight on [b4].} Qd6 {[%csl Gb4,Gd5][%cal Gc8f5] Black must defend the knight this way, and now threatens to recoup the pawn on [e5], as well as to win on the spot with 12...[Bf5].} 12. Bd2 $5 {White's trickiest try and also, perhaps unsurprisingly, Abdusattorov's choice.} Bf5 $5 ({Black sees White's idea and asks to be shown. This may even be objectively the best try, and certainly} 12... O-O 13. a3 Nbxd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. O-O-O $1 Nf6 16. Qb4 {gave White a definite pull with the two bishops in Abdusattorov-Guseynov, Mersin 2019.}) 13. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Rb5d6] The only move for White, if a good one at that.} Nxc2+ $1 {[%cal Ra6b5,Rf5e4] Black counters with an intermezzo of our own.} 14. Qxc2 axb5 15. Bxb5+ Kf8 $5 {[%cal Gd6d5,Gf5c2] Giving up castling rights in return for a decent central presence once the pawn has been regained on [d5].} 16. Qb3 Qxd5 {[%cal Gd5b3,Gd5g2]} 17. Qxd5 Nxd5 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gf7f6,Gf5e6,Gh8d8,Gh8c8,Ge7f6] White is fractionally for choice here, but no more than that according to the engines, likely with good reason. Black is set to go 18...[Ke7] then ...[Rhc8] or just ...[Rhd8], while there's always ...[f6] or ...[Kf6] if White is causing trouble down the e-file and ...[Be6] to bolster Black's central presence. Indeed, the knight and [e5]-pawn are both well placed, while the rook on [a8] will help to slow down the advance of White's queenside majority.} *

