Gf6g6,Gd5d4]} ({It's high time to get on with the key break and annoy the white queen. Slightly strangely,} 9... O-O {has been more common in practice, but then} 10. Be3 d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Bf5 13. Qd2 {favours White. Instead, after the text move Black is ready to increase the pressure with ...[Qg6] or advance through ...[d4], so White pretty much has to accept the gambit.}) 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5f6,Rd5c7] White has tended to capture this way, presumably hoping that an exchange of knights will diminish the size of Black's initiative and compensation.} Nxd5 {Naturally the dangerous knight has to go and now White must actually be quite careful.} 11. exd5 $2 Nd4 $1 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gc8f5]} (11... Nd4 {All of a sudden White is in huge trouble with 12...Bf5 a very serious threat and note how} 12. Qc3 Bf5 13. Bd3 {doesn't help on account of simply} Rc8 {.}) 12. Qd1 Qg6 {[%csl Gc2,Gg2] White simply can't defend [c2] and [g2], and already resignation might not be misplaced.} 13. Bd3 {[%csl Rg6]} Qxg2 {[%cal Gg2h1]} 14. Kd2 Bg4 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Gg4d1,Gg2f2,Gg2d5,Ge5e4]} (14... Bg4 {Faced with all manner of threats, including} 15. Qf1 Qxd5 {then 16...[e4], White was already completely lost in Csolto-Egyed, Salgotarjan 2004.}) *

