[Black "8.Qd3 with 9.Nc3 d5 10.Nxd5 #2"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "28"]
[GameId "2141525858788648"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd3 {A slightly unwieldy square for the queen, since now a quick ...[d5] may expose her to attack, such as with [exd5] [Bf5], and she is also vulnerable to a well-timed ...[Nb4] raid. On the plus side, White covers [e4] and gets ready to complete kingside development with [Be2] and [O-O], while now ...[Qg6] may be able to be met by [Qg3].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Developing and supporting ...d5.} 8... Qg6 $6 {achieves little here after} 9. Nc3 {, but the immediate 8...d5!? is possible, when 9.exd5 Bf5 10.Qg3 Nb4 11.Na3 may work out a little better for White.}) {d5? Nxd5 leaves the white queen usefully defending [e4]} 9. Nc3 {White tends to develop in this way and should be wary of falling too far behind in development.} d5 $1 {[%cal Gf6g6,Gd5d4]} ({It's high time to get on with the key break and annoy the white queen. Slightly strangely,} 9... O-O {has been more common in practice, but then} 10. Be3 d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Bf5 13. Qd2 {favours White. Instead, after the text move Black is ready to increase the pressure with ...[Qg6] or advance through ...[d4], so White pretty much has to accept the gambit.}) 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5f6,Rd5c7] White has tended to capture this way, presumably hoping that an exchange of knights will diminish the size of Black's initiative and compensation.} Nxd5 {Naturally the dangerous knight has to go and now White must actually be quite careful.} 11. Qxd5 {The right recapture.} Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Ga8d8,Gc6d4] It's also possible to castle, but by attacking the queen straight away, Black creates the option of being able to do so again with 12...[Rd8].} (11... Be6 {The queen doesn't have to retreat down the d-file, but} 12. Qc5 Rc8 {also doesn't look overly comfortable for White.}) 12. Qd1 Qg6 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gg2][%cal Ga8d8]} ({This seems even stronger than} 12... Rd8 {. Black only wants to now go 13...[Rd8] with White unable to block with [Bd3]. As such, the engines suggest that the first player must rather contort.}) 13. f3 Rd8 14. Qe2 f5 {[%csl Ge1,Ge2][%cal Ge6f5,Ge8g8,Gf5e4] Black would be delighted if allowed to double pieces on the [b1]-[h7] diagonal. In any case, ...[O-O] is coming, and it doesn't look at all easy for White to unravel, '-0.18' though the cold-blooded engines may only proclaim.} *

