1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd3 {A slightly unwieldy square for the queen, since now a quick ...[d5] may expose her to attack, such as with [exd5] [Bf5], and she is also vulnerable to a well-timed ...[Nb4] raid. On the plus side, White covers [e4] and gets ready to complete kingside development with [Be2] and [O-O], while now ...[Qg6] may be able to be met by [Qg3].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Developing and supporting ...d5.} 8... Qg6 $6 {achieves little here after} 9. Nc3 {, but the immediate 8...d5!? is possible, when 9.exd5 Bf5 10.Qg3 Nb4 11.Na3 may work out a little better for White.}) {d5? Nxd5 leaves the white queen usefully defending [e4]} 9. Nc3 {White tends to develop in this way and should be wary of falling too far behind in development.} d5 $1 {[%cal Gf6g6,Gd5d4]} ({It's high time to get on with the key break and annoy the white queen. Slightly strangely,} 9... O-O {has been more common in practice, but then} 10. Be3 d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Bf5 13. Qd2 {favours White. Instead, after the text move Black is ready to increase the pressure with ...[Qg6] or advance through ...[d4], so White pretty much has to accept the gambit.}) 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5f6,Rd5c7] White has tended to capture this way, presumably hoping that an exchange of knights will diminish the size of Black's initiative and compensation.} Nxd5 {Naturally the dangerous knight has to go and now White must actually be quite careful.} 11. Qxd5 {The right recapture.} Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Ga8d8,Gc6d4] It's also possible to castle, but by attacking the queen straight away, Black creates the option of being able to do so again with 12...[Rd8].} (11... Be6 {The queen doesn't have to retreat down the d-file, but} 12. Qc5 Rc8 {also doesn't look overly comfortable for White.}) 12. Qd2 {Hoping to at least be able to swap off the queens via [g5].} Rd8 {[%csl Gd2]} ({Probably best here, or at least} 12... Qg6 13. f3 Rd8 {can now be met by} 14. Qf2 {when White would be somewhat less tangled up than in our line after 12. [Qd1] [Qg6].}) 13. Qg5 $2 {This may seem consistent, but now Black is able to seize the initiative by attacking the traditional Löwenthal weak-point in White's camp, [c2].} Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4c2]} 14. Bd3 {Fairly forced. Black has a few decent options here, including the most spectacular one.} Rxd3 $5 {[%cal Gb4c2]} 15. Qxf6 {White absolutely must trade the queens here if only so his king can then head to [d2].} gxf6 16. cxd3 Nc2+ {[%csl Ga1,Ge1]} 17. Kd2 $1 Nxa1 {Black has won a piece and threatens to extricate the knight with 18...[Bxa2]. Unfortunately though, it's White's move.} 18. b3 Nxb3+ 19. axb3 Bxb3 {[%csl Ga6,Gb7] The opposite-coloured bishops give White some drawing chances, but we shouldn't lose sight of the fact that there are still rooks on the board and that Black has two connected outside passed pawns.} *

