1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd3 {A slightly unwieldy square for the queen, since now a quick ...[d5] may expose her to attack, such as with [exd5] [Bf5], and she is also vulnerable to a well-timed ...[Nb4] raid. On the plus side, White covers [e4] and gets ready to complete kingside development with [Be2] and [O-O], while now ...[Qg6] may be able to be met by [Qg3].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Developing and supporting ...d5.} 8... Qg6 $6 {achieves little here after} 9. Nc3 {, but the immediate 8...d5!? is possible, when 9.exd5 Bf5 10.Qg3 Nb4 11.Na3 may work out a little better for White.}) {d5? Nxd5 leaves the white queen usefully defending [e4]} 9. Nc3 {White tends to develop in this way and should be wary of falling too far behind in development.} d5 $1 {[%cal Gf6g6,Gd5d4]} ({It's high time to get on with the key break and annoy the white queen. Slightly strangely,} 9... O-O {has been more common in practice, but then} 10. Be3 d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Bf5 13. Qd2 {favours White. Instead, after the text move Black is ready to increase the pressure with ...[Qg6] or advance through ...[d4], so White pretty much has to accept the gambit.}) 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5f6,Rd5c7] White has tended to capture this way, presumably hoping that an exchange of knights will diminish the size of Black's initiative and compensation.} Nxd5 {Naturally the dangerous knight has to go and now White must actually be quite careful.} 11. Qxd5 {The right recapture.} Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Ga8d8,Gc6d4] It's also possible to castle, but by attacking the queen straight away, Black creates the option of being able to do so again with 12...[Rd8].} (11... Be6 {The queen doesn't have to retreat down the d-file, but} 12. Qc5 Rc8 {also doesn't look overly comfortable for White.}) 12. Qd2 {Hoping to at least be able to swap off the queens via [g5].} Rd8 {[%csl Gd2]} ({Probably best here, or at least} 12... Qg6 13. f3 Rd8 {can now be met by} 14. Qf2 {when White would be somewhat less tangled up than in our line after 12. [Qd1] [Qg6].}) 13. Qe3 $5 {A slightly risky choice, if also a better square for the queen than [g5].} Nb4 $1 {[%csl Ga1,Ge1,Ge3][%cal Gb4c2] Ever a tempting raid, as well as one which threatens a family fork here.} 14. Qc3 $1 {[%cal Rc3b4] Calm and precise defence.} Nxa2 $5 {[%cal Ga2c3,Ga2c1] Unbalancing the position seems quite justified here, although we should note that Black would also be OK after 14...[Rd4].} 15. Rxa2 $1 {Another critical move.} Bxa2 16. b3 O-O {[%cal Gd8c8,Ga2b1,Gf6g6] This unbalanced position arose in Kosteniuk-Gazola, Istanbul Women's Olympiad 2012. The engines helpfully assess at '0.00', but clearly all three results are possible. The bishop is trapped on [a2], but White is still a few moves from completing development and with such resources as ...[Qg6] and ...[Rc8] then ...[Qc6], as well as a potentially disruptive ...[Bb1], we wouldn't mind taking the black pieces and trying to make something of the initiative.} *

