Gf6g6,Gd5d4]} ({It's high time to get on with the key break and annoy the white queen. Slightly strangely,} 9... O-O {has been more common in practice, but then} 10. Be3 d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Bf5 13. Qd2 {favours White. Instead, after the text move Black is ready to increase the pressure with ...[Qg6] or advance through ...[d4], so White pretty much has to accept the gambit.}) 10. Nxd5 {[%cal Rd5f6,Rd5c7] White has tended to capture this way, presumably hoping that an exchange of knights will diminish the size of Black's initiative and compensation.} Nxd5 {Naturally the dangerous knight has to go and now White must actually be quite careful.} 11. Qxd5 {The right recapture.} Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Ga8d8,Gc6d4] It's also possible to castle, but by attacking the queen straight away, Black creates the option of being able to do so again with 12...[Rd8].} (11... Be6 {The queen doesn't have to retreat down the d-file, but} 12. Qc5 Rc8 {also doesn't look overly comfortable for White.}) 12. Qd2 {Hoping to at least be able to swap off the queens via [g5].} Rd8 {[%csl Gd2]} ({Probably best here, or at least} 12... Qg6 13. f3 Rd8 {can now be met by} 14. Qf2 {when White would be somewhat less tangled up than in our line after 12. [Qd1] [Qg6].}) 13. Qe3 $5 {A slightly risky choice, if also a better square for the queen than [g5].} Nb4 $1 {[%csl Ga1,Ge1,Ge3][%cal Gb4c2] Ever a tempting raid, as well as one which threatens a family fork here.} 14. Qc3 $1 {[%cal Rc3b4] Calm and precise defence.} Nxa2 $5 {[%cal Ga2c3,Ga2c1] Unbalancing the position seems quite justified here, although we should note that Black would also be OK after 14...[Rd4].} 15. Rxa2 $1 {Another critical move.} Bxa2 16. b3 {Illustrative} O-O {[%cal Gd8c8,Gf6g6,Ga2b1] This unbalanced position arose in Kosteniuk-Gazola, Istanbul Women's Olympiad 2012. The engines helpfully assess at '0.00', but clearly all three results are possible. The bishop is trapped on [a2], but White is still a few moves from completing development and with such resources as ...[Qg6] and ...[Rc8] then ...[Qc6], as well as a potentially disruptive ...[Bb1], we wouldn't mind taking the black pieces and trying to make something of the initiative.Let's see an example.} 17. Ba3 {Alexandra Kosteniuk's choice.} (17. Bd3 $6 Rxd3 $1 {((An unexpected but fairly powerful blow as Black prepares to rescue the bishop if 18.cxd3 Qe6. ) . )} 18. Qxd3 Rc8 19. O-O Bb1 {The bishop lives and now White has to be slightly careful not to drift into too much trouble.} 20. Qh3 Rc7 $1 {A calm and good choice. The bishop will emerge on [c2] or [e4].}) 17... Rc8 $5 {[%csl Rc3]} ({Forcing the pace.} 17... Qg5 18. g3 Rc8 19. Qb2 Rfd8 20. Bd3 b5 {With Black looking for a timely ...[b4], the position remained extremely unclear in Kosteniuk-Gazola, where it wasn't long before Black panicked, losing her way and the game.}) 18. Qb2 Qg6 {[%csl Ge1,Ge4] Offering the rook to go after the fairly big pawn on [e4].} 19. Bxf8 Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gc8c2]} 20. Kd1 Rd8+ {[%csl Gd1] Pretty much forcing White's next.} 21. Bd3 Qxg2 {[%cal Gg2h1,Gg2f2]} 22. Re1 Qxf2 {[%csl Gb2,Gd1][%cal Gd8d3] Black has three pawns for the piece and threatens to win on the spot with 23...[Rxd3]+. The bishop on [a2] is still trapped though, and it's probably no surprise that the engines still assess at '0.00', since perpetual check is a likely outcome.} 23. Re2 Qg1+ 24. Kd2 Qg5+ 25. Kd1 Qg1+ {[%csl Gd1,Gg1] Neither side can easily deviate from the repetition.} *

