1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd2 {[%cal Rd2g5] While this retreat is unlikely to be played by an opponent unfamiliar with the Löwenthal, it has been used by a number of grandmasters and is quite a sensible choice, one even recommended by Spanish Grandmaster Miguel Santos on his Play the Open Sicilian course, and it's also touted in another Chessable course, The Complete Open Sicilian for White.} (8. Qd2 {In short, White angles for a superior version of the immediate queen exchange lines of Theory Three and will meet} Qg6 {with} 9. Nc3 {followed by [Qg5], not least in the event of} Nge7 {(( 9...d5!? isn't completely ridiculous, but 10.f3! is a surprisingly decent response))} 10. h4 $1 h5 11. Qg5 {.}) 8... Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d6,Gf6g6,Gc8e6] Sensible development as well as approach which keeps Black's options open, depending on what White does. Black may castle quickly or go ...[Qg6], or avoid both those moves in favour of quick queenside development with ...[d6] and ...[Be6].} 9. c4 {[%csl Gd4,Rd5] The Maroczy Bind gives White classic control over [d5], but also leaves him vulnerable on [d4], as well as potentially to attacks on the [c4]- and [e4]-pawns.} d6 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gc6d4] Opening lines for the final pieces to join in the fray and ...[Nd4] ideas are also high on Black's agenda.} 10. Nc3 Nd4 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga8c8,Gf6h4,Ge8g8] Leaping straight into the hole which White has kindly created. Black may follow up with ...[Be6] and ...[Rc8] or look for something more aggressive, such as with ...[Qh4], ...[O-O] and ...[f5].} 11. Bd3 Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gb7b5] Freeing [c8] for the rook and both sides should then be aware to sacrificial opportunities for Black with ...[b5], especially if the white queen can be deflected from, or overloaded on, [d2].} 12. O-O Rc8 {[%cal Ge6c4]} ({Forcing White to decide what to do about the pawn on c4. This leads to potential fun, if drawish fireworks at that, so if you're keen to keep the game alive, you might wish to prefer} 12... Ng6 $5 {here, bringing another piece over to the kingside and clamping down on the [f4]-square.}) 13. b3 (13. Nd5 $5 {((White appears to be better after 13...Bxd5 14.exd5! followed by [f2]-[f4], so Black should force matters in the same manner that we'll see after 13. [b3].))} Nxd5 14. cxd5 Nf3+ $1 15. gxf3 Bh3 {White is a whole piece ahead, but 16...[Rxc1] is a big threat and it transpires that neither side can deviate from the upcoming sequence:} 16. Qg5 $1 Rxc1 $1 17. Qxf6 gxf6 18. Rfxc1 Rg8+ {The bishop will shuffle between [h3] and [g2] to force perpetual check.}) 13... b5 $5 {[%cal Gb5c4,Gd4f3]} (13... b5 {This powerful and thematic advance should give Black decent counterplay. Note especially how} 14. cxb5 Nf3+ 15. gxf3 Bh3 {gives us enough for the piece, thanks to the ideas of ...[Qxf3] and ...[Rxc3].}) 14. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6]} Nxd5 {[%csl Ge6] This capture to preserve the light-squared bishop for duties on the kingside.} 15. cxd5 Nf3+ $1 {[%csl Gd2,Gg1] Olé!} 16. gxf3 Bh3 {[%cal Gc8c1] There's no knight on [c3] here, but there are still tactics down the c-file. Black threatens to force mate beginning with 17...[Rxc1] and White's reply is pretty much forced.} 17. Qg5 $1 Rxc1 $1 {Here Mohammad-Rahman, Dhaka 2010, was agreed drawn in view of the upcoming repetition involving the g-file.} 18. Qxf6 gxf6 19. Rfxc1 Rg8+ {[%csl Gg1][%cal Gh3g2]} 20. Kh1 Bg2+ 21. Kg1 Bh3+ {White cannot escape the perpetual net.} *

