1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd2 {[%cal Rd2g5] While this retreat is unlikely to be played by an opponent unfamiliar with the Löwenthal, it has been used by a number of grandmasters and is quite a sensible choice, one even recommended by Spanish Grandmaster Miguel Santos on his Play the Open Sicilian course, and it's also touted in another Chessable course, The Complete Open Sicilian for White.} (8. Qd2 {In short, White angles for a superior version of the immediate queen exchange lines of Theory Three and will meet} Qg6 {with} 9. Nc3 {followed by [Qg5], not least in the event of} Nge7 {(( 9...d5!? isn't completely ridiculous, but 10.f3! is a surprisingly decent response))} 10. h4 $1 h5 11. Qg5 {.}) 8... Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d6,Gf6g6,Gc8e6] Sensible development as well as approach which keeps Black's options open, depending on what White does. Black may castle quickly or go ...[Qg6], or avoid both those moves in favour of quick queenside development with ...[d6] and ...[Be6].} 9. c4 {[%csl Gd4,Rd5] The Maroczy Bind gives White classic control over [d5], but also leaves him vulnerable on [d4], as well as potentially to attacks on the [c4]- and [e4]-pawns.} Qh4 $5 {[%cal Gh4e4] A related idea which you may enjoy trying in blitz and rapid games is Dagoberto Diaz's bold gambit.} 10. Nc3 Nd4 11. Bd3 d5 $1 {[%cal Gc8h3,Gd5c4] This might well knock an opponent off kilter, not least if they fail to spot that 12...[Bh3] is all set to land, although, unfortunately, this amazing idea isn't completely sound.} 12. cxd5 Bh3 $1 {[%csl Gd2,Ge1][%cal Gh3g2,Gd4f3] Neatly exploiting one downside to the white queen being on [d2].} 13. Bf1 $1 Bg4 14. Qd3 f5 $1 {[%cal Gf5e4]} (14... f5 {This was but extremely unclear to the human eye and great fun for Black in Suri-Diaz, Havana 1999, even if it's just '+0.7' according to the Stockfish after the calm} 15. Be3 {.}) *

