1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd2 {[%cal Rd2g5] While this retreat is unlikely to be played by an opponent unfamiliar with the Löwenthal, it has been used by a number of grandmasters and is quite a sensible choice, one even recommended by Spanish Grandmaster Miguel Santos on his Play the Open Sicilian course, and it's also touted in another Chessable course, The Complete Open Sicilian for White.} (8. Qd2 {In short, White angles for a superior version of the immediate queen exchange lines of Theory Three and will meet} Qg6 {with} 9. Nc3 {followed by [Qg5], not least in the event of} Nge7 {(( 9...d5!? isn't completely ridiculous, but 10.f3! is a surprisingly decent response))} 10. h4 $1 h5 11. Qg5 {.}) 8... Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d6,Gf6g6,Gc8e6] Sensible development as well as approach which keeps Black's options open, depending on what White does. Black may castle quickly or go ...[Qg6], or avoid both those moves in favour of quick queenside development with ...[d6] and ...[Be6].} 9. b3 {The engines initially quite like this method of keeping the queen on [d2] while being able to develop the bishop from [c1], but it does seem that Black has an active and thematic counter to obtain reasonable counterplay.} Qg6 {[%csl Ge4,Gg2] Eyeing [e4] and [g2] in preparation for one of our favourite counterstrikes.} 10. f3 $5 (10. f3 {This doesn't do any wonders for White's development, but does rather take ...d5 ideas off the table, or at least} d5 $2 11. exd5 Nd4 12. Na3 {leaves Black coming up somewhat short.}) 10... f5 $1 {[%cal Gf5e4,Gd7d5]} (10... f5 {A new idea, and one we quite like. The first point is to induce, through the pressure against e4,} 11. Nc3 {when we can go} fxe4 12. fxe4 d5 $1 13. exd5 Nd4 {with decent compensation after all. The second is that the capture on [f5] need not be feared.}) 11. exf5 Qf6 $1 {[%cal Gd7d5]} (11... Qf6 {The plan is just to force through ...d5 and} 12. c4 $6 d5 $1 13. cxd5 Nd4 {would leave White's development and position looking a bit vulnerable.}) 12. Nc3 d5 $1 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gc6d4,Gh7h5]} (12... d5 {Offering a second pawn to try to get in ...Bxf5 and ...Nd4, or if} 13. g4 {stir up mayhem with} h5 $1 {.}) 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Bxf5 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gc6b4,Ge5e4] With all of ...[e4], ...[Nb4] and ...[Rd8] high on the agenda, it's clear that Black has promising play for the price of just a pawn.} *

