1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd2 {[%cal Rd2g5] While this retreat is unlikely to be played by an opponent unfamiliar with the Löwenthal, it has been used by a number of grandmasters and is quite a sensible choice, one even recommended by Spanish Grandmaster Miguel Santos on his Play the Open Sicilian course, and it's also touted in another Chessable course, The Complete Open Sicilian for White.} (8. Qd2 {In short, White angles for a superior version of the immediate queen exchange lines of Theory Three and will meet} Qg6 {with} 9. Nc3 {followed by [Qg5], not least in the event of} Nge7 {(( 9...d5!? isn't completely ridiculous, but 10.f3! is a surprisingly decent response))} 10. h4 $1 h5 11. Qg5 {.}) 8... Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d6,Gf6g6,Gc8e6] Sensible development as well as approach which keeps Black's options open, depending on what White does. Black may castle quickly or go ...[Qg6], or avoid both those moves in favour of quick queenside development with ...[d6] and ...[Be6].} 9. Nc3 {This natural move seems best, although practice has also seen a great many other moves tested.} O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc6d4,Gd7d5,Gd7d6] Calmly housing the king while keeping all our options open: a quick ...[b5] and/or ...[Nd4] may follow, ...[d5] as a gambit isn't entirely off the agenda and Black can always develop the remaining pieces after simply ...[d6].} 10. Bd3 {A safer square for the bishop, although here too Black can play against it.} Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd7d5] Targeting the bishop while offering support to the ...[d5] break.} 11. O-O {This calm choice was preferred in Schaefer-Buecker, German League 2007, where Black might have supported ...[d5] with 11...[Rd8] or broken straightaway.} d5 $5 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gf8d8] We're now ready to go ...[Rd8], as well as make a timely exchange on [d3] and should be happy if White spots the opportunity to grab a pawn.} 12. exd5 Nbxd5 {[%cal Gd5f4,Gd5c3,Ge7c6,Ge7d5] This recapture for once, as the knight heads for [f4] and Black also has the solid option of an exchange on [c3] followed by ...[Nc6].} 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxh7+ $5 {[%csl Rd5]} Kxh7 15. Qxd5 Rd8 {[%csl Gd5,Gd8][%cal Gf6g6,Gc8f5] Our first non-forced move for a few turns and also a logical one, activating the rook with tempo before completing development with ...[Bf5] and/or starting to attack on the light squares with ...[Qg6].} 16. Qe4+ {[%csl Rh7]} Bf5 $1 {[%csl Gc2,Ge4] Continuing in aggressive vein.} 17. Qxb7 Bxc2 {[%csl Gc2,Gd1][%cal Gf6g6,Ga8b8,Ga8c8] We're a pawn down, but should have enough for it. The bishop on [c2] rather interferes with the aspirations of the white rooks and will be supported by ...[Qg6], which will also threaten ...[Be4]. Meanwhile, the rook on [a8] will hop across to [b8] or even [c8], leaving Black pretty actively placed.} *

