1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd2 {[%cal Rd2g5] While this retreat is unlikely to be played by an opponent unfamiliar with the Löwenthal, it has been used by a number of grandmasters and is quite a sensible choice, one even recommended by Spanish Grandmaster Miguel Santos on his Play the Open Sicilian course, and it's also touted in another Chessable course, The Complete Open Sicilian for White.} (8. Qd2 {In short, White angles for a superior version of the immediate queen exchange lines of Theory Three and will meet} Qg6 {with} 9. Nc3 {followed by [Qg5], not least in the event of} Nge7 {(( 9...d5!? isn't completely ridiculous, but 10.f3! is a surprisingly decent response))} 10. h4 $1 h5 11. Qg5 {.}) 8... Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d6,Gf6g6,Gc8e6] Sensible development as well as approach which keeps Black's options open, depending on what White does. Black may castle quickly or go ...[Qg6], or avoid both those moves in favour of quick queenside development with ...[d6] and ...[Be6].} 9. Nc3 {This natural move seems best, although practice has also seen a great many other moves tested.} O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc6d4,Gd7d5,Gd7d6] Calmly housing the king while keeping all our options open: a quick ...[b5] and/or ...[Nd4] may follow, ...[d5] as a gambit isn't entirely off the agenda and Black can always develop the remaining pieces after simply ...[d6].} 10. Bd3 {A safer square for the bishop, although here too Black can play against it.} Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd7d5] Targeting the bishop while offering support to the ...[d5] break.} 11. Bc4 $5 {An ambitious policy, trying to retain the bishop.} d5 $5 {[%cal Gd5c4,Gf8d8,Gf6g6]} (11... d5 {Wasting no time breaking, with tempo too. Now} 12. exd5 $2 Qg6 {would not be wise for White and 12.Bxd5 Rd8 also looks a little awkward.}) 12. Nxd5 {[%csl Rb4,Rf6]} Nbxd5 (12... Nbxd5 {Forcing the pace and getting ready to meet} 13. exd5 {with} b5 {, followed by 14...[Bb7] and 15...[Rad8], which should regain the pawn with a decent game.}) 13. Bxd5 Nxd5 (13... Nxd5 {Continuing to force matters, just as} 14. Qxd5 Rd8 {now would, when Black would look to follow up with a quick ...[Qg6].}) 14. exd5 Bf5 {[%csl Gc2,Gd5,Gg2][%cal Gf6g6,Ga8c8,Gf8d8,Gf5e4] There are light-square targets on [c2], [d5] and [g2], and Black should again have enough for the pawn, with such moves as ...[Rac8], ...[Rfd8] and ...[Qg6] on the way, as well as a timely ...[Be4].} *

