1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd2 {[%cal Rd2g5] While this retreat is unlikely to be played by an opponent unfamiliar with the Löwenthal, it has been used by a number of grandmasters and is quite a sensible choice, one even recommended by Spanish Grandmaster Miguel Santos on his Play the Open Sicilian course, and it's also touted in another Chessable course, The Complete Open Sicilian for White.} (8. Qd2 {In short, White angles for a superior version of the immediate queen exchange lines of Theory Three and will meet} Qg6 {with} 9. Nc3 {followed by [Qg5], not least in the event of} Nge7 {(( 9...d5!? isn't completely ridiculous, but 10.f3! is a surprisingly decent response))} 10. h4 $1 h5 11. Qg5 {.}) 8... Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d6,Gf6g6,Gc8e6] Sensible development as well as approach which keeps Black's options open, depending on what White does. Black may castle quickly or go ...[Qg6], or avoid both those moves in favour of quick queenside development with ...[d6] and ...[Be6].} 9. Nc3 {This natural move seems best, although practice has also seen a great many other moves tested.} O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc6d4,Gd7d5,Gd7d6] Calmly housing the king while keeping all our options open: a quick ...[b5] and/or ...[Nd4] may follow, ...[d5] as a gambit isn't entirely off the agenda and Black can always develop the remaining pieces after simply ...[d6].} 10. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6] Forcing the pace.} Nxd5 $1 {[%cal Gc6e7]} (10... Nxd5 {Best, and Black should be quite happy to transform the structure so. Admittedly, White can take back with a piece, but} 11. Qxd5 Ne7 $1 {also feels comfortable for Black, with a rapid ...[b5] and/or ...[d5] imminent.}) 11. exd5 Ne7 12. Be2 b5 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gc8b7] Taking control of [c4] and so getting ready to target [d5] with ...[Bb7].} 13. b3 (13. b3 {White is keen to have a pawn, not a bishop, on c4 and now} e4 $6 14. Rb1 {was a too ambitious from one of your authors and left Black a little overextended in Gormally-Palliser, Scarborough 2007.}) 13... Ng6 {[%cal Gg6f4,Gf6g6] A much better policy, angling for kingside play with ...[Nf4] and ...[Qg6].} 14. Qg5 {[%csl Rf6]} Qb6 {[%cal Gb6d4,Gd7d6,Gc8d7] Running away from a queenless middlegame while threatening ...[Qd4]. Black may also just continue with ...[d6] and ...[Bd7] followed by contesting the queenside and likely getting ...[f5] in, which should secure a reasonable game.} *

