1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd2 {[%cal Rd2g5] While this retreat is unlikely to be played by an opponent unfamiliar with the Löwenthal, it has been used by a number of grandmasters and is quite a sensible choice, one even recommended by Spanish Grandmaster Miguel Santos on his Play the Open Sicilian course, and it's also touted in another Chessable course, The Complete Open Sicilian for White.} (8. Qd2 {In short, White angles for a superior version of the immediate queen exchange lines of Theory Three and will meet} Qg6 {with} 9. Nc3 {followed by [Qg5], not least in the event of} Nge7 {(( 9...d5!? isn't completely ridiculous, but 10.f3! is a surprisingly decent response))} 10. h4 $1 h5 11. Qg5 {.}) 8... Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d6,Gf6g6,Gc8e6] Sensible development as well as approach which keeps Black's options open, depending on what White does. Black may castle quickly or go ...[Qg6], or avoid both those moves in favour of quick queenside development with ...[d6] and ...[Be6].} 9. Nc3 {This natural move seems best, although practice has also seen a great many other moves tested.} O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc6d4,Gd7d5,Gd7d6] Calmly housing the king while keeping all our options open: a quick ...[b5] and/or ...[Nd4] may follow, ...[d5] as a gambit isn't entirely off the agenda and Black can always develop the remaining pieces after simply ...[d6].} 10. h4 $5 {An early [h4] is all the rage these days, although we were only able to track down one game where it was played here, Brueggemann-T.O'Donnell, World Senior Team Championship, Radebeul 2016, where 10...[d6] was sensible enough.} Nd4 $5 {[%csl Gc2] Ignoring White's kingside demonstration and preventing any [Qg5] possibilities for now due to the pressure against [c2].} 11. Bd3 d5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e4]} (11... d5 {Our favourite pawn sacrifice, angling to seize the initiative once we've got ...Bf5 in. For now, the idea is} 12. Z0 dxe4 {, and if} 13. Bxe4 $2 Bf5 {or 13.Nxe4 Qc6 , pressing on the light squares in either case, while 12.Qg5 can now be met easily enough with 12...Qd6 .}) 12. exd5 Bf5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gf8d8,Gf6g6,Gh7h5] Black has decent compensation with ...[Rfd8] and ...[Qg6] on the way, while it may even be possible to fix White's kingside pawns where they are with a timely ...[h5].} *

