1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd2 {[%cal Rd2g5] While this retreat is unlikely to be played by an opponent unfamiliar with the Löwenthal, it has been used by a number of grandmasters and is quite a sensible choice, one even recommended by Spanish Grandmaster Miguel Santos on his Play the Open Sicilian course, and it's also touted in another Chessable course, The Complete Open Sicilian for White.} (8. Qd2 {In short, White angles for a superior version of the immediate queen exchange lines of Theory Three and will meet} Qg6 {with} 9. Nc3 {followed by [Qg5], not least in the event of} Nge7 {(( 9...d5!? isn't completely ridiculous, but 10.f3! is a surprisingly decent response))} 10. h4 $1 h5 11. Qg5 {.}) 8... Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d6,Gf6g6,Gc8e6] Sensible development as well as approach which keeps Black's options open, depending on what White does. Black may castle quickly or go ...[Qg6], or avoid both those moves in favour of quick queenside development with ...[d6] and ...[Be6].} 9. Nc3 {This natural move seems best, although practice has also seen a great many other moves tested.} O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc6d4,Gd7d5,Gd7d6] Calmly housing the king while keeping all our options open: a quick ...[b5] and/or ...[Nd4] may follow, ...[d5] as a gambit isn't entirely off the agenda and Black can always develop the remaining pieces after simply ...[d6].} 10. b3 $5 {This method of developing the queenside pieces is yet to fully catch on perhaps it soon will, having been recommended on Miguel Santos's aforementioned Chessable course, but has been tried by a few decent players and is quite a critical approach.} (10. b3 {Here} Qg6 $6 11. Ba3 {followed by [O-O-O] doesn't make any sense, but you might wish to consider 10...d5!? in a blitz or rapid game. It certainly has shock value, as would 11.Nxd5 Nxd5 12.exd5 Nd4 , but unfortunately after 13.Bb2 Bf5 Black comes up short, due to 14.Rc1 or 14.Bd3 e4 15.Bxe4! Bxe4 16.O-O-O .}) 10... b5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gc6d4] Thematic queenside expansion. We now have the option of a timely ...[b4], although the immediate plan is to develop counterplay with ...[Bb7] and ...[Nd4].} 11. Bb2 {[%csl Rb2]} (11. Bb2 {Completing the fianchetto. White's king should now be relatively safe on the queenside and Black must watch the unopposed bishop on b2 and so avoid anything too ambitious, not least} b4 $2 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 $1 {.}) 11... Bb7 $5 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gc6d4]} (11... Bb7 {Continuing the plan while aiming to distract White with the hanging d-pawn. The queen's knight is likely to leap into d4, although in the event of the solid} 12. Bd3 {, the bishop-hunting} Nb4 {would be a good option.}) 12. Nd5 $5 {[%csl Rf6]} (12. Nd5 {Upping the ante as White also prepares to sacrifice a pawn for the initiative with} Qh4 13. O-O-O $1 {.}) 12... Nxd5 $1 {[%cal Gc6e7,Gc6d4]} (12... Nxd5 {A sensible choice, as well as one which sets a small trap. Now} 13. exd5 $1 Ne7 14. c4 d6 {can at most only be a touch worse for Black, who should quickly regroup the bishop via [c8].}) 13. Qxd5 $4 Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4c2,Ga8c8] The trap springs shut. The bishop on [b7] is falling, but so is [c2].} 14. Qxb7 Nxc2+ {[%csl Ga1,Ge1,Gf2][%cal Gc2a1]} (14... Nxc2+ {Not only is the rook on a1 falling, but if} 15. Kd1 {or 15.Kd2 Black will be able to create some very serious threats with ( 15...Qxf2+ , and already the engines consider White to be hopelessly lost.)}) 15. Ke2 Nxa1 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Ga1c2,Ga8c8] White's problem isn't so much that the knight will make it out, but that the black rooks will inflict a massacre upon him down the c-file.} 16. Bxa1 Rac8 {[%csl Ge2,Gf2][%cal Gc8c2,Gc8c1] There's just no good way for White to deal with the threats of 17...[Rc2]+ and 17...[Rc1].} (16... Rac8 {For example,} 17. Kd1 Qxf2 {(Threatening to force mate, beginning with 18...[Qc2]+.)} 18. Be2 d5 $1 {By no means the only good move, but both the strongest and most aesthetic way of ripping open further lines.} 19. exd5 Qe3 20. Bb2 Qe4 {There are quite simply far too many major threats for White to cope with.}) *

