t as well as approach which keeps Black's options open, depending on what White does. Black may castle quickly or go ...[Qg6], or avoid both those moves in favour of quick queenside development with ...[d6] and ...[Be6].} 9. Nc3 {This natural move seems best, although practice has also seen a great many other moves tested.} O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc6d4,Gd7d5,Gd7d6] Calmly housing the king while keeping all our options open: a quick ...[b5] and/or ...[Nd4] may follow, ...[d5] as a gambit isn't entirely off the agenda and Black can always develop the remaining pieces after simply ...[d6].} 10. b3 $5 {This method of developing the queenside pieces is yet to fully catch on perhaps it soon will, having been recommended on Miguel Santos's aforementioned Chessable course, but has been tried by a few decent players and is quite a critical approach.} (10. b3 {Here} Qg6 $6 11. Ba3 {followed by [O-O-O] doesn't make any sense, but you might wish to consider 10...d5!? in a blitz or rapid game. It certainly has shock value, as would 11.Nxd5 Nxd5 12.exd5 Nd4 , but unfortunately after 13.Bb2 Bf5 Black comes up short, due to 14.Rc1 or 14.Bd3 e4 15.Bxe4! Bxe4 16.O-O-O .}) 10... b5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gc6d4] Thematic queenside expansion. We now have the option of a timely ...[b4], although the immediate plan is to develop counterplay with ...[Bb7] and ...[Nd4].} 11. Bb2 {[%csl Rb2]} (11. Bb2 {Completing the fianchetto. White's king should now be relatively safe on the queenside and Black must watch the unopposed bishop on b2 and so avoid anything too ambitious, not least} b4 $2 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 $1 {.}) 11... Bb7 $5 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gc6d4]} (11... Bb7 {Continuing the plan while aiming to distract White with the hanging d-pawn. The queen's knight is likely to leap into d4, although in the event of the solid} 12. Bd3 {, the bishop-hunting} Nb4 {would be a good option.}) 12. O-O-O $1 {This direct approach seems both consistent and best.} Rac8 $5 {[%csl Gc1,Gc8] Placing the rook on the same file as the white king cannot be a bad policy, as we again aim to entice White with the d-pawn ( 12...d6 is also possible though if you don't like to sacrifice, with a likely transposition after 13.Kb1 Rfd8 or 13.Qxd6 Qxf2 .)} 13. Kb1 {A prudent choice, making the king safer.} d6 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gf8d8,Gc6d4]} (13... d6 {While this doesn't remove the pawn from danger, Black is no longer sacrificing as} 14. Qxd6 {can be met by} Qxf2 {. Objectively speaking, White must be slightly for choice here with a relatively safe king and the two bishops, but Black is not without counter-chances. 14...[Rfd8] is set to involve the final piece, after which 15...[Nd4] will threaten ...[b4]. Bringing the knight to [d4] and then dropping it back to [e6] is also a good policy should Black be worried that White might break with [f2]-[f4], aiming to open up lines for the unopposed bishop on [b2].}) 14. Bd3 {This would be in keeping with Santos's preferred approach as White in this line.} Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4d3]} (14... Nb4 {Black wastes no time seizing on the position of the bishop and now there's no time for White to force through f2-f4 with} 15. Rdf1 $6 {due to} Nxd3 16. Qxd3 b4 17. Na4 d5 {.}) 15. Ba3 {[%csl Rb4]} Nxd3 16. Qxd3 Qxf2 {[%cal Gf2b6,Gf2g2,Gf8d8] Not too hot a pawn to take, as the queen can always retreat to [b6] and it may also be possible to pick off [g2].} 17. Qxd6 {[%csl Re7]} Rfe8 {[%csl Gc2,Gc3,Gc8][%cal Ge7g6] With ...[Ng6] imminent ...[Rxc3] will then be a threat, White not having [Qxe7] in response, Black is pretty solid and should have enough counterplay.} *

