1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd2 {[%cal Rd2g5] While this retreat is unlikely to be played by an opponent unfamiliar with the Löwenthal, it has been used by a number of grandmasters and is quite a sensible choice, one even recommended by Spanish Grandmaster Miguel Santos on his Play the Open Sicilian course, and it's also touted in another Chessable course, The Complete Open Sicilian for White.} (8. Qd2 {In short, White angles for a superior version of the immediate queen exchange lines of Theory Three and will meet} Qg6 {with} 9. Nc3 {followed by [Qg5], not least in the event of} Nge7 {(( 9...d5!? isn't completely ridiculous, but 10.f3! is a surprisingly decent response))} 10. h4 $1 h5 11. Qg5 {.}) 8... Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d6,Gf6g6,Gc8e6] Sensible development as well as approach which keeps Black's options open, depending on what White does. Black may castle quickly or go ...[Qg6], or avoid both those moves in favour of quick queenside development with ...[d6] and ...[Be6].} 9. Nc3 {This natural move seems best, although practice has also seen a great many other moves tested.} O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc6d4,Gd7d5,Gd7d6] Calmly housing the king while keeping all our options open: a quick ...[b5] and/or ...[Nd4] may follow, ...[d5] as a gambit isn't entirely off the agenda and Black can always develop the remaining pieces after simply ...[d6].} 10. b3 $5 {This method of developing the queenside pieces is yet to fully catch on perhaps it soon will, having been recommended on Miguel Santos's aforementioned Chessable course, but has been tried by a few decent players and is quite a critical approach.} (10. b3 {Here} Qg6 $6 11. Ba3 {followed by [O-O-O] doesn't make any sense, but you might wish to consider 10...d5!? in a blitz or rapid game. It certainly has shock value, as would 11.Nxd5 Nxd5 12.exd5 Nd4 , but unfortunately after 13.Bb2 Bf5 Black comes up short, due to 14.Rc1 or 14.Bd3 e4 15.Bxe4! Bxe4 16.O-O-O .}) 10... b5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gc6d4] Thematic queenside expansion. We now have the option of a timely ...[b4], although the immediate plan is to develop counterplay with ...[Bb7] and ...[Nd4].} 11. Bb2 {[%csl Rb2]} (11. Bb2 {Completing the fianchetto. White's king should now be relatively safe on the queenside and Black must watch the unopposed bishop on b2 and so avoid anything too ambitious, not least} b4 $2 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 $1 {.}) 11... Bb7 $5 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gc6d4]} (11... Bb7 {Continuing the plan while aiming to distract White with the hanging d-pawn. The queen's knight is likely to leap into d4, although in the event of the solid} 12. Bd3 {, the bishop-hunting} Nb4 {would be a good option.}) 12. O-O-O $1 {This direct approach seems both consistent and best.} Rac8 $5 {[%csl Gc1,Gc8] Placing the rook on the same file as the white king cannot be a bad policy, as we again aim to entice White with the d-pawn ( 12...d6 is also possible though if you don't like to sacrifice, with a likely transposition after 13.Kb1 Rfd8 or 13.Qxd6 Qxf2 .)} 13. Kb1 {A prudent choice, making the king safer.} d6 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gf8d8,Gc6d4]} (13... d6 {While this doesn't remove the pawn from danger, Black is no longer sacrificing as} 14. Qxd6 {can be met by} Qxf2 {. Objectively speaking, White must be slightly for choice here with a relatively safe king and the two bishops, but Black is not without counter-chances. 14...[Rfd8] is set to involve the final piece, after which 15...[Nd4] will threaten ...[b4]. Bringing the knight to [d4] and then dropping it back to [e6] is also a good policy should Black be worried that White might break with [f2]-[f4], aiming to open up lines for the unopposed bishop on [b2].}) 14. f3 {[%cal Rd2d6]} Rfd8 (14... Rfd8 {Securing the d-pawn and now both} 15. Bd3 Nb4 {and 15.Nd5 Nxd5 16.exd5 Ne7 again look decent enough for Black.}) 15. h4 $5 Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd6d5]} (15... Nd4 {While White may be dreaming of kingside glory, it won't actually be so easy to mate us. Black threatens to seize the initiative with 16...d5 and allowing} 16. g4 $2 Qxf3 {also wouldn't be too wise by White.}) 16. Bd3 $1 (16. Bd3 {White calmly gets ready to meet} d5 {with} 17. Rhe1 {and then pressure [e5], so Black should change tack.}) 16... Ne6 $5 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Ge6f4,Ge6c5,Gb5b4,Gd6d5] White is still slightly for choice, but his position isn't trivial to play and Black has definite counterplay looming. We may look to go ...[Nc5] in conjunction with ...[b4] and ...[a5] or place the knight on [f4] an especially good square in the event of [g2]-[g4] from White, threatening a timely exchange on [d3] while adding further support to the ...[d5] break.} *

