1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd2 {[%cal Rd2g5] While this retreat is unlikely to be played by an opponent unfamiliar with the Löwenthal, it has been used by a number of grandmasters and is quite a sensible choice, one even recommended by Spanish Grandmaster Miguel Santos on his Play the Open Sicilian course, and it's also touted in another Chessable course, The Complete Open Sicilian for White.} (8. Qd2 {In short, White angles for a superior version of the immediate queen exchange lines of Theory Three and will meet} Qg6 {with} 9. Nc3 {followed by [Qg5], not least in the event of} Nge7 {(( 9...d5!? isn't completely ridiculous, but 10.f3! is a surprisingly decent response))} 10. h4 $1 h5 11. Qg5 {.}) 8... Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d6,Gf6g6,Gc8e6] Sensible development as well as approach which keeps Black's options open, depending on what White does. Black may castle quickly or go ...[Qg6], or avoid both those moves in favour of quick queenside development with ...[d6] and ...[Be6].} 9. Nc3 {This natural move seems best, although practice has also seen a great many other moves tested.} O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc6d4,Gd7d5,Gd7d6] Calmly housing the king while keeping all our options open: a quick ...[b5] and/or ...[Nd4] may follow, ...[d5] as a gambit isn't entirely off the agenda and Black can always develop the remaining pieces after simply ...[d6].} 10. Bc4 {[%csl Gc4] White's most popular choice, clamping down on the [d5]-square, but allowing Black to target the bishop.} b5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb5c4,Gb5b4] Exploiting the main downside to 10. [Bc4] without delay, expanding with tempo while clearing [b7] for the bishop.} (10... b5 {Note too how a timely ...b4 can be useful, not least in the event of} 11. Bd5 $6 b4 {to drive the white knight away from being in contact with the key [d5] point.}) 11. Bb3 Nd4 $1 {[%csl Gf3,Gg2][%cal Gd4b3,Gf6g6] A thematic leap, preparing to exchange on [b3] at some point soon, while also introducing potential tactics on [f3] for once White has castled kingside.} ({We should perhaps also mention the possibility of an unplayed gambit:} 11... a5 $5 {, and if} 12. Nxb5 a4 13. Bc4 Ba6 {followed by ...[Na5] and/or ...[Rab8], with decent activity and pressure for the pawn.}) 12. O-O $6 Bb7 {[%csl Gb3,Ge4][%cal Ga6a5,Gb5b4]} (12... Bb7 {Already Black is better! Why? Well, not only is there pressure against e4, but the bishop on b3 is a target and} 13. Z0 a5 {already a semi-threat, and if} 14. a4 b4 {followed by ...[Nxb3] to shatter White's queenside pawns and weaken him on the light squares.}) 13. Nd5 $6 {[%csl Rf6] This attempt to gain come counter-activity only serves to make matters worse.} Nxd5 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gf6g6]} (13... Nxd5 {Retaining for now the powerful bishop on b7 and after} 14. exd5 Qg6 {Black is clearly for choice, with 15...[Nf3]+ one threat and ...[Rac8] followed by ...[Rc5] and ...[Nxb3] another. Better that though for White than trading the bishops on [d5].}) 14. Bxd5 $2 Bxd5 15. exd5 Qg6 {[%csl Gc2,Gd2,Gg1,Gg2,Gg6][%cal Gd4f3,Gd4c2] Here the [g2]-pawn isn't attacked, but is pinned, meaning we have a variation on one of our favourite themes: White is badly overloaded due to the attack on [c2] and the pin on [g2], and was pretty much already lost in Kaganskiy-Paszewski, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023.} *

