1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qd2 {[%cal Rd2g5] While this retreat is unlikely to be played by an opponent unfamiliar with the Löwenthal, it has been used by a number of grandmasters and is quite a sensible choice, one even recommended by Spanish Grandmaster Miguel Santos on his Play the Open Sicilian course, and it's also touted in another Chessable course, The Complete Open Sicilian for White.} (8. Qd2 {In short, White angles for a superior version of the immediate queen exchange lines of Theory Three and will meet} Qg6 {with} 9. Nc3 {followed by [Qg5], not least in the event of} Nge7 {(( 9...d5!? isn't completely ridiculous, but 10.f3! is a surprisingly decent response))} 10. h4 $1 h5 11. Qg5 {.}) 8... Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d6,Gf6g6,Gc8e6] Sensible development as well as approach which keeps Black's options open, depending on what White does. Black may castle quickly or go ...[Qg6], or avoid both those moves in favour of quick queenside development with ...[d6] and ...[Be6].} 9. Nc3 {This natural move seems best, although practice has also seen a great many other moves tested.} O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc6d4,Gd7d5,Gd7d6] Calmly housing the king while keeping all our options open: a quick ...[b5] and/or ...[Nd4] may follow, ...[d5] as a gambit isn't entirely off the agenda and Black can always develop the remaining pieces after simply ...[d6].} 10. Bc4 {[%csl Gc4] White's most popular choice, clamping down on the [d5]-square, but allowing Black to target the bishop.} b5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb5c4,Gb5b4] Exploiting the main downside to 10. [Bc4] without delay, expanding with tempo while clearing [b7] for the bishop.} (10... b5 {Note too how a timely ...b4 can be useful, not least in the event of} 11. Bd5 $6 b4 {to drive the white knight away from being in contact with the key [d5] point.}) 11. Bb3 Nd4 $1 {[%csl Gf3,Gg2][%cal Gd4b3,Gf6g6] A thematic leap, preparing to exchange on [b3] at some point soon, while also introducing potential tactics on [f3] for once White has castled kingside.} ({We should perhaps also mention the possibility of an unplayed gambit:} 11... a5 $5 {, and if} 12. Nxb5 a4 13. Bc4 Ba6 {followed by ...[Na5] and/or ...[Rab8], with decent activity and pressure for the pawn.}) 12. Nd5 $1 {[%csl Rf6] White's counters in kind, and critically at that.} Nxd5 {[%cal Gf6g6]} (12... Nxd5 {A simple approach the related Qh4!? Nxe7+ Qxe7 Bd5 Rb8 also seems OK, as well as one which hopes for} 13. exd5 $2 Qg6 {.}) 13. Bxd5 $1 {[%csl Ra8]} Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gd4e6,Gf6g6]} ({Sensible and best.} 13... Qg6 $6 {may look tempting, but enables White to seize the initiative and upper hand with} 14. f4 $1 {, as in Sieg-Gfeller, Ellmedingen 1978. After the text move, Black is ready to challenge the bishop on [d5] with 14...[Bb7] and also has ideas of a timely ...[Qg6] and perhaps ...[Ne6]-[f4], obtaining some play on the kingside.}) 14. c3 {[%csl Rd4]} Ne6 {[%cal Ge6c5,Gc8b7,Gd7d6,Ge6f4] The best square for the knight, looking to leap into [f4]. It may also take up residency on [c5] which, if combined with ...[Bb7] and ...[d6], should leave Black with a fairly respectable Sicilian set-up.} 15. O-O Nf4 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gf6g6,Gf4d5]} (15... Nf4 {Black had equalised and arguably already enjoyed the more comfortable position in Ljukin-Todorovic, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2022. The simple idea is} 16. Z0 Nxd5 {, and if} 17. exd5 Qg6 {followed by ...[d6], with easy kingside play, or 17.Qxd5 Bb7 , attacking the queen and also X-raying the pawn on [e4]. Note too that White hasn't time to move the bishop out of danger.}) 16. Bb3 $6 d5 $1 {[%csl Gf1,Gg1,Gg2][%cal Gd5e4,Gc8h3,Gf6g6] An especially powerful version of our favourite central strike, seizing the initiative as we exploit the attacking presence of the knight on [f4] to threaten 17...[Bh3].} *

