1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qa3 {An aggressive choice, one favoured by such attacking players as Boris Spassky and Alexei Shirov. White aims to cause problems on the [a3]-[f8] diagonal and would like to follow up [Nc3] with [Be3]-[c5] and [O-O-O].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Straightforward development is definitely the best policy here. There's certainly no time for} 8... Qg6 $6 {due to} 9. Be3 $1 {when} Qxe4 10. Nc3 Qb4 11. Qxb4 Nxb4 12. O-O-O {leaves White with too big an advantage in terms of development and dark-square control.}) ({Likewise,} 8... Nd4 $6 9. Bd3 Qg6 10. O-O d5 11. f3 $1 {leaves White doing well, so Black should develop, threatening ...[d5] while facilitating castling.}) 9. Be3 {This isn't such a precise move order as now Black will be able to prevent White from continuing development with 10. [Nc3].} d5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gd5d4]} (9... d5 {Of course, and now} 10. Nc3 $4 d4 {would not be at all wise.}) 10. exd5 Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5e3] Naturally Black recaptures so, getting ready to remove a certain unopposed bishop on [e3].} 11. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5]} Nxe3 12. fxe3 Qh4+ $5 {Trying to force a small weakness, although there's nothing wrong with the straightforward 12...[Be6] followed by ...[Qe7].} 13. g3 {[%csl Rh4]} Qb4 $1 {[%cal Gc6b4,Gb4a3] Ensuring that the exchange of queens will happen on Black's terms, either with the knight activated from [c6] or White's queenside structure shattered.} 14. Qxb4 Nxb4 {[%cal Gb4c2]} 15. O-O-O {We've followed Alcazar Jimenez-Alonso Alvarez, Peniscola 2002, where Black might have continue to develop whilst hitting White's pieces.} Bg4 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Gg4f3,Gb4c6,Ga8d8] Not only does the bishop attack the rook on [d1], but it gets ready to pop into [f3], thereby covering [d5] for now. Meanwhile ...[Rd8] will be quick to challenge the d-file and the knight on [b4] can always drop back to [c6].} *

