1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qa3 {An aggressive choice, one favoured by such attacking players as Boris Spassky and Alexei Shirov. White aims to cause problems on the [a3]-[f8] diagonal and would like to follow up [Nc3] with [Be3]-[c5] and [O-O-O].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Straightforward development is definitely the best policy here. There's certainly no time for} 8... Qg6 $6 {due to} 9. Be3 $1 {when} Qxe4 10. Nc3 Qb4 11. Qxb4 Nxb4 12. O-O-O {leaves White with too big an advantage in terms of development and dark-square control.}) ({Likewise,} 8... Nd4 $6 9. Bd3 Qg6 10. O-O d5 11. f3 $1 {leaves White doing well, so Black should develop, threatening ...[d5] while facilitating castling.}) 9. Be3 {This isn't such a precise move order as now Black will be able to prevent White from continuing development with 10. [Nc3].} d5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gd5d4]} (9... d5 {Of course, and now} 10. Nc3 $4 d4 {would not be at all wise.}) 10. Bc5 $6 {Consistent with White's eighth move, but also a bit of a risky choice.} Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4c2,Gd5e4] Just like with 10.exd5 Nxd5 inserted, this is a fairly strong advance, although the engines point out that 10...O-O!? and then ...[Nd4] is also pretty good. The text move threatens a family fork and also sets a small trap.} 11. Bd3 {Covering [c2] while trying not to have to exchange off the dark-squared bishop.} dxe4 {[%cal Ge4d3] Refusing to let White settle.} 12. Bxe4 Bf5 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gf5e4,Ge5d4,Ga8c8,Ga8d8] With ...[Rc8] or even ...[Rd8] high on the agenda, as well as the light-square threats, Black has at least a pleasant early initiative.} *

