1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qa3 {An aggressive choice, one favoured by such attacking players as Boris Spassky and Alexei Shirov. White aims to cause problems on the [a3]-[f8] diagonal and would like to follow up [Nc3] with [Be3]-[c5] and [O-O-O].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Straightforward development is definitely the best policy here. There's certainly no time for} 8... Qg6 $6 {due to} 9. Be3 $1 {when} Qxe4 10. Nc3 Qb4 11. Qxb4 Nxb4 12. O-O-O {leaves White with too big an advantage in terms of development and dark-square control.}) ({Likewise,} 8... Nd4 $6 9. Bd3 Qg6 10. O-O d5 11. f3 $1 {leaves White doing well, so Black should develop, threatening ...[d5] while facilitating castling.}) 9. c4 {[%csl Gd4,Rd5] White clamps down on the [d5]-square, but not for the first time in the Lowenthal, erecting a Maroczy Bind so is a slightly risky business, in part due to the weakened [d4]-square.} Nd4 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gd4c2] Taking immediate advantage of the hole on [d4]. Not only does the knight threaten a certain check, but it also supports the ...[b5] break.} 10. Bd3 b5 $5 ({One of two tempting moves, the other being} 10... Qg6 {. With the pawn break, we get ready to take on [c4] and also entice White into grabbing a pawn.}) 11. cxb5 $2 Bb7 {[%cal Ga6b5,Gd7d5] Threatening to recapture on [b5], as well as to seize the initiative with 12...[d5]. White is already in some trouble and should aim not to make matters worse here with further greed.} 12. bxa6 $2 Rxa6 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Ge1][%cal Gd4c2,Gf6g6,Ga6b6,Ga6c6,Ga6a3]} (12... Rxa6 {Exploiting the potential fork on c2 to activate the rook. Black will continue to harry with} 13. Qb4 Rb6 {or 13.Qc3 Rc6 and simply enjoys a very dangerous early initiative, with ...[Qg6] also high on the agenda.}) *

