1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qa3 {An aggressive choice, one favoured by such attacking players as Boris Spassky and Alexei Shirov. White aims to cause problems on the [a3]-[f8] diagonal and would like to follow up [Nc3] with [Be3]-[c5] and [O-O-O].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Straightforward development is definitely the best policy here. There's certainly no time for} 8... Qg6 $6 {due to} 9. Be3 $1 {when} Qxe4 10. Nc3 Qb4 11. Qxb4 Nxb4 12. O-O-O {leaves White with too big an advantage in terms of development and dark-square control.}) ({Likewise,} 8... Nd4 $6 9. Bd3 Qg6 10. O-O d5 11. f3 $1 {leaves White doing well, so Black should develop, threatening ...[d5] while facilitating castling.}) 9. Nc3 {Invariably played as White clamps down on the ever-important [d5]-square.} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Gc3][%cal Gb7b5]} ({A change of approach, preparing to exploit the unusual position of the white queen with a quick ...b5. Instead,} 9... O-O $6 10. Be3 {enables White to take control, including after} d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Nd4 13. Bd3 {.}) 10. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Rd5c7]} Nxd5 {Dealing with the threats whilst forcing the pace.} 11. exd5 Ne7 {[%cal Gd7d6,Ge8g8,Gb7b5,Ge7d5] (Not only attacking d5 a pawn which would be attacked again in the case of 12.d6 Nf5 ,) but also preparing to complete development with ...[d6], ...[O-O] and ...[b5].} 12. Be3 $5 (12. Be3 {White angles to seize the initiative and strike on the dark squares with} Nxd5 $6 13. Bc5 {, but we don't have to allow that.}) 12... d6 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ge7d5] Keeping the bishop out of [c5] while renewing the threat to [d5] and enabling the [c8]-bishop to be developed.} 13. O-O-O Bf5 {[%cal Gb8c8] As ever, when White's king heads to the queenside, we may go after it and now ...[Rc8] will begin to ask questions over there.} 14. f3 {In English Attack style, White hints at a pawn attack on the kingside with [g2]-[g4] and [h2]-[h4].} Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c2]} 15. Rd2 h5 $5 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Gf5g6,Ge7f5,Ge8g8] Prophylaxis against any kingside pawn storm from White. Black may still castle kingside, with ...[Bg6] another idea to note, freeing [f5] for the knight to lead into the fray.} *

