1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qa3 {An aggressive choice, one favoured by such attacking players as Boris Spassky and Alexei Shirov. White aims to cause problems on the [a3]-[f8] diagonal and would like to follow up [Nc3] with [Be3]-[c5] and [O-O-O].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Straightforward development is definitely the best policy here. There's certainly no time for} 8... Qg6 $6 {due to} 9. Be3 $1 {when} Qxe4 10. Nc3 Qb4 11. Qxb4 Nxb4 12. O-O-O {leaves White with too big an advantage in terms of development and dark-square control.}) ({Likewise,} 8... Nd4 $6 9. Bd3 Qg6 10. O-O d5 11. f3 $1 {leaves White doing well, so Black should develop, threatening ...[d5] while facilitating castling.}) 9. Nc3 {Invariably played as White clamps down on the ever-important [d5]-square.} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Gc3][%cal Gb7b5]} ({A change of approach, preparing to exploit the unusual position of the white queen with a quick ...b5. Instead,} 9... O-O $6 10. Be3 {enables White to take control, including after} d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Nd4 13. Bd3 {.}) 10. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Rd5c7]} Nxd5 {Dealing with the threats whilst forcing the pace.} 11. exd5 Ne7 {[%cal Gd7d6,Ge8g8,Gb7b5,Ge7d5] (Not only attacking d5 a pawn which would be attacked again in the case of 12.d6 Nf5 ,) but also preparing to complete development with ...[d6], ...[O-O] and ...[b5].} 12. h4 $5 {[%cal Rc1g5]} (12. h4 {Modern chess and actually a perfectly decent move, facilitating Bg5 while White also hopes to seize the initiative after} Nxd5 $6 13. Bc4 {.}) 12... d6 {[%csl Gc8,Gd5] Prudently fixing the pawn on [d5] while freeing the light-squared bishop for action. The black queen has enough squares.} 13. Bg5 {[%csl Rf6]} Qg6 {[%csl Gd6] Clearly forced as we must hang on to [d6].} 14. Bd3 {[%csl Rg6]} Bf5 {[%cal Gf5d3]} 15. Bxe7 Kxe7 {[%csl Gc2,Gg2][%cal Gf5d3,Gh8c8,Gg6f5] While Black's king was in the centre, he was also fine in Rotaru-De Vassal, correspondence 2010. There's pressure against [g2], as well as [c2], with Black all set to exchange on [d3] then go ...[Rfc8].} *

