1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qa3 {An aggressive choice, one favoured by such attacking players as Boris Spassky and Alexei Shirov. White aims to cause problems on the [a3]-[f8] diagonal and would like to follow up [Nc3] with [Be3]-[c5] and [O-O-O].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Straightforward development is definitely the best policy here. There's certainly no time for} 8... Qg6 $6 {due to} 9. Be3 $1 {when} Qxe4 10. Nc3 Qb4 11. Qxb4 Nxb4 12. O-O-O {leaves White with too big an advantage in terms of development and dark-square control.}) ({Likewise,} 8... Nd4 $6 9. Bd3 Qg6 10. O-O d5 11. f3 $1 {leaves White doing well, so Black should develop, threatening ...[d5] while facilitating castling.}) 9. Nc3 {Invariably played as White clamps down on the ever-important [d5]-square.} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Gc3][%cal Gb7b5]} ({A change of approach, preparing to exploit the unusual position of the white queen with a quick ...b5. Instead,} 9... O-O $6 10. Be3 {enables White to take control, including after} d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Nd4 13. Bd3 {.}) 10. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Rd5c7]} Nxd5 {Dealing with the threats whilst forcing the pace.} 11. exd5 Ne7 {[%cal Gd7d6,Ge8g8,Gb7b5,Ge7d5] (Not only attacking d5 a pawn which would be attacked again in the case of 12.d6 Nf5 ,) but also preparing to complete development with ...[d6], ...[O-O] and ...[b5].} 12. c4 d6 {[%csl Gc4,Gc8,Gd5][%cal Ge7f5,Ge8g8,Gb7b5] Trying to keep the white pawns where they are. Black may now continue with ...[O-O] then look to undermine with ...[b5], or quickly begin counterplay by means of ...[Nf5].} 13. Be2 Nf5 $5 {[%cal Gf5d4,Gf6g6,Gf5h4] The knight heads for [d4] and also has certain ambitions on the kingside, ones likely to be associated with the support of ...[Qg6].} 14. Be3 Qg6 {[%csl Gg2]} 15. O-O Nh4 $1 {[%csl Gg1][%cal Gg6g2] Threatening mate and forcing White's reply.} 16. g3 Bh3 {[%csl Gg1][%cal Gh3f1,Gg6e4] Threatening the rook and especially 17...[Qe4].} 17. Qa4+ $1 {[%csl Re8][%cal Rc4c5]} (17. Qa4+ {Thanks to the disruptive idea of} Kf8 18. c5 {, White is able to deflect the bishop from [h3].}) 17... Bd7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7h3,Gb7b5] Once the queen moves, Black may either return the bishop to [h3] and repeat moves or play for more with 18...[O-O], possibly followed by breaking with ...[b5].} *

