1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qa3 {An aggressive choice, one favoured by such attacking players as Boris Spassky and Alexei Shirov. White aims to cause problems on the [a3]-[f8] diagonal and would like to follow up [Nc3] with [Be3]-[c5] and [O-O-O].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Straightforward development is definitely the best policy here. There's certainly no time for} 8... Qg6 $6 {due to} 9. Be3 $1 {when} Qxe4 10. Nc3 Qb4 11. Qxb4 Nxb4 12. O-O-O {leaves White with too big an advantage in terms of development and dark-square control.}) ({Likewise,} 8... Nd4 $6 9. Bd3 Qg6 10. O-O d5 11. f3 $1 {leaves White doing well, so Black should develop, threatening ...[d5] while facilitating castling.}) 9. Nc3 {Invariably played as White clamps down on the ever-important [d5]-square.} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Gc3][%cal Gb7b5]} ({A change of approach, preparing to exploit the unusual position of the white queen with a quick ...b5. Instead,} 9... O-O $6 10. Be3 {enables White to take control, including after} d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Nd4 13. Bd3 {.}) 10. Bd3 {A sensible enough move, if hardly one which deters us from carrying out the planned advance.} b5 {[%cal Gb5b4]} (10... b5 {Now} 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Ne7 {would once again be pretty comfortable for Black, and neither is retreating the knight at all scary.}) 11. Ne2 O-O {[%cal Gd7d5] Wisely getting the king to safety ahead of carrying out our favourite break.} 12. Be3 d5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gb5b4,Gd5d4] All of a sudden, Black has various tempting options with the pawns, including simply cramping White to a fair extent with ...[b4] then ...[d4]. And, no, we haven't just blundered, but are setting a trap if that confuses you, have a look for potential loose pieces and tactics.} 13. exd5 $6 Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5e3,Gb5b4]} (13... Nxd5 {Now} 14. O-O b4 {followed by ...[Nxe3] would be very comfortable for Black, but White should prefer allowing that to a life of greed.}) 14. Bxh7+ $2 {[%csl Rg8]} Kxh7 15. Qxf8 {And so the loose piece fell in Tomczak-Rolle, Rostock 2008, where Black took on [e3] and there was something even stronger.} Nde7 $1 {[%csl Gf8][%cal Gc8e6] Snaring the white queen and threatening to immediately win it with 16...[Be6].} 16. Bc5 Bg4 {[%cal Gb8f8] One of a few good moves and now there is a definite threat.} 17. Bxe7 Qe6 $1 {[%csl Ge1,Gf8]} (17... Qe6 {A key zwischenzug. After} 18. Qxb8 Nxb8 {White would have two rooks and a pawn for the queen, but Black's active queen, initiative and far safer king would leave him in huge trouble. Neither though will a clever-looking try save the day.}) 18. Bd8 $2 Rxd8 {[%csl Ge1,Gf8]} 19. Qa3 Bxe2 {[%cal Gc6d4,Ge6g4,Ge6c4] White is pretty much lost whether or not he recaptures on [e2] and talk about an exposed king!} (19... Bxe2 {For example,} 20. Kxe2 Qg4+ 21. Ke1 {Pretty much forced, not that it will come remotely close to saving the day.} Qxg2 22. Rf1 Nd4 {Threatening mate, beginning with 23...[Qe4]+.} 23. Qd3+ f5 24. Rd1 $5 Rd5 $1 {Renewing the threat to win on the spot.} 25. f3 Nxc2+ 26. Qxc2 Qxc2 27. Rxd5 e4 $1 {Material might be level, but the extra queen is simply running amok as we remain in greater than '+5' territory in engine speak.}) *

