square.} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Gc3][%cal Gb7b5]} ({A change of approach, preparing to exploit the unusual position of the white queen with a quick ...b5. Instead,} 9... O-O $6 10. Be3 {enables White to take control, including after} d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Nd4 13. Bd3 {.}) 10. Be3 {[%cal Re1c1] White's main move by quite some margin, threatening to take control after 11. [O-O-O].} (10. h4 $5 {Once again we see this modern advance, and here too it need not be feared.} b5 {Continuing with our thematic expansion.} 11. Bg5 $5 {This was certainly quite an ambitious try in Golubka-Baum, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2020, where there was no reason for Black not in turn to press ahead.} b4 {((Pretty much forcing the queens off, with both 12.Qa4? and 12.Qb3? well met by 12...Qg6. ) . )} 12. Bxf6 bxa3 13. Bxg7 axb2 14. Rb1 Rg8 {The pawn on [b2] might not be going anywhere for now and the engines do declare '0.00', but we'd certainly prefer to take Black here, since after ...[Rg6] or a rapid ...[d5] and/or ...[Nd4], it will be Black who enjoys the initiative.}) 10... b5 {[%cal Gb5b4] This was, of course, the main point behind 9...[Rb8] and now White is rather forced to deal with the threat.} 11. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6] The only really critical move, heading forwards, although Black certainly shouldn't mind the resulting structure as the d-file closes.} Nxd5 {Forcing White to close the d-file.} 12. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} b4 $5 {[%csl Ga3]} ({Forcing the pace. Black actually has something of a choice here, with} 12... Ne7 {a respectable choice too, as well as one which has been slightly more popular in practice. The critical line then looks to be} 13. Bc5 $5 Nxd5 14. O-O-O Bb7 15. Be2 {when White's dark-square and central pressure gives him decent play for the pawn.}) 13. Qd3 (13. Qd3 {This centralising choice has been as popular as 13.Qa4 in practice and here Black can no longer go} Nd4 {on account of just} 14. Bxd4 exd4 15. O-O-O {followed by 16. [Qxd4].}) 13... Ne7 {[%cal Gd7d6,Ge7f5] Keeping everything secure. Black is now ready to go 14...[d6] then perhaps break out with ...[Nf5], so White may be tempted into a critical if double-edged advance.} 14. d6 $5 {[%csl Re7]} Nf5 {[%csl Gd6,Ge3] Pressuring the far-advanced d-pawn as well as the unopposed dark-squared bishop.} 15. Ba7 $5 {This fairly radical try is best according to the engines.} Rb7 $1 {[%cal Gb7a7,Gb7b5]} (15... Rb7 {Staying active. By keeping the rook on the b-file, we're able to meet} 16. Bc5 {with} Rb5 {.}) 16. Qxa6 $1 {Exploiting the one downside to having the rook on [b7].} Qxd6 {[%csl Ga6,Ga7] But there goes the once mighty d-pawn and the bishop on [a7] is now indirectly en prise.} 17. Qxd6 Nxd6 {[%csl Gb4,Gd7,Ge5][%cal Gb7a7,Gd6e4,Gd6f5] With ...[Ne4] or ...[Nf5] next up, depending on where the bishop retreats to, Black enjoys decent counterplay and also has the preferable structure, with the two centre pawns and one currently holding three on the queenside.} *

