square.} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Gc3][%cal Gb7b5]} ({A change of approach, preparing to exploit the unusual position of the white queen with a quick ...b5. Instead,} 9... O-O $6 10. Be3 {enables White to take control, including after} d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Nd4 13. Bd3 {.}) 10. Be3 {[%cal Re1c1] White's main move by quite some margin, threatening to take control after 11. [O-O-O].} (10. h4 $5 {Once again we see this modern advance, and here too it need not be feared.} b5 {Continuing with our thematic expansion.} 11. Bg5 $5 {This was certainly quite an ambitious try in Golubka-Baum, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2020, where there was no reason for Black not in turn to press ahead.} b4 {((Pretty much forcing the queens off, with both 12.Qa4? and 12.Qb3? well met by 12...Qg6. ) . )} 12. Bxf6 bxa3 13. Bxg7 axb2 14. Rb1 Rg8 {The pawn on [b2] might not be going anywhere for now and the engines do declare '0.00', but we'd certainly prefer to take Black here, since after ...[Rg6] or a rapid ...[d5] and/or ...[Nd4], it will be Black who enjoys the initiative.}) 10... b5 {[%cal Gb5b4] This was, of course, the main point behind 9...[Rb8] and now White is rather forced to deal with the threat.} 11. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6] The only really critical move, heading forwards, although Black certainly shouldn't mind the resulting structure as the d-file closes.} Nxd5 {Forcing White to close the d-file.} 12. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} b4 $5 {[%csl Ga3]} ({Forcing the pace. Black actually has something of a choice here, with} 12... Ne7 {a respectable choice too, as well as one which has been slightly more popular in practice. The critical line then looks to be} 13. Bc5 $5 Nxd5 14. O-O-O Bb7 15. Be2 {when White's dark-square and central pressure gives him decent play for the pawn.}) 13. Qd3 (13. Qd3 {This centralising choice has been as popular as 13.Qa4 in practice and here Black can no longer go} Nd4 {on account of just} 14. Bxd4 exd4 15. O-O-O {followed by 16. [Qxd4].}) 13... Ne7 {[%cal Gd7d6,Ge7f5] Keeping everything secure. Black is now ready to go 14...[d6] then perhaps break out with ...[Nf5], so White may be tempted into a critical if double-edged advance.} 14. d6 $5 {[%csl Re7]} Nf5 {[%csl Gd6,Ge3] Pressuring the far-advanced d-pawn as well as the unopposed dark-squared bishop.} 15. O-O-O Bb7 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Ge8g8,Ga6a5] A fine diagonal for the bishop, as well as a move which halts [g2]-[g4] for now. Black is also all set to castle and may then consider beginning to advance the a-pawn.} 16. Rg1 O-O 17. g4 $1 {White badly needs some play of his own before Black whips up too strong an attack, such as after ...[Rfc8] and ...[a5]-[a4].} Nxe3 {We've followed another old game, Gunsberger-Baumbach, Marianske Lazne 1962, where even after the correct recapture on [e3], Black would have been pretty comfortable.} 18. Qxe3 Rfc8 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Ga6a5,Ga5a4,Ge5e4] Black's position is certainly the easier to handle, with the a-pawn set to trundle forwards and a timely ...[e4] also likely to prove useful to help activate the queen.} *

