1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qa3 {An aggressive choice, one favoured by such attacking players as Boris Spassky and Alexei Shirov. White aims to cause problems on the [a3]-[f8] diagonal and would like to follow up [Nc3] with [Be3]-[c5] and [O-O-O].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Straightforward development is definitely the best policy here. There's certainly no time for} 8... Qg6 $6 {due to} 9. Be3 $1 {when} Qxe4 10. Nc3 Qb4 11. Qxb4 Nxb4 12. O-O-O {leaves White with too big an advantage in terms of development and dark-square control.}) ({Likewise,} 8... Nd4 $6 9. Bd3 Qg6 10. O-O d5 11. f3 $1 {leaves White doing well, so Black should develop, threatening ...[d5] while facilitating castling.}) 9. Nc3 {Invariably played as White clamps down on the ever-important [d5]-square.} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Gc3][%cal Gb7b5]} ({A change of approach, preparing to exploit the unusual position of the white queen with a quick ...b5. Instead,} 9... O-O $6 10. Be3 {enables White to take control, including after} d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Nd4 13. Bd3 {.}) 10. Be3 {[%cal Re1c1] White's main move by quite some margin, threatening to take control after 11. [O-O-O].} (10. h4 $5 {Once again we see this modern advance, and here too it need not be feared.} b5 {Continuing with our thematic expansion.} 11. Bg5 $5 {This was certainly quite an ambitious try in Golubka-Baum, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2020, where there was no reason for Black not in turn to press ahead.} b4 {((Pretty much forcing the queens off, with both 12.Qa4? and 12.Qb3? well met by 12...Qg6. ) . )} 12. Bxf6 bxa3 13. Bxg7 axb2 14. Rb1 Rg8 {The pawn on [b2] might not be going anywhere for now and the engines do declare '0.00', but we'd certainly prefer to take Black here, since after ...[Rg6] or a rapid ...[d5] and/or ...[Nd4], it will be Black who enjoys the initiative.}) 10... b5 {[%cal Gb5b4] This was, of course, the main point behind 9...[Rb8] and now White is rather forced to deal with the threat.} 11. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6] The only really critical move, heading forwards, although Black certainly shouldn't mind the resulting structure as the d-file closes.} Nxd5 {Forcing White to close the d-file.} 12. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} b4 $5 {[%csl Ga3]} ({Forcing the pace. Black actually has something of a choice here, with} 12... Ne7 {a respectable choice too, as well as one which has been slightly more popular in practice. The critical line then looks to be} 13. Bc5 $5 Nxd5 14. O-O-O Bb7 15. Be2 {when White's dark-square and central pressure gives him decent play for the pawn.}) 13. Qb3 $5 {A fairly sensible and flexible square for the queen.} Ne7 ({Black gets ready to go ...d6 and ...O-O once again. Here, if you don't mind early simplification,} 13... Nd4 $5 14. Bxd4 exd4 {can also be considered, although it may not equalise after} 15. Qf3 $1 {.}) 14. Ba7 {[%csl Rb8]} Rb7 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gb7a7] Keeping the rook in contact with the pawn on [b4].} 15. Bc5 {[%cal Rd5d6] At first sight, a rather strange manoeuvre from White and we should not be bluffed: the d-pawn can advance.} d6 $1 {[%cal Gd6c5,Ge8g8,Gb7b8,Gb7d7]} (15... d6 {Now} 16. Be3 Rb8 {or even 16...O-O!? must be fine for Black, as is 16.Qa4+ Rd7! , and if 17.Bxb4 Qf4!? or simply here 17...Nxd5 .}) 16. Bxa6 $5 {[%csl Rb7] A big and quite radical decision, ceding the bishop-pair to totally transform the position.} dxc5 17. Bxb7 Bxb7 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge8g8] Clearly we would be doing very well if White now allowed us to castle, but he's unlikely to} 18. Qa4+ $1 Kd8 {[%csl Gb7,Gd5,Ge7][%cal Gd8c8,Gc8b8]} (18... Kd8 {The position is certainly quite complex, but Black shouldn't have anything to worry about. We have two minor pieces for the rook and pawn, the king is en route to relative safety on b8 and the d-pawn may well become weak, with} 19. d6 $2 Qxd6 20. Rd1 Nd5 {absolutely nothing to fear.}) (18... Kd8 {For example,} 19. Qa5+ Kd7 {((Even simpler would be 19...Kc8!? 20.Qxc5+ Kb8 , saving a tempo.))} 20. Qb5+ Kc8 21. Qxc5+ Kb8 {((Finally the king reaches relative safety and here 22.Qxb4?! Nxd5 followed by ...[Qa6] or ...[Rc8] would leave Black beginning to take over.))} 22. Rd1 {(( 22.O-O-O !? A try for more than acquiescing in a repetition, one Black can counter with 22...[Rc8] or something even more aggressive. 22...b3!? 23.axb3 Nf5 White may have an extra three pawns, but in this very unclear position we'd prefer to take Black who is all set to seize a strong initiative after ...[Rc8] and/or ...[Nd4], after which ...[Qa6] or ...[Qxf2] might follow.))} Rd8 23. d6 Nf5 {Renewing the threat to the d-pawn, and now White would be well advised to force a draw:} 24. Qc7+ {and ½-½ in Link-Baumbach, correspondence 1964, in view of the upcoming pendulum of checks on [c7] and [a5].}) *

