1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qa3 {An aggressive choice, one favoured by such attacking players as Boris Spassky and Alexei Shirov. White aims to cause problems on the [a3]-[f8] diagonal and would like to follow up [Nc3] with [Be3]-[c5] and [O-O-O].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Straightforward development is definitely the best policy here. There's certainly no time for} 8... Qg6 $6 {due to} 9. Be3 $1 {when} Qxe4 10. Nc3 Qb4 11. Qxb4 Nxb4 12. O-O-O {leaves White with too big an advantage in terms of development and dark-square control.}) ({Likewise,} 8... Nd4 $6 9. Bd3 Qg6 10. O-O d5 11. f3 $1 {leaves White doing well, so Black should develop, threatening ...[d5] while facilitating castling.}) 9. Nc3 {Invariably played as White clamps down on the ever-important [d5]-square.} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Gc3][%cal Gb7b5]} ({A change of approach, preparing to exploit the unusual position of the white queen with a quick ...b5. Instead,} 9... O-O $6 10. Be3 {enables White to take control, including after} d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Nd4 13. Bd3 {.}) 10. Be3 {[%cal Re1c1] White's main move by quite some margin, threatening to take control after 11. [O-O-O].} (10. h4 $5 {Once again we see this modern advance, and here too it need not be feared.} b5 {Continuing with our thematic expansion.} 11. Bg5 $5 {This was certainly quite an ambitious try in Golubka-Baum, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2020, where there was no reason for Black not in turn to press ahead.} b4 {((Pretty much forcing the queens off, with both 12.Qa4? and 12.Qb3? well met by 12...Qg6. ) . )} 12. Bxf6 bxa3 13. Bxg7 axb2 14. Rb1 Rg8 {The pawn on [b2] might not be going anywhere for now and the engines do declare '0.00', but we'd certainly prefer to take Black here, since after ...[Rg6] or a rapid ...[d5] and/or ...[Nd4], it will be Black who enjoys the initiative.}) 10... b5 {[%cal Gb5b4] This was, of course, the main point behind 9...[Rb8] and now White is rather forced to deal with the threat.} 11. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6] The only really critical move, heading forwards, although Black certainly shouldn't mind the resulting structure as the d-file closes.} Nxd5 {Forcing White to close the d-file.} 12. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} b4 $5 {[%csl Ga3]} ({Forcing the pace. Black actually has something of a choice here, with} 12... Ne7 {a respectable choice too, as well as one which has been slightly more popular in practice. The critical line then looks to be} 13. Bc5 $5 Nxd5 14. O-O-O Bb7 15. Be2 {when White's dark-square and central pressure gives him decent play for the pawn.}) 13. Qa4 {[%cal Rd5c6] Trying to keep the queen active.} Nd4 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc8b7]} ({A change of approach, leaping forwards while intending to quickly complete development with ...O-O and ...Bb7, rather than allow White to cramp and cause problems with} 13... Ne7 14. O-O-O O-O {(unpinning the d-pawn, but...)} 15. d6 $1 {.}) 14. c3 {[%csl Rd4] A more forcing approach.} bxc3 {[%csl Gb8][%cal Gd4f5] Naturally Black is quite happy to open up the file for the rook on [b8] ahead of retreating the knight.} 15. bxc3 Nf5 16. Bc5 {[%csl Re8]} Ne7 $1 {Yet another knight move, but a necessary retreat if Black wants to castle.} 17. Bc4 O-O {[%cal Gd7d6,Ge7g6,Ge7f5] Black is all set to take over on the kingside after 18...[d6] and ...[Ng6] or ...[Nf5], while White's queenside configuration creates a strange impression unless he now increases the dark-square pressure.} 18. Qa3 $1 {[%csl Re7,Rf8]} Re8 {[%cal Ge7f5] Unpinning while preparing to break out with ...[Nf5] then ...[d6]. The open queenside files should give Black decent play and this position looks fine for us.} (18... Re8 {For example,} 19. Bd6 Rb6 20. Bc5 Rb8 {Wisely repeating and so once again getting ready to go ...[Nf5] then ...[d6], if allowed.} 21. Bd6 Rb6 {(Consenting to a potential repetition if you wanted to avoid such a scenario, 21...[Ra8]!? would be far from ridiculous.)} 22. Bc7 $2 Rb7 23. d6 Qf4 {All of a sudden Black had seized a serious initiative in Freitag-Neulinger, Austrian League 1996, with the bishop on [c4] hanging, 24...[Qe4]+ also a threat and} 24. Bd3 {running into} e4 {(and, according to the engines, 23...[Ng6] and 23...[Qh4]!? might be even stronger.)}) *

