1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 {Naturally the knight must go. Black has no desire whatsoever to be moving the king.} 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qa3 {An aggressive choice, one favoured by such attacking players as Boris Spassky and Alexei Shirov. White aims to cause problems on the [a3]-[f8] diagonal and would like to follow up [Nc3] with [Be3]-[c5] and [O-O-O].} Nge7 {[%cal Gd7d5]} ({Straightforward development is definitely the best policy here. There's certainly no time for} 8... Qg6 $6 {due to} 9. Be3 $1 {when} Qxe4 10. Nc3 Qb4 11. Qxb4 Nxb4 12. O-O-O {leaves White with too big an advantage in terms of development and dark-square control.}) ({Likewise,} 8... Nd4 $6 9. Bd3 Qg6 10. O-O d5 11. f3 $1 {leaves White doing well, so Black should develop, threatening ...[d5] while facilitating castling.}) 9. Nc3 {Invariably played as White clamps down on the ever-important [d5]-square.} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Gc3][%cal Gb7b5]} ({A change of approach, preparing to exploit the unusual position of the white queen with a quick ...b5. Instead,} 9... O-O $6 10. Be3 {enables White to take control, including after} d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Nd4 13. Bd3 {.}) 10. Be3 {[%cal Re1c1] White's main move by quite some margin, threatening to take control after 11. [O-O-O].} (10. h4 $5 {Once again we see this modern advance, and here too it need not be feared.} b5 {Continuing with our thematic expansion.} 11. Bg5 $5 {This was certainly quite an ambitious try in Golubka-Baum, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2020, where there was no reason for Black not in turn to press ahead.} b4 {((Pretty much forcing the queens off, with both 12.Qa4? and 12.Qb3? well met by 12...Qg6. ) . )} 12. Bxf6 bxa3 13. Bxg7 axb2 14. Rb1 Rg8 {The pawn on [b2] might not be going anywhere for now and the engines do declare '0.00', but we'd certainly prefer to take Black here, since after ...[Rg6] or a rapid ...[d5] and/or ...[Nd4], it will be Black who enjoys the initiative.}) 10... b5 {[%cal Gb5b4] This was, of course, the main point behind 9...[Rb8] and now White is rather forced to deal with the threat.} 11. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6] The only really critical move, heading forwards, although Black certainly shouldn't mind the resulting structure as the d-file closes.} Nxd5 {Forcing White to close the d-file.} 12. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} b4 $5 {[%csl Ga3]} ({Forcing the pace. Black actually has something of a choice here, with} 12... Ne7 {a respectable choice too, as well as one which has been slightly more popular in practice. The critical line then looks to be} 13. Bc5 $5 Nxd5 14. O-O-O Bb7 15. Be2 {when White's dark-square and central pressure gives him decent play for the pawn.}) 13. Qa4 {[%cal Rd5c6] Trying to keep the queen active.} Nd4 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc8b7]} ({A change of approach, leaping forwards while intending to quickly complete development with ...O-O and ...Bb7, rather than allow White to cramp and cause problems with} 13... Ne7 14. O-O-O O-O {(unpinning the d-pawn, but...)} 15. d6 $1 {.}) 14. Bc4 {White's usual choice, supporting [d5] while getting ready to castle kingside.} O-O {[%cal Gf6h4,Gd4f5,Gd7d6] Black is again ready to push the d-pawn, although we may also consider too such aggressive moves as 15...[Nf5] and 15...[Qh4]!?.} 15. O-O {[%csl Gg1] A risky choice, considering the lack of white defenders on the kingside.} Nf3+ $5 ({Forcing a draw. Black does though have a couple of tempting alternatives to keep the game alive in} 15... d6 {and Nf5 . 15...d6 16.Bxd4 ((This forced resignation 0-1 in an old Lowenthal game, Olsson-Persson, correspondence 1900, with White set to be swept away on the kingside light squares:) ( 16.Bd2?? Nf3+! 17.gxf3 Bh3 )) 16...exd4 17.Rfe1 Bf5!? Counterattacking against [c2] so seemed fine for Black in Moline-A.Rodriguez, correspondence 2000, with Black intending ...[Qg6] or just ...[h5] and also ready to meet 18.Bxa6 with 18...Ra8 .}) 16. gxf3 Qxf3 {[%cal Gd7d6,Gc8h3] Threatening ...[d6] followed by ...[Bh3], hence White's next.} 17. Qb3 {[%cal Re3c5,Re3a7] And a draw as agreed in Marxen-Eschholz, Buesum 1999.} Qg4+ {[%csl Gg1][%cal Gg4f3,Gf3g4] Black will keep checking on [f3] and [g4].} *

