square.} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Gc3][%cal Gb7b5]} ({A change of approach, preparing to exploit the unusual position of the white queen with a quick ...b5. Instead,} 9... O-O $6 10. Be3 {enables White to take control, including after} d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Nd4 13. Bd3 {.}) 10. Be3 {[%cal Re1c1] White's main move by quite some margin, threatening to take control after 11. [O-O-O].} (10. h4 $5 {Once again we see this modern advance, and here too it need not be feared.} b5 {Continuing with our thematic expansion.} 11. Bg5 $5 {This was certainly quite an ambitious try in Golubka-Baum, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2020, where there was no reason for Black not in turn to press ahead.} b4 {((Pretty much forcing the queens off, with both 12.Qa4? and 12.Qb3? well met by 12...Qg6. ) . )} 12. Bxf6 bxa3 13. Bxg7 axb2 14. Rb1 Rg8 {The pawn on [b2] might not be going anywhere for now and the engines do declare '0.00', but we'd certainly prefer to take Black here, since after ...[Rg6] or a rapid ...[d5] and/or ...[Nd4], it will be Black who enjoys the initiative.}) 10... b5 {[%cal Gb5b4] This was, of course, the main point behind 9...[Rb8] and now White is rather forced to deal with the threat.} 11. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6] The only really critical move, heading forwards, although Black certainly shouldn't mind the resulting structure as the d-file closes.} Nxd5 {Forcing White to close the d-file.} 12. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} b4 $5 {[%csl Ga3]} ({Forcing the pace. Black actually has something of a choice here, with} 12... Ne7 {a respectable choice too, as well as one which has been slightly more popular in practice. The critical line then looks to be} 13. Bc5 $5 Nxd5 14. O-O-O Bb7 15. Be2 {when White's dark-square and central pressure gives him decent play for the pawn.}) 13. Qa4 {[%cal Rd5c6] Trying to keep the queen active.} Nd4 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc8b7]} ({A change of approach, leaping forwards while intending to quickly complete development with ...O-O and ...Bb7, rather than allow White to cramp and cause problems with} 13... Ne7 14. O-O-O O-O {(unpinning the d-pawn, but...)} 15. d6 $1 {.}) 14. Bc4 {White's usual choice, supporting [d5] while getting ready to castle kingside.} O-O {[%cal Gf6h4,Gd4f5,Gd7d6] Black is again ready to push the d-pawn, although we may also consider too such aggressive moves as 15...[Nf5] and 15...[Qh4]!?.} 15. O-O {[%csl Gg1] A risky choice, considering the lack of white defenders on the kingside.} Nf5 $5 {[%cal Gf5e3,Gd7d6] This is a reasonable way to retain pieces and play for a win.} 16. Bd2 d6 17. Rae1 $6 (17. Rae1 {White now went on to win quickly after} Nd4 $6 18. f4 $1 {in Gufeld-Gaprindashvili, Soviet Union 1981, but Black can do much better here.}) 17... Nh4 $1 {[%csl Gg1,Gg2][%cal Gf6g6,Gc8h3] Not only is ...[Qg6] imminent, but 18...[Bh3]! threatened and like the engines, we'd certainly prefer to take Black here.} *

