square.} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Gc3][%cal Gb7b5]} ({A change of approach, preparing to exploit the unusual position of the white queen with a quick ...b5. Instead,} 9... O-O $6 10. Be3 {enables White to take control, including after} d5 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Nd4 13. Bd3 {.}) 10. Be3 {[%cal Re1c1] White's main move by quite some margin, threatening to take control after 11. [O-O-O].} (10. h4 $5 {Once again we see this modern advance, and here too it need not be feared.} b5 {Continuing with our thematic expansion.} 11. Bg5 $5 {This was certainly quite an ambitious try in Golubka-Baum, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2020, where there was no reason for Black not in turn to press ahead.} b4 {((Pretty much forcing the queens off, with both 12.Qa4? and 12.Qb3? well met by 12...Qg6. ) . )} 12. Bxf6 bxa3 13. Bxg7 axb2 14. Rb1 Rg8 {The pawn on [b2] might not be going anywhere for now and the engines do declare '0.00', but we'd certainly prefer to take Black here, since after ...[Rg6] or a rapid ...[d5] and/or ...[Nd4], it will be Black who enjoys the initiative.}) 10... b5 {[%cal Gb5b4] This was, of course, the main point behind 9...[Rb8] and now White is rather forced to deal with the threat.} 11. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6] The only really critical move, heading forwards, although Black certainly shouldn't mind the resulting structure as the d-file closes.} Nxd5 {Forcing White to close the d-file.} 12. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} b4 $5 {[%csl Ga3]} ({Forcing the pace. Black actually has something of a choice here, with} 12... Ne7 {a respectable choice too, as well as one which has been slightly more popular in practice. The critical line then looks to be} 13. Bc5 $5 Nxd5 14. O-O-O Bb7 15. Be2 {when White's dark-square and central pressure gives him decent play for the pawn.}) 13. Qa4 {[%cal Rd5c6] Trying to keep the queen active.} Nd4 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc8b7]} ({A change of approach, leaping forwards while intending to quickly complete development with ...O-O and ...Bb7, rather than allow White to cramp and cause problems with} 13... Ne7 14. O-O-O O-O {(unpinning the d-pawn, but...)} 15. d6 $1 {.}) 14. Bc4 {White's usual choice, supporting [d5] while getting ready to castle kingside.} O-O {[%cal Gf6h4,Gd4f5,Gd7d6] Black is again ready to push the d-pawn, although we may also consider too such aggressive moves as 15...[Nf5] and 15...[Qh4]!?.} 15. Bxd4 {A prudent exchange ahead of housing the white king.} exd4 {[%csl Ge1,Gf2]} 16. O-O {The safest spot for the white king, as well as one which keeps [f2] secure.} d6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf6g6,Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Gh4h3]} ({Correspondence encounters have debated} 16... Bb7 {and 16...d3?! , but we're not sure what's wrong with the simple text. Black may follow up with ...[Bf5] and ...[Qg6], although it's also very tempting to quickly advance the h-pawn in a bid to soften up the white king's defences.}) (16... d6 {For example,} 17. Rfe1 h5 $5 {((Black calmly wants to go ...h4 then ...h3 if allowed and while White can consider 18.Qb3 that would allow Black to make a pretty useful move on the queenside in 18...a5. ) . )} 18. Re8 {An attempt to force the pace and as good a move as anything according to the engines.} Bf5 $1 {Keeping [b4] secure, while still intending to shove the h-pawn further, as well as pressurise [c2]. 20.Bxa6 b3! ((An unexpected and fairly powerful blow. Clearly the queen can't capture and 21.axb3? Bxc2 would also be bad news for White.)) 21.cxb3 d3 Black is two pawns down, but it's White who must tread carefully to maintain the '0.00' here. All of a sudden, ...[Re8] is imminent, the black queen pretty active and there's a big passed pawn on [d3].}) *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5A) 6.N5a3"]
[Black "6.N5a3 Nf6 7.Bd3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "20"]
[GameId "2141525860365653"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) {In at least 90% of your games, opponents are likely to be consistent and check on d6, but the odd one will instead retreat the knight. In this section we'll examine N1a3 and 6.N5c3 (. We should also perhaps note that if you play enough blitz or bullet online, an occasional opponent may go) 6.N1c3?? or 6.c4?? , pre-moves assuming that we were going to play not the Löwenthal, but the Kalashnikov with 5...[d6].} 6. N5a3 $6 {A strange choice. Yes, the knight can head to [c4] and gaze towards [d6], but if that's the plan, why didn't it go straight to [d6]? The retreat is most likely to be tried by opponents new to the Open Sicilian, who perhaps just remember that in the Kalashnikov and Sveshnikov the white knights land up on [a3] and [c3].} Nf6 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d5] Pressuring [e4], while supporting ...[d5] in classic Löwenthal fashion.} 7. Bd3 d5 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gc8g4] There's no reason whatsoever not to break so. We increase the pressure against [e4] and also prepare to discombobulate a little with ...[Bg4].} 8. exd5 Nxd5 $1 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gf8c5,Ge8g8,Gf7f5,Gd5b4] The best way to recapture, keeping the queen safe at home for now. Black may no longer lead in development, but our development is somewhat more pointed and harmonious than White's. Already ...[Ndb4] is a definite idea, and Black may also simply continue with ...[Be6], perhaps followed by ...[f5] even or, more simply, ...[Bc5] and ...[O-O].} 9. Nc4 $6 {This got the knight off the rim in Savchenko-Oganian, Russian Blitz Championship, Sochi 2016, not that much else can be said about the move.} Be6 {[%csl Gc4,Gd3][%cal Gd5b4]} ({Even better than the game's} 9... b5 {as Black makes ...[Ndb4] an even stronger positional threat.}) 10. c3 f5 $5 {[%cal Gf8c5,Gd8f6,Ge5e4,Gd5f4] Ambitious, but why not be ambitious in such a position? White may now become worried by ideas of a timely ...[e4] and Black can always meet [Ne3] with ...[Nf4], although in the short term we're most likely to get to continue development with ...[Bc5] and ...[Qf6] in some order.} *

