1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) {In at least 90% of your games, opponents are likely to be consistent and check on d6, but the odd one will instead retreat the knight. In this section we'll examine N1a3 and 6.N5c3 (. We should also perhaps note that if you play enough blitz or bullet online, an occasional opponent may go) 6.N1c3?? or 6.c4?? , pre-moves assuming that we were going to play not the Löwenthal, but the Kalashnikov with 5...[d6].} 6. N5a3 $6 {A strange choice. Yes, the knight can head to [c4] and gaze towards [d6], but if that's the plan, why didn't it go straight to [d6]? The retreat is most likely to be tried by opponents new to the Open Sicilian, who perhaps just remember that in the Kalashnikov and Sveshnikov the white knights land up on [a3] and [c3].} Nf6 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d5] Pressuring [e4], while supporting ...[d5] in classic Löwenthal fashion.} 7. Bg5 {A natural enough try to disrupt Black by pinning, but it doesn't prevent our favourite break.} d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd8b6] Increasing the pressure against [e4] while already 8... [Qb6] is something of a threat. Note too that there's no need to fear an exchange on [f6].} 8. exd5 Qxd5 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gd5d1]} (8... Qxd5 {Now} 9. Qxd5 Nxd5 {followed by ...[f6], then perhaps ...[Be6] and ...[Bc5] would be very pleasant for Black, but better that for White than giving up the bishop-pair.}) 9. Bxf6 $2 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 gxf6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gc8e6,Ge8c8,Gf6f5,Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Gh8g8,Ga8d8,Gf8h6] This is a superb and dynamic position after just 10 moves for Black. We're all set to go ...[Be6] or ...[Bf5] and ...[O-O-O]+, with ...[f5] and even ...[h5]-[h4] likely to prove useful, as could well such moves as ...[Rg8] and ...[Bh6].} 11. c3 Be6 {[%cal Ge8c8]} 12. Nc2 $6 O-O-O+ {[%cal Gf6f5,Gf8h6] Completing the first phase of the mini-plan and with ...[Bh6] and ...[f5] on their way, White's position is already extremely suspect.} 13. Nd2 Bh6 {[%cal Gd8d2]} 14. Ne3 f5 {[%cal Gf5f4,Ge6f5] With ...[f4] then probably ...[Bf5] on the way, it was already quite some massacre in Zimmermann-Kresz, correspondence 2006.} *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5A) 6.N5a3"]
[Black "6.N5a3 Nf6 7.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
