1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) {In at least 90% of your games, opponents are likely to be consistent and check on d6, but the odd one will instead retreat the knight. In this section we'll examine N1a3 and 6.N5c3 (. We should also perhaps note that if you play enough blitz or bullet online, an occasional opponent may go) 6.N1c3?? or 6.c4?? , pre-moves assuming that we were going to play not the Löwenthal, but the Kalashnikov with 5...[d6].} 6. N5a3 $6 {A strange choice. Yes, the knight can head to [c4] and gaze towards [d6], but if that's the plan, why didn't it go straight to [d6]? The retreat is most likely to be tried by opponents new to the Open Sicilian, who perhaps just remember that in the Kalashnikov and Sveshnikov the white knights land up on [a3] and [c3].} Nf6 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d5] Pressuring [e4], while supporting ...[d5] in classic Löwenthal fashion.} 7. Nc3 {Natural development, if by no means forced.} Bb4 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gd7d5] (Active and straightforward development, pinning and threatening to take on e4 Evgeny Postny's 7...b5!? is also quite tempting for Black.)} 8. Bg5 {A counter pin.} d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5d4,Gd8d5] Black is yet to be brave and break so, at least over the board, but our favourite break is simply a pretty good gambit here.} 9. exd5 {A safe choice, but now Black is able to recapture.} Qxd5 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gd5d4]} (9... Qxd5 {Clearly} 10. Qxd5 $2 Nxd5 {would now only help Black and meanwhile the neat 10...[Qd4] is a threat, so White should probably hoover.}) 10. Bxf6 {[%csl Rd5]} Qxd1+ {It's also possible to check on [e4], but there's no reason not to keep things simple.} 11. Rxd1 gxf6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gb7b5,Ge8c8,Ge8e7,Gf6f5,Ge8g8] With ...[Be6] on the way, perhaps followed by ...[f5], Black has a pleasant edge with the more dynamic set-up, as well as, for once, the two bishops. If you prefer, a quick ...[b5] is very much also an option to begin to annoy the white knights, while the king should be safe enough on [e7] after ...[Be6], if not [c8] or [g8].} *

