1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) {In at least 90% of your games, opponents are likely to be consistent and check on d6, but the odd one will instead retreat the knight. In this section we'll examine N1a3 and 6.N5c3 (. We should also perhaps note that if you play enough blitz or bullet online, an occasional opponent may go) 6.N1c3?? or 6.c4?? , pre-moves assuming that we were going to play not the Löwenthal, but the Kalashnikov with 5...[d6].} 6. N5c3 {[%csl Rd5] A more logical try than the retreat to [a3]. White clamps down on the [d5]-square and may even want to go 7. [Nd5] followed by 8. [N1c3].} Bc5 ({Black's most active approach. Placing the bishop on b4 achieves less now that it doesn't threaten structural damage, but there's certainly nothing wrong with the solid main line for Black,} 6... Nf6 7. Bg5 Be7 {. Instead, we take early aim at [f2] and White may even worry that a quick ...[Qf6] is imminent. Most likely though our first priority will be to bolster the centre and help to develop the queenside with 7...[d6].}) 7. Be2 {White's second most popular approach, developing in calm fashion and getting ready to castle.} d6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gg8e7] Consistent development and now ...[Be6] and ...[Nge7] will follow, the latter designed to avoid any sort of annoying pin with [Bg5].} 8. O-O Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gd8h4,Gg8e7] While we may continue with 9...[Nge7] regardless, if White is now a little slow other, more aggressive ideas may be possible, be they facilitating future queenside counterplay with ...[Rc8] or even the direct ...[Qh4].} 9. Nd5 (9. Nd5 {Occupying the outpost must be fairly critical and here} Qh4 $2 10. Nc7+ {would not, of course, be wise, while 9...Bxd5 10.exd5 , and if 10...Nce7 11.c4 , is perhaps very slightly in White's favour.}) 9... Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8]} (9... Nge7 {A useful development scheme. Black gets ready to castle and will play around the knight on d5. Note too that while} 10. c4 {is possible, it also gives Black a big square, one we might even occupy with the immediate} Nd4 {.}) 10. Nbc3 O-O {[%cal Ga8c8,Gb7b5,Ge7g6,Gd6e7] Black's position is compact, but what are the key plans here? Firstly, ...[Rc8] is unlikely to be a useless move, after which Black may begin to consider queenside expansion with ...[b5]. The other main idea is to regroup the knights with ...[Ng6] and ...[Nce7], only then looking to exchange knights on [d5] and then to the kingside for counterplay.} 11. Be3 Bxe3 {A simple approach, although it may also be possible to allow the exchange on [c5].} 12. Nxe3 Nd4 $5 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gd8b6,Gg7g6,Gf7f5] With ...[Rc8] imminent, Black was fairly comfortable in Lengyel-Werner, Budapest 2005. We might follow up with ...[Qb6] or prefer to expand on the kingside in Kalashnikov fashion with ...[g6] and ...[f5].} *

