1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) {In at least 90% of your games, opponents are likely to be consistent and check on d6, but the odd one will instead retreat the knight. In this section we'll examine N1a3 and 6.N5c3 (. We should also perhaps note that if you play enough blitz or bullet online, an occasional opponent may go) 6.N1c3?? or 6.c4?? , pre-moves assuming that we were going to play not the Löwenthal, but the Kalashnikov with 5...[d6].} 6. N5c3 {[%csl Rd5] A more logical try than the retreat to [a3]. White clamps down on the [d5]-square and may even want to go 7. [Nd5] followed by 8. [N1c3].} Bc5 ({Black's most active approach. Placing the bishop on b4 achieves less now that it doesn't threaten structural damage, but there's certainly nothing wrong with the solid main line for Black,} 6... Nf6 7. Bg5 Be7 {. Instead, we take early aim at [f2] and White may even worry that a quick ...[Qf6] is imminent. Most likely though our first priority will be to bolster the centre and help to develop the queenside with 7...[d6].}) 7. Nd5 (7. Nd5 {White wastes no time in occupying the square and while} Qh4 $6 {might look tempting, unfortunately} 8. Qf3 {is good for White, and if} Nd4 9. Qd3 {.}) 7... d6 {[%cal Gg8e7]} ({Continuing our standard approach in this variation: ...d6 followed by ...Nge7, a policy which also usefully sidesteps the possibility of} 7... Nge7 8. Qg4 $5 {.}) 8. Nbc3 Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Ge7d5] Now we're all set to castle and may then consider a trade of knights on [d5].} 9. Bd3 (9. Qh5 $6 {Super-aggressive, if not particularly convincing from White.} Be6 {Freeing [d7] for the queen and especially threatening to go 10...[Bxd5] followed by ...[Nb4] to seize the initiative.} 10. Bg5 Qd7 $1 {Unpinning and so facilitating ...[Ng6] or even ...[Nxd5] followed by ...[Bg4]. ((Yes, 11.-- Nxd5! 12.exd5 Bg4 is a threat, because after 13.dxc6? we can play 13...Bxf2+ , winning the white queen after 14.Kxf2 Qf5+ or 14.Kd2 bxc6. ) . )} 11. Bc4 Ng6 $1 {With [f1] available to the white king, the aforementioned tactical possibility no longer works, but after the text move, calmly playing around the knight on [d5], Black had no reason to complain in Stambulian-Gurianov, Krasnodar 2014. The threat is 12...[Bg4] and we're also all set to expand with ...[b5] and ...[Nd4].}) 9... O-O {[%cal Ge7d5,Gc8e6,Gf7f5] Making the king safe and we may now exchange on [d5] or simply go ...[Be6], with ...[f5] another idea to consider if you'd like some early counterplay.} 10. O-O Nxd5 (10... Nxd5 {Freeing Black's position with an exchange of pieces and now} 11. exd5 $6 Ne7 {followed by 12...[f5] would not be good news for White.}) 11. Nxd5 Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc6e7,Gf7f5] Completing development, with rough equality. Once again, ...[Rc8] is likely to prove useful and we can challenge for control of [d5] with ...[Ne7] and/or look to undermine the outpost with a timely ...[f5].} *

