1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb5 {As we'll see, this isn't completely forced, but must be critical focussing on the square which Black has just weakened, [d6].} a6 ({Boldly tempting the knight forwards. This marks the start of what the term 'Löwenthal Variation' nowadays refers to, the Evgeny Sveshnikov-pioneered} 5... d6 {(being an important alternative, the Kalashnikov variation, which has its own excellent Chessable courses, King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian.)}) {In at least 90% of your games, opponents are likely to be consistent and check on d6, but the odd one will instead retreat the knight. In this section we'll examine N1a3 and 6.N5c3 (. We should also perhaps note that if you play enough blitz or bullet online, an occasional opponent may go) 6.N1c3?? or 6.c4?? , pre-moves assuming that we were going to play not the Löwenthal, but the Kalashnikov with 5...[d6].} 6. N5c3 {[%csl Rd5] A more logical try than the retreat to [a3]. White clamps down on the [d5]-square and may even want to go 7. [Nd5] followed by 8. [N1c3].} Bc5 ({Black's most active approach. Placing the bishop on b4 achieves less now that it doesn't threaten structural damage, but there's certainly nothing wrong with the solid main line for Black,} 6... Nf6 7. Bg5 Be7 {. Instead, we take early aim at [f2] and White may even worry that a quick ...[Qf6] is imminent. Most likely though our first priority will be to bolster the centre and help to develop the queenside with 7...[d6].}) 7. Bc4 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Rc4f7] White has tended to counter in similar fashion with this aggressive development, one which already threatens to exploit the position of the bishop on [c5] with 8. [Bxf7]+!.} d6 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gg8e7,Gc8e6,Gd8h4]} ({Calmly continuing our standard approach rather than get involved in} 7... Qh4 $2 8. Bxf7+ $1 {.}) (7... d6 {Now that the bishop on c5 is defended, Black may though meet something slow, like} 8. a4 {, with} Qh4 {, although here 8...Be6 also looks pretty reasonable.}) 8. O-O {A sensible policy from White, keeping his king and [f2] secure.} Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc8e6,Gb7b5] By no means the only decent approach, and 8...[Qh4]!? isn't completely ridiculous here, but, again, a simple one, simply preparing to castle, after which Black may challenge for control of the [a2]-[g8] diagonal with ...[Be6] and/or expand in true Sicilian fashion with ...[b5]. Indeed, on occasion White has been known to advance his a-pawn here, a policy we'll see in the illustrative game Szikszai-Codirlasu, Eforie Nord 1998.} 9. Bg5 {White attempts to pin after all, as in Jurcik-Skreno, Slovakian League 2011, where 9...[Qc7], while fine, created a slightly strange impression.} h6 $5 {[%csl Gg5] Asking an immediate question to the bishop and forcing White to be a little careful.} 10. Bh4 $2 g5 $1 {[%cal Gg5h4] A powerful advance.} 11. Bg3 h5 {[%csl Gc5,Gg1,Gg3][%cal Gh5h4,Ge7g6] Simply threatening to trap the bishop. Such play may appear a little crude, but it's also very strong. Note the strength of the bishop on [c5], as well as the pressure on the white kingside, pressure which ...[Ng6] will but support.} 12. h3 Ng6 {[%csl Gg1,Gg3][%cal Gg5g4] Threatening to crash through with ...[g4]. White is already in trouble.} *

