1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {In 80-90% of games, you're likely to face 5.Nb5 when, of course, 5...[a6] brings about our favourite Lowenthal variation. However, other knight moves are possible, especially at lower levels. In rough ascending order of popularity, White has been known to try: 6A: 5.Nf5 6B: 5.Nxc6 6C: 5. [Nf3] 6D: 5.Nb3 If you play a fair bit of blitz or even bullet online, very occasionally you'll also receive a dose of early fortune and the pre-move 5. [Nc3]?? when after 5...[exd4] White should resign. That just leaves:} 5. Ne2 (5. Ne2 {This rare retreat intends to place the knight on g3, or maybe c3, and after} Nf6 {Nc3 (we're into a sideline of the Pelikan or Sveshnikov, one which Richard has dabbled in as White, namely ) 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Nde2!? .}) 5... Bc5 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gd8b6] We take immediate aim at [f2] and already 6...[Qf6] is something of a threat.} 6. Nbc3 $6 {White underestimates the threat or possibly overestimates his response.} Qb6 {[%cal Gc5f2] Pretty much forcing White's next move unless he wants to be ruined on [f2].} 7. Be3 Bxe3 {[%cal Ge3f2]} 8. fxe3 {[%csl Rd5]} (8. fxe3 {White's doubled e-pawns are ugly, but he does have a hold on d5 and} Qxe3 $4 9. Nd5 {would not be wise for Black.}) 8... Nf6 $1 {[%csl Gd5] Developing and contesting control of [d5].} 9. Qd2 {We've followed the game Corden-Bellin, British Under-18 Championship, Bristol 1968, where 9...[Ne7], while sensible, was a little defensive for our tastes.} d6 $1 {[%cal Gc8e6] Dangling the d-pawn before White while facilitating ...[Be6].} 10. Qxd6 $4 {A rather greedy grab.} ({White should ignore the pawn, although even} 10. O-O-O Be6 {is very pleasant for Black, who is all set to go ...[Rd8] and ...[d5], as well as to safely castle kingside while attacking on the queenside. Let's see though what happens if White does bite:}) 10... Be6 {[%csl Gd6,Ge1][%cal Ga8d8,Gf6g4,Gb6e3] Calmly does it as we threaten to sideline the white queen, then strike with 11...Rd8 12.Qa3 Qxe3 , as well as 11...Ng4 .} 11. Qd2 Rd8 {[%csl Gd2] With tempo and, of course, White is in no position to block with [Bd3].} 12. Qc1 Ng4 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gg4e3,Gb6e3]} (12... Ng4 {Black threatens not only} 13. Z0 Nxe3 {, but 13.-- Qxe3 14.Qxe3 Nxe3 when 15.Rc1 Nb4 will cause [c2] to collapse. Indeed, the engines already consider White's cause as hopeless and assess at '-4'.}) *

