1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {In 80-90% of games, you're likely to face 5.Nb5 when, of course, 5...[a6] brings about our favourite Lowenthal variation. However, other knight moves are possible, especially at lower levels. In rough ascending order of popularity, White has been known to try: 6A: 5.Nf5 6B: 5.Nxc6 6C: 5. [Nf3] 6D: 5.Nb3 If you play a fair bit of blitz or even bullet online, very occasionally you'll also receive a dose of early fortune and the pre-move 5. [Nc3]?? when after 5...[exd4] White should resign. That just leaves:} 5. Ne2 (5. Ne2 {This rare retreat intends to place the knight on g3, or maybe c3, and after} Nf6 {Nc3 (we're into a sideline of the Pelikan or Sveshnikov, one which Richard has dabbled in as White, namely ) 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Nde2!? .}) 5... Bc5 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gd8b6] We take immediate aim at [f2] and already 6...[Qf6] is something of a threat.} 6. Be3 {[%csl Rc5] A radical choice and an offer which we should be happy to take up.} Bxe3 7. fxe3 Nf6 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gf6e4] Simplest and best. There's no point in taking risks and activating the queen potentially too early when we can develop with tempo against [e4].} (7... Nf6 {Now White should go} 8. Nbc3 {when} Qb6 {would return play to a position we considered via a 6. [N1c3] [Qb6] move order.}) 8. Ng3 $6 d5 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf6g4,Gd5d4,Gd8b6]} ({An active and good alternative to the obvious} 8... Qb6 {when White can fight on after} 9. Be2 $1 {. Now though [e4] is attacked and Black ready to go 9...[Qb6] or even 9...[Ng4] then 10...[d4].}) 9. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5e3,Gd8a5] Black's disruptive ideas of ...[Qa5]+ and ...[Nxe3] are already quite annoying for White.} 10. Qd2 Qa5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e3,Ga5c5] We can't believe 10...[O-O] can be bad, but this consistent approach secures a clear edge.} (10... Qa5 11. c3 $2 Qc5 {wouldn't be wise for White, who is definitely also worse after 11.e4 Ne3 , exploiting the pin.}) *

