1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {In 80-90% of games, you're likely to face 5.Nb5 when, of course, 5...[a6] brings about our favourite Lowenthal variation. However, other knight moves are possible, especially at lower levels. In rough ascending order of popularity, White has been known to try: 6A: 5.Nf5 6B: 5.Nxc6 6C: 5. [Nf3] 6D: 5.Nb3 If you play a fair bit of blitz or even bullet online, very occasionally you'll also receive a dose of early fortune and the pre-move 5. [Nc3]?? when after 5...[exd4] White should resign. That just leaves:} 5. Ne2 (5. Ne2 {This rare retreat intends to place the knight on g3, or maybe c3, and after} Nf6 {Nc3 (we're into a sideline of the Pelikan or Sveshnikov, one which Richard has dabbled in as White, namely ) 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Nde2!? .}) 5... Bc5 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gd8b6] We take immediate aim at [f2] and already 6...[Qf6] is something of a threat.} 6. g3 $4 {Yes, remarkably a few white players have tried to calmly develop so, completely missing the point behind our fifth move.} Qb6 {[%cal Gc5f2] Ouch.} 7. Bg2 Bxf2+ 8. Kf1 {Here 8...[Be3] was sensible, if arguably also a little meek in Wrench-Bezuidenhout, Ryde 2024.} Bc5 $5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gb6d8,Gd7d6] Retaining the more powerful of the two dark-squared bishops. Black may now continue development with 9...[d6] or even consider quickly rerouting the queen via [d8].} 9. Nbc3 d6 {[%csl Gb2,Gf1] Calmly does it for now, and just how is White supposed to coordinate his pieces here?} 10. Nd5 Qd8 {[%csl Gf1][%cal Gg8e7,Ge7d5,Gf7f5,Ge8g8] Black threatens to go 11...[Nge7] then trade on [d5] and/or castle and is simply doing very well, with the white king far from well placed on [f1].} *

