1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {In 80-90% of games, you're likely to face 5.Nb5 when, of course, 5...[a6] brings about our favourite Lowenthal variation. However, other knight moves are possible, especially at lower levels. In rough ascending order of popularity, White has been known to try: 6A: 5.Nf5 6B: 5.Nxc6 6C: 5. [Nf3] 6D: 5.Nb3 If you play a fair bit of blitz or even bullet online, very occasionally you'll also receive a dose of early fortune and the pre-move 5. [Nc3]?? when after 5...[exd4] White should resign. That just leaves:} 5. Ne2 (5. Ne2 {This rare retreat intends to place the knight on g3, or maybe c3, and after} Nf6 {Nc3 (we're into a sideline of the Pelikan or Sveshnikov, one which Richard has dabbled in as White, namely ) 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Nde2!? .}) 5... Bc5 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gd8b6] We take immediate aim at [f2] and already 6...[Qf6] is something of a threat.} 6. Ng3 {Consistent and best, directing the knight towards the kingside while continuing development.} d6 $5 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gg8e7,Gh7h5]} ({Staying in independent waters. We're a little suspicious of} 6... Qf6 $6 {due to} 7. Be3 $1 {, but 6...Nf6 7.Nc3 d6 was pretty comfortable for Black, who was quickly much better after 8.Bd3? Ng4 (in Abdusattorov-Nakamura, Champions Tour Finals, Toronto rapid 2023.The text move may yet be followed up by ...[Nf6], but we can also develop with ...[Nge7] and even have ideas of a quick ...[h5] if White is careless.)}) 7. Bd3 $6 h5 $1 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gh5h4]} (7... h5 {Seizing the initiative and now} 8. h4 Nf6 {followed by 9...[Ng4] or} 9. Bg5 Qb6 {would be pretty uncomfortable for White. He should probably minimise the disadvantage with 8.h3 when Black can go 8...Qf6!? or simply 8...h4 9.Nf1 d5! .}) 8. Nxh5 $2 {Rather a hot pawn to snatch.} Qh4 {[%csl Gf2,Gh5]} (8... Qh4 {With a double-threat and, of course,} 9. Nxg7+ Kf8 {would pick up the knight due to the mate threat.}) 9. Ng3 Nf6 {[%csl Gh1,Gh2,Gh4][%cal Gf6g4,Gf6h5]} (9... Nf6 {There's already no good way for White to defend against the threat of ...Ng4, due to both the weakness of f2 and Black's pressure down the h-file. Indeed, both} 10. f3 $2 {and 10.h3 run into 10...Nh5 .}) 10. Qe2 Ng4 {[%cal Gc5f2,Gg4f2]} 11. Be3 {[%csl Rc5]} Bxe3 {Continuing to force the pace.} 12. fxe3 Qxg3+ $1 {The aforementioned pressure down the h-file more than comes into play.} 13. hxg3 Rxh1+ 14. Kd2 Nf6 {[%csl Ga1,Gb1,Gd2,Gh1][%cal Gc8g4,Ga8c8]} (14... Nf6 {Black has rook and bishop for the queen, and clearly the pin along the back rank is a major problem for White. Moreover,} 15. Z0 Bg4 16. Qf2 Rc8 {is a big threat, followed by 17...[Rd1]+, and already White is just in serious trouble, which is scarcely a surprise considering his lack of coordination.}) *

