1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {In 80-90% of games, you're likely to face 5.Nb5 when, of course, 5...[a6] brings about our favourite Lowenthal variation. However, other knight moves are possible, especially at lower levels. In rough ascending order of popularity, White has been known to try: 6A: 5.Nf5 6B: 5.Nxc6 6C: 5. [Nf3] 6D: 5.Nb3 If you play a fair bit of blitz or even bullet online, very occasionally you'll also receive a dose of early fortune and the pre-move 5. [Nc3]?? when after 5...[exd4] White should resign. That just leaves:} 5. Ne2 (5. Ne2 {This rare retreat intends to place the knight on g3, or maybe c3, and after} Nf6 {Nc3 (we're into a sideline of the Pelikan or Sveshnikov, one which Richard has dabbled in as White, namely ) 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Nde2!? .}) 5... Bc5 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gd8b6] We take immediate aim at [f2] and already 6...[Qf6] is something of a threat.} 6. Ng3 {Consistent and best, directing the knight towards the kingside while continuing development.} d6 $5 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gg8e7,Gh7h5]} ({Staying in independent waters. We're a little suspicious of} 6... Qf6 $6 {due to} 7. Be3 $1 {, but 6...Nf6 7.Nc3 d6 was pretty comfortable for Black, who was quickly much better after 8.Bd3? Ng4 (in Abdusattorov-Nakamura, Champions Tour Finals, Toronto rapid 2023.The text move may yet be followed up by ...[Nf6], but we can also develop with ...[Nge7] and even have ideas of a quick ...[h5] if White is careless.)}) 7. Nc3 {Sensible and likely best.} Be6 {[%cal Gg8e7] Straightforward development, stopping [Bc4] in the process, and we prefer this to the slightly artificial 7...[Qf6] of Ganguly-Stremavicius, Chennai Olympiad 2022.} (7... Be6 {We're now set to go 8...Nge7 and note that} 8. Nh5 Kf8 $1 {isn't anything to fear. After ... [g6] the knight will be pushed back and the black king emerge, well enough placed, on [g7].}) 8. Be2 (8. Be2 {Modest development from White and now there's absolutely nothing wrong with} Nge7 {followed by 9...[O-O].}) 8... Qh4 $5 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Gg8f6,Gf6g4] A tempting and provocative change of approach, intending a rapid ...[Nf6]-[g4].} 9. O-O Nf6 {[%cal Ge8g8,Ge8c8,Gh7h5] This is very comfortable for Black. We may simply castle kingside, but the king can also go long and if White is careless, 10...[h5] will be quick to increase the pressure.} 10. a3 $2 h5 $1 {[%csl Gc5,Gg3,Gh2][%cal Gf6g4,Gh5g4]} (10... h5 {All of a sudden 11...Ng4 is a massive threat, one not so easy to prevent either and even after} 11. Qd3 $1 a6 {the engines agree that Black must be clearly for choice.}) *

