1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {In 80-90% of games, you're likely to face 5.Nb5 when, of course, 5...[a6] brings about our favourite Lowenthal variation. However, other knight moves are possible, especially at lower levels. In rough ascending order of popularity, White has been known to try: 6A: 5.Nf5 6B: 5.Nxc6 6C: 5. [Nf3] 6D: 5.Nb3 If you play a fair bit of blitz or even bullet online, very occasionally you'll also receive a dose of early fortune and the pre-move 5. [Nc3]?? when after 5...[exd4] White should resign. That just leaves:} 5. Ne2 (5. Ne2 {This rare retreat intends to place the knight on g3, or maybe c3, and after} Nf6 {Nc3 (we're into a sideline of the Pelikan or Sveshnikov, one which Richard has dabbled in as White, namely ) 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Nde2!? .}) 5... Bc5 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gd8b6] We take immediate aim at [f2] and already 6...[Qf6] is something of a threat.} 6. Ng3 {Consistent and best, directing the knight towards the kingside while continuing development.} d6 $5 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gg8e7,Gh7h5]} ({Staying in independent waters. We're a little suspicious of} 6... Qf6 $6 {due to} 7. Be3 $1 {, but 6...Nf6 7.Nc3 d6 was pretty comfortable for Black, who was quickly much better after 8.Bd3? Ng4 (in Abdusattorov-Nakamura, Champions Tour Finals, Toronto rapid 2023.The text move may yet be followed up by ...[Nf6], but we can also develop with ...[Nge7] and even have ideas of a quick ...[h5] if White is careless.)}) 7. Nc3 {Sensible and likely best.} Be6 {[%cal Gg8e7] Straightforward development, stopping [Bc4] in the process, and we prefer this to the slightly artificial 7...[Qf6] of Ganguly-Stremavicius, Chennai Olympiad 2022.} (7... Be6 {We're now set to go 8...Nge7 and note that} 8. Nh5 Kf8 $1 {isn't anything to fear. After ... [g6] the knight will be pushed back and the black king emerge, well enough placed, on [g7].}) 8. Na4 $5 (8. Na4 {Hunting down the bishop-pair, although it should be said that now} Nge7 9. Nxc5 dxc5 10. Qxd8+ Rxd8 {followed by ...[Nc8]-[d6] cannot be too bad for Black.}) 8... Bb4+ $5 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gg8f6]} (8... Bb4+ {Retaining the bishop, while intending quick development in the event of} 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Nf6 {.}) 9. c3 {[%csl Rb4]} Ba5 10. Be3 Nf6 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf6g4,Ga5c7,Ge8g8,Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Gd6d5] Here rather than [e7], to keep White out of [h5] and have ideas of ...[Ng4]. The bishop can drop back to [c7] if attacked and Black will castle kingside, then look to fight back on the queenside with ...[a6] and ...[b5], ideally as a prelude to then breaking and taking over with ...[d5].} *

