1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {In 80-90% of games, you're likely to face 5.Nb5 when, of course, 5...[a6] brings about our favourite Lowenthal variation. However, other knight moves are possible, especially at lower levels. In rough ascending order of popularity, White has been known to try: 6A: 5.Nf5 6B: 5.Nxc6 6C: 5. [Nf3] 6D: 5.Nb3 If you play a fair bit of blitz or even bullet online, very occasionally you'll also receive a dose of early fortune and the pre-move 5. [Nc3]?? when after 5...[exd4] White should resign. That just leaves:} 5. Ne2 (5. Ne2 {This rare retreat intends to place the knight on g3, or maybe c3, and after} Nf6 {Nc3 (we're into a sideline of the Pelikan or Sveshnikov, one which Richard has dabbled in as White, namely ) 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Nde2!? .}) 5... Bc5 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gd8b6] We take immediate aim at [f2] and already 6...[Qf6] is something of a threat.} 6. Ng3 {Consistent and best, directing the knight towards the kingside while continuing development.} d6 $5 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gg8e7,Gh7h5]} ({Staying in independent waters. We're a little suspicious of} 6... Qf6 $6 {due to} 7. Be3 $1 {, but 6...Nf6 7.Nc3 d6 was pretty comfortable for Black, who was quickly much better after 8.Bd3? Ng4 (in Abdusattorov-Nakamura, Champions Tour Finals, Toronto rapid 2023.The text move may yet be followed up by ...[Nf6], but we can also develop with ...[Nge7] and even have ideas of a quick ...[h5] if White is careless.)}) 7. Nc3 {Sensible and likely best.} Be6 {[%cal Gg8e7] Straightforward development, stopping [Bc4] in the process, and we prefer this to the slightly artificial 7...[Qf6] of Ganguly-Stremavicius, Chennai Olympiad 2022.} (7... Be6 {We're now set to go 8...Nge7 and note that} 8. Nh5 Kf8 $1 {isn't anything to fear. After ... [g6] the knight will be pushed back and the black king emerge, well enough placed, on [g7].}) 8. Nd5 (8. Nd5 {An attempt to cause trouble in the event of} Nge7 $6 9. Nh5 $1 {, since now ...[g6] won't be so easy to arrange due to Black's lack of control over [h6].}) 8... Nf6 {[%cal Gd8f6,Gf6g4]} (8... Nf6 {A change of approach, threatening ...Ng4, and clearly, considering Black's excellent development,} 9. Nxf6+ $2 Qxf6 {is the opposite of anything to fear.}) ({If you are determined though to play for a win and avoid the upcoming potential early repetition,} 8... a6 $5 {may be considered, followed by ...[Nce7].}) 9. Bg5 {[%csl Rd8,Rf6]} Qa5+ $1 {[%csl Ge1]} (9... Qa5+ {Wisely unpinning and now} 10. c3 $5 Nxe4 $1 {would transpose to our main line, while saving two on the move number.}) 10. Bd2 {[%csl Ra5]} Qd8 {There just isn't really anywhere else for the queen to go.} 11. Bg5 {[%csl Rd8,Rf6]} Qa5+ {Repeating so is wise to escape the pin.} 12. c3 $5 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Rb2b4] White plays for a win...} Nxe4 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge4g5] ...and Black gets in a a tactic, one of the key points behind unpinning with ...[Qa5]+.} 13. Nxe4 Bxd5 {[%csl Gd1,Ge1,Gf2][%cal Gd5e4,Ga5c5]} (13... Bxd5 {Now} 14. Qxd5 $4 Bxf2+ $1 {would, of course, not be good news for White and Black is also OK after 14.Nxc5 Qxc5 15.Be3 Qa5 , and if 16.b4? Qa3! .}) 14. b4 $1 {[%csl Ra5,Rc5] The critical test, but Black should be happy enough with the upcoming piece sacrifice and compensation.} Bxb4 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Ge4]} 15. cxb4 Qxb4+ {[%csl Ge1,Ge4] Continuing to force the pace and so discombobulate.} 16. Nd2 Nd4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge8g8,Ga8c8] With three good pawns for the piece, the bishop on [d5] a monster and both ...[Rc8] and ...[O-O] high on the agenda, Black has full compensation for the piece, and arguably even more than that from a practical perspective.} *

