1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf5 {A perhaps unexpected move, if also one which has been used by some decent players over the years, most notably the Armenian-American Grandmaster Melikset Khachiyan.} Nf6 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d5] (Offering a transposition to a line of the Sveshnikov and no, 5...a6? would not lead to a Löwenthal after all, but leave White in control with 6.Nc3! ) .} ({A good question would be: why, when the immediate} 5... d5 {break is available? It is, but unfortunately after} 6. Qxd5 Qxd5 7. exd5 Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 9. Bd3 $1 {it's not so easy to play for a win as Black, as Michael Adams no less once discovered against Khachiyan. Adams's play can be improved on, as explained in the excellent courses King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian, but we prefer to retain queens with the more tricky text move, striking against [e4] while supporting ...[d5].}) 6. Bg5 $6 d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc8f5]} (6... d5 {White has been tricked and Black is already better, including after} 7. exd5 Qxd5 $1 8. Qxd5 Nxd5 {when White's developed pieces rather float in mid-air and [c2] may also prove vulnerable.}) 7. Bxf6 gxf6 8. Qxd5 {[%csl Rd8] Trying to reduce the amount of dynamism at Black's disposal, but this is now a trade queen to welcome since Black has the bishop-pair.} Qxd5 9. exd5 Bxf5 10. dxc6 bxc6 {[%cal Gf5c2,Ga8d8,Gf5e6,Gh7h5,Gf8h6,Gf6f5]} (10... bxc6 {Black already enjoyed a pleasant edge in Shmuter-Stripunsky, Volgograd 1994, with c2 attacked and} 11. Bd3 Be6 {set to retain the bishop-pair, when ...[f5] might follow. Meanwhile ...[Rd8], ...[Bc5] or ...[Bh6] and perhaps even ...[h5] are on their way, with White surely set to come under pressure in the resulting middlegame.}) *

