1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf5 {A perhaps unexpected move, if also one which has been used by some decent players over the years, most notably the Armenian-American Grandmaster Melikset Khachiyan.} Nf6 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d5] (Offering a transposition to a line of the Sveshnikov and no, 5...a6? would not lead to a Löwenthal after all, but leave White in control with 6.Nc3! ) .} ({A good question would be: why, when the immediate} 5... d5 {break is available? It is, but unfortunately after} 6. Qxd5 Qxd5 7. exd5 Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 9. Bd3 $1 {it's not so easy to play for a win as Black, as Michael Adams no less once discovered against Khachiyan. Adams's play can be improved on, as explained in the excellent courses King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian, but we prefer to retain queens with the more tricky text move, striking against [e4] while supporting ...[d5].}) 6. Bd3 $6 d5 $1 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gd5e4] The same theme, undermining the white centre and knight on [d5].} 7. exd5 Nxd5 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Gd5b4,Gd5f4] Now Black can develop comfortably with ...[g6] and ...[Bg7], or even look to seize an early initiative with ...[Nb4] or perhaps ...[Nf4].} 8. Ne3 Nf4 {[%csl Gd1,Gd3,Gg2] Going after the bishop-pair.} 9. Be4 Qxd1+ 10. Nxd1 Bd7 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gf7f5,Ge5f4] Black enjoys at least a pleasant edge, with ...[O-O-O] then ...[f5] imminent and absolutely no reason to fear an e-file-opening exchange on [f4].} *

