[GameId "2141525860975978"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf5 {A perhaps unexpected move, if also one which has been used by some decent players over the years, most notably the Armenian-American Grandmaster Melikset Khachiyan.} Nf6 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d5] (Offering a transposition to a line of the Sveshnikov and no, 5...a6? would not lead to a Löwenthal after all, but leave White in control with 6.Nc3! ) .} ({A good question would be: why, when the immediate} 5... d5 {break is available? It is, but unfortunately after} 6. Qxd5 Qxd5 7. exd5 Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 9. Bd3 $1 {it's not so easy to play for a win as Black, as Michael Adams no less once discovered against Khachiyan. Adams's play can be improved on, as explained in the excellent courses King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian, but we prefer to retain queens with the more tricky text move, striking against [e4] while supporting ...[d5].}) 6. Nc3 {Sensible development and we're now in Pelikan or Sveshnikov waters, this position also arising on the odd occasion via a 4...Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Nf5 move order.} d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5][%cal Gd5d4]} (6... d5 {Only now do we break and} 7. Nxd5 $6 Nxe4 8. Nfe3 Be6 {would only leave the white knights in a small pickle, so White really should prefer the other capture.}) 7. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 $5 ({Consistent with our policy of retaining pieces, although it should be said that} 8... Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 bxc6 {should just be quite an easy equaliser.}) 9. Qxd8+ $6 Rxd8 {[%cal Gf5c2,Gf8b4] The queen's rook joins in the fray and we're now ready to pick off [c2] or begin to obtain some pressure with ...[Bb4].} 10. Be3 Bxc2 ({Simple and good chess, swapping the a-pawn for one nearer the centre.} 10... Rd7 {is possible, but after} 11. Ba6 $5 Bxc2 12. O-O {White has enough for the pawn.}) 11. Bxa7 Ra8 {[%csl Ga2,Ga7] The rook returns to its starting square, but is happy to do so, being well placed to exert pressure down the now half-open file.} 12. Rc1 {[%csl Rc2]} Bf5 {Keeping pieces on and the bishop as active as possible.} 13. Be3 Nd5 $5 {[%cal Gd5e3,Ga8b8,Gd5b4] Striving to seize the initiative or the bishop-pair. As well as an exchange on [e3], Black can increase the pressure with ...[Nb4] or ...[Rb8] and is already slightly for choice, or quickly much more than that if White now allows a huge centre with a mistaken trade on [d5].} (13... Nd5 {For example,} 14. Nxd5 $2 cxd5 15. Bb5+ Bd7 {A simple risposte.} 16. Bxd7+ Kxd7 17. a3 Bd6 {With ...[d4] and ...[Rfb8]-[b3] imminent, Black is clearly doing well and is even borderline winning in the view of the engines.}) *

