1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf5 {A perhaps unexpected move, if also one which has been used by some decent players over the years, most notably the Armenian-American Grandmaster Melikset Khachiyan.} Nf6 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d5] (Offering a transposition to a line of the Sveshnikov and no, 5...a6? would not lead to a Löwenthal after all, but leave White in control with 6.Nc3! ) .} ({A good question would be: why, when the immediate} 5... d5 {break is available? It is, but unfortunately after} 6. Qxd5 Qxd5 7. exd5 Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 9. Bd3 $1 {it's not so easy to play for a win as Black, as Michael Adams no less once discovered against Khachiyan. Adams's play can be improved on, as explained in the excellent courses King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian, but we prefer to retain queens with the more tricky text move, striking against [e4] while supporting ...[d5].}) 6. Nc3 {Sensible development and we're now in Pelikan or Sveshnikov waters, this position also arising on the odd occasion via a 4...Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Nf5 move order.} d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5][%cal Gd5d4]} (6... d5 {Only now do we break and} 7. Nxd5 $6 Nxe4 8. Nfe3 Be6 {would only leave the white knights in a small pickle, so White really should prefer the other capture.}) 7. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 $5 ({Consistent with our policy of retaining pieces, although it should be said that} 8... Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 bxc6 {should just be quite an easy equaliser.}) 9. Bd3 e4 $1 {[%csl Gd3]} (9... e4 {Keeping pieces on. Here} 10. Qe2 Bb4 {is nothing to fear and neither is 10.Be2 Qc7! followed by ...[Rd8] and ...[Bd6].}) 10. Bc4 Bd6 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd8e7,Ge7e5] Continuing to keep pieces on. We're now ready to castle and may stir up trouble with a quick ...[Qe7] and ...[Qe5].} 11. h3 O-O 12. Be3 {White tried to delay castling so in Gisler-Sveshnikov, Bern 1992, where the great Sicilian maestro was content to rely on his technique with 12...[Be5], and there's even better.} Qe7 $1 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gf8d8,Gd6e5,Ga7a5,Ga5a4,Ge7e5] Tony Rotella's idea from his excellent 2014 Kalashnikov repertoire, The Killer Sicilian. Black gets ready to meet [O-O] with ...[Qe5] and if White continues to wait, may increase the pressure with ...[Rfd8], ...[Be5] and even ...[a5]-[a4].} *

