1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf5 {A perhaps unexpected move, if also one which has been used by some decent players over the years, most notably the Armenian-American Grandmaster Melikset Khachiyan.} Nf6 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d5] (Offering a transposition to a line of the Sveshnikov and no, 5...a6? would not lead to a Löwenthal after all, but leave White in control with 6.Nc3! ) .} ({A good question would be: why, when the immediate} 5... d5 {break is available? It is, but unfortunately after} 6. Qxd5 Qxd5 7. exd5 Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 9. Bd3 $1 {it's not so easy to play for a win as Black, as Michael Adams no less once discovered against Khachiyan. Adams's play can be improved on, as explained in the excellent courses King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian, but we prefer to retain queens with the more tricky text move, striking against [e4] while supporting ...[d5].}) 6. Nc3 {Sensible development and we're now in Pelikan or Sveshnikov waters, this position also arising on the odd occasion via a 4...Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Nf5 move order.} d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5][%cal Gd5d4]} (6... d5 {Only now do we break and} 7. Nxd5 $6 Nxe4 8. Nfe3 Be6 {would only leave the white knights in a small pickle, so White really should prefer the other capture.}) 7. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 $5 ({Consistent with our policy of retaining pieces, although it should be said that} 8... Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 bxc6 {should just be quite an easy equaliser.}) 9. Qf3 {[%csl Rc6,Rf5] White's main move by some margin, one once used by Maxime Vachier-Lagrave to eventually get the better of Magnus Carlsen in a Chess.com Speed Championship game.} Qd7 {[%csl Gc6,Gf5][%cal Gf5c2,Gf8b4] Sensibly securing the two en prise units. Black may now go after [c2] or keep developing actively with ... [Bb4].} 10. Bc4 $5 (10. Bc4 {A pawn sacrifice and also a fairly critical choice. Black has often declined with, for example,} Be7 {, but it's also possible to accept.}) 10... Bxc2 $5 11. O-O Be7 $1 {[%cal Gc2g6,Ge8g8] A good defensive square for the bishop. We're now ready to castle, as well as go ...[Bg6], so White probably should regain the pawn without delay.} 12. Qe2 Bg6 {Keeping everything tight at the back ahead of safely housing the king.} 13. Qxe5 O-O 14. Rd1 Qb7 {[%csl Gb2,Gc5,Gg1][%cal Gc6c5,Gf8e8,Gf8d8] Black has slightly the worse structure here, but we'd also slightly prefer to be in his shoes and Black has scored 3/4 from here on the Mega Database 2024, including winning the all-GM encounter Zelcic-Saric, Stari Mikanovci 2010. So why would we prefer to take Black?Firstly, the pressure down the b-file is mildly annoying for White and if [Bb3], Black will be able to consider playing for ...[c4]. Secondly, ...[Rfe8] will drive the white queen backwards or Black might prefer to challenge for the d-file with ...[Rfd8]. If White was forced to cede that, ...[Bd6] would become a possibility as well as ...[Nd5], looking to seize the initiative and ideally eventually attack on the kingside, a sector of the board currently devoid of white pieces.} *

