1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf5 {A perhaps unexpected move, if also one which has been used by some decent players over the years, most notably the Armenian-American Grandmaster Melikset Khachiyan.} Nf6 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d5] (Offering a transposition to a line of the Sveshnikov and no, 5...a6? would not lead to a Löwenthal after all, but leave White in control with 6.Nc3! ) .} ({A good question would be: why, when the immediate} 5... d5 {break is available? It is, but unfortunately after} 6. Qxd5 Qxd5 7. exd5 Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 9. Bd3 $1 {it's not so easy to play for a win as Black, as Michael Adams no less once discovered against Khachiyan. Adams's play can be improved on, as explained in the excellent courses King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian, but we prefer to retain queens with the more tricky text move, striking against [e4] while supporting ...[d5].}) 6. Nc3 {Sensible development and we're now in Pelikan or Sveshnikov waters, this position also arising on the odd occasion via a 4...Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Nf5 move order.} d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5][%cal Gd5d4]} (6... d5 {Only now do we break and} 7. Nxd5 $6 Nxe4 8. Nfe3 Be6 {would only leave the white knights in a small pickle, so White really should prefer the other capture.}) 7. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 $5 ({Consistent with our policy of retaining pieces, although it should be said that} 8... Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 bxc6 {should just be quite an easy equaliser.}) 9. Qf3 {[%csl Rc6,Rf5] White's main move by some margin, one once used by Maxime Vachier-Lagrave to eventually get the better of Magnus Carlsen in a Chess.com Speed Championship game.} Qd7 {[%csl Gc6,Gf5][%cal Gf5c2,Gf8b4] Sensibly securing the two en prise units. Black may now go after [c2] or keep developing actively with ... [Bb4].} 10. Bd3 $6 {[%csl Rf5]} e4 $1 {[%csl Gd3,Gf3][%cal Gf8b4]} (10... e4 {A fairly powerful rejoinder to White's attempt to force exchanges. White should now go} 11. Qe2 {when} Bb4 {followed by ...[O-O] is very pleasant for Black, but also doesn't leave us material ahead.}) 11. Nxe4 $4 Bxe4 {[%csl Gd3,Gf3]} 12. Bxe4 Qe6 {The pin is a winner, just as it would be were a white knight, not bishop, on [e4].} 13. O-O Qxe4 {[%cal Gf8e7] It's just an extra piece, 14...[Be7] is imminent and White hasn't a successful counter-tactic.} 14. Qxe4+ Nxe4 15. Re1 {[%csl Re4,Re8]} O-O-O $1 {[%csl Gd1,Gg1] The potential back-rank mate means that we stay a piece ahead and White could resign.} *

