1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf5 {A perhaps unexpected move, if also one which has been used by some decent players over the years, most notably the Armenian-American Grandmaster Melikset Khachiyan.} Nf6 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d5] (Offering a transposition to a line of the Sveshnikov and no, 5...a6? would not lead to a Löwenthal after all, but leave White in control with 6.Nc3! ) .} ({A good question would be: why, when the immediate} 5... d5 {break is available? It is, but unfortunately after} 6. Qxd5 Qxd5 7. exd5 Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 9. Bd3 $1 {it's not so easy to play for a win as Black, as Michael Adams no less once discovered against Khachiyan. Adams's play can be improved on, as explained in the excellent courses King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian, but we prefer to retain queens with the more tricky text move, striking against [e4] while supporting ...[d5].}) 6. Nc3 {Sensible development and we're now in Pelikan or Sveshnikov waters, this position also arising on the odd occasion via a 4...Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Nf5 move order.} d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5][%cal Gd5d4]} (6... d5 {Only now do we break and} 7. Nxd5 $6 Nxe4 8. Nfe3 Be6 {would only leave the white knights in a small pickle, so White really should prefer the other capture.}) 7. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 $5 ({Consistent with our policy of retaining pieces, although it should be said that} 8... Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 bxc6 {should just be quite an easy equaliser.}) 9. Qf3 {[%csl Rc6,Rf5] White's main move by some margin, one once used by Maxime Vachier-Lagrave to eventually get the better of Magnus Carlsen in a Chess.com Speed Championship game.} Qd7 {[%csl Gc6,Gf5][%cal Gf5c2,Gf8b4] Sensibly securing the two en prise units. Black may now go after [c2] or keep developing actively with ... [Bb4].} 10. Bg5 {White's most common choice by some margin, freeing his queen's rook for action while hinting at structural damage on the kingside.} e4 {[%cal Ge4f3,Gf8b4,Gf8d6]} (10... e4 {Continuing to seize space and fight for the initiative, a policy which} 11. Qf4 $6 Bd6 {would now but continue.}) 11. Qd1 {MVL's simple choice and now Magnus stood well enough after 11...[Qe6] and Black might also be more provocative.} Bd6 $5 {[%cal Ge8g8,Ga8b8,Gd7e7,Ge7e5] Both ...[Qe7] and ...[O-O] are likely to prove useful here, with counterplay imminent as soon as ...[Rb8] or ...[Qe5] are played. Meanwhile, there's absolutely no reason to fear doubled f-pawns.} 12. Qd4 Qe7 13. Bxf6 {Black was now happy to remove the queens in A.Muzychuk-Ushenina, European Women's Individual Championship, Rijeka 2010, but with such a dark-squared bishop and the white queen looking a little misplaced, Black can do even better.} gxf6 $1 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gd6c5,Ge8g8] Black's king will be quite safe on [g8] the bishop can always drop back to [g6] if needed, whereas its counterpart can be attacked on either flank. In any case, both ...[Rb8] and ...[Bc5] are imminent and even a little trick won't enable White to equalise.} 14. Bb5 $5 {[%csl Ra8,Rf5][%cal Rb5c6]} Rc8 $1 {[%cal Gc6b5]} 15. Nd5 $5 Qe5 {[%csl Gb5,Gd4] Forcing the queens off - on Black's terms.} 16. Qxe5+ Bxe5 {[%cal Gc6b5]} 17. Ba4 h5 $5 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gh8g8,Gf5e6,Gf6f5] By no means the only good move, but why grab [b2] and allow White some counterplay down the b-file? Instead, Black annexes space and begins a slow but inexorable march forwards on the kingside: ...[h4], ...[Rg8], ...[Be6] and ...[f5] may all follow.} *

