1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf5 {A perhaps unexpected move, if also one which has been used by some decent players over the years, most notably the Armenian-American Grandmaster Melikset Khachiyan.} Nf6 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d5] (Offering a transposition to a line of the Sveshnikov and no, 5...a6? would not lead to a Löwenthal after all, but leave White in control with 6.Nc3! ) .} ({A good question would be: why, when the immediate} 5... d5 {break is available? It is, but unfortunately after} 6. Qxd5 Qxd5 7. exd5 Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 9. Bd3 $1 {it's not so easy to play for a win as Black, as Michael Adams no less once discovered against Khachiyan. Adams's play can be improved on, as explained in the excellent courses King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian, but we prefer to retain queens with the more tricky text move, striking against [e4] while supporting ...[d5].}) 6. Nc3 {Sensible development and we're now in Pelikan or Sveshnikov waters, this position also arising on the odd occasion via a 4...Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Nf5 move order.} d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5][%cal Gd5d4]} (6... d5 {Only now do we break and} 7. Nxd5 $6 Nxe4 8. Nfe3 Be6 {would only leave the white knights in a small pickle, so White really should prefer the other capture.}) 7. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 $5 ({Consistent with our policy of retaining pieces, although it should be said that} 8... Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 bxc6 {should just be quite an easy equaliser.}) 9. Qf3 {[%csl Rc6,Rf5] White's main move by some margin, one once used by Maxime Vachier-Lagrave to eventually get the better of Magnus Carlsen in a Chess.com Speed Championship game.} Qd7 {[%csl Gc6,Gf5][%cal Gf5c2,Gf8b4] Sensibly securing the two en prise units. Black may now go after [c2] or keep developing actively with ... [Bb4].} 10. Bg5 {White's most common choice by some margin, freeing his queen's rook for action while hinting at structural damage on the kingside.} e4 {[%cal Ge4f3,Gf8b4,Gf8d6]} (10... e4 {Continuing to seize space and fight for the initiative, a policy which} 11. Qf4 $6 Bd6 {would now but continue.}) 11. Qe2 Bb4 $5 {[%cal Gf6d5] Once again, the most uncompromising choice, threatening 12...[Nd5] and provoking an exchange on [f6]. It should be said that there's also absolutely nothing wrong with the solid and sensible 11...[Be7].} 12. Bxf6 gxf6 {[%csl Gb4,Ge2,Gf1,Gh1][%cal Ga8b8,Ga8d8,Gd7e7,Ge7c5,Ge7e5,Gd7e6] Black is now ready to contest the d-file with ...[Rd8] or perhaps prefer ...[Rb8], looking to then strike on the dark squares after ...[Ba5]. Meanwhile, the queen would be good on any of [e5], [c5] or just [e6], while the king should be safe enough on [g8]. And, finally, don't forget that White is still some way from developing his kingside.} 13. Rd1 Qe7 $5 {[%cal Ge8g8,Ge7e5,Ge7c5] Keeping everything secure while looking to activate the queen via [c5] or [e5], or just castle. We're also trying to entice White into grabbing a pawn.} 14. Qa6 $2 O-O $1 {[%cal Ge4e3,Ge7c5,Gf8d8] Now even ...[e3], as well as ...[Rfd8] and ...[Qc5] is high on the agenda.} 15. Qxc6 $2 Rac8 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gc8c6,Gc8c3] Once the queen moves, Black will go 16...[Rxc3]! 17. [bxc3] [Bxc3]+ with a devastating attack.} *

