1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf5 {A perhaps unexpected move, if also one which has been used by some decent players over the years, most notably the Armenian-American Grandmaster Melikset Khachiyan.} Nf6 $5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d5] (Offering a transposition to a line of the Sveshnikov and no, 5...a6? would not lead to a Löwenthal after all, but leave White in control with 6.Nc3! ) .} ({A good question would be: why, when the immediate} 5... d5 {break is available? It is, but unfortunately after} 6. Qxd5 Qxd5 7. exd5 Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 9. Bd3 $1 {it's not so easy to play for a win as Black, as Michael Adams no less once discovered against Khachiyan. Adams's play can be improved on, as explained in the excellent courses King's Kalashnikov Sicilian and Lifetime Repertoires: Kalashnikov Sicilian, but we prefer to retain queens with the more tricky text move, striking against [e4] while supporting ...[d5].}) 6. Nc3 {Sensible development and we're now in Pelikan or Sveshnikov waters, this position also arising on the odd occasion via a 4...Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Nf5 move order.} d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5][%cal Gd5d4]} (6... d5 {Only now do we break and} 7. Nxd5 $6 Nxe4 8. Nfe3 Be6 {would only leave the white knights in a small pickle, so White really should prefer the other capture.}) 7. exd5 {[%csl Rc6]} Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6 $5 ({Consistent with our policy of retaining pieces, although it should be said that} 8... Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 bxc6 {should just be quite an easy equaliser.}) 9. Qf3 {[%csl Rc6,Rf5] White's main move by some margin, one once used by Maxime Vachier-Lagrave to eventually get the better of Magnus Carlsen in a Chess.com Speed Championship game.} Qd7 {[%csl Gc6,Gf5][%cal Gf5c2,Gf8b4] Sensibly securing the two en prise units. Black may now go after [c2] or keep developing actively with ... [Bb4].} 10. Bg5 {White's most common choice by some margin, freeing his queen's rook for action while hinting at structural damage on the kingside.} e4 {[%cal Ge4f3,Gf8b4,Gf8d6]} (10... e4 {Continuing to seize space and fight for the initiative, a policy which} 11. Qf4 $6 Bd6 {would now but continue.}) 11. Qe2 Bb4 $5 {[%cal Gf6d5] Once again, the most uncompromising choice, threatening 12...[Nd5] and provoking an exchange on [f6]. It should be said that there's also absolutely nothing wrong with the solid and sensible 11...[Be7].} 12. Bxf6 gxf6 {[%csl Gb4,Ge2,Gf1,Gh1][%cal Ga8b8,Ga8d8,Gd7e7,Ge7c5,Ge7e5,Gd7e6] Black is now ready to contest the d-file with ...[Rd8] or perhaps prefer ...[Rb8], looking to then strike on the dark squares after ...[Ba5]. Meanwhile, the queen would be good on any of [e5], [c5] or just [e6], while the king should be safe enough on [g8]. And, finally, don't forget that White is still some way from developing his kingside.} 13. Qc4 {[%csl Rb4]} Rd8 $1 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gd7d2] Ignoring the hanging bishop to threaten mate.} 14. Be2 Qd2+ {[%csl Ge1] It's still a good square for the queen, preventing White from ever castling.} 15. Kf1 {[%csl Rc4,Rc6]} (15. Kf1 {Here Black preserved his bishop with} Be7 {in McKenzie-Abrahamson, New Zealand Championship, Dunedin 1992, and we can do even better by following Tony Rotella's 2014 recommendation.}) 15... Bxc3 $1 {It's well worth the cost of the pawn on [c6] to completely ruin White's own queenside pawns.} 16. Qxc6+ {[%csl Re8]} Kf8 {[%cal Gf8g7] The king will be quite safe on [g7] and clearly ...[Rc8] is imminent.} 17. Qxc3 {[%csl Rf6]} Qxc3 18. bxc3 Rc8 {[%csl Ga2,Gc2,Gc3][%cal Gc8c3,Gf5e6,Gf6f5,Gf8g7,Gg7f6,Gf6e5]} (18... Rc8 {Black is about to regain the pawn, on c3 or c4, after} 19. c4 Be6 {, after which we'll have an edge in the resulting endgame thanks to the ongoing pressure against White's queenside and the potentially useful central pawn majority, especially if there's time to get in ...[Kg7], ...[f5], ...[Kf6] and ...[Ke5].}) *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
