[White "6C) 5.Nxc6"]
[Black "5.Nxc6 bxc6 6.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B33"]
[PlyCount "26"]
[GameId "2141525861193074"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nxc6 {A slightly strange decision perhaps, if a move often chosen by inexperienced opponents surprised by 4...[e5]. This exchange has also been tried by a couple of grandmasters, as well as by Morphy and Anderssen back in the day, that despite the fact they must have been familiar with a very famous McDonnell-de La Bourdonnais clash in this line.} bxc6 {[%csl Gd5] Naturally we recapture towards the centre and can already be pleased to enjoy an extra central pawn and control of our regular weak point, [d5]. Black is now set to develop with ... [Nf6] and ...[Bc5], after which, a quick ...[d5] may well be possible.} 6. Nc3 Nf6 ({Straightforward and sensible development, although you can also start with} 6... Bc5 {if you wish. After 6...Nf6 White usually goes 7.Bc4 after all, transposing to the same position as 6.Nc3 Nf6 7.Bc4 .}) 7. Bg5 $6 {[%csl Gd5] Such a bishop development rarely packs much weight when it's Black, not White, in control of [d5].} Rb8 {[%cal Gb8b2]} ({There's nothing wrong with the immediate} 7... h6 {, but why not activate the rook without delay? Note too that this early rook deployment would also be a good response to 7. [Be3].}) 8. Rb1 {The least weakening way of defending [b2].} h6 $1 {[%csl Gg5]} (8... h6 {Prodding the bishop without delay and actually already causing White some problems. Indeed,} 9. Be3 $2 d5 {would already leave Black with a strong initiative and some advantage, as did 9.Bd2? d5 in Julian-Pein, Uzes 1989. White should also be rather wary about retreating to [h4].}) 9. Bxf6 {Best, if also something of a concession.} Qxf6 10. Bc4 Bc5 {[%csl Gc5,Ge1,Gf6][%cal Gf6f2] Developing with a certain threat and already we might well say that Black is master of the dark squares.} 11. O-O O-O {[%cal Gc5d4,Gf8d8,Gc8b7,Gd7d6,Gd7d5] Black may now disrupt with ...[Bd4] and can look to force through ...[d5] after ...[Rd8] and ...[Bb7]. Alternatively, you might prefer a ...[d6] set-up, perhaps followed by ...[Qh4] and/or ...[Kh8], looking to attack on the kingside.} 12. Na4 {[%csl Rc5]} Be7 {Retaining the unopposed bishop.} 13. Nc3 Rd8 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge7c5] Black was ready to go ...[Bb7] then return the other bishop to [c5] and enjoyed a pleasant edge, with White looking a little planless in Casares Pedride-Munoz Pantoja, Santiago de Compostela rapid 2022.} *

