1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nxc6 {A slightly strange decision perhaps, if a move often chosen by inexperienced opponents surprised by 4...[e5]. This exchange has also been tried by a couple of grandmasters, as well as by Morphy and Anderssen back in the day, that despite the fact they must have been familiar with a very famous McDonnell-de La Bourdonnais clash in this line.} bxc6 {[%csl Gd5] Naturally we recapture towards the centre and can already be pleased to enjoy an extra central pawn and control of our regular weak point, [d5]. Black is now set to develop with ... [Nf6] and ...[Bc5], after which, a quick ...[d5] may well be possible.} 6. Nc3 Nf6 ({Straightforward and sensible development, although you can also start with} 6... Bc5 {if you wish. After 6...Nf6 White usually goes 7.Bc4 after all, transposing to the same position as 6.Nc3 Nf6 7.Bc4 .}) 7. Bg5 $6 {[%csl Gd5] Such a bishop development rarely packs much weight when it's Black, not White, in control of [d5].} Rb8 {[%cal Gb8b2]} ({There's nothing wrong with the immediate} 7... h6 {, but why not activate the rook without delay? Note too that this early rook deployment would also be a good response to 7. [Be3].}) 8. Rb1 {The least weakening way of defending [b2].} h6 $1 {[%csl Gg5]} (8... h6 {Prodding the bishop without delay and actually already causing White some problems. Indeed,} 9. Be3 $2 d5 {would already leave Black with a strong initiative and some advantage, as did 9.Bd2? d5 in Julian-Pein, Uzes 1989. White should also be rather wary about retreating to [h4].}) 9. Bh4 $2 Qa5 $1 {[%csl Ga5,Ge1][%cal Gb8b2,Gf6e4,Gf8b4]} (9... Qa5 {Black threatens 10...Rxb2, as well as 10...Nxe4 and already White is pretty much lost, including after} 10. Qd2 Bb4 {.}) 10. Bxf6 Rxb2 $1 {[%cal Ga5c3]} 11. Kd2 {A hideous move to have to make, but also best according to the engines.} Rxb1 12. Qxb1 gxf6 {[%cal Gf8b4] Black enjoyed an extra pawn and the compensation, and won quickly in Pawlitzki-Salai, German League 1994.} *

