1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nxc6 {A slightly strange decision perhaps, if a move often chosen by inexperienced opponents surprised by 4...[e5]. This exchange has also been tried by a couple of grandmasters, as well as by Morphy and Anderssen back in the day, that despite the fact they must have been familiar with a very famous McDonnell-de La Bourdonnais clash in this line.} bxc6 {[%csl Gd5] Naturally we recapture towards the centre and can already be pleased to enjoy an extra central pawn and control of our regular weak point, [d5]. Black is now set to develop with ... [Nf6] and ...[Bc5], after which, a quick ...[d5] may well be possible.} 6. Nc3 Nf6 ({Straightforward and sensible development, although you can also start with} 6... Bc5 {if you wish. After 6...Nf6 White usually goes 7.Bc4 after all, transposing to the same position as 6.Nc3 Nf6 7.Bc4 .}) 7. Bd3 {At least this supplies a solid enough central grip for White.} Bc5 ({A fine diagonal for the bishop once again and a decent alternative to the more common} 7... Bb4 {.}) 8. O-O O-O {[%cal Gf8e8,Ga8b8,Gh7h6]} ({Sensible and best to sidestep any small issues with} 8... d6 9. Na4 {. Now if 9.Na4 Black can just go 9...Be7 , while 9.Bg5 should again see the bishop prodded with 9...h6 when 10.Bh4 can be met by 10...a5 if you're not totally sure about 10...g5 . Meanwhile, the rooks are en route to [e8] and [b8], and ...[h6] may even be played as a prophylactic device, preventing [Bg5] ahead of breaking with ...[d5].}) 9. Kh1 $5 {The start of a pretty aggressive plan by White.} d5 {Black responds in good, classical fashion to the potential attack on the flank by responding in the centre.} 10. f4 (10. f4 {Here} Ng4 $5 {, with the threats of 11...[Nf2]+ and 11...[Qh4] was pretty tempting in Dushyant-Oleksienko, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, where, unfortunately, White found} 11. Qe1 $1 {and stood slightly better.}) 10... dxe4 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4,Ge4d3]} (10... dxe4 {A simple and sound policy, and now} 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 {can be well met by} Ba6 $1 {, giving Black a pleasant set-up and the initiative.}) 11. fxe5 exd3 {Refusing to fear any damage to the kingside.} 12. exf6 Re8 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6] Calmly done. Black menaces ...[Ba6], ensures that [fxg7] won't come with tempo and stands at least equal with the bishop-pair and central play fully offsetting any kingside damage.} 13. fxg7 $2 dxc2 {Possible when there isn't a rook hanging on [f8].} 14. Qxc2 Ba6 {[%csl Ga6,Gc5,Gh1][%cal Gd8h4] Black's bishops rule the roost and while the en prise rook can move to [d1], that won't prevent us from landing the queen on [h4] and continuing to take over.} *

