1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nxc6 {A slightly strange decision perhaps, if a move often chosen by inexperienced opponents surprised by 4...[e5]. This exchange has also been tried by a couple of grandmasters, as well as by Morphy and Anderssen back in the day, that despite the fact they must have been familiar with a very famous McDonnell-de La Bourdonnais clash in this line.} bxc6 {[%csl Gd5] Naturally we recapture towards the centre and can already be pleased to enjoy an extra central pawn and control of our regular weak point, [d5]. Black is now set to develop with ... [Nf6] and ...[Bc5], after which, a quick ...[d5] may well be possible.} 6. c4 $6 {Erecting a Maroczy Bind is a little strange when Black controls the key [d5] point.} Bc5 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gg8f6,Gd8h4] A familiar policy. We may well follow up with 7...[Nf6], although if White now does something slow then 7...[Qh4] may become tempting.} 7. Nc3 Nf6 ({Straightforward development and White should be fine here after} 7... Qh4 8. g3 {.}) 8. Bd3 d6 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf6g4,Gc5d4,Gc8e6,Ga8b8] Creating a small threat rather than rush to castle. Of course, ...[O-O] will prove a good move, but so most likely will ...[Be6], ...[Rb8] and even ... [Bd4].} (8... d6 {In short, Black already enjoys an active and pleasant set-up, and here White would be to castle or go in for} 9. h3 Rb8 {.}) 9. a3 $2 {There won't be any time for [b2]-[b4].} Ng4 $1 {Already there's just no good way of defending [f2] as castling...} 10. O-O $2 Qh4 {[%csl Gg1][%cal Gh4h2,Gg4f2] ...only serves to make matters worse. Richard has enjoyed this position and similar cases of the same trap several times over many years online. White can prevent mate, but not Black then crashing through on [f2] with near decisive effect.} *

