1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nxc6 {A slightly strange decision perhaps, if a move often chosen by inexperienced opponents surprised by 4...[e5]. This exchange has also been tried by a couple of grandmasters, as well as by Morphy and Anderssen back in the day, that despite the fact they must have been familiar with a very famous McDonnell-de La Bourdonnais clash in this line.} bxc6 {[%csl Gd5] Naturally we recapture towards the centre and can already be pleased to enjoy an extra central pawn and control of our regular weak point, [d5]. Black is now set to develop with ... [Nf6] and ...[Bc5], after which, a quick ...[d5] may well be possible.} 6. Bc4 {White's most common follow-up, eyeing [f7]. Plenty of other moves have been tried, but very few pose Black any problems.} Nf6 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Gf6e4]} (6... Nf6 {Natural and good development, and with a threat. Note too that again} 7. Bg5 $6 {wouldn't be a great policy here for White: as well as} h6 ({de La Bourdonnais preferred} 7... Be7 {, Black can go})) {7...Qa5+!? 8.Bd2 Qb6 when we may well already be better.} 7. Nc3 Bc5 $5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d6,Gc8e6,Gh7h6]} ({A rare choice compared to} 7... Bb4 {, if also a pretty logical move and one consistent with the repertoire in this theory section. We place the bishop on a good diagonal, will again meet any [Bg5] with ...[h6], and get ready to continue development with ...[O-O], ...[d6] and ...[Be6].}) 8. O-O O-O {[%cal Gc5d4,Gd7d6]} (8... O-O {By no means forced, but if now} 9. Na4 {we again have} Be7 {. It may seem that [Na4] will remain a problem and yet we can usually avoid any such issues by prefacing ...[d6] with the slightly disruptive concept that is ... [Bd4].}) 9. Bg5 {White's main move by some margin in practice, developing the final minor piece as actively as possible.} h6 $1 {[%csl Gg5] Our familiar watchword: challenging the bishop and not letting White exploit the pin down the [h4]-[d8] diagonal in any way.} (9... h6 {Once again,} 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 {would now be quite pleasant with our dark-square control and} 11. Na4 {able to be met by} Be7 {or even 11...Bd6!? .}) 10. Bh4 Bd4 $5 {[%csl Gb2,Gc3][%cal Ga8b8,Gd7d6,Gg7g5] Another Rotella-endorsed idea back in his excellent Kalashnikov repertoire, The Killer Sicilian. Black worries White about an exchange on [c3], while strong-pointing [e5]. As well as ...[d6], ...[Rb8] and/or ...[g5] may quickly occur.} 11. Qd3 {White shores up his central defences.} g5 {[%csl Gh4] Forcing the white bishop to a rather offside location.} 12. Bg3 Qe7 {[%csl Gc3,Ge4][%cal Gd7d6,Ga8b8]} (12... Qe7 {Covering e5 and enabling} 13. Ne2 $6 {to still be met by} Bxb2 {. We will likely continue with ...[d6], further securing [e5], after which ...[Bxc3] may become a possibility, as well as ...[Rb8].}) 13. Rad1 d6 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gc8e6,Gc8g4,Gg4h5,Gh5g6] Black enjoys a comfortable set-up. We may simply follow up with ...[Be6] and ...[Rb8], but the disruptive 14...[Bg4] is actually a mini-threat, discombobulating followed by manoeuvring the bishop round to a decent spot on [g6].} *

