1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf3 {Another line often seen when White is both fairly lowly-rated and surprised by ...[e5].} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] Developing with a threat. Not exactly for the first time in this repertoire, Black's early lead in development is a useful asset.} 6. Bc4 $6 {[%csl Rf7] White eyes the traditional weak spot in Black's camp in general, [f7], but this gambit is not an especially convincing one.} Nxe4 $1 {[%csl Gf7] Calling White's bluff and hoping that he will now carry out the 'threat'.} 7. Qd5 $1 (7. Qd5 {The best try, if also not really what a gambiteer would want to be doing. Now they would, however, likely be quite happy with White's compensation after} Nd6 8. Bb3 {, so we should prefer to return the pawn and exchange the queens.}) 7... Qa5+ $1 {[%csl Gd5,Ge1]} 8. Qxa5 Nxa5 9. Nxe5 Nxc4 {Accruing the bishop-pair.} 10. Nxc4 d5 {[%csl Gc8,Gf8][%cal Gf8c5,Gf8b4,Gd5c4] The dark-squared bishop will be developed to [c5] or maybe [b4], and Black's easier development and two bishops should more than outweigh the small weakness on [d5].} *

