1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf3 {Another line often seen when White is both fairly lowly-rated and surprised by ...[e5].} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] Developing with a threat. Not exactly for the first time in this repertoire, Black's early lead in development is a useful asset.} 6. Bc4 $6 {[%csl Rf7] White eyes the traditional weak spot in Black's camp in general, [f7], but this gambit is not an especially convincing one.} Nxe4 $1 {[%csl Gf7] Calling White's bluff and hoping that he will now carry out the 'threat'.} 7. Bxf7+ $6 Kxf7 {Necessary, but also quite effective.} 8. Qd5+ {[%csl Rf7]} Ke8 9. Qxe4 d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4]} (9... d5 {Obtaining an ideal centre, and with gain of tempo. Note too the white queen's lack of a great square and how} 10. Qa4 $2 Bd7 {would now continue to harry her.}) 10. Qe2 e4 $5 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Gc8g4,Gf8e7,Gc8f5] With ...[Bg4], or perhaps ...[Bf5], and ...[Be7] on the way, Black has seized the early initiative and the powerful centre and bishop-pair should more than offset our inability to castle.} *

