1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf3 {Another line often seen when White is both fairly lowly-rated and surprised by ...[e5].} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] Developing with a threat. Not exactly for the first time in this repertoire, Black's early lead in development is a useful asset.} 6. Bg5 {Another slightly shady bishop deployment.} Qa5+ $1 {[%csl Ge1] By no means the only decent move, but a good response, as well as one which sets a small trap.} 7. Bd2 {A prudent choice, although Black can hardly object to dropping the queen back, with gain of tempo against [b2].} Qb6 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gf6e4]} 8. Nc3 {[%csl Rb2]} (8. Nc3 {Best and now} Qxb2 $2 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. Nb5 {would not make for good viewing for Black.}) 8... Bc5 $1 {[%cal Gc5f2] Our favourite bishop deployment in these lines, one which here carries a definite threat.} 9. Qe2 (9. Qe2 {Here Alex Shabalov once couldn't resist} Ng4 $6 {, but after} 10. O-O-O $1 Nxf2 $2 11. Na4 {he was in some trouble in Felber-Shabalov, Saint Paul 2000.}) 9... Nd4 $5 {[%csl Ge2]} ({A preferable ambitious knight move. Also decent is a more solid approach with} 9... d6 {, and if} 10. Na4 Qc7 {.}) 10. Nxd4 Bxd4 {With [c2] no longer defended, Black was now threatening to take on [b2] in Tevzadze-Butskhrikidze, Tbilisi 2002, where White probably should have castled.} 11. O-O-O a6 $5 {[%cal Gd7d6,Gc8e6,Ge8g8,Ga8c8] Keeping the white knight out of [b5] ahead of intending to complete development with ...[d6], ...[Be6], ...[Rc8] and ...[O-O], with a decent game and the ...[d5] break to aim for as Black.} *

