1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf3 {Another line often seen when White is both fairly lowly-rated and surprised by ...[e5].} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] Developing with a threat. Not exactly for the first time in this repertoire, Black's early lead in development is a useful asset.} 6. Bg5 {Another slightly shady bishop deployment.} Qa5+ $1 {[%csl Ge1] By no means the only decent move, but a good response, as well as one which sets a small trap.} 7. Qd2 $2 Bb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4d2,Gf6e4]} 8. c3 Nxe4 $1 {[%csl Gd2,Ge1][%cal Gc6b4,Ge4d2]} (8... Nxe4 {The refutation. It shouldn't be too hard to see that White's position completely collapses after} 9. cxb4 $2 Nxb4 10. Qe2 Nd3+ {and neither does moving the queen especially help him.}) 9. Qe3 d5 $3 {[%cal Gb4c5] Tony Rotella's stunning discovery. Black threatens ...[Bc5] and the piece sacrifice remains a near-winner.} 10. cxb4 Nxb4 {[%cal Gb4c2]} 11. Kd1 Bf5 {[%cal Gd5d4,Gb4c2] With ...[d4] high on the agenda and even 12...[Nc2] a threat, White surely won't manage to survive.} *

