1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf3 {Another line often seen when White is both fairly lowly-rated and surprised by ...[e5].} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] Developing with a threat. Not exactly for the first time in this repertoire, Black's early lead in development is a useful asset.} 6. Nc3 ({White's main move, competing for control of e4 and d5. Of the alternatives,} 6. Bd3 {allows Black to either equalise straight away with} d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 {or prefer 6...Bc5!? when 7.Nc3 would transpose to a position we'll consider, below, via a 6.Nc3 Bc5 7.Bd3 move order.}) 6... Bc5 $5 {[%cal Gf6g4,Ge8g8]} ({A consistent choice for us in these lines, although it should be said that Black has also done well with the more forcing and somewhat more common} 6... Bb4 {, as recommended by King and Cuenca. The text move introduces the threat of 7...[Ng4] while facilitating castling.}) 7. Bd3 d6 {[%cal Gc5b4,Gh7h6]} (7... d6 {There's no rush to castle against such modest development from White and here} 8. Na4 {would run into} Qa5+ {, while 8.Bg5 Bb4!? is also slightly inconvenient for the first player.}) 8. O-O a6 $5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gc8e6,Gh7h6] Continuing our provocative [d5]-defying stance. The bishop now has a retreat square on [a7] and we're ready to go ...[Be6], either pre or post any prophylactic ...[h6].} 9. Bg5 {[%cal Rc3d5] This must be critical and, of course, the good, old [Nd5] is now very much a positional threat.} h6 $1 {[%csl Gg5]} (9... h6 {Black absolutely must break the pin whilst hoping to entomb the white bishop after} 10. Bh4 $2 g5 {.}) 10. Bxf6 $1 Qxf6 11. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Rd5c7]} Qd8 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc8e6,Gc6e7,Gg8h8,Gf7f5] White has conquered [d5], but is still slightly short of a good plan, and Black must be fine here. We'll castle next, after which ...[Be6] and/or ...[Ne7] will deal with the intruder on [d5] and in the medium term Black may play to break with ...[f5].} *

