1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf3 {Another line often seen when White is both fairly lowly-rated and surprised by ...[e5].} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] Developing with a threat. Not exactly for the first time in this repertoire, Black's early lead in development is a useful asset.} 6. Nc3 ({White's main move, competing for control of e4 and d5. Of the alternatives,} 6. Bd3 {allows Black to either equalise straight away with} d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 {or prefer 6...Bc5!? when 7.Nc3 would transpose to a position we'll consider, below, via a 6.Nc3 Bc5 7.Bd3 move order.}) 6... Bc5 $5 {[%cal Gf6g4,Ge8g8]} ({A consistent choice for us in these lines, although it should be said that Black has also done well with the more forcing and somewhat more common} 6... Bb4 {, as recommended by King and Cuenca. The text move introduces the threat of 7...[Ng4] while facilitating castling.}) 7. Bg5 {Not for the first time, this active-looking bishop deployment fails to fully convince.} Qb6 $1 {[%cal Gb6b2,Gc5f2]} (7... Qb6 {The problem: both b2 and f2 hang. Note too how} 8. Qd2 $2 {would run into} Bxf2+ {and White really needs to think outside of the box here to stay afloat.}) 8. Be2 $5 (8. Be2 {Now} Qxb2 9. Nb5 $1 {isn't at all clear, so we should take the other pawn.}) 8... Bxf2+ {[%csl Ge1]} 9. Kf1 Bd4 $1 {[%csl Gd5]} (9... Bd4 {Played to cover e5 and prevent White from successfully invading d5:} 10. Nd5 $2 {would now be met by} Nxd5 11. exd5 e4 $1 {.}) 10. Bxf6 $1 {[%cal Rc3d5]} Bxc3 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gg7f6] The point of Black's play.} 11. Bxg7 {[%csl Rh8]} Rg8 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gg8g7]} 12. bxc3 Rxg7 {[%csl Gf1][%cal Gb6c5,Gd7d6] Neither king is totally happy nor the position completely clear, but Black has slightly the better structure and slightly the easier position to play with ...[Qc5] and ...[d6] on their way.} *

