1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf3 {Another line often seen when White is both fairly lowly-rated and surprised by ...[e5].} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] Developing with a threat. Not exactly for the first time in this repertoire, Black's early lead in development is a useful asset.} 6. Nc3 ({White's main move, competing for control of e4 and d5. Of the alternatives,} 6. Bd3 {allows Black to either equalise straight away with} d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 {or prefer 6...Bc5!? when 7.Nc3 would transpose to a position we'll consider, below, via a 6.Nc3 Bc5 7.Bd3 move order.}) 6... Bc5 $5 {[%cal Gf6g4,Ge8g8]} ({A consistent choice for us in these lines, although it should be said that Black has also done well with the more forcing and somewhat more common} 6... Bb4 {, as recommended by King and Cuenca. The text move introduces the threat of 7...[Ng4] while facilitating castling.}) 7. Bc4 (7. Bc4 {Active development, hoping for} Ng4 $2 8. Bxf7+ $1 {.}) 7... d6 {[%cal Gc8e6]} ({Calm and consistent queenside development, although if you really want to prevent Bg5, it's also possible to begin with} 7... h6 $5 {.}) 8. O-O Be6 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf7e6]} (8... Be6 {Challenging the bishop on c4, while hoping for} 9. Bxe6 fxe6 {when Black would have nice central control and use of the half-open f-file.}) 9. Bb3 a6 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gb7b5,Ge8g8,Gh7h6] Hinting at possible and standard Sicilian expansion with ...[b5], while also giving the bishop on [c5] a potential retreat square. We're now ready to castle, as well as meet any [Bg5] with ...[h6].} 10. Be3 $5 {This radical try was unveiled in Ditiatev-Voitsekhovsky, Kaluga 2007, where Black might have taken up the offer.} Bxe3 11. fxe3 O-O {[%cal Gd8e7,Ga8c8,Gc6a5] Calmly does it. There's no need for any ...[Qb6] ideas when the queen can tuck into [e7], thereby facilitating ...[Rfd8], if needed, to defend [d6]. Meanwhile ...[Rac8] and ...[Na5] will begin counterplay on the queenside and Black enjoys a decent, classic Sicilian set-up.} *

