1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nf3 {Another line often seen when White is both fairly lowly-rated and surprised by ...[e5].} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] Developing with a threat. Not exactly for the first time in this repertoire, Black's early lead in development is a useful asset.} 6. Nc3 ({White's main move, competing for control of e4 and d5. Of the alternatives,} 6. Bd3 {allows Black to either equalise straight away with} d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 {or prefer 6...Bc5!? when 7.Nc3 would transpose to a position we'll consider, below, via a 6.Nc3 Bc5 7.Bd3 move order.}) 6... Bc5 $5 {[%cal Gf6g4,Ge8g8]} ({A consistent choice for us in these lines, although it should be said that Black has also done well with the more forcing and somewhat more common} 6... Bb4 {, as recommended by King and Cuenca. The text move introduces the threat of 7...[Ng4] while facilitating castling.}) 7. Bc4 (7. Bc4 {Active development, hoping for} Ng4 $2 8. Bxf7+ $1 {.}) 7... d6 {[%cal Gc8e6]} ({Calm and consistent queenside development, although if you really want to prevent Bg5, it's also possible to begin with} 7... h6 $5 {.}) 8. Bg5 (8. Bg5 {Pinning so feels critical now that} Qb6 $2 {would run into} 9. O-O {or even 9.Bxf6! .}) 8... Bb4 $5 {[%csl Gc3,Ge1][%cal Gh7h6] First played by Henry Buckle back in 1849, this second bishop move gives White some of his own medicine, i.e. it creates a slightly annoying pin, and Black also gets ready to go ...[h6] without needing to fear [Nd5] ideas.} ({It should be said too that just like when the white bishop is on d3,} 8... h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Nd5 Qd8 {followed by playing around the knight on [d5] is also a reasonable choice.}) 9. Qd3 {Developing and shoring up [e4] so feels critical.} Bxc3+ $1 {[%csl Ge1]} (9... Bxc3+ {Damaging White's structure while we can in view of} 10. Qxc3 Nxe4 {.}) 10. bxc3 h6 {[%csl Gg5] Attempting to drive the bishop offside once again, so White should likely exchange and switch his focus to the backwards d-pawn.} 11. Bxf6 $1 Qxf6 12. Rd1 {[%csl Rd6]} O-O $5 ({Gambitting the pawn, although if you don't mind not castling, there may well be nothing wrong with} 12... Ke7 {.}) 13. Qxd6 Qf4 $1 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gf8d8,Ga8c8,Gf4e4] The point. Black keeps the queens on, attacks [e4] and easily has enough compensation. Very likely ...[Bg4] will follow, freeing the way for ...[Rfd8] and ...[Rac8], the second rook move of which will begin to target the somewhat shattered white queenside.} *

