1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb3 ({A fairly modest, but sensible sideline. Unlike after} 5. Nf3 {, White doesn't obstruct his kingside options and also takes control of [c5].}) 5... Bb4+ $5 {[%csl Ge1]} ({An unusual choice compared to the main line,} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 {(as covered by King and Cuenca, if also one we hope may confuse more experienced opponents who stick with 5. [Nb3] because it's solid or where they normally retreat the knight to in the Open Sicilian we did also look into 5...[a5], but couldn't see any great benefits of including that if White counters with 6.a4. Will White still go 6. [Nc3]?)}) {when Bd2 is unspectacular but fine for White,} 6. Bd2 a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5b4,Gd8h4,Gg8f6]} (6... a5 {An extremely rare advance here, if one we quite like. Actually, 7...a4 isn't really a threat, but we would be pretty happy to see} 7. Bxb4 axb4 $1 {, opening up the file for the rook on [a8] while clamping down on the white queenside.}) ({Of Black's other options,} 6... Qh4 7. Qe2 $1 {feel a little shaky, but if you don't mind a Kalashnikov-type set-up, there's nothing wrong with 6...[Be7] followed by ...[d6] and ..Nf6. After 6...[a5] we may though consider 7...[Qh4] if White now does something pretty slow, as well as straightforward development with 7...[Nf6].}) 7. Nc3 Bxc3 $5 {(One of two good and tempting options, forcing the pace the other is 7...a4!? when White really needs to find 8.Nd5! , with an extremely original and interesting position then arising after 8...Bd6!? ) .} 8. Bxc3 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Ga5a4,Ge8g8,Gd7d5] Black enjoys active and easy development, and can easily seize an early initiative if White is slightly careless. Of course, 9...[Nxe4] is now a threat, with all of ...[a4], ...[O-O] and ...[d5] also high on the agenda.} 9. Bc4 $5 {[%csl Re4]} (9. Bc4 {Setting a small trap:} Nxe4 $2 10. Qd5 Ng5 11. O-O-O {would give White a powerful initiative.}) 9... a4 {[%csl Gb3,Ge4]} 10. Nd2 O-O {[%cal Gd7d5,Gd7d6,Gc8e6] With ...[d5] on the way, or even ...[d6] and ...[Be6] if you prefer, Black shouldn't have any problems.} *

