1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb3 ({A fairly modest, but sensible sideline. Unlike after} 5. Nf3 {, White doesn't obstruct his kingside options and also takes control of [c5].}) 5... Bb4+ $5 {[%csl Ge1]} ({An unusual choice compared to the main line,} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 {(as covered by King and Cuenca, if also one we hope may confuse more experienced opponents who stick with 5. [Nb3] because it's solid or where they normally retreat the knight to in the Open Sicilian we did also look into 5...[a5], but couldn't see any great benefits of including that if White counters with 6.a4. Will White still go 6. [Nc3]?)}) {when Bd2 is unspectacular but fine for White,} 6. Bd2 a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5b4,Gd8h4,Gg8f6]} (6... a5 {An extremely rare advance here, if one we quite like. Actually, 7...a4 isn't really a threat, but we would be pretty happy to see} 7. Bxb4 axb4 $1 {, opening up the file for the rook on [a8] while clamping down on the white queenside.}) ({Of Black's other options,} 6... Qh4 7. Qe2 $1 {feel a little shaky, but if you don't mind a Kalashnikov-type set-up, there's nothing wrong with 6...[Be7] followed by ...[d6] and ..Nf6. After 6...[a5] we may though consider 7...[Qh4] if White now does something pretty slow, as well as straightforward development with 7...[Nf6].}) 7. a4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Ga5b4,Ge8g8,Gd7d5]} (7... Nf6 {With White having gone 6.Bd2, not 6.Nc3, the position seems fine for Black. We can still recapture with} 8. Bxb4 axb4 {and are also well enough placed in the centre, the knight supporting ...[d5] while attacking [e4].}) 8. Nc3 $5 ({A principled choice from White, and one that's more of a challenge than} 8. Bd3 d5 {, if also a move that by no means every solid 5. [Nb3] player will feel happy making.}) 8... Bxc3 {Taking up the challenge...} 9. Bxc3 Nxe4 $5 {[%cal Ge4c3]} ({Black's most ambitious choice. If this seems too much though, by all means prefer} 9... O-O 10. Bd3 d5 {, which equalises.}) 10. Qg4 $1 {[%csl Re4,Rg7] Otherwise, White would simply be a pawn down with a pretty miserable position.} d5 {Meeting aggression with counter-aggression as Black is quick to dominate the centre of the board.} 11. Qxg7 Ke7 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5][%cal Gd8b6,Gc8e6,Gh8g8]} ({A much more combative and better choice than allowing} 11... Qf6 12. Qxf6 Nxf6 13. Bb5 {. The king is actually safe enough on [e7] and Black should be OK with the big centre in this rather unbalanced and unclear position.}) (11... Ke7 {(One idea and even threat is ...Qb6, another ...Be6 and ...Rg8 may also prove quite useful, not least in the event of )} 12. Bxe5 $4 Rg8 {.}) *

