1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb3 ({A fairly modest, but sensible sideline. Unlike after} 5. Nf3 {, White doesn't obstruct his kingside options and also takes control of [c5].}) 5... Bb4+ $5 {[%csl Ge1]} ({An unusual choice compared to the main line,} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 {(as covered by King and Cuenca, if also one we hope may confuse more experienced opponents who stick with 5. [Nb3] because it's solid or where they normally retreat the knight to in the Open Sicilian we did also look into 5...[a5], but couldn't see any great benefits of including that if White counters with 6.a4. Will White still go 6. [Nc3]?)}) {when Bd2 is unspectacular but fine for White,} 6. Bd2 a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5b4,Gd8h4,Gg8f6]} (6... a5 {An extremely rare advance here, if one we quite like. Actually, 7...a4 isn't really a threat, but we would be pretty happy to see} 7. Bxb4 axb4 $1 {, opening up the file for the rook on [a8] while clamping down on the white queenside.}) ({Of Black's other options,} 6... Qh4 7. Qe2 $1 {feel a little shaky, but if you don't mind a Kalashnikov-type set-up, there's nothing wrong with 6...[Be7] followed by ...[d6] and ..Nf6. After 6...[a5] we may though consider 7...[Qh4] if White now does something pretty slow, as well as straightforward development with 7...[Nf6].}) 7. a3 {[%csl Rb4] Forcing the pace.} Bxd2+ {[%cal Gg8f6,Ga5a4,Ge8g8] Refusing to lose time with the bishop while looking to continue actively with ...[Nf6] and ...[O-O], or perhaps even ...[a4].} 8. Qxd2 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4]} 9. Nc3 a4 {[%cal Gd8b6,Ge8g8] Discombobulating. If the knight retreats, ...[Qb6] may become an issue and in any case, Black will quickly castle.} 10. Nc5 O-O $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d6,Gd6d5,Gd8a5]} (10... O-O {A dangerous and decent pawn sacrifice. The threat is} 11. Z0 d6 {, and if} 12. N5xa4 d5 {, with decent compensation. Meanwhile ... [Qa5] is imminent and 11.Qd6?! runs into 11...b6 12.N5xa4 Nxe4! .}) 11. N5xa4 d5 $1 {[%cal Gd5d4] Threatening to win a piece and the knight on [c6] may also make good use of the [d4]-square.} 12. exd5 Nd4 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Gf6d5,Ga8a4]} (12... Nd4 {We're two pawns down, but just what is that knight doing on a4? Moreover, the engines already slightly favour Black, who will be pretty active after ...Nxd5 and has an even bigger threat in} 13. Z0 Rxa4 $1 14. Nxa4 Ne4 {, overloading the white queen with decisive effect.}) *

