1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb3 ({A fairly modest, but sensible sideline. Unlike after} 5. Nf3 {, White doesn't obstruct his kingside options and also takes control of [c5].}) 5... Bb4+ $5 {[%csl Ge1]} ({An unusual choice compared to the main line,} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 {(as covered by King and Cuenca, if also one we hope may confuse more experienced opponents who stick with 5. [Nb3] because it's solid or where they normally retreat the knight to in the Open Sicilian we did also look into 5...[a5], but couldn't see any great benefits of including that if White counters with 6.a4. Will White still go 6. [Nc3]?)}) {when Bd2 is unspectacular but fine for White,} 6. Nc3 {A sensible if rare choice and now Black can transpose to the main line in practice with 6...[Nf6] or play more independently, as we'd again prefer to.} d6 {[%cal Gb4c3,Gg8f6,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Black can continue development along straightforward lines with ...[Nf6], ...[O-O] and ...[Be6] or look for more imbalance with a quick exchange on [c3], a policy now possible as after ...[Nf6] the pressure against [e4] will make it hard for White to easily go after [d6].} 7. Bc4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gb4c3,Gc8e6]} (7... Nf6 {Development with a threat, one of our favourite tools, and now} 8. Qd3 Be6 {should be fine for Black.}) 8. O-O $5 Bxc3 9. bxc3 (9. bxc3 {With the position beginning to open, we're not entirely sure about} Nxe4 $5 10. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 11. Qd5+ {here, but that's by no means a forced option.}) 9... O-O $1 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gd8c7] A prudent policy; ...[Be6] and perhaps ...[Qc7] will follow.} 10. Ba3 {[%csl Rd6]} Nxe4 {This was why the knight went to [f6] in the first place.} 11. Qd3 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ra1e1]} (11. Qd3 {Slightly tricky play from White, and it would be wise to remember here not to allow} Bf5 $2 12. Rae1 $1 {when White stands better.}) 11... Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gd6d5]} (11... Nf6 {A simple and actually fairly strong retreat. If now} 12. Qxd6 {Black can simply go} Qxd6 13. Bxd6 Rd8 {followed by ...[Bf5], with easy development and the better structure, and neither is the other capture any better for White.}) 12. Bxd6 {[%csl Rf8]} Bf5 $1 {[%csl Gd3,Gd6,Gf5]} (12... Bf5 {Discombobulating, a policy which} 13. Qd1 $2 Bxc2 $1 {would now continue, which means that White should indirectly exchange bishops, leaving Black with the superior structure and a pleasant edge.}) *

