1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb3 ({A fairly modest, but sensible sideline. Unlike after} 5. Nf3 {, White doesn't obstruct his kingside options and also takes control of [c5].}) 5... Bb4+ $5 {[%csl Ge1]} ({An unusual choice compared to the main line,} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 {(as covered by King and Cuenca, if also one we hope may confuse more experienced opponents who stick with 5. [Nb3] because it's solid or where they normally retreat the knight to in the Open Sicilian we did also look into 5...[a5], but couldn't see any great benefits of including that if White counters with 6.a4. Will White still go 6. [Nc3]?)}) {when Bd2 is unspectacular but fine for White,} 6. c3 {[%csl Rb4]} ({Driving the bishop back without delay. Both this and} 6. Bd2 {have been fairly popular in the limited over-the-board practice with 5...[Bb4]+, 6. [Nc3] notably much less so.}) 6... Be7 {[%cal Gg8f6] A prudent retreat. Black is now ready to go 7... [Nf6] followed by ...[d5] or just ...[d6] and, of course, White doesn't have [Nc3] available here.} 7. Be3 $6 {This move has also been quite popular, presumably because White wants to get the bishop out before going [N1d2], but it's a method of development which Black should be especially happy to see.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gd7d5]} (7... Nf6 {Attacking e4 and supporting the key pawn break, once again, and here} 8. Bc4 $6 Nxe4 $1 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. Qd5+ Ke8 11. Qxe4 d5 {would already be pretty good for Black.}) 8. N1d2 d5 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gd5e3,Gd5e4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Black threatens to take on [e4], while being ready to continue development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} 9. Qc2 $6 d4 $1 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gd4e3]} (9... d4 {A powerful advance to exploit the position of the queen on c2 and now} 10. Bg5 O-O {would be very pleasant for White, but better that for White than disturbing the central status quo.}) 10. cxd4 $2 exd4 {[%cal Gd4e3]} 11. Bg5 Nb4 $1 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gd4d3]} (11... Nb4 {All of a sudden, White faces grave difficulties on the light squares, including after} 12. Qd1 d3 {.}) 12. Bb5+ {[%csl Re8]} Bd7 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {[%cal Gd7b5,Gb4c2,Ga8c8]} (13... Qxd7 {With ...Qb5 on the way to prevent White from castling and} 14. Qc4 {running into} Rc8 {, White was already pretty much lost in Djakovic-Voiska, Kragujevac 2015.}) *

