1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb3 ({A fairly modest, but sensible sideline. Unlike after} 5. Nf3 {, White doesn't obstruct his kingside options and also takes control of [c5].}) 5... Bb4+ $5 {[%csl Ge1]} ({An unusual choice compared to the main line,} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 {(as covered by King and Cuenca, if also one we hope may confuse more experienced opponents who stick with 5. [Nb3] because it's solid or where they normally retreat the knight to in the Open Sicilian we did also look into 5...[a5], but couldn't see any great benefits of including that if White counters with 6.a4. Will White still go 6. [Nc3]?)}) {when Bd2 is unspectacular but fine for White,} 6. c3 {[%csl Rb4]} ({Driving the bishop back without delay. Both this and} 6. Bd2 {have been fairly popular in the limited over-the-board practice with 5...[Bb4]+, 6. [Nc3] notably much less so.}) 6... Be7 {[%cal Gg8f6] A prudent retreat. Black is now ready to go 7... [Nf6] followed by ...[d5] or just ...[d6] and, of course, White doesn't have [Nc3] available here.} 7. Be3 $6 {This move has also been quite popular, presumably because White wants to get the bishop out before going [N1d2], but it's a method of development which Black should be especially happy to see.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gd7d5]} (7... Nf6 {Attacking e4 and supporting the key pawn break, once again, and here} 8. Bc4 $6 Nxe4 $1 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. Qd5+ Ke8 11. Qxe4 d5 {would already be pretty good for Black.}) 8. N1d2 d5 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gd5e3,Gd5e4,Gc8e6,Ge8g8] Black threatens to take on [e4], while being ready to continue development with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6].} 9. exd5 Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5e3] Threatening to acquire the bishop-pair, with a pleasant edge.} 10. Bc5 $6 {An understandable move, but only serves to make matters even worse for White.} O-O {[%cal Ge7c5,Gd5f4] Getting the king to safety ahead of planning to seize the initiative with 11...Bxc5 12.Nxc5 Nf4 .} 11. Bxe7 {[%csl Rd8]} Qxe7 12. Bc4 Be6 $1 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gf7f5]} ({Making way for the rook on d8 is even better than} 12... Nf4 13. Qf3 {. White's knights aren't at all well placed and Black will enjoy a very pleasant advantage after 13...[Rad8] and 14...[f5].}) *

