1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb3 ({A fairly modest, but sensible sideline. Unlike after} 5. Nf3 {, White doesn't obstruct his kingside options and also takes control of [c5].}) 5... Bb4+ $5 {[%csl Ge1]} ({An unusual choice compared to the main line,} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 {(as covered by King and Cuenca, if also one we hope may confuse more experienced opponents who stick with 5. [Nb3] because it's solid or where they normally retreat the knight to in the Open Sicilian we did also look into 5...[a5], but couldn't see any great benefits of including that if White counters with 6.a4. Will White still go 6. [Nc3]?)}) {when Bd2 is unspectacular but fine for White,} 6. c3 {[%csl Rb4]} ({Driving the bishop back without delay. Both this and} 6. Bd2 {have been fairly popular in the limited over-the-board practice with 5...[Bb4]+, 6. [Nc3] notably much less so.}) 6... Be7 {[%cal Gg8f6] A prudent retreat. Black is now ready to go 7... [Nf6] followed by ...[d5] or just ...[d6] and, of course, White doesn't have [Nc3] available here.} 7. c4 {Setting up a Maroczy Bind while facilitating [Nc3] feels sensible, if it's also a policy which Black should certainly not fear.} Nf6 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf6e4,Ge7b4,Ga7a5,Ga5a4] Our familiar attack on [e4] and as well as being able to castle, Black may be able to quickly return the bishop to [b4] and/or disrupt with the a-pawn after all.} 8. Nc3 Bb4 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gb4c3] Renewing the threat while threatening to double White's pawns. Black surely has nothing to fear here.} 9. Bg5 $6 h6 {[%csl Gg5]} (9... h6 {Another familiar motif, quickly challenging the bishop and, yes,} 10. Bh4 {can be met by} g5 {.}) 10. Bxf6 {We've followed the game Zvan-Sveshnikov, Nova Gorica 1998, where it seems that the great Sicilian authority could have done even better than double White's pawns.} Qxf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6g6,Gc6d4,Gd7d6,Gb4c3] Black can already hope to seize the initiative here after a quick ...[Nd4] or ...[Qg6], while also only wanting to take on [c3] when after ...[Bxc3]+; [bxc3] there's ...[d6] before White can get in [c4]-[c5].} 11. Qd3 d6 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gf6g6,Gc6d4] Taking control of [c5], while freeing a path for the bishop on [c8], ahead of aiming for more with ... [Qg6] or ...[Nd4].} 12. Be2 Nd4 $1 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Ge5d4]} (12... Nd4 {Black is definitely for choice, as castling would walk into an exchange on c3, while} 13. Nxd4 exd4 {would exploit the pin on the [e1]-[a5] diagonal.}) *

