1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb3 ({A fairly modest, but sensible sideline. Unlike after} 5. Nf3 {, White doesn't obstruct his kingside options and also takes control of [c5].}) 5... Bb4+ $5 {[%csl Ge1]} ({An unusual choice compared to the main line,} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 {(as covered by King and Cuenca, if also one we hope may confuse more experienced opponents who stick with 5. [Nb3] because it's solid or where they normally retreat the knight to in the Open Sicilian we did also look into 5...[a5], but couldn't see any great benefits of including that if White counters with 6.a4. Will White still go 6. [Nc3]?)}) {when Bd2 is unspectacular but fine for White,} 6. c3 {[%csl Rb4]} ({Driving the bishop back without delay. Both this and} 6. Bd2 {have been fairly popular in the limited over-the-board practice with 5...[Bb4]+, 6. [Nc3] notably much less so.}) 6... Be7 {[%cal Gg8f6] A prudent retreat. Black is now ready to go 7... [Nf6] followed by ...[d5] or just ...[d6] and, of course, White doesn't have [Nc3] available here.} 7. Bc4 {The most aggressive square for the bishop and the most popular move here, presumably partly because it's how plenty of white players are used to following up 5.Nb3 , i.e. with 5...Nf6 6.Nc3 Bb4 7.Bc4!? , gambitting the e-pawn for the initiative.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4]} (7... Nf6 {Thematic development and Black is now again ready to go} 8. Z0 Nxe4 {, and if} 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. Qd5+ Ke8 11. Qxe4 d5 {when the strong centre and bishop-pair will more than offset the loss of castling rights.}) 8. Qd3 {Probably White's best move, defending [e4] while maintaining a clamp on the [d5]-square.} d6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gd6d5] Black wastes no time looking to challenge light-squared bishops with ...[Be6], then get the key ...[d5] break in, one which may well leave the white knights looking a little offside.} 9. Bg5 (9. Bg5 {Continuing to fight for control of d5 and now} Nd7 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {was about equal in Papastavropoulos-Skembris, Greek Championship, Athens 1988, where Black might have been more ambitious.}) 9... a6 $5 {[%cal Gf6e4] Refusing to fear an exchange on [f6] while actually threatening not only ...[b5], but 10...[Nxe4].} 10. a4 {Ruling out ...[b5], but allow Black to execute the main idea.} Nxe4 $1 {[%csl Gg5] Pretty much forcing White's reply.} 11. Bxe7 Nxe7 {[%csl Gb5] And now we can see why 9... [a6] was so useful: there's no [Bb5]+ to win a piece.} 12. Qxe4 d5 {[%cal Gd5c4,Gd5e4]} 13. Qxe5 dxc4 {[%cal Gc4b3,Ge8g8,Gh8f8,Gf8e8]} (13... dxc4 {Black has successfully unbalanced the position and is at least OK here, with ...O-O and ...Re8 set to follow, that is unless White prefers to lose a piece after} 14. Qxg7 $4 Rg8 15. Qxh7 cxb3 {.}) *

