1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {This direct central challenge dates back to the McDonnell-de la Bourdonnais matches of 1834. You may well have seen a certain 16th game with it think of the three connected passed black pawns!, and the move also appealed to Howard Staunton before being taken up by Johann Löwenthal 1810–1876, a world-class Hungarian-British player.} 5. Nb3 ({A fairly modest, but sensible sideline. Unlike after} 5. Nf3 {, White doesn't obstruct his kingside options and also takes control of [c5].}) 5... Bb4+ $5 {[%csl Ge1]} ({An unusual choice compared to the main line,} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 {(as covered by King and Cuenca, if also one we hope may confuse more experienced opponents who stick with 5. [Nb3] because it's solid or where they normally retreat the knight to in the Open Sicilian we did also look into 5...[a5], but couldn't see any great benefits of including that if White counters with 6.a4. Will White still go 6. [Nc3]?)}) {when Bd2 is unspectacular but fine for White,} 6. c3 {[%csl Rb4]} ({Driving the bishop back without delay. Both this and} 6. Bd2 {have been fairly popular in the limited over-the-board practice with 5...[Bb4]+, 6. [Nc3] notably much less so.}) 6... Be7 {[%cal Gg8f6] A prudent retreat. Black is now ready to go 7... [Nf6] followed by ...[d5] or just ...[d6] and, of course, White doesn't have [Nc3] available here.} 7. Bc4 {The most aggressive square for the bishop and the most popular move here, presumably partly because it's how plenty of white players are used to following up 5.Nb3 , i.e. with 5...Nf6 6.Nc3 Bb4 7.Bc4!? , gambitting the e-pawn for the initiative.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4]} (7... Nf6 {Thematic development and Black is now again ready to go} 8. Z0 Nxe4 {, and if} 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. Qd5+ Ke8 11. Qxe4 d5 {when the strong centre and bishop-pair will more than offset the loss of castling rights.}) 8. Qd3 {Probably White's best move, defending [e4] while maintaining a clamp on the [d5]-square.} d6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gd6d5] Black wastes no time looking to challenge light-squared bishops with ...[Be6], then get the key ...[d5] break in, one which may well leave the white knights looking a little offside.} 9. Bg5 (9. Bg5 {Continuing to fight for control of d5 and now} Nd7 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {was about equal in Papastavropoulos-Skembris, Greek Championship, Athens 1988, where Black might have been more ambitious.}) 9... a6 $5 {[%cal Gf6e4] Refusing to fear an exchange on [f6] while actually threatening not only ...[b5], but 10...[Nxe4].} 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 {[%cal Gc6e7,Gb7b5,Ge8g8] Not only is Black ready to castle, but also to compete for control of the key [d5] point with ...[Ne7] ahead of getting in ...[b5].} 11. N3d2 $5 {Freeing a retreat path for the bishop on [c4] and perhaps hoping to bring the knight round to [e3] one day.} b5 $5 {[%cal Gb5c4]} ({A provocative advance, and you may prefer to play it safe with the perfectly respectable} 11... O-O {.}) 12. Bd5 Qd7 $1 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gc6e7,Ge8g8,Gf6g5]} ({A much better policy than allowing} 12... Bb7 $2 13. a4 {. Now 13.a4 Rb8 will secure [b5] and leave Black set to untangle with ...[Ne7]. The resulting unbalanced position should be dynamic enough for Black, who may castle and play for .... [d5] and/or look to activate the bishop on [f6] via [g5].}) *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7A) Fourth moves alternatives"]
[Black "4.Bc4 Nf6 5.Nxd4"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "18"]
[GameId "2141525861975435"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. Bc4 $2 {Perhaps the odd Sicilian Sozin player 6. [Bc4] against the Classical Sicilian and Najdorf might consider this, but it's simply not very good.} Nf6 $1 {[%csl Gd8,Ge1,Ge5][%cal Gf6e4]} (4... Nf6 {Unfortunately for White,} 5. e5 $2 {would now run into} Nxe5 $1 6. Nxe5 Qa5+ {and it's also hard to view 5.Qe2 e6 as being especially impressive for the first player. Perhaps they would thus try to bluff their way into an Open Sicilian after all.}) 5. Nxd4 $5 {[%cal Rb1c3]} Nxe4 $1 {Refusing to be move ordered and allow White to defend [e4] with 6. [Nc3]. Instead, we pick off the hanging pawn and threaten ...[d5], which only really leaves White with one fairly desperate try.} (5... Nxe4 6. Nxc6 $2 bxc6 {would leave Black in control of [d5], as does 6.O-O e6 when White has very little to show for the pawn.}) 6. Bxf7+ $5 {[%csl Re8]} Kxf7 7. Qh5+ {[%csl Rf6,Gg8]} (7. Qh5+ {The point is clear: a check on d5. However, Black is currently a piece up, so we should be quite happy to allow the check and definitely not go in for} Kf6 $4 8. Qf5# {.}) 7... Kg8 {[%cal Ge7e6] The king will be quite safe here and the central majority will be quick to make its presence felt after 8...[e6].} 8. Qd5+ {[%csl Rg8]} e6 9. Qxe4 d5 {[%csl Gc8,Gf8][%cal Gb7c6,Ge6e5] Expanding with tempo and ...[e5] is likely to quickly follow, whether or not White exchanges knights on [c6]. With a handy central majority and the two bishops, Black must be at least pleasantly slightly for choice.} *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7A) Fourth moves alternatives"]
[Black "4.c3 dxc3 5.Bc4"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "20"]
[GameId "2141525862045068"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 $5 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Bc4 $6 {This double Danish-style gambit is occasionally seen at blitz, but Black shouldn't mind being offered a second pawn.} cxb2 {[%cal Gb2a1]} 6. Bxb2 d6 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gg8f6,Ge7e6,Gc8g4] Just as in our main line, Black is likely to find ...[a6] then ...[Nf6] useful moves, after which ...[e6], before or after ...[Bg4], will help us to complete development.} 7. O-O a6 ({It should be said that} 7... Nf6 {is actually a decent move here, but taking control of [b5] and learning to go ...[a6] before ...[Nf6] against the Morra is no bad thing.}) 8. Qe2 $5 (8. Qe2 {White gets ready to meet} Nf6 {with} 9. Rd1 {, menacing [e4]-[e5], so here Black should change tack slightly.}) 8... e6 {[%csl Gc4] Shutting down any tricks for now on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} 9. Rd1 Na5 $5 {[%csl Gb5,Gc4] Challenging an important piece in the Morra, one which White usually wants to retain, and note too here how ...[a6] is already proving its worth.} 10. Bd3 Ne7 $1 {[%cal Ge7c6,Ge6e5,Gf8e7,Ge8g8]} ({Here rather than} 10... Nf6 $2 11. e5 {. Exploiting the absence of a white b-pawn, the king's knight heads for [c6], after which ...[e5] will usefully close the long, dark-square diagonal, enabling Black to complete development with ...[Be7] and ...[O-O]. The knight on [a5] is a little cumbersome, but that shouldn't give White enough for two pawns, especially as Black can always return one of them if needed, such as with ...[b5] and ...[Nc4] or ...[e5] and ...[Nd4].}) *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7A) Fourth moves alternatives"]
[Black "4.c3 dxc3 5.Nxc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B21"]
[PlyCount "30"]
[GameId "2141525862069645"]

1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 $5 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Nxc3 {Standard Morra fare.} d6 {[%csl Gc8] A standard Sicilian move, as well as one which frees the light-squared bishop for duty.} 6. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7] The best diagonal for this bishop and now Black must be wary of tricks which exploit the potential weakness of [f7].} a6 $1 {[%cal Gg8f6] Recommended by Joe Gallagher way back in 1994 in his classic work Beating the Anti-Sicilians, the first such repertoire for Black, this line has stood the test of time. It's certainly served Richard well over the years, both over the board and being his primary recommendation against the Smith-Morra when he wrote Fighting the Anti-Sicilians.} ({It should be said that the point of} 6... a6 {is prophylactic, and not to prepare a quick ...[b5]. The problem with 6...Bg4? is 7.Bxf7+! and the issue with 6...Nf6?! , to prepare said ...[Bg4], is 7.e5! , and if 7...dxe5?! 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5 . As such, Black first takes control of [b5] to facilitate 7...[Nf6] then ideally 8...[Bg4].}) 7. Bg5 $5 {Recommended by Hannes Langrock in The Modern Morra Gambit, and an attempt to inflict some structural damage on Black.} Nf6 {[%cal Gg7f6]} (7... Nf6 {We should not be afraid of the exchange on f6 and, instead,} 8. O-O e6 {will be covered via a 7.O-O Nf6 8.Bg5 e6 move order.}) 8. Bxf6 gxf6 $1 {[%cal Ge7e6] The correct recapture, keeping the e-pawn to close down the bishop on [c4]. The resulting structure is reminiscent of Richter-Rauzer lines of the Classical Sicilian, except that here Black is a pawn ahead.} 9. Nh4 $6 e6 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gb7b5,Gc8d7,Ga8c8] Blocking out the bishop on [c4] and Black may even now be able to consider ideas of ...[b5], as well as of ...[Bd7] and ...[Rc8].} 10. Qh5 $6 {The point of White's play and a bold raid he'd love to make work, but unfortunately for him, Black has a strong reply.} Qa5 $1 {[%cal Ga5h5,Gc6a5,Gb7b5]} (10... Qa5 {Of course, White doesn't want to exchange queens having gambitted a pawn and} 11. Qe2 b5 {would leave Black in the driver's seat, if better that for White than throwing more wood on to the fire.}) 11. Nf5 $2 {[%csl Rf7]} Ne5 $1 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Ge5c4,Ge6f5] Covering [f7] while attacking the attacker on [c4].} 12. Bb3 exf5 13. O-O {This was all seen in Marciniak-Bricard, Condom 2004, and here Richard's old analysis still seems to be holding up.} fxe4 $5 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8d8,Gc8g4] Black avoids any ideas of [exf5] in conjunction with [f2]-[f4] and is now ready to go 14...[Be7] or even 14... [Bg4] and 15...[O-O], while the king will be safe enough on [d8].} 14. Bxf7+ $5 {[%csl Ra5,Re5,Rh5]} Kd8 15. Nxe4 Be7 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gd8c7,Gc7b8] With ...[Bg4] and/ or ...[Kc7]-[b8] on the way, White surely doesn't have anything like enough for the piece.} *

