1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 $5 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Nxc3 {Standard Morra fare.} d6 {[%csl Gc8] A standard Sicilian move, as well as one which frees the light-squared bishop for duty.} 6. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7] The best diagonal for this bishop and now Black must be wary of tricks which exploit the potential weakness of [f7].} a6 $1 {[%cal Gg8f6] Recommended by Joe Gallagher way back in 1994 in his classic work Beating the Anti-Sicilians, the first such repertoire for Black, this line has stood the test of time. It's certainly served Richard well over the years, both over the board and being his primary recommendation against the Smith-Morra when he wrote Fighting the Anti-Sicilians.} ({It should be said that the point of} 6... a6 {is prophylactic, and not to prepare a quick ...[b5]. The problem with 6...Bg4? is 7.Bxf7+! and the issue with 6...Nf6?! , to prepare said ...[Bg4], is 7.e5! , and if 7...dxe5?! 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5 . As such, Black first takes control of [b5] to facilitate 7...[Nf6] then ideally 8...[Bg4].}) 7. Bg5 $5 {Recommended by Hannes Langrock in The Modern Morra Gambit, and an attempt to inflict some structural damage on Black.} Nf6 {[%cal Gg7f6]} (7... Nf6 {We should not be afraid of the exchange on f6 and, instead,} 8. O-O e6 {will be covered via a 7.O-O Nf6 8.Bg5 e6 move order.}) 8. Bxf6 gxf6 $1 {[%cal Ge7e6] The correct recapture, keeping the e-pawn to close down the bishop on [c4]. The resulting structure is reminiscent of Richter-Rauzer lines of the Classical Sicilian, except that here Black is a pawn ahead.} 9. O-O {Straightforward play.} e6 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gf8e7,Gf8g7,Ge8g8,Gh7h5] Once again, a useful move, if not from the perspective of the bishop on [c4]. Black may now continue solidly with ...[Bd7] and ...[Be7] or even try to get the king to safety via ...[Bg7] and ...[O-O]. If the former plan is followed, ...[h5] may well prove a useful space-gainer, ruling out [Qh5] from White for good while claiming some space.} (9... e6 {Indeed, if now} 10. Nh4 {then} h5 {would be a decent response.}) 10. Nd4 {White tries to play actively, freeing the f-pawn for duty, while hoping to land a blow on [e6] at some stage soon.} (10. Qd2 Bd7 {Ever a useful development move in this structure, as well as quite a flexible one. Black may continue with any or all of ...[Rc8], ...[Qa5] and ...[Ne5], and note too that it's far from easy to come up with a great plan for White, so solid is the black set-up.} 11. Qf4 Ne5 {((Activating the knight with tempo and now 12.Nxe5? fxe5 would only serve to make Black's central preponderance even stronger.))} 12. Be2 h5 $1 {This powerful advance left Black able to consider seizing the initiative with ... [Bh6] and ...[h4], as well as clearly for choice in Robertson-Rowson, Scottish Championship, Largs 1998.}) 10... Nxd4 ({Swapping off the knight on d4, in the process deflecting the white queen from her journey to h5, is a sensible approach. Other moves which you may wish to explore are} 10... Qb6 {and 10...h5!? .}) 11. Qxd4 Bd7 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gf8e7]} ({It's rarely a bad idea to prioritise queenside development in this structure, and we prefer this to the} 11... Be7 12. f4 Qa5 {of Lower-Wharton, Tucson 2010, where} 13. b4 $1 {would have thrown a small spanner in the works. After 11...[Bd7] we're ready to go 12...[Rc8] and only maybe then ... [Be7].}) 12. f4 Rc8 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Gf8,Gg1][%cal Gd6d5] With the not insignificant threat of ...[d5].} 13. Kh1 Be7 {[%cal Gd8a5,Ga5c5,Ga5e5,Ge8g8,Gg8h8,Gh8f8,Gf8g8] Black's position remains pretty solid and while White has an active-looking set-up, we'd be surprised if he had enough for the pawn and bishop-pair. As Black, ...[Qa5] is likely to be a useful move, heading for [c5] or even [e5] in the event of [f4]-[f5]. You may even follow up with ...[h5] and leaving the king in the centre if you wish.The alternative, very Richter-Rauzer plan is to go ...[O-O], ...[Kh8] and ...[Rg7], when there will always be ...[Rg7], if necessary, to help defend [h7].} *

