1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 $5 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Nxc3 {Standard Morra fare.} d6 {[%csl Gc8] A standard Sicilian move, as well as one which frees the light-squared bishop for duty.} 6. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7] The best diagonal for this bishop and now Black must be wary of tricks which exploit the potential weakness of [f7].} a6 $1 {[%cal Gg8f6] Recommended by Joe Gallagher way back in 1994 in his classic work Beating the Anti-Sicilians, the first such repertoire for Black, this line has stood the test of time. It's certainly served Richard well over the years, both over the board and being his primary recommendation against the Smith-Morra when he wrote Fighting the Anti-Sicilians.} ({It should be said that the point of} 6... a6 {is prophylactic, and not to prepare a quick ...[b5]. The problem with 6...Bg4? is 7.Bxf7+! and the issue with 6...Nf6?! , to prepare said ...[Bg4], is 7.e5! , and if 7...dxe5?! 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5 . As such, Black first takes control of [b5] to facilitate 7...[Nf6] then ideally 8...[Bg4].}) 7. e5 $5 {[%csl Re5]} (7. e5 {This direct try is a fairly new white weapon against the ...d6 and ...a6 defence, and one we should take seriously. It's been used on a few occasions with success by American GM Aleks Lenderman and hopes for the obvious} dxe5 $2 {when} 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 $2 9. Nd5 {is already extremely dangerous for Black.}) 7... e6 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5][%cal Gc6e5,Gd6d5] A semi-refutation, closing the [a2]-[g8] diagonal, threatening ...[d5], as well as to take on [e5] and leaving White with little better than to exchange on [d6].} 8. exd6 Bxd6 {[%cal Gg8f6,Ge8g8] Not forced, but an active and good recapture: ... [Nf6] and ..O-O will follow, when Black won't be too far behind in the development stakes.} 9. O-O Nf6 10. Qe2 O-O {[%cal Gh7h6,Gd6e7]} (10... O-O {Plan complete and now} 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bh4 Be7 $1 {followed by ...[Qb6] kept everything tight and Black better in Lenderman-Michelakos, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2022.}) 11. Rd1 {[%cal Rc1f4]} Qc7 {Wisely stepping off the d-file and out of the way of [Bf4].} 12. Bg5 Be7 $1 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gb7b5,Gf8d8] Ever the right response to [Bg5] in this sub-variation. Black is now ready to challenge the bishop on [g5] with ...[h6], as well as challenge the d-file with ...[Rd8] and/or expand with ...[b5]. White's compensation was already in danger of fizzling out in Lenderman-Sharifov, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2022, where Black went on to pull off a rating upset.} *

