1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 $5 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Nxc3 {Standard Morra fare.} d6 {[%csl Gc8] A standard Sicilian move, as well as one which frees the light-squared bishop for duty.} 6. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7] The best diagonal for this bishop and now Black must be wary of tricks which exploit the potential weakness of [f7].} a6 $1 {[%cal Gg8f6] Recommended by Joe Gallagher way back in 1994 in his classic work Beating the Anti-Sicilians, the first such repertoire for Black, this line has stood the test of time. It's certainly served Richard well over the years, both over the board and being his primary recommendation against the Smith-Morra when he wrote Fighting the Anti-Sicilians.} ({It should be said that the point of} 6... a6 {is prophylactic, and not to prepare a quick ...[b5]. The problem with 6...Bg4? is 7.Bxf7+! and the issue with 6...Nf6?! , to prepare said ...[Bg4], is 7.e5! , and if 7...dxe5?! 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5 . As such, Black first takes control of [b5] to facilitate 7...[Nf6] then ideally 8...[Bg4].}) 7. O-O ({Invariably played, continuing the standard Morra development scheme. Instead,} 7. Bf4 Nf6 {would prepare 8...[Bg4] and we'll see} 8. O-O {by transposition in Chapter 7d, but there are a couple of other seventh moves which Black should be ready for.}) 7... Nf6 {Continuing the standard development plan. Left unopposed, Black is likely to continue with 8...[Bg4] and only then complete kingside development with ...[e6] and ...[Be7].} (7... Nf6 {Here we'll focus on White's three main tries:} 8. Qe2 {, 8.h3 and 8.Bf4 . That leaves a few options, of which perhaps the trickiest to face is a second gambit.}) 8. Bg5 e6 $1 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gf8e7] A good approach here, preparing to break the pin and develop with ...[Be7] or even challenge the pinning bishop with ...[h6] now that the queen can recapture on [f6].} ({You may wonder: why not} 8... Bg4 $2 {The problem here is that} 9. Qb3 {is an annoying response, attacking both [f7] and [b7], and Black doesn't have anything amazing after} e6 10. Qxb7 $1 Na5 11. Qb4 {.}) 9. Qe2 {White continues with standard Morra development.} h6 $5 {[%csl Gg5] There's nothing wrong with placing the bishops on [e7] and [d7], but Black has scored well with this more dynamic approach.} 10. Bh4 $2 g5 $1 {[%csl Gh4] A powerful advance. Suddenly Black is going to secure all the dark squares, as well as an extra pawn.} 11. Bg3 Nh5 {[%cal Gh5g3,Gg5g4,Gh6h5] The simple and strong plan is to exchange on [g3] then advance the h- and g-pawns.} 12. Rad1 Nxg3 13. hxg3 (13. hxg3 {Here} Qf6 $6 14. e5 $1 {wasn't completely clear in Costa-Gallagher, Lisbon 2000, but Black can do much better than that.}) 13... h5 $1 {[%csl Gf8][%cal Gg5g4,Gc6e5]} (13... h5 {This left Black fully in charge in Garcia Serrano-Alvarez Serrano, Madrid 2017, with} 14. Z0 g4 {next up and after} 15. Nd4 {or 15.Nh4 , 15...Ne5 , leaving White without any real play and rather weak on the dark squares.}) *

