1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 $5 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Nxc3 {Standard Morra fare.} d6 {[%csl Gc8] A standard Sicilian move, as well as one which frees the light-squared bishop for duty.} 6. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7] The best diagonal for this bishop and now Black must be wary of tricks which exploit the potential weakness of [f7].} a6 $1 {[%cal Gg8f6] Recommended by Joe Gallagher way back in 1994 in his classic work Beating the Anti-Sicilians, the first such repertoire for Black, this line has stood the test of time. It's certainly served Richard well over the years, both over the board and being his primary recommendation against the Smith-Morra when he wrote Fighting the Anti-Sicilians.} ({It should be said that the point of} 6... a6 {is prophylactic, and not to prepare a quick ...[b5]. The problem with 6...Bg4? is 7.Bxf7+! and the issue with 6...Nf6?! , to prepare said ...[Bg4], is 7.e5! , and if 7...dxe5?! 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5 . As such, Black first takes control of [b5] to facilitate 7...[Nf6] then ideally 8...[Bg4].}) 7. O-O ({Invariably played, continuing the standard Morra development scheme. Instead,} 7. Bf4 Nf6 {would prepare 8...[Bg4] and we'll see} 8. O-O {by transposition in Chapter 7d, but there are a couple of other seventh moves which Black should be ready for.}) 7... Nf6 {Continuing the standard development plan. Left unopposed, Black is likely to continue with 8...[Bg4] and only then complete kingside development with ...[e6] and ...[Be7].} (7... Nf6 {Here we'll focus on White's three main tries:} 8. Qe2 {, 8.h3 and 8.Bf4 . That leaves a few options, of which perhaps the trickiest to face is a second gambit.}) 8. Bg5 e6 $1 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gf8e7] A good approach here, preparing to break the pin and develop with ...[Be7] or even challenge the pinning bishop with ...[h6] now that the queen can recapture on [f6].} ({You may wonder: why not} 8... Bg4 $2 {The problem here is that} 9. Qb3 {is an annoying response, attacking both [f7] and [b7], and Black doesn't have anything amazing after} e6 10. Qxb7 $1 Na5 11. Qb4 {.}) 9. Qe2 {White continues with standard Morra development.} h6 $5 {[%csl Gg5] There's nothing wrong with placing the bishops on [e7] and [d7], but Black has scored well with this more dynamic approach.} 10. Bf4 {Probably best, if a move which also hasn't seemed at all obvious to plenty of Richard's opponents.} g5 $5 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gg5f4,Gf6g4,Gf6h5]} (10... g5 {Even here the advance is possible and now, as we've seen via a 10.Bh4 move order,} 11. Bg3 $2 Nh5 {would be very promising for Black and 11.Be3 Ng4 followed by ...[Bg7] was also quite pleasant in Mayerhofer-J.Horvath, Aschach 2011.}) 11. e5 $1 {[%csl Rf6]} (11. e5 {A critical response and now} gxf4 12. exf6 Qxf6 13. Nd5 $1 Qd8 14. Nxf4 {gave White some pressure and compensation in Ask-Jansson, Stockholm 2013.}) 11... Nh5 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Gf4][%cal Gg5g4] This looks like a small improvement for Black, playing against the bishop and the pawn on [e5].} 12. Be3 dxe5 {The simplest approach, as well as one which firmly clamps down on the [f4]-square.} 13. Rfd1 Qc7 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gh5f4] The safest square for the queen. Black's kingside is a little airy, but two pawns are two pawns and with ...[Be7] and ...[Nf4] on their way, we'd be surprised if White had enough compensation.} *

