1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 $5 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Nxc3 {Standard Morra fare.} d6 {[%csl Gc8] A standard Sicilian move, as well as one which frees the light-squared bishop for duty.} 6. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7] The best diagonal for this bishop and now Black must be wary of tricks which exploit the potential weakness of [f7].} a6 $1 {[%cal Gg8f6] Recommended by Joe Gallagher way back in 1994 in his classic work Beating the Anti-Sicilians, the first such repertoire for Black, this line has stood the test of time. It's certainly served Richard well over the years, both over the board and being his primary recommendation against the Smith-Morra when he wrote Fighting the Anti-Sicilians.} ({It should be said that the point of} 6... a6 {is prophylactic, and not to prepare a quick ...[b5]. The problem with 6...Bg4? is 7.Bxf7+! and the issue with 6...Nf6?! , to prepare said ...[Bg4], is 7.e5! , and if 7...dxe5?! 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5 . As such, Black first takes control of [b5] to facilitate 7...[Nf6] then ideally 8...[Bg4].}) 7. O-O ({Invariably played, continuing the standard Morra development scheme. Instead,} 7. Bf4 Nf6 {would prepare 8...[Bg4] and we'll see} 8. O-O {by transposition in Chapter 7d, but there are a couple of other seventh moves which Black should be ready for.}) 7... Nf6 {Continuing the standard development plan. Left unopposed, Black is likely to continue with 8...[Bg4] and only then complete kingside development with ...[e6] and ...[Be7].} (7... Nf6 {Here we'll focus on White's three main tries:} 8. Qe2 {, 8.h3 and 8.Bf4 . That leaves a few options, of which perhaps the trickiest to face is a second gambit.}) 8. Be3 (8. Be3 {This develops a piece and hopes for} Bg4 9. Qb3 e6 10. Nd4 $1 {, but it's not too clear what else the move achieves if Black keeps things tight.}) 8... e6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gc8d7,Ge8g8] Straightforward play. Black will now continue development with ...[Be7], ...[Bd7] and ...[O-O].} 9. Qe2 Be7 10. Rfd1 {[%cal Re4e5]} (10. Rfd1 {A fairly standard Morra ploy from White, menacing e4-e5. There was nothing wrong now with} Bd7 11. Bf4 e5 {in Mosadeghpour-Konguvel, Mumbai 2019, but Black can even try to do without being forced to weaken slightly with ...[e5].}) 10... Qa5 $5 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc8d7] We're now all set to complete development with ...[O-O] and ...[Bd7], and are also ready to deal with any assault on [d6].} 11. Bf4 {[%cal Rf4d6]} Ne5 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Gd6][%cal Ge8g8] A key resource, shutting down lines while tickling the bishop on [c4].} 12. Nxe5 dxe5 {[%cal Ge5f4]} 13. Bd2 {[%csl Ra5]} Qc7 $1 {[%cal Gc8d7] Keeping the queen safe and here White isn't quite in time to cause any problems for her down the c-file.} 14. Rac1 Bd7 {[%cal Gc7b8,Ga8c8,Gd7c6] White lacks a tactical blow and Black will be able to meet any bishop or knight retreat with either 15...[Bc6] or 15...[Qb8], while if White proceeds more slowly there may even be time for 15...[Rc8].} *

