1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 $5 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Nxc3 {Standard Morra fare.} d6 {[%csl Gc8] A standard Sicilian move, as well as one which frees the light-squared bishop for duty.} 6. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7] The best diagonal for this bishop and now Black must be wary of tricks which exploit the potential weakness of [f7].} a6 $1 {[%cal Gg8f6] Recommended by Joe Gallagher way back in 1994 in his classic work Beating the Anti-Sicilians, the first such repertoire for Black, this line has stood the test of time. It's certainly served Richard well over the years, both over the board and being his primary recommendation against the Smith-Morra when he wrote Fighting the Anti-Sicilians.} ({It should be said that the point of} 6... a6 {is prophylactic, and not to prepare a quick ...[b5]. The problem with 6...Bg4? is 7.Bxf7+! and the issue with 6...Nf6?! , to prepare said ...[Bg4], is 7.e5! , and if 7...dxe5?! 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5 . As such, Black first takes control of [b5] to facilitate 7...[Nf6] then ideally 8...[Bg4].}) 7. O-O ({Invariably played, continuing the standard Morra development scheme. Instead,} 7. Bf4 Nf6 {would prepare 8...[Bg4] and we'll see} 8. O-O {by transposition in Chapter 7d, but there are a couple of other seventh moves which Black should be ready for.}) 7... Nf6 {Continuing the standard development plan. Left unopposed, Black is likely to continue with 8...[Bg4] and only then complete kingside development with ...[e6] and ...[Be7].} (7... Nf6 {Here we'll focus on White's three main tries:} 8. Qe2 {, 8.h3 and 8.Bf4 . That leaves a few options, of which perhaps the trickiest to face is a second gambit.}) 8. b4 $5 {[%csl Rb4] The aforementioned gambit as White aims to distract with a quick [b4]-[b5].} Bg4 $5 ({Meeting activity with counter-activity. We should avoid against} 8... Nxb4 $2 9. e5 $1 {as Black, but as well as the text move, with the positional threat of 9... [Bxf3], there's absolutely nothing wrong with 8...e6 followed by ...[Be7].}) 9. b5 {[%csl Rc6]} axb5 $5 {[%csl Gc4]} ({Simple and likely best. Richard used to prefer} 9... Bxf3 {, but it does now seem that the complications after} 10. gxf3 $1 axb5 11. Nxb5 {may be slightly in White's favour.}) 10. Bxb5 {[%cal Re4e5]} Nd7 $5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Ge8g8]} ({A new idea, regaining control of e5. Instead,} 10... e6 {allows White reasonable compensation after} 11. h3 {or 11.e5 , although as well as the text move, 10...g6 also offers Black chances to emerge with the upper hand. After 10...Nd7 , Black is ready to obtain a very comfortable Dragon set-up with 11...[g6] and 12...[Bg7], one where White would also, of course, be a pawn down, so he should probably try to play quite actively here.}) 11. Nd5 $5 {[%cal Rc1b2]} (11. Nd5 {This prepares to meet} g6 {with} 12. Bb2 {, so Black should change tack.}) 11... e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8e7] Hoping to drive the knight away ahead of completing development with ...[Be7] and ...[O-O].} 12. Re1 $1 (12. Re1 {A fairly typical Open Sicilian and Morra piece sacrifice. Matters look a little scary for Black after} exd5 $6 13. exd5+ Nce5 14. Nxe5 $1 {, but we should remember that not every sacrifice has to be accepted.}) 12... Be7 $1 {[%cal Ge6d5] Now the knight is definitely en prise.} 13. Nxe7 Qxe7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7e5,Gd7c5,Ge6e5] White has the two bishops, but Black is still quite solid and a pawn up. We'd certainly slightly prefer to be in his shoes, with ...[O-O] imminent or even ...[Nde5] if White is a little careless. Meanwhile, the rook on [a8] prevents [Ba3] for now and Black may even be able to consider improving our own dark-square situation with ...[e5] and ...[Nc5].} *

