1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Nxc3 {Standard Morra fare.} d6 {A standard Sicilian move, as well as one which frees the light-squared bishop for duty.} 6. Bc4 {The best diagonal for this bishop and now Black must be wary of tricks which exploit the potential weakness of [f7].} a6 {Recommended by Joe Gallagher way back in 1994 in his classic work Beating the Anti-Sicilians, the first such repertoire for Black, this line has stood the test of time. It's certainly served Richard well over the years, both over the board and being his primary recommendation against the Smith-Morra when he wrote Fighting the Anti-Sicilians.} ({It should be said that the point of} 6... a6 {is prophylactic, and not to prepare a quick ...[b5]. The problem with 6...Bg4? is 7.Bxf7+! and the issue with 6...Nf6?! , to prepare said ...[Bg4], is 7.e5! , and if 7...dxe5?! 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5 . As such, Black first takes control of [b5] to facilitate 7...[Nf6] then ideally 8...[Bg4].}) 7. O-O ({Invariably played, continuing the standard Morra development scheme. Instead,} 7. Bf4 Nf6 {would prepare 8...[Bg4] and we'll see} 8. O-O {by transposition in Chapter 7d, but there are a couple of other seventh moves which Black should be ready for.}) 7... Nf6 {Continuing the standard development plan. Left unopposed, Black is likely to continue with 8...[Bg4] and only then complete kingside development with ...[e6] and ...[Be7].} (7... Nf6 {Here we'll focus on White's three main tries:} 8. Qe2 {, 8.h3 and 8.Bf4 . That leaves a few options, of which perhaps the trickiest to face is a second gambit.}) 8. Qe2 $6 {White's most common choice and one which follows the standard Morra development scheme, but it's also a move which we should welcome and are set up well to meet.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge7e6,Gc6e5] This was, of course, the main point of our sophisticated move order. Black gets the bishop outside the pawn chain and would now like to go 9...[e6] then 10...[Ne5], followed by inflicting structural damage on [f3].} (8... Bg4 {Our control of e5 also means that} 9. e5 $6 {can be largely neutralised by} Bxf3 10. Qxf3 dxe5 ({avoiding} 10... Nxe5 $6 11. Qxb7)) {.} 9. h3 Bxf3 $1 ({Sensible and best, unlike} 9... Nd4 $2 10. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 11. Qc4+ {.}) 10. Qxf3 ({Sensible too; there's no need for White to increase his suffering with} 10. gxf3 $6 Qd7 11. Kh2 g6 {.}) 10... g6 $5 {[%cal Gf8g7]} ({Heading for a comfortable Dragon style set-up.} 10... Ne5 {may look obvious and has been somewhat more popular, but after} 11. Qe2 Nxc4 12. Qxc4 {then [Rd1] White does have a bit of activity for the pawn.}) 11. Rd1 Bg7 {[%csl Ge5] Entirely possible, with [e5] firmly under Black's control.} 12. Bf4 {[%cal Re4e5]} Qa5 $1 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ga8c8,Ge8g8] This vacated the d-file to leave Black with a pleasant advantage in Katona-Agardi, Hungarian League 2005, where ideas of ...[Ne5] were now imminent, as well as just ...[O-O] and ...[Rc8].} *

