1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Nxc3 {Standard Morra fare.} d6 {A standard Sicilian move, as well as one which frees the light-squared bishop for duty.} 6. Bc4 {The best diagonal for this bishop and now Black must be wary of tricks which exploit the potential weakness of [f7].} a6 {Recommended by Joe Gallagher way back in 1994 in his classic work Beating the Anti-Sicilians, the first such repertoire for Black, this line has stood the test of time. It's certainly served Richard well over the years, both over the board and being his primary recommendation against the Smith-Morra when he wrote Fighting the Anti-Sicilians.} ({It should be said that the point of} 6... a6 {is prophylactic, and not to prepare a quick ...[b5]. The problem with 6...Bg4? is 7.Bxf7+! and the issue with 6...Nf6?! , to prepare said ...[Bg4], is 7.e5! , and if 7...dxe5?! 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5 . As such, Black first takes control of [b5] to facilitate 7...[Nf6] then ideally 8...[Bg4].}) 7. O-O ({Invariably played, continuing the standard Morra development scheme. Instead,} 7. Bf4 Nf6 {would prepare 8...[Bg4] and we'll see} 8. O-O {by transposition in Chapter 7d, but there are a couple of other seventh moves which Black should be ready for.}) 7... Nf6 {Continuing the standard development plan. Left unopposed, Black is likely to continue with 8...[Bg4] and only then complete kingside development with ...[e6] and ...[Be7].} (7... Nf6 {Here we'll focus on White's three main tries:} 8. Qe2 {, 8.h3 and 8.Bf4 . That leaves a few options, of which perhaps the trickiest to face is a second gambit.}) 8. Qe2 $6 {White's most common choice and one which follows the standard Morra development scheme, but it's also a move which we should welcome and are set up well to meet.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge7e6,Gc6e5] This was, of course, the main point of our sophisticated move order. Black gets the bishop outside the pawn chain and would now like to go 9...[e6] then 10...[Ne5], followed by inflicting structural damage on [f3].} (8... Bg4 {Our control of e5 also means that} 9. e5 $6 {can be largely neutralised by} Bxf3 10. Qxf3 dxe5 ({avoiding} 10... Nxe5 $6 11. Qxb7)) {.} 9. Be3 e6 {[%cal Gf8e7] Standard development, although against White's fairly slow approach, 9...[g6] must also be decent.} 10. Bb3 Be7 11. h3 {[%csl Rg4]} Bh5 $5 ({Ambitiously retaining the bishop; simpler souls might well have settled for} 11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 O-O {with a pleasant edge.}) 12. Rfd1 {[%csl Rd1,Rd6,Rd8][%cal Rg2g4,Re4e5]} Qa5 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gh8f8,Gf8d8,Ga8d8] Wisely stepping off the d-file and reclaiming control over [e5]. With [d8] free for either rook, Black must be somewhere between slightly and clearly better.} (12... Ne5 $2 {This, however, is one to avoid. Black prevents [e4]-[e5], but not for longer...} 13. g4 $1 Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 Bg6 15. e5 {This was very much a Morra Gambit gone wrong for Black in Jakobeit-Golubev, Titled Tuesday Blitz. 2023}) *

