1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Nxc3 {Standard Morra fare.} d6 {A standard Sicilian move, as well as one which frees the light-squared bishop for duty.} 6. Bc4 {The best diagonal for this bishop and now Black must be wary of tricks which exploit the potential weakness of [f7].} a6 {Recommended by Joe Gallagher way back in 1994 in his classic work Beating the Anti-Sicilians, the first such repertoire for Black, this line has stood the test of time. It's certainly served Richard well over the years, both over the board and being his primary recommendation against the Smith-Morra when he wrote Fighting the Anti-Sicilians.} ({It should be said that the point of} 6... a6 {is prophylactic, and not to prepare a quick ...[b5]. The problem with 6...Bg4? is 7.Bxf7+! and the issue with 6...Nf6?! , to prepare said ...[Bg4], is 7.e5! , and if 7...dxe5?! 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5 . As such, Black first takes control of [b5] to facilitate 7...[Nf6] then ideally 8...[Bg4].}) 7. O-O ({Invariably played, continuing the standard Morra development scheme. Instead,} 7. Bf4 Nf6 {would prepare 8...[Bg4] and we'll see} 8. O-O {by transposition in Chapter 7d, but there are a couple of other seventh moves which Black should be ready for.}) 7... Nf6 {Continuing the standard development plan. Left unopposed, Black is likely to continue with 8...[Bg4] and only then complete kingside development with ...[e6] and ...[Be7].} (7... Nf6 {Here we'll focus on White's three main tries:} 8. Qe2 {, 8.h3 and 8.Bf4 . That leaves a few options, of which perhaps the trickiest to face is a second gambit.}) 8. Qe2 $6 {White's most common choice and one which follows the standard Morra development scheme, but it's also a move which we should welcome and are set up well to meet.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge7e6,Gc6e5] This was, of course, the main point of our sophisticated move order. Black gets the bishop outside the pawn chain and would now like to go 9...[e6] then 10...[Ne5], followed by inflicting structural damage on [f3].} (8... Bg4 {Our control of e5 also means that} 9. e5 $6 {can be largely neutralised by} Bxf3 10. Qxf3 dxe5 ({avoiding} 10... Nxe5 $6 11. Qxb7)) {.} 9. Rd1 {[%csl Re5]} (9. Rd1 {White continues the standard Morra policy while hoping for} Ne5 $4 10. Nxe5 $1 {.}) 9... e6 {[%csl Ge5]} (9... e6 {Yet more sensible development and now} 10. e5 $2 {can safely be met by} Nxe5 {.}) 10. Bb3 {White tries to retreat the bishop out of the way of any ...[Ne5] possibilities.} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] With White again not up to too much, Black is quite content to simply continue development.} 11. h3 {[%csl Re5,Rg4]} Bxf3 $1 ({Once more, a somewhat more alert choice than} 11... Bh5 $2 12. g4 $1 {would be.}) 12. Qxf3 Qa5 $5 {[%csl Ge5]} ({One of two good approaches here, the other being} 12... O-O 13. Bf4 Qb8 $1 {. In either case, Black retains a strong grip over the [e5]-square.}) 13. Bf4 {[%csl Rd6]} Rd8 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc6e5] Securing [d6] and with ...[O-O] on the way, followed by ...[Ne5] and perhaps then even ...[Nfd7], Black was in control and just a pawn up in Karasek-Mielke, correspondence 1990.} (13... Rd8 {It might be worth seeing a few more moves.} 14. Rd2 O-O 15. Rad1 Ne5 {((Retaining the extra pawn and note how 16.Bxe5? dxe5 would now leave Black in complete control of the dark squares, with his bishop massively more effective than the white one on [b3].))} 16. Qe2 Nfd7 $5 {Heading round to the queenside to begin active operations there.} 17. Be3 $6 Nc5 18. Bd5 $5 {((This hoped for 18...exd5? 19.Nxd5 followed by [b2]-[b4], but yet again we should remember that not every sacrifice has to be accepted.)) In the game, the 2515-rated black player eventually went on to win after 18...b5 and here he had something even stronger.} Bf6 $1 {((Threatening 19...exd5 20.Nxd5 Ncd7 and leaving White rather out of good moves.))} 19. f4 $5 Ng6 {Straightforward play, although leaping into [d3] also looks pretty tempting - and strong.} 20. f5 Bxc3 $1 21. bxc3 Ne5 {Black is simply doing very well, with White unable to save both his bishop and e-pawn.}) *

