1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Nxc3 {Standard Morra fare.} d6 {A standard Sicilian move, as well as one which frees the light-squared bishop for duty.} 6. Bc4 {The best diagonal for this bishop and now Black must be wary of tricks which exploit the potential weakness of [f7].} a6 {Recommended by Joe Gallagher way back in 1994 in his classic work Beating the Anti-Sicilians, the first such repertoire for Black, this line has stood the test of time. It's certainly served Richard well over the years, both over the board and being his primary recommendation against the Smith-Morra when he wrote Fighting the Anti-Sicilians.} ({It should be said that the point of} 6... a6 {is prophylactic, and not to prepare a quick ...[b5]. The problem with 6...Bg4? is 7.Bxf7+! and the issue with 6...Nf6?! , to prepare said ...[Bg4], is 7.e5! , and if 7...dxe5?! 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5 . As such, Black first takes control of [b5] to facilitate 7...[Nf6] then ideally 8...[Bg4].}) 7. O-O ({Invariably played, continuing the standard Morra development scheme. Instead,} 7. Bf4 Nf6 {would prepare 8...[Bg4] and we'll see} 8. O-O {by transposition in Chapter 7d, but there are a couple of other seventh moves which Black should be ready for.}) 7... Nf6 {Continuing the standard development plan. Left unopposed, Black is likely to continue with 8...[Bg4] and only then complete kingside development with ...[e6] and ...[Be7].} (7... Nf6 {Here we'll focus on White's three main tries:} 8. Qe2 {, 8.h3 and 8.Bf4 . That leaves a few options, of which perhaps the trickiest to face is a second gambit.}) 8. Qe2 $6 {White's most common choice and one which follows the standard Morra development scheme, but it's also a move which we should welcome and are set up well to meet.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge7e6,Gc6e5] This was, of course, the main point of our sophisticated move order. Black gets the bishop outside the pawn chain and would now like to go 9...[e6] then 10...[Ne5], followed by inflicting structural damage on [f3].} (8... Bg4 {Our control of e5 also means that} 9. e5 $6 {can be largely neutralised by} Bxf3 10. Qxf3 dxe5 ({avoiding} 10... Nxe5 $6 11. Qxb7)) {.} 9. Rd1 {[%csl Re5]} (9. Rd1 {White continues the standard Morra policy while hoping for} Ne5 $4 10. Nxe5 $1 {.}) 9... e6 {[%csl Ge5]} (9... e6 {Yet more sensible development and now} 10. e5 $2 {can safely be met by} Nxe5 {.}) 10. Bf4 $2 {Another common choice and another which Black should be delighted to see.} Nh5 $1 {Richard has long followed the Gallagher method and done well with 10...[Qb8] here, but while writing this course finally accepted that the radical text move is just even stronger. Black attacks the bishop, readies ...[Ne5] once the bishop has moved or been exchanged, and White lacks anything radical and good.} (10... Nh5 {For example,} 11. Bg5 Qxg5 $1 12. Nxg5 Bxe2 13. Bxe2 Nf6 {is just a clear extra pawn for Black and 11.Bxd6? Bxd6 12.e5 Nxe5 13.Ne4 O-O 14.Rxd6 Qe7 even more than that.}) 11. Be3 Ne5 {[%csl Gc4,Ge2,Gf3,Gg4][%cal Gg4f3,Gd8h4]} (11... Ne5 {Direct and even stronger than 11...Qf6, with the main threat that of taking over on the kingside after} 12. Z0 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Qh4 {.}) 12. Bb3 {Preserving a fairly important piece for White, but now Black can carry out the aforementioned kingside strike.} Bxf3 13. gxf3 Qh4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h3,Gh5f4,Gf8e7,Ge7g5]} (13... Qh4 {Here to threaten both 14...Qh3 and 14...Nf4, while if} 14. Kg2 {Black even has time to go} Be7 {and 15...[Bg5].}) 14. Ba4+ {Desperately seeking some counterplay.} b5 $1 {[%csl Ga4] A fearless and uncompromising response, preparing to sacrifice the rook on [a8] for some counterplay 14...[Ke7] is also pretty strong. As confirmed by the engines, White is already lost.} *

