1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Nxc3 {Standard Morra fare.} d6 {A standard Sicilian move, as well as one which frees the light-squared bishop for duty.} 6. Bc4 {The best diagonal for this bishop and now Black must be wary of tricks which exploit the potential weakness of [f7].} a6 {Recommended by Joe Gallagher way back in 1994 in his classic work Beating the Anti-Sicilians, the first such repertoire for Black, this line has stood the test of time. It's certainly served Richard well over the years, both over the board and being his primary recommendation against the Smith-Morra when he wrote Fighting the Anti-Sicilians.} ({It should be said that the point of} 6... a6 {is prophylactic, and not to prepare a quick ...[b5]. The problem with 6...Bg4? is 7.Bxf7+! and the issue with 6...Nf6?! , to prepare said ...[Bg4], is 7.e5! , and if 7...dxe5?! 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5 . As such, Black first takes control of [b5] to facilitate 7...[Nf6] then ideally 8...[Bg4].}) 7. O-O ({Invariably played, continuing the standard Morra development scheme. Instead,} 7. Bf4 Nf6 {would prepare 8...[Bg4] and we'll see} 8. O-O {by transposition in Chapter 7d, but there are a couple of other seventh moves which Black should be ready for.}) 7... Nf6 {Continuing the standard development plan. Left unopposed, Black is likely to continue with 8...[Bg4] and only then complete kingside development with ...[e6] and ...[Be7].} (7... Nf6 {Here we'll focus on White's three main tries:} 8. Qe2 {, 8.h3 and 8.Bf4 . That leaves a few options, of which perhaps the trickiest to face is a second gambit.}) 8. Qe2 $6 {White's most common choice and one which follows the standard Morra development scheme, but it's also a move which we should welcome and are set up well to meet.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge7e6,Gc6e5] This was, of course, the main point of our sophisticated move order. Black gets the bishop outside the pawn chain and would now like to go 9...[e6] then 10...[Ne5], followed by inflicting structural damage on [f3].} (8... Bg4 {Our control of e5 also means that} 9. e5 $6 {can be largely neutralised by} Bxf3 10. Qxf3 dxe5 ({avoiding} 10... Nxe5 $6 11. Qxb7)) {.} 9. Rd1 {[%csl Re5]} (9. Rd1 {White continues the standard Morra policy while hoping for} Ne5 $4 10. Nxe5 $1 {.}) 9... e6 {[%csl Ge5]} (9... e6 {Yet more sensible development and now} 10. e5 $2 {can safely be met by} Nxe5 {.}) 10. Bf4 $2 {Another common choice and another which Black should be delighted to see.} Nh5 $1 {Richard has long followed the Gallagher method and done well with 10...[Qb8] here, but while writing this course finally accepted that the radical text move is just even stronger. Black attacks the bishop, readies ...[Ne5] once the bishop has moved or been exchanged, and White lacks anything radical and good.} (10... Nh5 {For example,} 11. Bg5 Qxg5 $1 12. Nxg5 Bxe2 13. Bxe2 Nf6 {is just a clear extra pawn for Black and 11.Bxd6? Bxd6 12.e5 Nxe5 13.Ne4 O-O 14.Rxd6 Qe7 even more than that.}) 11. Be3 Ne5 {[%csl Gc4,Ge2,Gf3,Gg4][%cal Gg4f3,Gd8h4]} (11... Ne5 {Direct and even stronger than 11...Qf6, with the main threat that of taking over on the kingside after} 12. Z0 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Qh4 {.}) 12. Bb3 {Preserving a fairly important piece for White, but now Black can carry out the aforementioned kingside strike.} Bxf3 13. gxf3 Qh4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h3,Gh5f4,Gf8e7,Ge7g5]} (13... Qh4 {Here to threaten both 14...Qh3 and 14...Nf4, while if} 14. Kg2 {Black even has time to go} Be7 {and 15...[Bg5].}) 14. Ba4+ {Desperately seeking some counterplay.} b5 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Gg1] A fearless and uncompromising response, preparing to sacrifice the rook on [a8] for some counterplay 14...[Ke7] is also pretty strong. As confirmed by the engines, White is already lost.Let's see an example.} 15. Nxb5 {One of two desperate, last-ditch tries in what is already pretty much a hopeless position for White.} (15. Bxb5+ $5 {((White hopes to be allowed to limp on after 15...axb5 16.Qxb5+ Ke7 17.f4! Nf3+ 18.Kf1 , but Black can do even better than that.))} Ke7 $1 {The bishop on [b5] hangs and so does the white kingside, with ...[Qh3] the most direct threat and even ...[g5] a strong possibility in reserve.} 16. Bxa6 Qh3 {There's just no good way to prevent 17...[Nxf3]+.}) 15... axb5 16. Qxb5+ Ke7 {An only but very strong move.} 17. f4 $5 (17. Qb7+ Kf6 {The king is surprisingly safe here and now 18...[Be7] is imminent, as is, of course, 18... [Qh3].} 18. Qxa8 Qh3 {White is once again completely undone on the kingside.}) 17... Nxf4 $1 {[%csl Gg1,Gh2][%cal Ge5f3]} ({Even more brutal than the} 17... Nf3+ {of Rezaee-Gholami, Tehran 2017, as Black threatens mate in two, beginning with 18...[Nf3]+.}) 18. Bxf4 Qxf4 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gf4g4,Ge5g4] The king will be quite safe on [f6] and meanwhile we have a multitude of threats of our own.} 19. Qb7+ Kf6 20. Qxa8 d5 $1 {[%cal Gf8c5] Adding 21...[Bc5] to the list of threats. White is the exchange up, but completely lacking defenders and quite lost here. The finish might be:} 21. Qd8+ {[%csl Rf6]} Be7 $1 {[%csl Gd8]} 22. Qxh8 (22. Qa5 Nf3+ 23. Kg2 Qg4+ {White will quickly be mated after checks on [h2] and [e4] if the king runs to [f1], but neither will it be safe in the corner.} 24. Kh1 Bd6 {25... [Qh3] or} 25. Qc3+ Be5 {will clean White up.}) 22... Bc5 {[%csl Gg1][%cal Gf4f2]} 23. Qd8+ Kg6 {[%cal Gf4f2,Gf2f3,Ge5f3]} (23... Kg6 {It's now an extra rook and bishop, but how on earth to defend on the kingside, not least again the immediate threat of} 24. Z0 Qxf2+ 25. Kh1 Qf3# $2) 24. Rf1 Nf3+ {[%csl Gg1]} 25. Kg2 dxe4 {[%cal Gf4h2] Cementing the knight in place to threaten mate on [h2].} 26. Rh1 Ne1+ $1 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Gf4f2] Concluding a lovely attack in style. It's mate in three.} 27. Rhxe1 Qxf2+ 28. Kh3 Qf3+ 29. Kh4 Bf2# {[%csl Gh4] Pretty stuff, as well as an impressive attack, but when the opening flows so well for Black and the white kingside has been severely compromised, such things can occur.} *

