1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Nxc3 {Standard Morra fare.} d6 {A standard Sicilian move, as well as one which frees the light-squared bishop for duty.} 6. Bc4 {The best diagonal for this bishop and now Black must be wary of tricks which exploit the potential weakness of [f7].} a6 {Recommended by Joe Gallagher way back in 1994 in his classic work Beating the Anti-Sicilians, the first such repertoire for Black, this line has stood the test of time. It's certainly served Richard well over the years, both over the board and being his primary recommendation against the Smith-Morra when he wrote Fighting the Anti-Sicilians.} ({It should be said that the point of} 6... a6 {is prophylactic, and not to prepare a quick ...[b5]. The problem with 6...Bg4? is 7.Bxf7+! and the issue with 6...Nf6?! , to prepare said ...[Bg4], is 7.e5! , and if 7...dxe5?! 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5 . As such, Black first takes control of [b5] to facilitate 7...[Nf6] then ideally 8...[Bg4].}) 7. O-O ({Invariably played, continuing the standard Morra development scheme. Instead,} 7. Bf4 Nf6 {would prepare 8...[Bg4] and we'll see} 8. O-O {by transposition in Chapter 7d, but there are a couple of other seventh moves which Black should be ready for.}) 7... Nf6 {Continuing the standard development plan. Left unopposed, Black is likely to continue with 8...[Bg4] and only then complete kingside development with ...[e6] and ...[Be7].} (7... Nf6 {Here we'll focus on White's three main tries:} 8. Qe2 {, 8.h3 and 8.Bf4 . That leaves a few options, of which perhaps the trickiest to face is a second gambit.}) 8. h3 ({Not a particularly impressive move, if one which several Morra players turned to after realising the problems that} 8. Qe2 Bg4 {could cause them.}) 8... e6 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gf8e7,Gc8d7,Gb7b5] Not a move we ever mind making, blunting the bishop on [c4], and the way is now clear for 9...[Be7] followed by ...[Bd7] or perhaps even ...[b5].} 9. Bf4 Be7 {A simple choice, ensuring Black is only one move away from castling before thinking about any notion of counterplay on the queenside.} 10. Qe2 {[%cal Rf1d1,Re4e5]} (10. Qe2 {White gets ready to go 11.Rfd1 then blast through with 12.e5. Black can counter such a plan with} Qa5 {, 10...e5 or even expand on the queenside.}) 10... b5 $5 {[%csl Gc4]} 11. Bb3 Na5 {[%cal Ga5b3,Ga5c4] Hunting down the bishop-pair or hoping to land the knight on [c4] one day.} 12. Rfd1 {[%cal Re4e5]} Qb6 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc8b7,Ga8d8]} (12... Qb6 {Wisely stepping off the d-file. Black may now go 13...Bb7 and} 13. Qd3 $6 Bb7 $1 {counterattacking against [e4], should White go after [d6].} 14. Bc2 Rd8 {was already clearly better for Black in Savitski-A.Zhigalko, Minsk 2017.}) 13. Bc2 $1 {Preserving the bishop while covering [e4].} Bb7 {[%cal Ge8g8] Everything is now set for 14...[O-O] to complete development, and we shouldn't forget that Black is a pawn up.} 14. e5 $5 dxe5 15. Nxe5 Rc8 $1 {[%cal Ga5c4] White's activity gave him some, but not quite enough compensation for the pawn in E.Berg-Hillarp Persson, Gothenburg 2013.} *

