1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Nxc3 {Standard Morra fare.} d6 {A standard Sicilian move, as well as one which frees the light-squared bishop for duty.} 6. Bc4 {The best diagonal for this bishop and now Black must be wary of tricks which exploit the potential weakness of [f7].} a6 {Recommended by Joe Gallagher way back in 1994 in his classic work Beating the Anti-Sicilians, the first such repertoire for Black, this line has stood the test of time. It's certainly served Richard well over the years, both over the board and being his primary recommendation against the Smith-Morra when he wrote Fighting the Anti-Sicilians.} ({It should be said that the point of} 6... a6 {is prophylactic, and not to prepare a quick ...[b5]. The problem with 6...Bg4? is 7.Bxf7+! and the issue with 6...Nf6?! , to prepare said ...[Bg4], is 7.e5! , and if 7...dxe5?! 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5 . As such, Black first takes control of [b5] to facilitate 7...[Nf6] then ideally 8...[Bg4].}) 7. O-O ({Invariably played, continuing the standard Morra development scheme. Instead,} 7. Bf4 Nf6 {would prepare 8...[Bg4] and we'll see} 8. O-O {by transposition in Chapter 7d, but there are a couple of other seventh moves which Black should be ready for.}) 7... Nf6 {Continuing the standard development plan. Left unopposed, Black is likely to continue with 8...[Bg4] and only then complete kingside development with ...[e6] and ...[Be7].} (7... Nf6 {Here we'll focus on White's three main tries:} 8. Qe2 {, 8.h3 and 8.Bf4 . That leaves a few options, of which perhaps the trickiest to face is a second gambit.}) 8. h3 ({Not a particularly impressive move, if one which several Morra players turned to after realising the problems that} 8. Qe2 Bg4 {could cause them.}) 8... e6 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gf8e7,Gc8d7,Gb7b5] Not a move we ever mind making, blunting the bishop on [c4], and the way is now clear for 9...[Be7] followed by ...[Bd7] or perhaps even ...[b5].} 9. Qe2 {White continues with the standard Morra play, preparing to bring the king's rook over to [d1].} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc8d7,Gb7b5] Our standard approach and now Black may castle or first prefer 10...[Bd7] or even 10...[b5].} ({While playable, there's just no need to get involved in} 9... b5 10. Bb3 Ra7 $5 {here, while 9...Bd7 10.Bf4 would be slightly awkward.}) 10. Rd1 {[%cal Re4e5] With a familiar threat.} Qc7 $5 {[%cal Gc6e5,Gb7b5]} ({A slightly unusual approach in general, but a good one here b5!? Bb3 Qb6 , as endorsed by Daniel King on King's Anti-Sicilians for Black, is also a good choice. The queen leaves the d-file, while avoiding being prodded further with} 10... Qa5 11. Bd2 {. Black is now ready to go 11...[b5] or 11...[Ne5], and this seems a simpler way of handling the black pieces than allowing White some play after 10...Bd7 11.Bf4 b5 12.Bb3 Qb8 13.e5 .}) 11. Bf4 {[%cal Re4e5] White tends to respond so, looking to force through [e4]-[e5] after all.} Ne5 $1 {[%csl Gc4]} (11... Ne5 {Nyet, says Black, who should now again enjoy being left master of the dark squares if} 12. Bxe5 $2 dxe5 {.}) 12. Bb3 O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8d7] Removing the king from the centre is by no means forced, but makes sense. We can now look to follow up with ...[b5] and/or ...[Bd7].} 13. Rac1 {[%cal Rc3d5] A typical Morra set-up from White, but with the knight on [e5] Black has little to fear and the threat of 14. [Nd5] is easily dealt with. Illustrative} Qb8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5] The safest square for the queen. With ongoing control of [e5] and ...[b5] imminent, it's hard to believe White can have enough for a pawn.Let's see an example.} 14. Bh2 $5 {A not unknown regrouping in such positions; White wants to get in [f2]-[f4].} (14. g4 $5 b5 15. g5 Nfd7 {Keeping everything tight at the back, while preparing to activate this knight via [e5] or [c5].} 16. Nd4 {This was Jobava-Rakotomaharo, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2021, no less, where Black might have pressed ahead on the queenside without delay:} Nc5 $1 17. Bc2 b4 18. Na4 Bd7 {White simply looks overextended, the knight on [a4] hangs and he must also be very careful about ...[Bb5] ideas or, in other words, Black is doing very well.}) 14... b5 {Thematic expansion.} 15. Nd4 (15. Nd4 {Here} Bb7 16. f4 Nc4 $5 {was far from ridiculous and continued to favour Black in Jakobeit-Golubev, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, where it was also possible to avoid even any notion of a sacrifice on [e6].}) 15... Bd7 $5 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gf8c8] Intending to press ahead with ...[b4] and ...[Rc8] if allowed.} 16. f4 {[%csl Re5]} Nc6 {[%cal Gb8b6,Gb5b4,Gd7c6] Now 17...[Qb6] is a threat, as well as 17...[b5], and even a standard Morra tactical device doesn't come close to giving White enough compensation.} 17. Nd5 $5 {[%csl Rc6,Re7]} exd5 {Black is quite happy to accept and simplify.} 18. Nxc6 {[%csl Rb8]} Bxc6 19. Rxc6 dxe4 {[%csl Gd6,Ge4][%cal Gb8b7,Gd6d5,Ga6a5,Ga5a4] The position is a bit messy, but Black is set to expand with ...[Qb7] and ...[d5], as well as possibly ...[a5]-[a4], and is still two pawns to the good.} *

