1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Nxc3 {Standard Morra fare.} d6 {A standard Sicilian move, as well as one which frees the light-squared bishop for duty.} 6. Bc4 {The best diagonal for this bishop and now Black must be wary of tricks which exploit the potential weakness of [f7].} a6 {Recommended by Joe Gallagher way back in 1994 in his classic work Beating the Anti-Sicilians, the first such repertoire for Black, this line has stood the test of time. It's certainly served Richard well over the years, both over the board and being his primary recommendation against the Smith-Morra when he wrote Fighting the Anti-Sicilians.} ({It should be said that the point of} 6... a6 {is prophylactic, and not to prepare a quick ...[b5]. The problem with 6...Bg4? is 7.Bxf7+! and the issue with 6...Nf6?! , to prepare said ...[Bg4], is 7.e5! , and if 7...dxe5?! 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5 . As such, Black first takes control of [b5] to facilitate 7...[Nf6] then ideally 8...[Bg4].}) 7. O-O ({Invariably played, continuing the standard Morra development scheme. Instead,} 7. Bf4 Nf6 {would prepare 8...[Bg4] and we'll see} 8. O-O {by transposition in Chapter 7d, but there are a couple of other seventh moves which Black should be ready for.}) 7... Nf6 {Continuing the standard development plan. Left unopposed, Black is likely to continue with 8...[Bg4] and only then complete kingside development with ...[e6] and ...[Be7].} (7... Nf6 {Here we'll focus on White's three main tries:} 8. Qe2 {, 8.h3 and 8.Bf4 . That leaves a few options, of which perhaps the trickiest to face is a second gambit.}) 8. Bf4 {White limbers up for [e4]-[e5] and this has largely been the choice of the stronger players to have reached this position in recent years.} Bg4 $5 {[%csl Gd1,Gf3,Gg4]} ({Once again, there's nothing wrong with} 8... e6 {, but here we can pin, while provoking 9. [Qb3].}) 9. Qb3 $6 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Rc4f7] This works well when the bishop on [e3], but not here as White won't be able to run with his knight to [d4].} e6 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gg4f3,Gf8e7,Gc6a5] We're now ready to exchange on [f3], as well as go ...[Be7] or even ...[Na5], and the b-pawn is at least semi-poisoned.} 10. Qxb7 $2 Na5 $1 {[%csl Gb7,Gc4]} (10... Na5 {Forking and so pretty much forcing White's reply,} 11. Bb5+ $2 axb5 12. Qxb5+ Qd7 {just being an extra piece for Black.}) 11. Qb4 {[%cal Rb4a4]} e5 $1 {[%csl Gb4,Gc4,Gf4][%cal Ge5f4,Ga8b8,Gg4d7]} (11... e5 {A powerful advance one much stronger than the Bxf3 Qa4+! Nd7 gxf3 of Nakamura-Le Quang Liem, Titled Tuesday Blitz no less, enabling} 12. Qa4+ {to be met by} Bd7 {, while threatening 12...[exf4] and 12...[d5], as well as 12...[Rb8].}) 12. Bd5 $5 {[%csl Ra8] Arguably the best of the various ways White might choose to lose the piece.} Rb8 {[%csl Gb4,Gf4] Saving the rook, with tempo too.} 13. Qa4+ Bd7 {The key point behind 11...[e5].} 14. Qd1 exf4 {And there goes a piece. Moreover, the powerful-looking bishop on [d5] can easily be removed.} 15. Ng5 {[%csl Rf7]} Nxd5 16. Qxd5 Be6 $1 {We've followed Richard's analysis from 2007, analysis which has held up well here. Black returns a pawn to simplify and avoid any real danger.} 17. Nxe6 {[%csl Rd8]} fxe6 18. Qxe6+ Be7 {[%cal Gd8d7,Gb8c8,Ga5c6] While we can't castle, White only has one pawn for the piece and surely clearly insufficient compensation as Black will be quick to go ...[Qd7], ...[Rc8] and/or ...[Nc6] to regroup.} *

