1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. d4 cxd4 {The title of this theoretical section, 'Fourth Move Alternatives', may seem a little surprising, since surely 2...[Nc6], unlike 2...[d6], prevents White from going 4. [Qxd4]. However, in about one percent of games, opponents will eschew 4. [Nxd4] here.} 4. c3 (4. c3 {White offers transposition after} dxc3 5. Nxc3 {in to the Smith-Morra Gambit, a gambit which you may already accept in your repertoire depending on how you counter 1.e4 c5 2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 ( 3...dxc3 4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 would be a standard transposition to the line under discussion here.That all doesn't really leave many moves, and it's very hard to believe that ) 4.b4? Nxb4 5.c3 dxc3 6.Nxc3 e6 gives White enough for two pawns.}) 4... dxc3 {Accepting the Morra. An acid test, especially as it's not completely impossible White isn't bluffing with 4. [c3], or at least you'd expect a Morra die-hard to have played the gambit back on move 2.} ({Of the alternatives,} 4... Nf6 {is fine, if you like to meet the c3 Sicilian so, with a transposition to such lines after} 5. e5 Nd5 {.}) 5. Nxc3 {Standard Morra fare.} d6 {A standard Sicilian move, as well as one which frees the light-squared bishop for duty.} 6. Bc4 {The best diagonal for this bishop and now Black must be wary of tricks which exploit the potential weakness of [f7].} a6 {Recommended by Joe Gallagher way back in 1994 in his classic work Beating the Anti-Sicilians, the first such repertoire for Black, this line has stood the test of time. It's certainly served Richard well over the years, both over the board and being his primary recommendation against the Smith-Morra when he wrote Fighting the Anti-Sicilians.} ({It should be said that the point of} 6... a6 {is prophylactic, and not to prepare a quick ...[b5]. The problem with 6...Bg4? is 7.Bxf7+! and the issue with 6...Nf6?! , to prepare said ...[Bg4], is 7.e5! , and if 7...dxe5?! 8.Qxd8+ Nxd8 9.Nb5 . As such, Black first takes control of [b5] to facilitate 7...[Nf6] then ideally 8...[Bg4].}) 7. O-O ({Invariably played, continuing the standard Morra development scheme. Instead,} 7. Bf4 Nf6 {would prepare 8...[Bg4] and we'll see} 8. O-O {by transposition in Chapter 7d, but there are a couple of other seventh moves which Black should be ready for.}) 7... Nf6 {Continuing the standard development plan. Left unopposed, Black is likely to continue with 8...[Bg4] and only then complete kingside development with ...[e6] and ...[Be7].} (7... Nf6 {Here we'll focus on White's three main tries:} 8. Qe2 {, 8.h3 and 8.Bf4 . That leaves a few options, of which perhaps the trickiest to face is a second gambit.}) 8. Bf4 {White limbers up for [e4]-[e5] and this has largely been the choice of the stronger players to have reached this position in recent years.} Bg4 $5 {[%csl Gd1,Gf3,Gg4]} ({Once again, there's nothing wrong with} 8... e6 {, but here we can pin, while provoking 9. [Qb3].}) 9. h3 {White tends to deal with the pin so.} Bxf3 {[%csl Gd1]} ({A simple and prudent approach, avoiding allowing White to sideline the bishop and seize the initiative with} 9... Bh5 10. g4 $1 {.}) 10. Qxf3 e6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Black has a typically solid set-up for the variation and is all set to go 11...[Be7] followed by castling.} 11. Rfd1 {[%cal Re4e5] White usually uses this rook to threaten the good, old [e4]-[e5].} Qb8 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf8e7,Gc6e5]} (11... Qb8 {An approach we should by now be familiar with. The queen steps away from the gaze of the rook on d1 as Black takes control of the e5-square. We're now ready once again to go ...Be7 and then maybe even 12...Ne5, while} 12. Qg3 $2 Nh5 {would only serve to help Black.}) 12. Rac1 Be7 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge8g8]} (12... Be7 {Calmly continuing development and now} 13. Qd3 Ne5 14. Bxe5 $6 dxe5 15. Qe2 O-O {followed by ...[b5] left Black in full control in Simoncini-Rowson, Porto Mannu 2013.}) 13. Bb3 $5 {A more tricky try.} O-O 14. Na4 {[%cal Ra4b6]} (14. Na4 {Here after} Nd7 15. Qg3 {White's pressure against d6 and b6 gave him enough for the pawn in Lenderman-Wieczorek, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2022.}) 14... Qc7 $1 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gf6d7,Gc7a5]} (14... Qc7 {A much better way of covering the d6-square. Black remains for choice here with ...Rfd8 and ...Nd7 one plan and even} 15. Z0 Qa5 $5 {a possibility, intending to regain the pawn after} 16. Bxd6 Bxd6 17. Rxd6 {with} Qe5 {.}) *

