1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 {White keeps his options open and may well be aiming to avoid the Löwenthal and Kalashnikov while reaching an Open Sicilian after all following 4. [d4] [cxd4] 5. [Nxd4].} a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. Bc4 $6 {Not a great choice, if one which might well seem natural to an inexperienced junior.} b5 {[%csl Gc4]} (4... b5 {Helping ourselves to the advance 3...a6 prepared, and getting it in with gain of tempo. Clearly} 5. Bb3 $4 c4 {would be embarrassing for White, 5.Be2 (loses time Black might then go 5...Bb7 or 5...Nd4!? , if you'd like to rule out [d2]-[d4] for good, and even heading forwards with the bishop isn't too concerning.)}) 5. Bd5 {[%cal Rd5c6] With something of a positional threat.} Bb7 {[%cal Ge7e6] Preserving our structure while getting ready to make another useful move with gain of tempo in the shape of ...[e6].} 6. d4 $5 {White tries to go down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 {[%cal Gd4c3]} 7. Nxd4 Qc7 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gd7c6,Gg8f6] (This is simply a very comfortable version of a Kan Variation 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 a6 ) for Black. We're set to continue development with ...[e6] and ...[Nf6], and will recapture in the event of any exchange on [c6] with the d-pawn, following up with ...[c5] to seize space and open up the now particularly fine bishop on [b7].} *

