1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 {White keeps his options open and may well be aiming to avoid the Löwenthal and Kalashnikov while reaching an Open Sicilian after all following 4. [d4] [cxd4] 5. [Nxd4].} a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. a4 {White rules out ... [b5], but an early [a4] is rarely a problem for Black in the Sicilian, and this position is no exception.} Nf6 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gd7d5] Knights before bishops as we continue development. If White now does something very quiet 5...[d5] may be possible or just 5...[e6] and then 6...[d5].} 5. e5 $6 {White is provoked and now the pawn on [e5] can quickly be targeted.} Ng4 {[%cal Gg4e5]} 6. Qe2 {How else to defend the pawn?} f6 $1 {[%csl Ge5]} ({Not allowing White any respite and a much better policy than} 6... Qc7 7. Nd5 {.}) 7. exf6 Nxf6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge2][%cal Gd7d5,Gc8g4] Black's development was already the more harmonious in Grutter-Szpar, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2024, with ...[d5] followed by ...[Bg4] an aggressive way to begin to look to make good use of our central control.} *

