1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 {White keeps his options open and may well be aiming to avoid the Löwenthal and Kalashnikov while reaching an Open Sicilian after all following 4. [d4] [cxd4] 5. [Nxd4].} a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. a4 {White rules out ... [b5], but an early [a4] is rarely a problem for Black in the Sicilian, and this position is no exception.} Nf6 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gd7d5] Knights before bishops as we continue development. If White now does something very quiet 5...[d5] may be possible or just 5...[e6] and then 6...[d5].} 5. Bc4 $6 {White reasons that the bishop is safe here now that ...[b5] has been ruled out, but it's simply a target for a different pawn break.} e6 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gd7d5] Simple chess: ...[d5] is imminent and Black already enjoys a pleasant game.} 6. O-O d5 {[%cal Gd5c4,Gd5e4,Gd5d4] Expanding with tempo while giving Black several useful options in the centre.} 7. exd5 exd5 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gc8e6,Gc8g4] Now the light-squared bishop is free and may take up residence on [e6] or even [g4].} 8. Re1+ {Probably White's best try, aiming to tidy up his position.} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd5d4,Gd5c4]} (8... Be7 {A straightforward block and now} 9. Ba2 O-O {would just leave the white bishop looking a little misplaced on [a2].}) 9. Bf1 d4 $5 {[%csl Gc3]} (9... d4 {By no means forced, but a tempting advance to gain space and if} 10. Ne2 {we can even continue to disrupt with} d3 $5 {.}) 10. Ne4 {[%cal Re4f6]} Nxe4 {Exchanging on our terms.} 11. Rxe4 (11. Rxe4 {We've followed Vignesh-Nakamura, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, where} Be6 12. Rxe6 $5 fxe6 {didn't give White quite enough for the exchange and Black doesn't even have to allow the possibility.}) 11... O-O 12. d3 Bd6 $1 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gd8d7,Gd8c7,Ga8e8] Improving the bishop. Black has a pleasant edge here with the extra space and will look to mobilise with ...[Bf5] followed by ...[Qd7] or ...[Qc7] and ...[Rae8], perhaps even angling for a kingside attack.} *

