1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 {White keeps his options open and may well be aiming to avoid the Löwenthal and Kalashnikov while reaching an Open Sicilian after all following 4. [d4] [cxd4] 5. [Nxd4].} a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. a4 {White rules out ... [b5], but an early [a4] is rarely a problem for Black in the Sicilian, and this position is no exception.} Nf6 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gd7d5] Knights before bishops as we continue development. If White now does something very quiet 5...[d5] may be possible or just 5...[e6] and then 6...[d5].} 5. d4 {Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 {Naturally, we make the standard Sicilian exchange...} 6. Nxd4 e5 {[%csl Gd4] ...ahead of following up with our favourite advance. This position can be closely compared with 3. [Nc3] with 4. [d4] chapter, and it's not hard to believe that the insertion of [a2]-[a4] and ...[Nf6] must be in Black's favour.} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gf8c5,Ge8g8,Gd7d6] With control of [d5], Black can already be fairly happy and will look to continue development with ...[Bc5], ...[d6] and ...[O-O].} 8. Bg5 h6 {[%csl Gg5] You may remember this policy from the lines in Theory Six - once again, we refuse to let the bishop settle.} 9. Bh4 Bc5 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gc5d4,Gd7d6,Gg7g5] A fine spot for the bishop and there are now ideas of ...[Rb8] and ...[Bd4], as well as of ...[d6] and ...[g5].} 10. Bc4 d6 {[%cal Gc8e6] Freeing the light-squared bishop for duties, most likely on [e6].} 11. Qf3 $6 {[%csl Rf6]} g5 $1 {Dealing with the threat in a most powerful manner.} 12. Bg3 {[%csl Gg3] The bishop was hardly happy here in Kurilin-Yagupov, Tula 2006, where Black might have pressed ahead on the queenside.} Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8b2,Ga6a5]} (12... Rb8 {A slightly awkward move for White to have to face, as would be} 13. O-O-O $6 Bg4 {. Black attacks [b2] and is also ready to increase our dark-square control even further with ...[a5].}) *

