1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 {White keeps his options open and may well be aiming to avoid the Löwenthal and Kalashnikov while reaching an Open Sicilian after all following 4. [d4] [cxd4] 5. [Nxd4].} a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. a4 {White rules out ... [b5], but an early [a4] is rarely a problem for Black in the Sicilian, and this position is no exception.} Nf6 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gd7d5] Knights before bishops as we continue development. If White now does something very quiet 5...[d5] may be possible or just 5...[e6] and then 6...[d5].} 5. d4 {Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 {Naturally, we make the standard Sicilian exchange...} 6. Nxd4 e5 {[%csl Gd4] ...ahead of following up with our favourite advance. This position can be closely compared with 3. [Nc3] with 4. [d4] chapter, and it's not hard to believe that the insertion of [a2]-[a4] and ...[Nf6] must be in Black's favour.} 7. Nf5 {Trying to land the knight on [d6] after all must be critical.} d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5]} ({The thematic advance, played to undermine the white knight, although we should point out that the engines also quite like} 7... Nb4 $5 {.}) 8. exd5 Nxd5 $5 {[%cal Gc8f5,Ga8c8,Gd6c3]} ({A pawn sacrifice and dynamic alternative to the equality on offer after} 8... Bxf5 9. dxc6 bxc6 {. As well as attacking the knight, Black threatens ...[Nxc3] and 9.Nxd5 Bxf5 followed by ...[Rc8] should be comfortable enough.}) 9. Nxg7+ $5 {[%csl Re8] Taking up the challenge.} Bxg7 {[%cal Gc8e6]} 10. Nxd5 ({This seems slightly more challenging than} 10. Qxd5 Be6 $1 11. Qxd8+ Rxd8 {when Black will be very quick to begin counterplay with ...[Nb4].}) 10... Be6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gd8d1,Ga8d8,Ge5e4,Ge8g8] Black's lead in development offsets the extra pawn. As well as the pressure against [d5], there are ideas involving ...[Qa5]+, with ...[Rd8], ...[Nb4] and just ...[O-O] followed by ...[e4] all potentially pretty useful too.} 11. Bc4 O-O {Housing the king ahead of pursuing counterplay.} 12. O-O Rc8 {[%cal Gc6d4] With 13...[Nd4] imminent, Black's activity fully compensates for the pawn in both our view and that of the engines.} *

