1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 {White keeps his options open and may well be aiming to avoid the Löwenthal and Kalashnikov while reaching an Open Sicilian after all following 4. [d4] [cxd4] 5. [Nxd4].} a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. Be2 {A modest but by no means bad development as White keeps open the option of d2-d4. It should be pointed out too that this position also sometimes arises these days via a 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.Bb5 Nd4 4.Nf3 a6 5.Bd3 Nc6 6.Be2 move order.} Nf6 {[%cal Ge7e5,Gd7d5] Black too develops in a natural fashion and may now consider breaking with ...[d5], as well as advancing with ...[e5]. Of the many playable alternatives, 4...[Nd4]!?, as played by Rauf Mamedov, also avoids too much theory and seems reasonable for Black.} 5. d4 {[%cal Rd4c5,Rd4d5]} cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gf8b4,Gf8c5]} (6... e5 {Our favourite advance yet again and now both} 7. Nf3 Bc5 {and 7.Nb3 Bb4 look comfortable enough for Black.}) 7. Nf5 {This must be critical, but does also rather ask for a certain central counter-strike.} d5 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5]} (7... d5 {We're again quick to undermine the knight on f5, a policy which now} 8. Nxd5 Nxe4 {would continue.}) 8. exd5 Bxf5 ({As 4.Be2 is a more useful move than 4.a4, here} 8... Nxd5 $5 9. Nxg7+ Bxg7 {probably doesn't give Black quite enough for the pawn, so we should head down the exchanging route.}) 9. dxc6 bxc6 {[%cal Gd8c7,Ga8d8,Ge5e4,Gd8d1]} (9... bxc6 {Now ...Qc7 and ...Rd8 is one approach and} 10. Bf3 {can be met by} Qxd1+ 11. Nxd1 e4 {, so perhaps White might opt to exchange.}) 10. Qxd8+ Rxd8 {[%csl Gc2]} 11. Bxa6 Bxc2 {[%cal Gf8c5,Gc5d4,Gf6d5] An unbalanced, roughly level middlegame has arisen, one in which Black's central control offsets the passed a-pawn. One decent way to make use of the extra central control and pawns would be to go ...[Bc5]-[d4] and/or ...[Nd5].} *

