1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 {White keeps his options open and may well be aiming to avoid the Löwenthal and Kalashnikov while reaching an Open Sicilian after all following 4. [d4] [cxd4] 5. [Nxd4].} a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. Be2 {A modest but by no means bad development as White keeps open the option of d2-d4. It should be pointed out too that this position also sometimes arises these days via a 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.Bb5 Nd4 4.Nf3 a6 5.Bd3 Nc6 6.Be2 move order.} Nf6 {[%cal Ge7e5,Gd7d5] Black too develops in a natural fashion and may now consider breaking with ...[d5], as well as advancing with ...[e5]. Of the many playable alternatives, 4...[Nd4]!?, as played by Rauf Mamedov, also avoids too much theory and seems reasonable for Black.} 5. O-O e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gf8e7,Gd7d6,Gc8e6,Ge8g8]} ({Taking d2-d4 off the agenda for good and a much better way of doing so than} 5... Nd4 $2 6. e5 {. (We're now ready to solidly continue development with ...[Be7], ...[d6], ...[Be6] and ...[O-O], after which we can look to either flank for counterplay ...[b5]; ...[g6] and ...[Nh5].)}) 6. Bc4 {[%cal Rf3g5] A more active approach from White, albeit one which also moves the bishop for a second time.} Be7 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8]} (6... Be7 {The right way to develop, ensuring that} 7. Ng5 {can be safely met by} O-O {.}) 7. d3 d6 8. a4 {Ruling out ...[b5] for the time being.} O-O {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga8b8] We're now set to contest the [a2]-[g8] diagonal with ...[Be6] and may also look for counterplay with ...[Rb8].} 9. Bg5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Rg5f6] White plays for control of [d5], but we have absolutely no intention of allowing an exchange on [f6].} Ne8 $5 {[%cal Gc6e7,Gg8h8,Gf7f5]} (9... Ne8 {Trying to exchange off the bad bishop on e7. If} 10. Bxe7 {we can recapture while contesting [d5] with} Nxe7 {and if the bishop instead retreats, for example 10.Be3 , Black can either return the knight to [f6] or consider 10...Kh8!? , looking to get in a quick ...[f5].}) *

