1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 {White keeps his options open and may well be aiming to avoid the Löwenthal and Kalashnikov while reaching an Open Sicilian after all following 4. [d4] [cxd4] 5. [Nxd4].} a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. Be2 {A modest but by no means bad development as White keeps open the option of d2-d4. It should be pointed out too that this position also sometimes arises these days via a 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.Bb5 Nd4 4.Nf3 a6 5.Bd3 Nc6 6.Be2 move order.} Nf6 {[%cal Ge7e5,Gd7d5] Black too develops in a natural fashion and may now consider breaking with ...[d5], as well as advancing with ...[e5]. Of the many playable alternatives, 4...[Nd4]!?, as played by Rauf Mamedov, also avoids too much theory and seems reasonable for Black.} 5. O-O e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gf8e7,Gd7d6,Gc8e6,Ge8g8]} ({Taking d2-d4 off the agenda for good and a much better way of doing so than} 5... Nd4 $2 6. e5 {. (We're now ready to solidly continue development with ...[Be7], ...[d6], ...[Be6] and ...[O-O], after which we can look to either flank for counterplay ...[b5]; ...[g6] and ...[Nh5].)}) 6. d3 Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d6] Sensible development; ...[d6] and ...[O-O] will follow.} 7. Bg5 d6 {[%cal Ge7f6] There's no reason to fear an exchange on [f6] here, when Black might follow up with ...[Be6] and perhaps even ...[g6] and ...[Bg7].} 8. Nd2 $5 O-O ({A simpler approach than} 8... b5 $5 {.}) 9. Nc4 Be6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga8b8]} (9... Be6 {Completing development, and now we're all set to expand with ...b5, or if} 10. a4 Rb8 {.}) 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Ne3 Bg5 $1 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gc6e7,Gf7f5,Gb7b5] While White was in control of [d5], Black was quite comfortable and even went on to pull off a major upset in Carlsen-Lenic, PRO League rapid 2018. Black can contest [d5] with ...[Ne7] and will look to expand with ...[b5] and/or ...[g6] and ...[f5].} *

