1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. g3 ({This is perhaps the most sensible of White's alternatives to} 4. d4 {, bringing the light-squared bishop to [g2] while keeping open the option of a timely [d2]-[d4].}) 4... d6 {[%cal Gc8g4] (By no means Black's only decent approach if you have some experience of the Dragon, 4...g6 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4 Bg7 should be a reasonable type of fianchetto Dragon, and 4...[e5]!? is a decent, independent option, one which can be followed up in reverse Botvinnik English fashion with ...[g6], ...[Bg7] and ...[Nge7], but by freeing the light-squared bishop for early duties, we get ready to compete for the [d4]-square with ...[Bg4].)} 5. d4 $5 Bg4 $5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gd6c5]} ({Even here the bishop development is possible and a good alternative to} 5... cxd4 {. We immediately pressure [d4] and would stand well after dxc5 dxc5 when Qxd8+?! Rxd8 would threaten not only ...[Bxf3], but ...[Nb4].}) 6. d5 Nd4 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] With a certain threat and in this active type of Benoni situation, Black will look to control the long dark-square diagonal after ...[g6] and ...[Bg7].} 7. Bg2 g6 {[%cal Gf8g7]} 8. h3 {[%csl Rg4]} Bxf3 {Early exchanges are fine for Black, with the dark-squared bishop en route to a fine diagonal.} 9. Bxf3 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Rf3g2,Rc3b1]} Nxf3+ $1 (9... Nxf3+ {Yes, we give up the good-looking knight for the bishop. Why? Well, Bg2 is actual a small threat and then Nb1! , creating problems for the knight on [d4] while preparing to regroup the white knight to a fine and thematic post on [c4].}) 10. Qxf3 Bg7 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gg8f6] Now we may even consider 11...[b5], as well as just 11...[Nf6].} 11. a4 b6 $1 {[%cal Gd8d7,Gg8f6,Ge8g8] Preventing White from clamping down with [a4]-[a5] and now Black may look to force through ...[b5] after ...[Nf6] and ...[O-O], perhaps just with ...[Qd7].} 12. O-O Nf6 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd8d7,Gf6e8,Ge8c7] This was a reasonable Benoni set-up for Black in Savicevic-Ljangov, Nis 1997. The early piece exchanges have helped Black avoid any cramp and ...[O-O] will follow, then perhaps ...[Qd7] or ...[Ne8]-[c7], unfurling the bishop on [g7] while forcing through ...[b5].} *

