1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. g3 ({This is perhaps the most sensible of White's alternatives to} 4. d4 {, bringing the light-squared bishop to [g2] while keeping open the option of a timely [d2]-[d4].}) 4... d6 {[%cal Gc8g4] (By no means Black's only decent approach if you have some experience of the Dragon, 4...g6 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4 Bg7 should be a reasonable type of fianchetto Dragon, and 4...[e5]!? is a decent, independent option, one which can be followed up in reverse Botvinnik English fashion with ...[g6], ...[Bg7] and ...[Nge7], but by freeing the light-squared bishop for early duties, we get ready to compete for the [d4]-square with ...[Bg4].)} 5. Bg2 {White has usually tended to complete the fianchetto so.} Bg4 {[%csl Gd4,Gf3][%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] Pinning while taking control of d4, and this position can arise from a few different move orders, including 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.Nc3 a6 4.g3 Nc6 5.Bg2 Bg4 .} 6. Nd5 $5 (6. Nd5 {A typically creative idea from Oleg Romanishin. White prepares to meet} g6 {with} 7. c3 {, so Black should change tack and take the tempo gain on offer.}) 6... e6 {[%csl Gd5]} 7. Ne3 Bh5 $1 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Retaining the bishop makes sense here. With ...[Nf6] imminent, it won't be at all easy for White to force through [c2]-[c3] and [d2]-[d4], while Black should be able to complete development with ...[Be7] and ...[O-O].} 8. g4 $5 {[%csl Rh5]} Bg6 {[%csl Ge4]} 9. d3 h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5g4]} (9... h5 {Challenging White's ambitious approach head on. We're all set to exchange on g4 and} 10. h3 f6 $1 {also looks fairly comfortable followed by ...[Bf7] and ...[Nge7].}) 10. g5 {[%cal Rh2h4]} h4 $1 (10... h4 {Preventing White from making this move himself and threatening to take over with} 11. Z0 h3 12. Bf1 Nge7 {followed by ...[d5].}) 11. h3 Nge7 {[%cal Gg6h5,Ge7g6,Gf8e7,Gd8c7,Ge8c8,Gd6d5]} ({A sensible alternative to the} 11... Be7 12. Ng4 f6 $5 {of Romanishin-Timman, Tilburg 1979. With the text move, we get ready to return the bishop to [h5], after which Black may untangle with ...[Ng6] and ...[Be7] or go in for something more aggressive in the shape of ...[Qc7], ...[O-O-O] and ...[d5].}) *

