1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. g3 ({This is perhaps the most sensible of White's alternatives to} 4. d4 {, bringing the light-squared bishop to [g2] while keeping open the option of a timely [d2]-[d4].}) 4... d6 {[%cal Gc8g4] (By no means Black's only decent approach if you have some experience of the Dragon, 4...g6 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4 Bg7 should be a reasonable type of fianchetto Dragon, and 4...[e5]!? is a decent, independent option, one which can be followed up in reverse Botvinnik English fashion with ...[g6], ...[Bg7] and ...[Nge7], but by freeing the light-squared bishop for early duties, we get ready to compete for the [d4]-square with ...[Bg4].)} 5. Bg2 {White has usually tended to complete the fianchetto so.} Bg4 {[%csl Gd4,Gf3][%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] Pinning while taking control of d4, and this position can arise from a few different move orders, including 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.Nc3 a6 4.g3 Nc6 5.Bg2 Bg4 .} 6. h3 {White tends to challenge the bishop so before Black simply reinforces our control of [d4] with ...[g6] and ... [Bg7].} Bxf3 $1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7]} ({Exchanging to take control of d4. Now ...g6 will quickly follow and this is a much better approach than} 6... Bh5 $6 7. g4 Bg6 8. d4 {.}) 7. Qxf3 e6 $5 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5][%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7]} ({Carlsen no less has preferred} 7... g6 {, but then} 8. e5 $5 {is slightly annoying with the positional threat of} Z0 9. Qxc6+ bxc6 10. Bxc6+ {. With the text, we improve our central control while still intending to fianchetto on the kingside.}) 8. O-O g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gg8e7,Ge8g8] Black is set to complete development in fairly harmonious fashion with ...[Bg7], ...[Nge7] and ...[O-O], so perhaps White would aim for a quick [d2]-[d4].} 9. Ne2 Bg7 10. c3 Nge7 {[%cal Gd6d5]} (10... Nge7 {We're ready to castle and even have ideas of breaking with ...d5. Moreover, if now} 11. d4 $5 cxd4 12. cxd4 {you may prefer the positionally sensible} d5 $5 {to grabbing the d-pawn.}) 11. Rd1 O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4,Ga8b8,Gd6d5,Ge7d5]} (11... O-O {Black can now look to ...b5, ...Rb8 and ...b4 for counterplay or simply hit back with} 12. Z0 d5 {, and if} 13. exd5 Nxd5 {.}) 12. d4 cxd4 13. cxd4 d5 $1 {[%cal Ge7d5]} (13... d5 {Preventing White from dominating the centre, and he would now be saddled with an IQP in the event of} 14. exd5 Nxd5 {.}) 14. e5 f6 $5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gf6e5,Gg7f6,Ge7f5]} (14... f6 {Black enjoys decent counterplay, either against e5 or d4 in the event of} 15. exf6 Bxf6 {.}) *

