1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. g3 ({This is perhaps the most sensible of White's alternatives to} 4. d4 {, bringing the light-squared bishop to [g2] while keeping open the option of a timely [d2]-[d4].}) 4... d6 {[%cal Gc8g4] (By no means Black's only decent approach if you have some experience of the Dragon, 4...g6 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4 Bg7 should be a reasonable type of fianchetto Dragon, and 4...[e5]!? is a decent, independent option, one which can be followed up in reverse Botvinnik English fashion with ...[g6], ...[Bg7] and ...[Nge7], but by freeing the light-squared bishop for early duties, we get ready to compete for the [d4]-square with ...[Bg4].)} 5. Bg2 {White has usually tended to complete the fianchetto so.} Bg4 {[%csl Gd4,Gf3][%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] Pinning while taking control of d4, and this position can arise from a few different move orders, including 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.Nc3 a6 4.g3 Nc6 5.Bg2 Bg4 .} 6. h3 {White tends to challenge the bishop so before Black simply reinforces our control of [d4] with ...[g6] and ... [Bg7].} Bxf3 $1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7]} ({Exchanging to take control of d4. Now ...g6 will quickly follow and this is a much better approach than} 6... Bh5 $6 7. g4 Bg6 8. d4 {.}) 7. Bxf3 {The more popular recapture.} g6 {[%cal Gf8g7] The bishop will be pretty happy on the long dark-square diagonal.} 8. d3 Bg7 9. Be3 e6 $1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gg8e7] By preparing to bring the knight to [e7], rather than develop it to [f6], Black keeps the fianchettoed bishop unobstructed and has firm control over [d4].} 10. Bg2 Nge7 11. Qd2 (11. Qd2 {Here Black went} Rc8 {in Pribyl-Ubilava, Tbilisi 1980, and it was also possible to advance without delay.}) 11... b5 $5 {[%cal Gb5b4,Ga8b8,Gh7h5] We're now ready to drive the knight back to [d1] with ...[b4], after which ...[Rb8] is likely to be a useful move, stepping off the long diagonal and getting ready for any [c2]-[c3] break from White.} (11... b5 {It may also be prudent to wait for White to castle before doing so and here} 12. h4 h5 $1 {will usefully keep lines closed.}) 12. Bh6 {[%csl Rg7]} Bxh6 13. Qxh6 Nd4 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gd8a5]} (13... Nd4 {We can't castle for the time, but best play would now be} 14. Qd2 O-O {as both 14.Rc1? Qa5 and 14.O-O-O?? Qa5 would leave Black doing pretty well on the queenside.}) *

