1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. g3 ({This is perhaps the most sensible of White's alternatives to} 4. d4 {, bringing the light-squared bishop to [g2] while keeping open the option of a timely [d2]-[d4].}) 4... d6 {[%cal Gc8g4] (By no means Black's only decent approach if you have some experience of the Dragon, 4...g6 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4 Bg7 should be a reasonable type of fianchetto Dragon, and 4...[e5]!? is a decent, independent option, one which can be followed up in reverse Botvinnik English fashion with ...[g6], ...[Bg7] and ...[Nge7], but by freeing the light-squared bishop for early duties, we get ready to compete for the [d4]-square with ...[Bg4].)} 5. Bg2 {White has usually tended to complete the fianchetto so.} Bg4 {[%csl Gd4,Gf3][%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] Pinning while taking control of d4, and this position can arise from a few different move orders, including 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.Nc3 a6 4.g3 Nc6 5.Bg2 Bg4 .} 6. h3 {White tends to challenge the bishop so before Black simply reinforces our control of [d4] with ...[g6] and ... [Bg7].} Bxf3 $1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7]} ({Exchanging to take control of d4. Now ...g6 will quickly follow and this is a much better approach than} 6... Bh5 $6 7. g4 Bg6 8. d4 {.}) 7. Bxf3 {The more popular recapture.} g6 {[%cal Gf8g7] The bishop will be pretty happy on the long dark-square diagonal.} 8. O-O {A fairly flexible choice, keeping White's options open.} (8. Nd5 $5 Bg7 9. O-O e6 {Here we even get to develop with tempo.} 10. Ne3 Nge7 {All is now set for castling and we may seize some fairly useful space with ...[b5].} 11. Bg2 O-O 12. f4 f5 $1 {One of two good moves, the other being 12...[d5]. The text borrowed a well-known idea from the Closed Sicilian to frustrate White's kingside ambitions in Zvjaginsev-Nepomniachtchi, Serpukhov 2008, where Black was set to follow up with either ...[d5] or queenside expansion thorough ...[b5] and ...[Rb8]. And, yes, just like in the Closed Sicilian,} 13. exf5 gxf5 {would be possible to leave Black with good central control.}) 8... Bg7 9. Bg2 e6 $5 {[%cal Gg8e7]} ({Several grandmasters have preferred} 9... Nf6 10. d3 O-O {here, but our favourite development scheme is also a decent option.}) 10. d3 Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gb7b5] Facilitating castling ahead of queenside expansion with ...[b5].} 11. Be3 O-O {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4] Everything is now in place for 12...[b5], seizing space and looking to target [b2].} 12. Qd2 b5 {[%cal Gb5b4,Ga6a5,Gc6d4] With ...[b4] and ...[a5] on the way, as well as a timely ...[Nd4], Black enjoyed easy play in Fuller-Iskov, Nice Olympiad 1974, where the unopposed bishop on [g2] was yet to really influence the game.} *

