1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nde2 {Nakamura's choice in a rapid game.} Bc5 {[%cal Gd7d6,Gd8b6] Our favourite post for the bishop in such structures. As we've seen, without ...[a6] in Black would have 6...[Qb6] here, but ...[a6] can hardly be a terrible move to have included, and we're now ready to develop with ...[d6], assuming that is White spots and deals with the threat of 7...[Qb6].} 7. Nd5 {[%csl Rb6]} ({An alert choice, whereas} 7. g3 $2 Qb6 8. Be3 Bxe3 9. fxe3 {might just have been met by} Qxe3 {in Player-Sariego, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023.}) 7... Nge7 {[%cal Ge7d5]} (7... Nge7 {The best way to challenge the white knight. We're ready to go} 8. Z0 Nxd5 {, and if} 9. Qxd5 Qb6 {or 9.exd5 Ne7 , while unlike after 7...[Nf6] any [Bg5] pin is now somewhat easier to meet, including with 8.Bg5 h6 .}) 8. Nec3 d6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ge8g8,Ga8c8,Gb7b5] Our favourite development scheme. Black is fine here with 9...[Be6] and 10...[O-O] the plan, after which we might look to the queenside for counterplay with ...[Rc8] and/or ...[b5], or consider kingside ideas involving ...[Ng6].} *

