1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nf3 {Against this unassuming retreat Black has tended to go 6... [Bb4], but our favourite spot for the bishop is also available.} Bc5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd7d6] Playing as per Line 6C. This isn't quite such a good version, but still seems fine for Black with ...[Nf6] and ...[d6] on their way. The early ...[a6] also gives the bishop a potential retreat square and enables us to consider a fairly early ...[b5].} 7. Be2 d6 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gg8e7] A move we definitely want to play and the king's knight may come to [e7], as well as [f6].} 8. Nd5 Nge7 $1 {[%cal Ge7d5]} ({Much stronger than} 8... Nf6 $6 9. Bg5 {and now 9.Bg5 can be met by 9...h6 , and if 10.Bh4? g5 , driving the bishop into something of a tomb on [g3]. We're also all set to exchange on [d5].}) 9. Nxe7 Nxe7 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge8g8] Not allowing White to dominate [d5] ahead of castling.} 10. O-O O-O 11. a3 Ng6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga8c8,Gf7f5,Gd6d5] Black was very comfortable here in Blandon-Burgos Figueroa, Managua 2015, with ...[Be6] and ...[Rc8] on the way, after which we might force through ...[d5] and there's also the ...[f5] break if you prefer a more aggressive kingside policy.} *

