1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nf3 {Against this unassuming retreat Black has tended to go 6... [Bb4], but our favourite spot for the bishop is also available.} Bc5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd7d6] Playing as per Line 6C. This isn't quite such a good version, but still seems fine for Black with ...[Nf6] and ...[d6] on their way. The early ...[a6] also gives the bishop a potential retreat square and enables us to consider a fairly early ...[b5].} 7. Bc4 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Rc4f7] The only really challenging move, one which does carry a definite threat.} Nf6 {[%csl Gd5]} ({A far stronger way of covering d5 and h5 than} 7... Nge7 $2 8. Ng5 {would be, and if} O-O 9. Qh5 {.}) 8. Bg5 d6 $5 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gc8e6,Gh7h6]} (8... d6 {Very calm and now play may transpose to our 8.O-O line after} 9. O-O h6 {, but what happens if White is provoked?}) 9. Nd5 $6 Bxf2+ $1 {[%csl Gc4,Gg5]} (9... Bxf2+ {(The problem: White's bishops yes, both are loose. Now)} 10. Ke2 Ba7 {would give him some compensation thanks to the pin, whereas taking the bishop isn't especially wise.}) 10. Kxf2 Nxe4+ {[%csl Gf2,Gg5]} 11. Kg1 {The relatively best square according to the engines.} Nxg5 12. Nxg5 Qxg5 {[%csl Gc4,Gg1][%cal Ge8g8] Taking stock, we find Black two pawns up, albeit with the rook on [a8] in trouble. However, so is the bishop on [c4], just as it would be being the white king on [f1] ...[Qf4]+ or [e1] ...[Qh4]+.} 13. Nc7+ {[%csl Re8]} Ke7 14. Nxa8 Qe3+ $1 {The key resource and now the bishop must fall after all.} 15. Kf1 Qf4+ 16. Kg1 Qxc4 {[%csl Ga8] Black has a strong centre and two pawns for the exchange, and the white knight is far from happy. Stockfish assesses at over '+3' for Black.} *

