1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nf3 {Against this unassuming retreat Black has tended to go 6... [Bb4], but our favourite spot for the bishop is also available.} Bc5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd7d6] Playing as per Line 6C. This isn't quite such a good version, but still seems fine for Black with ...[Nf6] and ...[d6] on their way. The early ...[a6] also gives the bishop a potential retreat square and enables us to consider a fairly early ...[b5].} 7. Bc4 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Rc4f7] The only really challenging move, one which does carry a definite threat.} Nf6 {[%csl Gd5]} ({A far stronger way of covering d5 and h5 than} 7... Nge7 $2 8. Ng5 {would be, and if} O-O 9. Qh5 {.}) 8. O-O d6 {[%cal Gc8e6] Preparing to continue development while challenging the bishop on [c4] with ...[Be6].} 9. h3 {Slow, but possibly White was concerned by ...[Bg4] ideas.} Be6 {[%csl Gc4]} (9... Be6 {The right square for our bishop in any case, yet again hoping to be left with a dynamic centre, half-open f-file and control of d5 after} 10. Bxe6 $6 fxe6 {.}) 10. Bb3 O-O (10... O-O {Calmly continuing the plan while preserving the tension down the a2-g8 diagonal and now} 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Nd5 Qd8 {followed by ...[Ne7] would remain very solid and fine for Black.}) 11. Qd3 h6 {[%csl Gg5] Ruling out [Bg5] ideas for good. Black might also have sought counterplay with the immediate 11...[Na5]!?.} 12. Be3 Bxe3 ({The most natural way of dealing with the semi-threat, although it should be said that the engines indicate the radical} 12... Qc7 $5 {is also fine.}) 13. Qxe3 {We've followed Shevelev-Pantsulaia, European Individual Championship, Batumi 2018, where Black went 13...[Na5] and it was also possible to fully equalise with the ideal Sicilian central break.} Bxb3 $5 14. axb3 d5 {[%cal Gd5d4] The aforementioned, classic break.} 15. exd5 Nxd5 {[%cal Gd5e3]} 16. Nxd5 Qxd5 {[%cal Gd5e6,Ga8d8] The queen can drop back to [e6] if attacked and with ...[Rad8] on the way, Black has absolutely no problems.} *

