1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nf3 {Against this unassuming retreat Black has tended to go 6... [Bb4], but our favourite spot for the bishop is also available.} Bc5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gg8f6,Gd7d6] Playing as per Line 6C. This isn't quite such a good version, but still seems fine for Black with ...[Nf6] and ...[d6] on their way. The early ...[a6] also gives the bishop a potential retreat square and enables us to consider a fairly early ...[b5].} 7. Bc4 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Rc4f7] The only really challenging move, one which does carry a definite threat.} Nf6 {[%csl Gd5]} ({A far stronger way of covering d5 and h5 than} 7... Nge7 $2 8. Ng5 {would be, and if} O-O 9. Qh5 {.}) 8. O-O d6 {[%cal Gc8e6] Preparing to continue development while challenging the bishop on [c4] with ...[Be6].} 9. Bg5 {[%cal Rc3d5]} h6 {[%csl Gg5] With [f2] secure, the bishop absolutely must be challenged.} 10. Bxf6 ({The critical choice and more of a challenge for Black than} 10. Bh4 $2 g5 {would be.}) 10... Qxf6 11. Nd5 {[%csl Rc7,Rf6]} Qd8 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ge8g8,Gg8h8,Gh8f8,Gf7f5,Gc8e6] A forced move. While White does dominate [d5], compared to, say, a Sveshnikov our dark-squared bishop is outside the pawn chain and we can play around the knight on [d5]. Indeed, while castling might be followed up by ...[Be6], a more aggressive approach with ... [Kh8] and ...[f5] may also be possible.} 12. c3 O-O 13. b4 $5 {[%csl Rc5]} Ba7 {Making good use of the inclusion of ...[a6] back on move three.} 14. Qe2 Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc6e7] With ...[Rc8] and ...[Ne7] on the way, Black was fine in Anwesh-Minasian, Dubai 2011.} *

