1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nb3 {White's second most common move in tournament praxis, if not one Black needs to fear.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gd7d6,Gf8b4] Keeping options open for the dark-squared bishop: we can either go ... [Bb4] or ...[Be7] and ...[d6].} 7. Nd5 $5 (7. Nd5 {Now} Nxd5 8. exd5 Nb8 {(would be Pelikan Sveshnikov like, but we can also be provocative in turn.)}) 7... d6 $5 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gc6e7] Black is now ready to exchange on [d5] followed by bringing the knight round to the kingside via [e7], and refuses to fear a certain pin.} 8. Bg5 {[%cal Rg5f6]} Be7 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gf6d5,Ge7f6]} (8... Be7 {Keeping the structure intact, creating a big threat, and Black's control of d5 and easy development would offset the bishop-pair if now} 9. Nxe7 Qxe7 {.}) 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Bc4 Bg5 $5 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ge8g8,Ga8c8,Gc6e7] Preserving the bishop while getting ready for a timely ...[Ne7]. With ....[Be6], ...[O-O], ...[Rc8] and the aforementioned ...[Ne7] on the way, Black shouldn't be doing too badly.} *

