1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nb3 {White's second most common move in tournament praxis, if not one Black needs to fear.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gd7d6,Gf8b4] Keeping options open for the dark-squared bishop: we can either go ... [Bb4] or ...[Be7] and ...[d6].} 7. Be2 Bb4 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gd7d5]} (7... Bb4 {With White not looking too active, the more ambitious bishop development is tempting. Black has an immediate threat and would already stand better after} 8. f3 $6 d5 {.}) 8. O-O $5 {[%cal Rc3d5]} Bxc3 {Taking up the challenge.} 9. bxc3 Nxe4 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gd7d6,Ge4f6]} (9... Nxe4 {Stealing the pawn. Black can follow up with ...d5 or if} 10. Bd3 {simply go} Nf6 {then ...[d6] and ...[O-O].}) 10. Qd3 $5 {[%csl Re4]} d5 11. Ba3 Be6 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gd5c4]} (11... Be6 {White's dark-squared bishop gave him some compensation for the pawn, but Black still appeared comfortable enough in Sandor-Ordog, Miercurea Ciuc 2017, with ...f5 on possibility and that of meeting} 12. c4 {with} dxc4 {another.}) *

