1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nb3 {White's second most common move in tournament praxis, if not one Black needs to fear.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gd7d6,Gf8b4] Keeping options open for the dark-squared bishop: we can either go ... [Bb4] or ...[Be7] and ...[d6].} 7. Bg5 {[%cal Rc3d5] Threatening to cause havoc with [Nd5].} Bb4 {[%cal Gb4c3,Gh7h6]} ({This counter-pin, with the ideas of ...Bxc3+ and ...h6, is a more active approach than allowing White a small if tolerable edge after} 7... Be7 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. Nd5 {.}) 8. Qd3 Bxc3+ $5 {[%csl Ge4]} (8... Bxc3+ {Insisting on structural ruin after all, unless White prefers to lose a pawn to} 9. Qxc3 $6 Nxe4 {.}) 9. bxc3 d6 $1 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gh7h6] Preparing to go ...[Be6], while keeping ...[h6] prods in reserve.} 10. Rd1 Be6 {[%csl Ge4]} (10... Be6 {Clearly Black would be delighted to see} 11. Qxd6 $4 Qxd6 12. Rxd6 Nxe4 {, so White must preface any pawn grab with an exchange on [f6].}) 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Qxd6 Qg6 {[%csl Ge4,Gg2][%cal Ga8d8,Gg6e4] The position is quite unclear, with neither king completely happy, but Black looks to have decent compensation. As well as the standard Lowenthal pressure against [e4] and [g2], White's queenside pawns are wrecked and ...[Rd8] on the way.} 13. f3 Qg5 {[%cal Gg5e3,Ga8d8] A timely switch to the dark squares.} 14. Qd2 Qe7 $5 {[%csl Ga2,Gc3][%cal Ge8g8,Ga8c8] This must be at least full compensation. Black is now ready to castle and after, say, ...Rac8 and ...[Qa3] may begin to target the white queenside.} *

