1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nxc6 $5 {White angles for an improved version of 5. [Nxc6]} dxc6 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd8d1,Ge8d8,Gd8h4] A perhaps unexpected recapture, but as Löwenthal players we don't mind an early exchange of queens and this way take control of [d5] and obtain a fairly comfortable game.} ({If you really would though prefer something more lively,} 6... bxc6 $5 {is playable, even if the value of having gone ...[a6] is then fairly low and the critical line may be} 7. Qh5 $1 Bd6 $1 8. Bc4 Qe7 {followed by ...[Nf6]. The text move avoids such contortions and gets ready to exchange on [d1] or even go 7...[Qh4] should White, slightly strangely, not exchange on [d8].}) 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gf8c5,Gc8e6] Left alone, Black will now improve the bishops with ...[Be6] and ...[Bc5], likely also placing the king on [c7]. The one small downside to our position is the slightly weakened dark squares on the queenside, although in return we do have full control of [d5].} 8. Bc4 {[%csl Gf7]} (8. Bc4 {This must be critical and now} Be6 $6 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Ke2 {was pretty grim for Black in Dubov-Ashiku, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2022.}) (8. Bc4 {Likewise,} f6 9. Be3 {saw White's lead in development become a little annoying back in Rossolimo-Steiner, Venice 1950, so we should defend the f-pawn.}) 8... Ke7 $5 {[%cal Gc8e6]} ({A perhaps unexpected approach compared to} 8... Ke8 {, but the idea is clear: to challenge for control of the [a2]-[g8] diagonal with 9...[Be6].}) 9. f4 $5 {This pawn break is ever a critical try when ever there's an early exchange of queens on [d8].} Be6 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Ge5f4]} (9... Be6 {Developing with tempo and now} 10. Be2 exf4 11. Bxf4 Nf6 {followed by ... [Rd8] or ...[Nd7] would be very solid for Black, so White might prefer to exchange.}) 10. Bxe6 Kxe6 {[%cal Ga8d8,Ge5f4,Gg8e7,Gg8f6,Gf8c5] We're now ready to weaken White's structure with an exchange on [f4], as well as bring the rook to [d8] or just go ...[Bc5].} (10... Kxe6 {Note too how} 11. fxe5 Ne7 {followed by ...[Ng6] and ...[Nxe5] will regain the pawn while activating the knight.}) 11. f5+ $5 Kd7 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf8b4,Gg8f6] White has a small space advantage here, but Black's position is quite playable with ...[Bb4] and ...[Nf6] on the way, pressuring [e4] while meeting any checks on the d-file with ...[Kc7].} 12. Be3 {[%cal Rc3a4]} (12. Be3 {Now} Bb4 13. O-O-O+ Kc7 14. Na4 $1 {is a little awkward for Black, so we should first activate the knight to pressure [e4].}) 12... Nf6 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7c7,Gf8b4,Gf6d7,Gb7b5,Gh7h5]} (12... Nf6 {Only now do we want to consider ...Bb4 as an idea, while meeting} 13. O-O-O+ Kc7 14. Na4 $2 {with} b5 $1 {to seize the initiative. Once the king is on [c7], the knight may regroup via [d7] while a a timely...[h5] may help to battle for space on the kingside.}) *

