1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nxc6 $5 {White angles for an improved version of 5. [Nxc6]} dxc6 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd8d1,Ge8d8,Gd8h4] A perhaps unexpected recapture, but as Löwenthal players we don't mind an early exchange of queens and this way take control of [d5] and obtain a fairly comfortable game.} ({If you really would though prefer something more lively,} 6... bxc6 $5 {is playable, even if the value of having gone ...[a6] is then fairly low and the critical line may be} 7. Qh5 $1 Bd6 $1 8. Bc4 Qe7 {followed by ...[Nf6]. The text move avoids such contortions and gets ready to exchange on [d1] or even go 7...[Qh4] should White, slightly strangely, not exchange on [d8].}) 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gf8c5,Gc8e6] Left alone, Black will now improve the bishops with ...[Be6] and ...[Bc5], likely also placing the king on [c7]. The one small downside to our position is the slightly weakened dark squares on the queenside, although in return we do have full control of [d5].} 8. Bc4 {[%csl Gf7]} (8. Bc4 {This must be critical and now} Be6 $6 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Ke2 {was pretty grim for Black in Dubov-Ashiku, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2022.}) (8. Bc4 {Likewise,} f6 9. Be3 {saw White's lead in development become a little annoying back in Rossolimo-Steiner, Venice 1950, so we should defend the f-pawn.}) 8... Ke7 $5 {[%cal Gc8e6]} ({A perhaps unexpected approach compared to} 8... Ke8 {, but the idea is clear: to challenge for control of the [a2]-[g8] diagonal with 9...[Be6].}) 9. Na4 {White plays to probe the holes on the queenside.} Be6 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Ga8d8] A consistent choice, one which also frees [d8] for the rook.} 10. Be3 $5 {[%cal Re3c5] Now [Bc5]+ may become annoying, but this is only really a slightly clever way of exchanging pieces. A challenge which Black should take up.} Bxc4 {Forcing the pace.} 11. Nb6 {[%csl Ra8,Rc4]} Rd8 12. Nxc4 {[%csl Re5]} (12. Nxc4 {Now} Nf6 $2 13. Bb6 {quickly became unpleasant for Black's king and e-pawn in De Waele-Ottenweller, correspondence 2009, but it's not so hard to improve here.}) 12... Ke6 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Gf8][%cal Gg8f6,Gf8e7] Securing the e-pawn while freeing the dark-squared bishop for action. Black will likely continue with 13...[Nf6] then simply go 14...[Be7] to connect the rooks, after which ...[Nd7] will be one plan, ...[Ne8]-[d6] another and it may also be possible to begin to advance the kingside pawns.} 13. Ke2 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4]} 14. f3 {Securing [e4] while also keeping the knight out of [g4].} Be7 {[%cal Gd8d7,Gf6d7,Gh7h5] Development is complete and Black might now fight on the kingside with ...[h5], regroup the knight via [d7] or simply use that square to double the rooks.} 15. g4 $5 {Seizing the space on offer.} (15. Na5 {Keeping everything secure while creating the possibility of doubling rooks.} Rd7 16. Rhd1 Rhd8 17. Rxd7 {White single-mindedly plays to target [b7].} Rxd7 18. Rd1 Rc7 $1 {Keeping the rooks on and maintaining the balance. Moreover, Black is all set to begin to assume the upper hand with ...[b5] and ...[Nd7]-[c5].} 19. Bb6 Rc8 20. Nxb7 $5 {((Actually possible as 20...Rb8? 21.Nc5+ Bxc5 22.Bxc5 Rxb2 23.Bf8! is very annoying, but Black can easily sidestep that issue.))} Nd7 $1 21. Be3 Rb8 {Black will regain the pawn on [b2] with an active game and at least full equality.}) 15... Nd7 $1 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Gb7b5,Gh7h5] Improving the knight while covering [b6]. We may now look to expand with ...[b5] or even ...[h5].} 16. Na5 Rc8 $1 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gb7b5]} (16... Rc8 {Black is fine here and having covered c6, may begin to advance with ...b5. White can take on b7, but it would seem unlikely that} 17. Nxb7 Rb8 18. Na5 Rxb2 {is going to be a great trade for him.}) *

