1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nf5 $1 {Eyeing the weakness on [d6] must again be critical.} d6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gc8f5]} ({Necessary here, as} 6... d5 $2 7. Nxd5 {achieves little. As such, we have to go in for more of a Kalashnikov approach. Black is ready to go ...[Be6] and may also meet something slow from White with the unbalancing 7.-- Bxf5 8.exf5 Nge7 .}) 7. Bc4 $5 {The second-most common played move here, provoking the exchange on [d5].} Be6 {[%csl Gc4]} ({And our standard response to a white bishop appearing on c4, wasting no time in contesting the diagonal while preventing White from taking control with} 7... Nf6 8. Bg5 {or 7...Bxf5?! 8.exf5 Nf6 9.O-O Be7 10.Nd5 and [c2]-[c3].}) 8. Nd5 $5 (8. Nd5 {Now} g6 9. Nfe3 {would leave White with the right piece on [d5], one which Black should perhaps challenge without delay.}) 8... Nb4 $5 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5,Ge6][%cal Gg8f6,Gb4d5] A new idea, exploiting the pin and intending 9...Nxd5 10.Bxd5 Qd7 then ...[Nf6] or even 9...Nf6 .} 9. Nxb4 Bxc4 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gc4e6]} (9... Bxc4 {Now we're all set to go ...Nf6 and} 10. Ne3 Be6 {would retain the bishop, at least for now.}) 10. Nd5 Nf6 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gf6e4,Gd8a5]} (10... Nf6 {Developing with more than one threat and here} 11. Bg5 $6 {would run into} Bxd5 $1 12. exd5 Qa5+ {.}) 11. Nxf6+ {[%csl Re8]} Qxf6 {[%cal Gd6d5]} 12. Ne3 {[%csl Rc4] Ruling out the threatening liberating break whilst regrouping the knight with tempo.} Be6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Gf6g6] Now as well as ...[Be7] and ...[O-O], Black may be able to get in our favourite ...[Qg6] device.} 13. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Rd5c7]} Bxd5 $5 {Refusing to retreat the queen.} 14. Qxd5 {[%csl Rb7]} Rb8 {[%cal Gf6e6,Ge6d5] White may be a touch better thanks to his control of [d5], but the black position shouldn't be too concerning. 15...[Qe6] is top of the agenda, angling for ...[Qxd5], and if [exd5] [f5]. As such, White might hurry a rook to [d1].} 15. Be3 Qe6 {[%cal Ge6d5]} 16. Rd1 Be7 {[%cal Ge6d5,Ge8d7]} (16... Be7 {There's no huge rush to exchange. Only now do we want to go} 17. Z0 Qxd5 {, and if} 18. Rxd5 Kd7 {, connecting the rooks and perhaps intending queenside counterplay with ...[b5] and ...[Rhc8], as well as to bring the king to [e6].}) *

