1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nf5 $1 {Eyeing the weakness on [d6] must again be critical.} d6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gc8f5]} ({Necessary here, as} 6... d5 $2 7. Nxd5 {achieves little. As such, we have to go in for more of a Kalashnikov approach. Black is ready to go ...[Be6] and may also meet something slow from White with the unbalancing 7.-- Bxf5 8.exf5 Nge7 .}) 7. Bc4 $5 {The second-most common played move here, provoking the exchange on [d5].} Be6 {[%csl Gc4]} ({And our standard response to a white bishop appearing on c4, wasting no time in contesting the diagonal while preventing White from taking control with} 7... Nf6 8. Bg5 {or 7...Bxf5?! 8.exf5 Nf6 9.O-O Be7 10.Nd5 and [c2]-[c3].}) 8. Bb3 $1 ({Preserving the bishop so makes more sense than} 8. Bd5 {when Black should be OK after} g6 9. Ne3 Nf6 {.}) 8... Rc8 $5 {[%cal Gc6a5,Gc6d4,Gg7g6]} ({Improving the rook while waiting to see what White is up to. Black has sometimes preferred} 8... g6 9. Ne3 Nd4 {, but then} 10. Ned5 $1 {followed by [Be3] only helps White to take control. Instead, we place a bit of potential pressure on the c-file, which may help ...[g6] and ...[Nd4] ideas, and ...[Na5] will also help to open up the rook's gaze.}) 9. O-O g6 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gf8g7] Driving the knight back while creating the option of a fianchetto.} 10. Ne3 Nd4 {[%cal Gd4b3,Gf8g7,Gg8f6] We may now get to remove the bishop on [b3] and/or develop the kingside with ...[Nf6] and ...[Bg7].} 11. Ned5 Bg7 {[%cal Gg8f6]} ({A somewhat sounder method of development than} 11... Nf6 $2 12. Bg5 {when} Bg7 13. f4 $1 {would already be quite awkward. Now though we are ready to go 12...Nf6 , and if 13.Bg5 h6 .}) 12. Be3 Nf6 $5 {[%cal Gf6d5] Ignoring the attack on [d4] to catch up in the development stakes. White may be slightly better here, but Black's position is quite playable, and we're ready to exchange knights on [d5]. White can take the pawn, but then Black will certainly obtain decent activity in return.} 13. Bxd4 exd4 14. Qxd4 O-O {[%csl Gb2,Gc3,Gg7][%cal Gf6d5] Threatening ...[Nxd5] even more strongly and we'll likely make that exchange even if the queen retreats, thereby opening up the suddenly rather powerful and unopposed bishop on [g7], a piece which may look to exchange on [c3] or even grab [b2] one day soon.} *

