1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nf5 $1 {Eyeing the weakness on [d6] must again be critical.} d6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gc8f5]} ({Necessary here, as} 6... d5 $2 7. Nxd5 {achieves little. As such, we have to go in for more of a Kalashnikov approach. Black is ready to go ...[Be6] and may also meet something slow from White with the unbalancing 7.-- Bxf5 8.exf5 Nge7 .}) 7. Nd5 Nf6 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4,Gf5][%cal Gf6e4]} ({Challenging on the light squares looks like a better policy here than allowing White good compensation after} 7... Bxf5 8. exf5 {and 9. [Bc4]. If now 8.Bc4 then we can safely snatch the e-pawn, 8...Nxe4 and if then 9.Qf3 safely retreat with 9...Nf6 .}) 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {[%cal Gc8f5] Preparing to take over after capturing on [f5], so White should now retreat the knight after all.} 9. Ne3 Qg6 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf8e7,Gc8e6,Ge8g8]} (9... Qg6 {One of our favourite squares for the queen. Now} 10. Bd3 Be7 {would be sensible, when Black will continue with ...[O-O] and ...[Be6], with a decent enough set-up.}) 10. Nd5 $5 Qxe4+ {[%csl Ge1] Accepting the challenge and now the position is very reminiscent of the world of Theory One.} 11. Be3 Nd4 $1 {[%csl Gc2,Gd5]} 12. Nc7+ Kd8 $5 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gd4c2] The engines confirm that 12...[Ke7] is also fine, but this way Black should be able to mobilise the kingside pieces faster.} 13. Nxa8 Nxc2+ 14. Kd2 Bf5 $1 {[%cal Gd6d5,Gc2a1]} ({Securing the knight in place is a much better policy than} 14... Nxa1 $2 15. Bd3 {. Only now are we ready to take the rook or even go 15...[d5] and, as confirmed by the engines, Black has full compensation for the rook.}) *

