1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nf5 $1 {Eyeing the weakness on [d6] must again be critical.} d6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gc8f5]} ({Necessary here, as} 6... d5 $2 7. Nxd5 {achieves little. As such, we have to go in for more of a Kalashnikov approach. Black is ready to go ...[Be6] and may also meet something slow from White with the unbalancing 7.-- Bxf5 8.exf5 Nge7 .}) 7. g3 Be6 $5 {[%cal Ga8c8] A new idea in this sideline, ignoring the knight for now and intending to quickly mobilise the queenside pieces with ...[Rc8].} 8. Bg2 Rc8 {[%cal Gg7g6] Ever a decent spot for the rook in an Open Sicilian structure and only now will we look to deal with the knight via a ...[g6] method, while also provoking White into castling.} 9. O-O h5 $1 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gh5h4]} (9... h5 {An important move to insert, as well as Simon's favourite advance in general, of course. Now} 10. Z0 g6 11. Ne3 h4 {would begin to exert some pressure, so White might well prefer to block.}) 10. h4 g6 {[%csl Gf5] Finally kicking the knight away.} 11. Ne3 Bh6 $5 {[%csl Gc2,Gg1][%cal Gc6d4,Gc6e7]} (11... Bh6 {We're now ready to activate further with ...Nd4 and can meet} 12. Ncd5 {with} Nce7 {. Meanwhile, White must be wary of moving his knight from [e3] as then ...[g5] could well become an issue.}) *

