1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nf5 $1 {Eyeing the weakness on [d6] must again be critical.} d6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gc8f5]} ({Necessary here, as} 6... d5 $2 7. Nxd5 {achieves little. As such, we have to go in for more of a Kalashnikov approach. Black is ready to go ...[Be6] and may also meet something slow from White with the unbalancing 7.-- Bxf5 8.exf5 Nge7 .}) 7. g4 $5 (7. g4 {A radical idea, but} Bxf5 $6 8. gxf5 {would help White to obtain control.}) 7... h5 $5 {[%cal Gh5g4]} (7... h5 {This little advance again, as we hit back on the kingside and would like to take over there, including with} 8. gxh5 Bxf5 9. exf5 Qh4 {.}) 8. g5 {This original position arose in E.Xu-Bailey, Guelph 2019, where Black's best might well be to deal with the knight straightaway.} g6 {[%csl Gf5]} 9. Ne3 Bg7 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Gg8e7,Gc6d4] This unbalanced position should be OK for Black, who after 10...[Nge7] may even be able to consider activating with ...[Nd4]. There's also an important point in that where will the white king now find safety? And we can even provoke and allow a certain check.} 10. Ncd5 $5 Nge7 {[%cal Ge7d5] Getting ready to exchange on [d5] while not worrying about [f6].} 11. Nf6+ {[%csl Re8]} Bxf6 $1 {Critical and fearless play.} 12. gxf6 Ng8 {[%cal Gg8f6]} 13. Nd5 Be6 {The position is pretty unclear, but seems fine for Black. We're ready to stir up trouble with 14...[Nd4] against [c2] and with ... [Bg4], as well as to go ...[Bxd5], and if [exd5] [Nb8] followed by ...[Nbd7] and picking off the pawn on [f6] after all.} *

