1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nf5 $1 {Eyeing the weakness on [d6] must again be critical.} d6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gc8f5]} ({Necessary here, as} 6... d5 $2 7. Nxd5 {achieves little. As such, we have to go in for more of a Kalashnikov approach. Black is ready to go ...[Be6] and may also meet something slow from White with the unbalancing 7.-- Bxf5 8.exf5 Nge7 .}) 7. Ne3 {[%csl Rd5] White's main choice, avoiding any exchange on [d5] while clamping down on [d5]. We now have a Kalashnikov where his knight is on [e3], not [a3], a factor which you might assume would slightly favour him.} Nf6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga8c8,Gf8e7,Gg7g6,Gf8g7] Black's main move, placing a bit of pressure on [e4] to deter 8. [Ncd5], while intending to continue development with 8...[Be6] when ...[Be7] may follow or even something more dynamic, such as a ...[Rc8], ...[g6] and ...[Bg7] set-up.} 8. a4 {This takes ...[b5] off the agenda, not that we were intending to rush with that advance and so walk into an awkward undermining with only then [a2]-[a4].} Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gf8e7,Gg7g6,Gf8g7] Contesting [d5] while freeing [c8] for the rook. The king's bishop may come to [e7] or even [g7] depending on how slow White now is.} 9. Bc4 Be7 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf7e6,Gc6b4]} (9... Be7 {Avoiding slightly weakening the kingside is, in general, a wise policy whenever there is potential tension on the a2-g8 diagonal and now if} 10. Ned5 {Black might well again be able to go} Nb4 {.}) 10. O-O Rc8 {[%cal Gc6b4]} (10... Rc8 {Ever a useful move to flick in, as well as one which supports the idea of} 11. Ned5 Nb4 {and also might intimidate some opponents into rushing into an exchange on [e6].}) 11. Bxe6 $6 fxe6 {[%csl Gd5,Gf5][%cal Ge8g8,Gd8e8,Ge8g6] With control of the key [d5]- and [f5]-squares, Black is already for choice and after castling may even be able to drum up an attack with ...[Qe8]-[g6].} *

