1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nf5 $1 {Eyeing the weakness on [d6] must again be critical.} d6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gc8f5]} ({Necessary here, as} 6... d5 $2 7. Nxd5 {achieves little. As such, we have to go in for more of a Kalashnikov approach. Black is ready to go ...[Be6] and may also meet something slow from White with the unbalancing 7.-- Bxf5 8.exf5 Nge7 .}) 7. Ne3 {[%csl Rd5] White's main choice, avoiding any exchange on [d5] while clamping down on [d5]. We now have a Kalashnikov where his knight is on [e3], not [a3], a factor which you might assume would slightly favour him.} Nf6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga8c8,Gf8e7,Gg7g6,Gf8g7] Black's main move, placing a bit of pressure on [e4] to deter 8. [Ncd5], while intending to continue development with 8...[Be6] when ...[Be7] may follow or even something more dynamic, such as a ...[Rc8], ...[g6] and ...[Bg7] set-up.} 8. g3 {Bringing the bishop to [g2] to influence from afar the [d5]-square makes a certain degree of sense.} h5 $5 {[%cal Gh5h4] Wasting no time in looking to disrupt with ...[h4] and so not allow White to comfortably build up his position as he pleases.} 9. h4 Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc6d4] With the white bishop bound for [g2], ...[Rc8] and ...[Nd4] ideas make a good deal of sense, looking to exert some pressure down the c-file.} 10. Bg2 Rc8 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gg7g6] Everything is now ready for ...[Nd4] and then ideally even ...[g6], hence White's attempt now to disrupt in turn.} 11. Ncd5 (11. Ncd5 {The point is that} Nd4 $6 12. c3 {would lead nowhere for Black, but we are though well placed to exchange.}) 11... Bxd5 $5 (11... Bxd5 {Continuing to make use of the rook being on c8, while after} 12. exd5 {we'd now regroup with ...[Nb8] and ...[Nbd7].}) 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 (12... Nxd5 {A second important point:} 13. Qxd5 $4 Nb4 {would, of course, not be good news for White.}) 13. exd5 {Here Black retreated to [e7] in Reefat-Gillani, New Delhi 2009, but we'd slightly prefer to go the other way.} Nb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Gd8b6,Ge8g8] The knight is bound for [d7] and Black should have sufficient counter-chances in this unbalanced position. Most likely, the dark-squared bishop can be developed to [g7], after which ...[O-O] and ...[f5] would definitely be the ideal plan, while if poked by [Bg5], the black queen will likely skip out to [b6].} *

