1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nf5 $1 {Eyeing the weakness on [d6] must again be critical.} d6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gc8f5]} ({Necessary here, as} 6... d5 $2 7. Nxd5 {achieves little. As such, we have to go in for more of a Kalashnikov approach. Black is ready to go ...[Be6] and may also meet something slow from White with the unbalancing 7.-- Bxf5 8.exf5 Nge7 .}) 7. Ne3 {[%csl Rd5] White's main choice, avoiding any exchange on [d5] while clamping down on [d5]. We now have a Kalashnikov where his knight is on [e3], not [a3], a factor which you might assume would slightly favour him.} Nf6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga8c8,Gf8e7,Gg7g6,Gf8g7] Black's main move, placing a bit of pressure on [e4] to deter 8. [Ncd5], while intending to continue development with 8...[Be6] when ...[Be7] may follow or even something more dynamic, such as a ...[Rc8], ...[g6] and ...[Bg7] set-up.} 8. Ned5 {The critical line, threatening [Bg5] while making full use of White's early hold on [d5].} Be7 $5 {A modest little move, setting a small trap while hoping too that White may be tempted to grab the bishop-pair.} 9. Nxe7 Qxe7 {[%cal Gc8e6]} ({Simple chess, although it should be pointed out that the engines think Black may be able to get away with} 9... Nxe7 $5 {, and if} 10. Bg5 Qb6 {.}) 10. Bg5 {[%cal Rc3d5]} Be6 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gh7h6] Thematic development, as well as a fairly necessary move here to cover [d5]. We're now all set to castle or even go ...[h6], and if [Bxf6] [Qxf6], offering the d-pawn for activity after [Qxd6] [Rd8] and ...[Nd4].} 11. Nd5 {[%csl Re7]} Bxd5 {A fairly essential exchange.} 12. exd5 Nb8 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gb8d7,Gh7h6] Perhaps White is slightly better with two bishops against two knights, but we quite like the compact and easy-to-play black position. Going 13...[O-O] and 14...[Nbd7] will complete development, after which Black might look to get in ...[f5], such as with an ...[h6]; [Be3] [Nh7] manoeuvre.} *

