1. e4 c5 {The famous Sicilian Defence, the cornerstone of our repertoire.} 2. Nf3 {White brings out a knight and gets ready to break in the centre with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Black follows suit, developing a knight and getting ready to advance the e-pawn two squares if White now heads for an Open Sicilian.} 3. Nc3 a6 ({A highly natural Sicilian move, if one which may slightly surprise opponents. We hint at ...b5, while remaining flexible in the centre. A good alternative is} 3... e5 {, as recommended by Cuenca and King on their Kalashnikov courses. That, along with 3...g6 , 3...d6 ( 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e5!? is then a decent sideline, ) 3...e6 and 3...Nf6 , is ahead of 3...a6 in the popularity stakes, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with the text move, one which has a small surprise in store lest White now does go down the Open Sicilian route after all. We will now concentrate on 4.g3 and 4.d4 . A few other moves also deserve a brief mention.}) 4. d4 {[%cal Rd4d5,Rd4c5] Going down the Open Sicilian route after all.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4]} ({A Löwenthalesque reaction. Black's main move here is} 5... e6 {, transposing to a Taimanov and 5...d6 followed by ...[e6] is also possible, leading to a Scheveningen, but again we prefer something radical.Is the move 100% sound? If that means can White obtain an edge, then no, but it does lead to a playable position and also carries significant surprise value. Of the just 594 games to reach this position on ChessBase's vast Mega Database 2024, the critical 6. [Nf5] was only played in 221 of them.}) 6. Nf5 $1 {Eyeing the weakness on [d6] must again be critical.} d6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gc8f5]} ({Necessary here, as} 6... d5 $2 7. Nxd5 {achieves little. As such, we have to go in for more of a Kalashnikov approach. Black is ready to go ...[Be6] and may also meet something slow from White with the unbalancing 7.-- Bxf5 8.exf5 Nge7 .}) 7. Ne3 {[%csl Rd5] White's main choice, avoiding any exchange on [d5] while clamping down on [d5]. We now have a Kalashnikov where his knight is on [e3], not [a3], a factor which you might assume would slightly favour him.} Nf6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga8c8,Gf8e7,Gg7g6,Gf8g7] Black's main move, placing a bit of pressure on [e4] to deter 8. [Ncd5], while intending to continue development with 8...[Be6] when ...[Be7] may follow or even something more dynamic, such as a ...[Rc8], ...[g6] and ...[Bg7] set-up.} 8. Ned5 {The critical line, threatening [Bg5] while making full use of White's early hold on [d5].} Be7 $5 {A modest little move, setting a small trap while hoping too that White may be tempted to grab the bishop-pair.} 9. Be3 $1 {[%cal Ge3b6]} ({Probably best, threatening 10.Bb6, and definitely a far superior choice to blundering a piece with} 9. Bg5 $4 Nxd5 {.}) 9... O-O {Ensuring that any subsequent [Nc7] won't come with check.} 10. Bb6 {[%csl Rd8]} Qd7 {[%cal Gf6d5,Ge7d8]} (10... Qd7 {Slightly clumsy development, but Black does now have the clear plan of dealing with the intruders via} 11. Z0 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Bd8 {and 13...[Ne7] or if} 13. Bxd8 Qxd8 {.}) 11. Qd2 $5 {Probably White's most dangerous try, looking for quick pressure down the d-file.} (11. Be2 Nxd5 {((The aforementioned plan, getting ready to go 12...Bd8 or 13...Bd8 if now 12.exd5 Nb8. ) . )} 12. Nxd5 Bd8 $1 13. O-O Ne7 {Play has transposed to Baramidze-Zozulia, Triesen 2004, where the bishop on [b6] was being thematically undermined and Black was at most only a touch worse.} 14. Bxd8 Qxd8 15. Ne3 Be6 {With the full equaliser that is 16...[d5] threatened and also such moves as ...[Rc8] and ...[Qb6] on their way, Black cannot have too many problems.}) 11... Nxd5 {Continuing the plan in any case.} 12. Nxd5 Bd8 $1 {[%cal Gc6e7]} ({Thematic, intending ...Ne7, whereas} 12... Qg4 $2 13. f3 Bh4+ $2 14. g3 $1 Qxf3 15. Bg2 {simply cost Black a piece in M.Van Foreest-Machlik, European Women's Team Championship, Terme Catez 2021.}) 13. O-O-O Rb8 $5 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gd7d8] Beginning to shadow-box ( 13...Ne7? 14.Bxd8 Qxd8 15.Ne3 would now leave [d6] weak and White in control, while ensuring that any subsequent [Nb6] won't fork rook and queen.) As such, Black is ready to go 14...Bxb6 15.Nxb6 Qd8 and shouldn't be more than slightly worse.} (13... Rb8 {For example,} 14. Kb1 $5 {((Calm, engine-approved and a move which bypasses the option of 14.Qe3 Ne7 for Black note that 14...Ne7? now runs into 15.Ba7. ) . )} Bxb6 15. Nxb6 Qd8 {Retreating with tempo while looking to get in ...[Be6] after all.} 16. Nxc8 Qxc8 {((It may also be possible to sacrifice the d-pawn with 16...Rxc8!? , but this way there's always ...[Rfd8], ...[b5] is imminent and, oh, yes, the d-pawn is taboo.))} 17. Qxd6 $4 Rd8 {Ouch. Capturing the poisoned pawn has immediately cost White the game.}) *

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
