1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 a6 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {This is, of course, the key tabiya of the Löwenthal, and we'll now see the main line in action.} 8. Qd1 Qg6 9. Nc3 d5 $5 {[%csl Gc2,Ge4]} (9... d5 {Our favourite gambit approach, not that White is especially advised to grab the pawn with} 10. exd5 $2 Nd4 {or even 10.Qxd5 Be6 .}) 10. Nxd5 Qxe4+ 11. Be3 Nd4 12. Nc7+ Ke7 {[%csl Ga1,Ra8] And this sharp position, with both queen's rooks in danger, is, in turn, the tabiya of the main line with 8. [Qd1]. Black hopes that greed will prove White's downfall and the rook on [a8] be snatched, although we most certainly must be fully ready too for 13. [Rc1], 13. [Be2] and a certain queen move.} 13. Qd3 {[%csl Re4]} Nxc2+ 14. Kd2 Qxd3+ {[%cal Gc2e3] An essential exchange ahead of taking on [e3], not [a1].} 15. Bxd3 Nxe3 16. Nxa8 Nd5 {[%csl Ga8] As we saw in 8. [Qd1] with 13. [Qd3] chapter, it's this retreat which rather underpins Black's play, keeping the white knight bottled up in the corner.} 17. Rac1 Ngf6 18. Nc7 Nb4 {[%csl Gd5,Gf6][%cal Gb4d3,Gb4a2] With the knight on [f6] covering the key [d5]-square to prevent [Nc7]-[d5], Black is able to head forwards, threatening ...[Rd8], while also introducing ideas of ...[Nxd3] and ...[Nxa2].} 19. Bb1 $5 {White's most ambitious move.} (19. a3 Nxd3 20. Kxd3 Bd7 $1 {was, instead, the main continuation we examined in 8. [Qd1] with 13. [Qd3] chapter.}) 19... Kd6 $5 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gb4c6] Keeping tabs on the white knight, which will now come under fire once its counterpart retreats to [c6].} (19... Rd8+ 20. Ke2 Nc6 21. Rhd1 Nd4+ {This is the alternative way Black can obtain counterplay. Once again, the bishop aims to come to a fine post on [c6] and in practice Black may well have enough for the exchange, '+0.4' or so though the engines may proclaim.}) 20. Rhd1 {[%csl Rd6]} Nc6 {The point of Black's play, condemning the knight to have to return to the corner.} 21. Na8 Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4d1,Gh8a8]} (21... Be6 $2 22. Nb6 {This would see the knight emerge from captivity, leaving White clearly for choice, which is why Black should prefer the double-attack set up by the text move.}) 22. f3 Rxa8 {This approach, rather than flicking in an exchange on [f3], is probably best, since now Black will enjoy both short-term activity and a passed e-pawn for the endgame.} 23. fxg4 Nxg4 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gc6d4,Gg4h2] As we commented back in chapter 1c, where we ended the line here, Black has two good pawns for the exchange and is all set to activate with ...[Nd4] and ...[h5] making ...[Nxh2] into a threat.} 24. h3 {[%csl Rg4]} Nf6 25. a3 {White is determined to keep the black knights at bay on both sides of the board, but now ...[Nd4] will threaten a certain fork, although Black prefers to first activate his rook.} Re8 $5 {[%cal Ge8e7]} (25... Rd8 26. Ke1+ Nd4 27. Ba2 Rd7 {This also seems fine for Black, with two good pawns for the exchange and, just like in the game, White slightly struggling for a plan.}) 26. Ba2 {[%csl Rf7]} Re7 {[%csl Gb7,Gf7] Mission accomplished. Only now that everything is secure does the Ukrainian Grandmaster push forwards in the centre of the board.} 27. Ke3+ Nd4 28. Rc8 {It's hard to imagine this rook finding a more active role, although even here Black is untroubled, as Oleksienko had no doubt realised in advance.} Nd7 $5 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gf7f5,Gd7c5] Looking to advance the f-pawn, as well as activate the knight via [c5] or [b6].} (28... Nd5+ 29. Bxd5 Kxd5 {This followed by ...[Rd7] or ...[Ke6] would have been rock solid for Black had he been happy with a draw against Smirnov, who the next year would also become a Ukrainian GM.}) 29. g4 $1 (29. g4 {Wisely White puts a stop to allowing Black too much space with ...f5 and would now meet} g6 {with} 30. g5 {.}) 29... f6 $5 {Trying to tempt White into some sort of action.} (29... g6 30. g5 f5 $1 31. gxf6 Nxf6 {This is preferred by the engines and likely maintains a rough balance, but would also leave Black perhaps struggling to find too many winning chances if White just sat tight.}) 30. Bb1 {[%csl Rh7]} (30. b4 $5 {The engines prefer to seize space and prevent ...[Nc5] to attacking [h7], as played in the game.} g6 $5 {This may well have been Oleksienko's plan, looking to get in ...[f5]:} 31. h4 f5 32. g5 Nb6 {Attacking the rook and allowing Black to consider ideas of ... [Nd5]+ after all. The engines assess as a small plus for White, but in practice absolutely anything might have happened from here, especially if Black found a way to roll his central pawns.}) 30... Nb6 {[%cal Gb6c8,Gg7g6] Counter-attacking against the rook ahead of either going ...[g6] or exploiting any opportunity to further unbalance the position.} 31. Rd8+ Kc7 {[%cal Gc7d8]} 32. Rf8 {Preventing ...[g6], but only at the cost of allowing Black to strike on the queenside.} Nc4+ $1 33. Kf2 Nxb2 {[%csl Gd1]} 34. Rc1+ Kb6 35. Bxh7 Ka5 $5 {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga5a4,Ge5e4,Ge4e3] We should take stock. According to the engines, the position is still about level, but Black's position appears the easier to play: his king is quite safe and will likely advance to [a4] to attack White's remaining queenside pawn, while ...[b5] is also imminent and there are very much ideas too of ...[e4]-[e3]+.} 36. Rfc8 $1 {[%cal Rc1c7] Threatening to invade on [c7]. Black can now retreat the knight to [b5] to prevent that, or rely on his own play.} e4 {[%cal Ge4e3]} 37. Ke3 {Trying to halt the mighty passed pawn.} (37. R1c7 e3+ 38. Ke1 Nf3+ 39. Ke2 {This feels rather risky for White, but while Black has various perpetual checks available, the engines can't see anything better for him, possible though it very much is to continue the struggle. For example:} Ng1+ 40. Ke1 Re6 $5 41. Rxb7 Na4 {White should be able to hold, although the king on [e1] might not be feeling too comfortable. Note too a further point:} 42. h4 e2 $4 43. Rb3 $1 {Trapping the knight on [g1] and so winning for White.}) 37... Nb5 {[%csl Gc7] Prudently keeping White out of [c7].} 38. R1c2 Na4 $6 {This and White's next move feel like time-trouble.} (38... Nd3 $1 39. Bg6 Ne5 {Refusing to allow White's bishop to settle, and so [Re8] to be played. The position remains rather unbalanced, but with such options as ...[Nd6] and ...[Ka4] available, Black should be slightly for choice.}) 39. Rd2 $6 (39. Bg6 $1 {Preparing [Re8] to try and swap off the piece holding Black's position together would seemingly have left White slightly for choice, albeit with all three results very much still possible}) 39... Re5 $6 {This definitely feels like a move frantically blitzed out. There was no particularly good reason not to take on [a3] or to abandon the second rank.} 40. Rc1 $6 (40. Bg8 $1 {would have left Black's pieces no longer looking so well coordinated and favoured White, but instead Smirnov was to return the favour.}) 40... Nac3 {[%cal Gc3d5] Threatening a fairly powerful check and especially making the presumed time control.} 41. Bg8 Rc5 (41... Ka4 $5 {Activating the king so would have prevented the possibility in our next note.}) 42. Rdc2 (42. a4 $5 {This was probably worth a punt:} Nxa4 43. Rxc5 Nxc5 44. Rb2 $1 {Holding up Black for now on the queenside and while there are now three pawns for the exchange, White is set to go [h4]-[h5] followed by [Rf2] and even [Rxf6], which may even leave White slightly for choice.}) 42... Ka4 $1 {[%csl Ga3] Black is now back in control of the queenside situation and will look for a safe moment to pick off the straggler on [a3].} 43. Be6 $5 {[%csl Ra3]} Rc7 $1 {Sensibly bringing the rook back around to a square on which it once sensibly and well stood, while also refusing to fall for White's trap.} (43... Kxa3 $4 44. Ra1+ Kb4 45. Rb2#) 44. Kd2 $2 {Missing or underestimating a tactic.} (44. h4 $1 Kxa3 $1 45. Ra1+ Kb4 46. Rb2+ Kc5 47. Rd2 {Here Black's king is safe and there are three pawns for the exchange, but further progress would be far from trivial in what is still a pretty complex position.}) 44... e3+ $5 {Tempting and a tactical trick which is quickly rewarded.} (44... Rc6 $1 45. Bf5 Rd6+ {The rook will invade on [d3], leaving Black having made definite progress and now able to enjoy fairly serious winning chances.}) 45. Kxe3 $4 (45. Kd3 $1 e2 46. Kd2 Kxa3 {This would still have left Black with a lot of work to do, but instead Smirnov collapses on the spot, so perhaps there wasn't a time control at move 40 or they only gained a small amount of extra time.}) 45... Re7 {[%csl Ge3,Ge6] Winning the bishop and the game.} 46. Rxc3 Rxe6+ 47. Kf4 Nxc3 48. Rxc3 b5 {[%csl Ga4] White has avoided losing a piece, but his cause is a hopeless one, largely thanks to Black's superbly-placed king and active majority.} 49. Kf5 {[%csl Re6]} Re7 {[%cal Ga6a5,Gb5b4] Keeping everything covered ahead of a decisive advance of the queenside pawns.} 50. Kg6 a5 51. h4 b4 52. axb4 axb4 53. Rc8 Rb7 $1 {[%cal Gb4b3,Gb3b2,Gb2b1] Rooks belong behind passed pawns. The game is up for Smirnov.} 54. Ra8+ Kb5 55. h5 b3 56. Ra1 Kb4 0-1

