1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 a6 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6 Qf6 {Our key tabiya of course.} 8. Qc7 Nge7 9. Nc3 Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gd7d5] An especially useful multipurpose move here, attacking [c2] while supporting the key ...[d5] break.} 10. Bd3 d5 11. exd5 Nbxd5 (11... Nexd5 {This move order is our slight preference, enabling Black to exchange on [d3] should White now move the queen rather than exchange knights and transpose into the game.}) 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Qc5 Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gf6e7] Securing the centralised knight in place ahead of developing the rook with tempo, then challenging for control of the [a3]-[f8] diagonal with ...[Qe7].} 14. O-O Rc8 15. Qd6 Rd8 {[%cal Gf6e7] The rook is just as good on [d8] as [c8] and now Black will be able to go ...[Qe7] without dropping the [e5]-pawn.} 16. Qa3 Qe7 17. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {[%cal Gd8d7,Gd5b4,Gd5f4] White might have the bishop-pair, but as we noted in chapter 2b, Black is well coordinated and our overall set-up is pretty harmonious. We're ready to head forwards with ...[Nb4], while, again, ... [Nf4] may also be an option, possibly in conjunction with doubling rooks on the d-file.} 18. a3 {[%csl Rb4] Taking control of [b4].} (18. b3 $5 {This alternative way of cutting out ...[Nb4] was preferred in another encounter from Germany back in the nineties.} f6 {Black prepares to go ... [Kf7] and only then ...[Nb4]. (( 18...Nb4? 19.Ba3 a5 20.f4! White has seized the initiative and the position is opening much faster than Black would like.))} 19. f4 $5 {Black is well-placed to deal with this, but it's far from easy to find an improvement for White. (( 19.Bb2?! Nf4 Black begins to exert pressure in the centre and is also now ready to expand on the kingside with ... [g5] and ...[h5], leaving us slightly for choice.)) (( 19.Bd2 g5! Here too Black has absolutely no problems. Again, ...[Nf4] and ... [h5] may follow and there's always ...[Rd7] if needed.))} exf4 {Naturally Black has no desire to see White exchange on [e5] and create a target there.} 20. Bxf4 Nxf4 21. Rxf4 Kf7 {(Having deprived White of the bishop-pair, Black was all set to improve the pieces with ...[Rhe8] and ...[Bd5], and enjoyed full equality in Wegener-Heidrich, German League 1998 ½-½, 45.)}) 18... h6 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gg7g5] Now ...[f5] may be possible without [Bg5]+ being slightly annoying in response and Black can also advance with ...[g5].} (18... Nf4 $5 {This more solid approach would again have been a decent alternative.} 19. Bxf4 {(( 19.Be4?! This may seem natural, but is also an instructive mistake: 19...Ne2+! 20.Kh1 Nxc1 21.Raxc1 b5 With ...[f5] on the way, as well as ...[Rd2] or just ... [Rd6], Black has definitely seized the initiative.))} exf4 20. Rfe1 Rd4 {Black is comfortable here, with ...[Rhd8] one possible follow-up, ...[g5], ...[h5] and ...[Kf6] another.}) 19. Re1 {[%csl Re5]} Kf6 $1 {[%cal Ge6f5] Calmly defending the en prise pawn while preparing another of our favourite manoeuvres in this semi-endgame: ...[Bf5] to deprive White of the bishop-pair and weaken his queenside.} 20. b3 $1 {White's dark-squared bishop has been struggling for a good role for some time and [b2] will be as good a square as any for it.} Bf5 {[%cal Gf5d3]} 21. Bb2 {[%csl Re5]} Rhe8 {Keeping everything tight at tight at the back while renewing the threat to weaken White's structure with a trade on [d3].} 22. Be4 $2 {White underestimates the long-term danger and allows Black to take control of the struggle.} ({A} 22. Rad1 {White calmly covers the bishop on [d3] and threatens to create significant problems in the centre with [Bc4].} Nf4 $1 {The knight moves before it is attacked, thereby keeping everything secure in the black camp while unfurling a further attack on [d3].} 23. Bxf5 Rxd1 $1 {Correctly exchanging rooks on Black's terms to keep the [e5]-pawn on the board.} 24. Rxd1 Kxf5 {The active knight is the equal of the bishop here and Black is fine, with ...[Ne6] and ...[Rc8] two possible continuations. Note too that while White can invade on the seventh, Black is quite ready for such a possibility:} 25. Rd7 Ke6 {It's important to keep the kingside pawns intact.} 26. Rxb7 Rd8 {The point, threatening mate, as well as to invade on the seventh.} 27. h4 $1 Rd1+ 28. Kh2 Rd2 {Black will regain the pawn and enjoy the more comfortable side of the draw, and that's assuming White defends well, beginning with 29. [Bc1]!.}) ({B} 22. Rxe5 $5 {This radical defence would also have avoided any trouble for White.} Rxe5 23. Re1 Rde8 {Ensuring that Black remains a rook up for now.} 24. Bc4 {((This calm follow-up is the problem. If the knight retreats, White has f2-f4 and even after 24...Nf4 25.g3 Nh3+ 26.Kg2 Black lacks a magic move.)) That all means that a drawn endgame is likely to arise. For example:} Nb6 25. Rxe5 Rxe5 26. f4 Nxc4 27. bxc4 Ke6 28. Bxe5 f6 29. Bc3 Bxc2 {With the c-pawn a slight weakness and the more active king, Black is nominally for choice, but no more than that.}) 22... Bxe4 {Dragging White's rook to a square where it can be attacked while Black also steps off the long diagonal.} 23. Rxe4 Kf5 $1 {[%cal Gf5e4]} 24. Rae1 f6 {[%cal Gh6h5,Gg7g5,Gb7b5,Gd8c8] Black enjoys a pleasant edge with White's pieces no longer so well coordinated. It will be possible to expand with ...[g5] and ..h5, while even ...[b5] in conjunction with ...[Rc8] is very much an idea.} 25. g3 g5 $1 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gh6h5]} (25... g5 {Seizing space, not fearing} 26. g4+ $2 {here, as that would merely create a hook for ...[h5] and allow the black knight a very juicy outpost on [f4].}) 26. f3 {Trying to prevent Black from seizing too much space with ...[g4] and ...[h5].} (26. h4 $5 {The engines prefer this more radical idea on the kingside, although even here Black can press:} Rd6 27. h5 Red8 28. f3 R8d7 $1 {Good prophylaxis. Black may now regroup with ...[Ne7] and perhaps ...[Ke6], looking to invade down the d-file. (( 28...Ne7?? 29.Bxe5! Ouch. Suddenly the tables have turned. 29...fxe5 30.Rxe5+ Kf6 31.Rxe7 Two pawns down, it's all gone wrong for Black.))}) 26... Ne7 $6 {Allowing White a perhaps unexpected chance to break free to an extent.} (26... Nc7 $1 {This would have been a much better retreat, preparing to bring the knight round via [e6] as well as to invade on [d2].}) 27. R1e2 $2 {Now Black gets in.} (27. f4 $1 {Exploiting the potential pin on the e-file would have put White right back in the game.} gxf4 {(( 27...Ke6!? 28.fxe5 f5 This would have been a decent practical alternative. While White should be OK here, Black has a firm blockade and can look to expand on either flank, as well as to play down the d-file or go after [e5] with ...[Nc6] or ...[Ng6]. In short, Black has enough play for the pawn.))} 28. gxf4 Ng6 29. fxe5 fxe5 30. R4e2 {With pressure still against [e5] and the black king now also not entirely happy, White cannot be any more than fractionally worse here.}) 27... Rd1+ 28. Kf2 Rb1 $2 {A rush of blood to the head. Black has invaded the white camp, but has failed to involve more than one piece in the process.} (28... Nc6 $1 {This would have avoided the tactic which now occurs while preparing ...[Red8], thereby involving all Black's pieces. White can still try to defend actively, but in any case Black would appear to be clearly better. For example:} 29. f4 $5 {(( 29.Re1 Red8 30.Rxd1 Rxd1 31.Re1 Rd7! Correctly keeping a pair of rooks on. Black now plans to lever open lines with ...[h5] then ...[g4]. 32.g4+!? Ke6 With ...[h5] and ...[Rh7] set to follow, White remains under definite pressure. The knight on [c6] may not currently be up to too much, but once it reaches [e7] then [d5] or [f4], things will quickly be a different story.))} gxf4 30. Rxf4+ Kg5 $1 31. Rf3 h5 {White's bishop is much less happy here than after 28...[Rb1]?, with Black able to gradually head forwards, beginning with ...[Red8] and perhaps even ...[b5].}) 29. Bxe5 $1 {Schramm is alert, taking full advantage of the opportunity offered, sacrificing his bishop to get right back into the game.} fxe5 30. Rxe5+ Kf6 {[%csl Ge7,Rh6] The extra knight is safe, but unfortunately for Black, he can't also save the h-pawn.} 31. Re6+ Kf7 32. Rxh6 {[%cal Rh6h7]} Nf5 {A tactical way of dealing with the threat of [Rh7]+ and as good a try as anything else. In any case, White has three pawns and enough compensation for the piece.} 33. Rh7+ Kg6 {[%csl Ge2,Re8,Gh7] The point. Black offers an indirect rook exchange.} 34. Rxb7 Rxe2+ 35. Kxe2 {[%cal Rb7b6]} Nd4+ {Black's only real hope is to activate the knight and hope to be able to remove all three of White's kingside pawns if there is to be any chance of winning.} 36. Kd3 (36. Ke3 $1 Nxc2+ 37. Ke4 {This would have been the simplest way to draw, liquidating the queenside:} Nxa3 38. Rb6+ Kg7 39. Rxa6 Rxb3 40. Kf5 {Black will, at best, land up with rook and knight against rook and two pawns.}) 36... Nxf3 37. Rb6+ Kf5 38. h4 $5 (38. h3 {This would have been a safer way to draw. For example:} Rh1 39. Ke3 Ne1 40. Kd2 Nf3+ 41. Ke3 {And it's far from obvious how Black can even try to make progress.}) 38... g4 $1 {Fixing [g3] as a target. Not Black will at least get to enjoy a race scenario, which is pretty much the only way he could hope to win.} 39. Rxa6 (39. Ke3 $2 Re1+ $1 40. Kf2 {An overly passive defence compared to the correct, active defence of the game.} Rc1 $1 41. Rc6 Nd4 42. Rc5+ Ke4 {Perhaps White can still draw, but Black is pretty active here and definitely pressing.}) 39... Rg1 40. Ra5+ Kf6 41. Ke4 $5 {Presumably White too was playing for a win or he would have simply kept checking.} Rxg3 42. Kf4 Rg1 {[%cal Gf3h4,Gf3d4] Threatening not just 43...[Nxh4], but to leave the g-pawn looking pretty quick after 43...[Nd4].} 43. Ra6+ $1 (43. h5 $2 Nd4 $1 44. Ra6+ Ne6+ 45. Ke3 Rh1 {White would have been in serious trouble here with the h-pawn falling.}) 43... Kf7 44. h5 $5 {Continuing to spurn the possibility of giving a barrage of checks.} Nd4 45. Ke5 $5 (45. Rg6 {would have been one safer choice, but Schramm was clearly really going for it.}) 45... g3 $1 {Tomczak seizes his chance, giving up the knight to get to touch down with the g-pawn.} 46. Kxd4 Rd1+ 47. Kc4 g2 {[%cal Gg2g1]} 48. Rg6 {Fairly obligatory, of course, and with three connected passed pawns, White should still have been able to hold the draw.} g1=Q 49. Rxg1 Rxg1 50. Kc5 $4 {We're told to keep the king active in the endgame, but this will prove a decisive mistake, as now the white pawns will be too slow.} (50. a4 $1 {This natural advance was the simplest way to draw. For example:} Ke7 {(( 50...Rh1 51.b4 Rh4+ 52.Kb5 Rxh5+ 53.Kb6 Here White is definitely OK with the king well placed and the pawns all able to advance.))} 51. a5 $1 {Racing the key pawns towards [a6] and [b5].} Kd7 52. b4 Kc6 {(( 52...Kc7 53.Kb3 Calmly does it as White frees the c-pawn to join the action. 53...Rh1 54.c4 Rxh5 55.b5 White will set up a pawn chain from [c4] to [a6], with a theoretical draw. You may wish to compare the sample line that follows with the notes to White's 51st move: 55...Kb7 56.a6+! Kb6 57.Kb2 Rh2+ 58.Kb3 Rh1 59.Kb2 Kc5 60.Kc2! The key point. Black will never be able to take on [c4] with the king and is unable to win. 60...Rh4 61.Kb3! Rxc4?? 62.a7 White is now even winning.))} 53. b5+ Kb7 54. a6+ $5 Kb6 55. Kd3 $1 {Calmly does it. White will now either get in [c2]-[c4] or be fast enough as Black hunts down the pawns:} Kxb5 56. a7 Ra1 57. Ke4 $1 Rxa7 58. Kf5 {The h-pawn is too far up the board for Black to hope for any real winning chances.}) 50... Ke7 $1 {Racing the king across to the queenside in the nick of time.} 51. Kb6 {This doesn't especially help, but already it seems that White was lost.} (51. a4 Rh1 52. a5 Rxh5+ 53. Kb6 {(( 53.Kb4 Kd6! 54.c4 Kc6 55.Ka4 Rh1! 56.b4 Rh3! White will be forced to move a pawn and is losing; compare with what follows after 53. [Kb6].))} Kd7 $1 54. b4 Kc8 55. b5 Kb8 56. a6 Rh4 $1 57. Kc5 Ka7 58. c4 {This looks like the ideal pawn chain for White and a draw, but actually Black is winning as the white king can't get back to the right square. Complex stuff! For instance:} Rh1 59. Kb4 Kb6 60. Kb3 Rc1 $1 {(( 60...Kc5 61.Kc2! Now it's a draw, as we saw above.))} 61. Kb4 Rb1+ $1 62. Ka3 $5 {(( 62.Kc3 Kc5 Unfortunately for White, his pawns are about to all fall.))} Kc7 63. Ka4 Kd6 64. Ka3 Kd7 $1 {Black triangulates, with decisive effect.} 65. Ka4 Kc7 66. Ka3 Kb6 $1 67. Ka4 Kc5 {This time Black will be able to safely pick off [c4] without allowing the a- and b-pawns to get out of hand.}) 51... Kd8 52. a4 Kc8 {Continuing to bring the king over.} 53. a5 Kb8 54. h6 $5 (54. b4 Rc1 {The c-pawn, then the h-pawn will fall.}) 54... Rg6+ 55. Kb5 Rxh6 56. c4 Kb7 {[%csl Ga6] An ideal set-up for Black; White isn't going to set up a [c4], [b5] and [a6] chain.} 57. b4 Rc6 $1 {Forcing White into an unfavourable and fatal pawn advance.} 58. c5 Rh6 (58... Rh6 59. Kc4 Ka6 60. b5+ Kxa5 61. b6 Ka6 {This would just have continued the theme; the black king and have rook have everything under control.}) 0-1

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Zawadzka, Jolanta vs. Heidrich"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "91"]
[GameId "2141525863970253"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 a6 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 Nge7 9. Nc3 Nb4 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gb4c2] The key move in this variation, counterattacking against [c2] whilst supporting ...[d5].} 10. Bd3 d5 11. O-O d4 12. Na4 $1 {[%cal Ra4b6] A critical test and with [Nb6] now imminent, Black must swing the queen across to aid the defence.} Qc6 {[%csl Ga4,Gc7]} 13. Qxc6+ Nexc6 14. Nb6 Rb8 {We've reached something of a key tabiya for the 8. [Qc7] variation. White perhaps has a small pull, but Black is very solid and most certainly not without potential counter-chances.} 15. f4 $5 {An aggressive advance...} f6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gc6e5] ...one best met by this solid defence, which actually supports recapturing on [e5] not with the pawn, but the knight.} 16. f5 $5 {Seizing as much space as possible. White may hope one day to get [g2]-[g4]-[g5] in, although the Polish WGM was probably mainly hoping to restrict the influence of the bishop on [c8].} (16. fxe5 Nxe5 {A key point, pressing against [d3].} 17. Bf4 Be6 {Black is now ready to go ...[Rd8] then ...[Rd6] and should be fine, as we saw in our coverage of Line 2B.}) 16... Kd8 $5 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Gd8c7] This manoeuvre is by no means forced here, but is especially tempting when the centre is so fixed. Black calmly walks the king over to [c7] to deal with the intruder on [b6].} 17. Bd2 Kc7 {[%cal Gc7b6]} 18. Nd5+ $5 {[%csl Rb4,Rc7] An ambitious approach as White plays to try to seize the initiative rather than be left with something of a sidelined knight as would be the case after 18.Na4?! [b6].} (18. Nc4 b6 $5 {Here too this calm, restrained choice makes decent sense, rather than forcing exchanges with 18...[b5] 19. [Na5]. Black would like to get in ...[a5], after which while ...[Ba6] may activate the bishop, in the short term, ...[Na6]-[c5] to improve the knight and press against [e4] might be an even better approach.}) 18... Nxd5 19. exd5 Ne7 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge7d5,Gh8d8] A second fairly forced move in a row for Black, who will now be quick to increase the pressure against the weakling on [d5].} 20. Be4 Rd8 21. c4 {A very natural choice, striving to open lines towards the black king.} (21. Rf3 $5 Nxd5 22. Rh3 {((An engine-approved idea, angling to overstretch the defence in the event of 22...h6? 23.Rg3. ) . )} Ne7 $1 23. Rf1 Bd7 $5 {(( 23...h6 24.Rg3 Rg8 25.Bb4 White's bishops are certainly quite active here and the black position not entirely comfortable.))} 24. Rxh7 Rg8 {The kingside is secure and with ...[Bc6] or even ...[Bb5] on the way, Black should be OK.} 25. Bb4 $6 Rbe8 $1 {White's bishops are somewhat less impressive than in the note above after 23...[h6] and the upcoming ...[Bc6] will further reduce their influence.}) 21... dxc3 $1 {A brave move, but also a good and logical one, since now the [d5]-pawn must fall.} 22. Rac1 Nxd5 23. Rfd1 $1 {Zawadzka makes the most of her attacking set-up, bringing another piece into the attack and threatening all manner of nasty things after [Bxc3]. The black king is a bit exposed, but that's not entirely uncommon in the Löwenthal and in many a queenless middlegame, the king can look exposed, but turn out to actually be quite safe while White expends too much energy trying to prove the opposite.} Rd7 $1 {[%cal Gc7d8] Excellent defence from the experienced German FM, keeping everything secure while creating a retreat square for his king.} 24. Bxc3 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Rc3e5]} Nxc3 25. Rxc3+ Kd8 {The point of Black's play. Heidrich is still a pawn ahead, although White is able to exploit her superior activity to regain it on the kingside.} 26. Rxd7+ Bxd7 27. Rg3 $1 Bc6 $1 {[%csl Gb8,Ge4][%cal Gb7c6] By no means forced, but a move we quite like, challenging White's well-placed bishop on [e4], while angling for a protected passed e-pawn and counterplay down the b-file.} 28. Bd3 (28. Bxc6 bxc6 29. Rxg7 Rxb2 {The engines may indicate their favourite '0.00', but in practice anything could happen here, with Black slightly for choice in practice on account of his extra pawns on the queenside.}) 28... g6 $5 {One of two decent ways to untangle.} (28... Ke8 29. Rxg7 Rd8 {Faced with such an active rook, White would be well advised to check on [g8], exchange and aim to hold the resulting bishop endgame.}) 29. fxg6 hxg6 30. Rxg6 Ke7 {[%csl Ge5,Gf6][%cal Ge7e6] The point of Heidrich's play becomes clear: if Black can get his king and central pawn duo rolling down the board, White will quickly be in trouble.} 31. Bc4 Rd8 {Not failing to activate the rook and claim control of the open file.} 32. Rg7+ Kd6 33. b4 $5 {A slightly risky choice, as now Black may have ideas of a timely ...[a5] to exploit the hook on [b4] and position of the king on [d6].} Be4 (33... Rh8 $5 {This would have been directed against White's need for counterplay with the h-pawn.} 34. Rf7 e4 $1 {The pawns begin to roll...} 35. Rxf6+ Ke5 36. Rf1 e3 {With such an active king and well advanced e-pawn, at least from a practical perspective, Black must be for choice.}) 34. h4 $1 {Adhering to the good, old adage: passed pawns must be pushed.} Rh8 35. g3 {Now White's own pawns are in play and it's not so easy for Black to conjure up any real winning tries.} Rc8 36. Bb3 Rc1+ 37. Kf2 Rh1 {Getting the rook behind the passed pawn, but White's own pieces are active enough for the position to be both unbalanced and equal.} 38. Ke3 f5 39. Bc4 Bc6 $5 {[%cal Gf5f4,Gh1h3]} (39... Bc6 {Hoping to get in} 40. Z0 f4+ {, and if} 41. gxf4 Rh3+ {followed by 42...[exf4].}) 40. Rg6+ Kc7 41. Rf6 $1 {Active and good defence from Zawadzka and now the game rather peters out.} f4+ 42. gxf4 Rh3+ 43. Kf2 Rxh4 {[%csl Gc4,Gf4]} 44. Kg3 {Remaining alert to the end.} Rxf4 45. Rxf4 exf4+ 46. Kxf4 1/2-1/2

[Event "The Killer Löwenthal Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Zuriel, Marisa vs. Nemcova"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "B32"]
[PlyCount "120"]
[GameId "2141525864023502"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 a6 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qxf6 Nxf6 9. Nc3 Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2] A key resource, forcing White to make a fairly important decision over how best to defend [c2]: to use the king and retain the bishop-pair or play it safe with 10. [Bd3]?} 10. Kd2 d6 11. a3 Nc6 12. Ke1 Be6 {Black's pieces flow to good squares as we maintain a healthy lead in development, while also being the only side who can still castle.} 13. Be3 Ne7 $1 {Further precision, preparing not to allow the bishop on [e3] a moment's rest as ...[d5] is pushed through with Black now, if needed, always able to recapture on [d5] with a knight.} 14. Bd3 d5 {[%cal Gd5d4] Forcing through the thematic break and already threatening to win a piece.} 15. exd5 Nexd5 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gd5e3,Gd5c3] The point of 13...[Ne7] should be clear by now: Black can always replace one knight with the other on [d5] should White now exchange.} 16. Bd2 (16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Bd2 Rc8 {((Ever a good square for the rook and now 18.c4 Ne7 will retreat with tempo against [c4], while also getting ready to make a favourable piece exchange with ...[Bf5].))} 18. f3 f6 {Keeping everything tight at the back. Black can now keep the king in touch with the centre while connecting the rooks with ...[Kf7], all the while as the strong knight on [d5] offsets White's bishop-pair.}) 16... Rc8 {[%cal Gd5c3,Ge5e4] Angling to exchange on [c3] then get to seize the initiative by advancing with ...[e4].} 17. f3 {White sensibly puts the kibosh on such plans and now enjoys full control over [e4].} Nxc3 $5 {By no means the only good plan there was also 17...[O-O] and 18...[Rfd8], for instance, but a decent one as the white bishop won't be entirely happy on [c3].} 18. Bxc3 Nd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gf7f6,Ge8f7] A key follow-up, making way for ...[f6] and ...[Kf7] while directing the knight towards [c5].} 19. Kf2 f6 20. Rhe1 Kf7 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gh8d8,Gc5a4] The first part of the mini-plan is complete. Black will now look to leap forwards with ...[Nc5], after which ...[Na4] or just ...[Rfd8] will follow.} 21. a4 {The pawn will eventually become a target here, but this logical enough move does keep the black knight out of [a4].} (21. Bb4 $5 Nc5 22. Bxc5 Rxc5 23. Rad1 {While White has returned the bishop-pair, she remains very solid and fully equal here.}) 21... Nc5 22. Bf1 $6 {A rather ambitious approach, retaining the bishop-pair at the cost of some loss of coordination. White would have done better to allow an exchange on [d3], then aimed to use the presence of opposite-coloured bishops to steer the game towards a draw.} Rhd8 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Ge6f5] The weakness of [a4] means that White can't contest the d-file and meanwhile ...[Bf5] is imminent, eyeing the weakness on [c2].} 23. g3 {An easy move to criticise, but already Zuriel's position is a little uncomfortable.} Bf5 {[%csl Gc2]} 24. Bc4+ Be6 $5 {American WGM Nemcova is in no rush, content to enjoy her position and gradually grind away. The exchange of bishops is also fine for Black, otherwise she would likely have instead moved the king to [e7] or even [g6].} 25. Bf1 (25. Bxe6+ Kxe6 {White is in danger of becoming rather passive here, while Black can easily expand on the kingside with ...[Kf5], ...[g5] and ...[h5].}) 25... Bd7 $5 {[%csl Ga4] Attacking [a4] rather than return straight to [f5].} 26. Red1 {[%csl Ra4] Tactically viable, but now two pawns will be en prise after Black's next move.} Bf5 $1 {[%cal Gf5c2,Gc5a4,Gd8d1] The a-pawn was clearly taboo ( 26...Nxa4?? 27.Rxd7! or 26...Bxa4?? 27.Rxd8 Rxd8 28.b4 , but now ) 27...Rxd1 28.Rxd1 Nxa4 is a threat, as well as 27...Bxc2 .} 27. Bc4+ (27. Rxd8 Rxd8 28. a5 $5 {An engine-approved defence.} Bxc2 29. Rc1 {Suddenly White has some tactics available to exploit the loose black pieces on the c-file.} Nd3+ 30. Bxd3 Bxd3 31. Rd1 $1 Rd7 32. Ke3 Bb5 33. Rxd7+ Bxd7 {Clearly Black would try to push here, but such an opposite-coloured bishop endgame should be a relatively easy draw for White.}) 27... Ke8 28. Rdc1 $6 {[%csl Ga1,Gc1] Holding on to all the pawns, but it's not hard to notice how passive the white rooks have become.} Rd6 {[%cal Gf5d7]} ({Making way for ...Bd7 Bd7? runs into Ba5 , a policy which quickly bears fruit, although Black might also have calmly begun to seize space on the kingside with} 28... g5 $5 {.}) 29. g4 $4 ({The pressure gets to the Argentinean WGM who lashes out rather than, say, sensibly improving her position with} 29. a5 {.}) 29... Bd7 {[%cal Gc5e4,Gc5a4] Black is clearly better after this, but there was something even stronger.} (29... Bxg4 $1 {Yes, tactics are ever present and we suspect that Nemcova may have overestimated an obvious white response:} 30. Rg1 {(( 30.fxg4 Ne4+ ))} Be6 {With tempo and if White now exchanges on [e6] then 31...[Nxe6] will cover the en prise [g7]-pawn.}) 30. Bb4 (30. Bb3 $5 {was a bit grim, but also likely a better try.} Be6 $1 31. Bxe6 Nxe6 {This way Black avoids any opposite-coloured bishop scenario and may look to break with ...[h5] and/or to increase the pressure through ...[Rdc6] and ...[Rc4].}) 30... Rd4 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,Gc4] Deftly exploiting White's unfortunate line-up along the third rank.} 31. b3 Nxa4 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4] A little tactic to win a pawn.} 32. bxa4 $4 {Badly underestimating the resulting danger.} (32. c3 Rdxc4 $1 33. bxc4 Rxc4 {A very strong positional exchange sacrifice. Black already has two pawns for it, including an outside passed pawn, as well as excellent coordination: ...[Bc6] and ...[Rf4] may follow. That would leave White in trouble on the kingside, while the knight can easily regroup via [b6] or even land on [b2].}) (32. Be1 $5 Nc5 {White is a clear pawn down here and ...[Ne6] on the way with a pleasant set-up for Black, but this was quite possibly still the best way to prolong the game.}) 32... Rcxc4 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4]} 33. c3 Rd2+ 34. Kg3 Bc6 {[%cal Gc4f4,Gd2d3] Both ...[Rf4] and ...[Rd3] are imminent, and White's king and f-pawn just far too weak.} 35. Rd1 Rxd1 (35... Rf4 $1 {This sacrificial approach would have been almost a game-ender:} 36. Rxd2 Rxf3+ {Black will either get to regain the rook after} 37. Kg2 Rd3+ {or to force mate on the kingside.}) 36. Rxd1 Bxa4 {Zuriel has survived on the kingside, but at the cost of a second pawn. There are opposite-coloured bishops present, but also rooks, meaning that Black has excellent winning chances and Nemcova now converts well.} 37. Rd6 Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6,Gc4f4] The bishop might also have gone straight to [c6]. In short, Black would quite like the rook on [f4] and the bishop on [c6] to tie White down to the weakness of [f3].} 38. Rd3 Bc6 39. Ba5 Kf7 {[%cal Gf7e6] With the white rook already back on [d3], there's no need to place the black rook on [f4], so Nemcova improves her king.} 40. Bb6 Ke6 41. Ba5 Bd5 {[%cal Gc4a4] Obstructing the d-file to deny White any counterplay down it and Black may now aim to break the queenside blockade with ...[Ra4].} 42. h4 g6 $5 {[%cal Gh7h5] A change of approach. Now that White has a pawn on [h4], Black would like to fix it there.} 43. Re3 (43. h5 gxh5 $1 44. gxh5 Bc6 {Here too White is lost, with Black able to go ...[Rf4] and then either ...[Rf5] or ...[Kf5]-[g5] to round up the stray h-pawn.}) 43... h5 $1 {[%csl Gh4]} 44. gxh5 gxh5 45. Rd3 Rf4 46. Bc7 b5 {With White's rook so tied down, Black can simply begin to push the queenside majority.} 47. Bd8 Kd6 (47... Ra4 $5 {This would have been a decent alternative to bringing the king over.}) 48. Bb6 Kc6 49. Ba5 Ra4 {[%cal Ga4a5]} 50. Bd8 Rf4 {Nemcova is happy, in Capablanca-approved fashion, to repeat the position, emphasise control and make the defender weary.} 51. Ba5 Kc5 $1 {[%csl Gc5,Gg3][%cal Gc5c4] Only Black has an active king, a factor which now quickly proves decisive.} 52. Bd8 (52. Bb4+ $5 Kc4 53. Re3 Bc6 {Keeping the bishop away from being attacked, ahead of making decisive inroads with the king.} 54. Ba5 Kb3 55. Bb4 Ka4 56. Be7 a5 {The pawns are running and Black winning in straightforward fashion.}) 52... Kc4 53. Re3 Kb3 54. Rd3 {[%csl Rd5]} Ba8 55. Re3 Kc2 $1 {[%csl Gc2] Nemcova certainly can't be accused of failing to make full use of the most important piece in the endgame, the king.} 56. Kf2 $6 (56. Ba5 Ra4 57. Bd8 Kd2 {Even here the defence finds itself at breaking point.} 58. Bb6 Rf4 59. Kf2 Rxf3+ $5 {The simplest route to the full point.} 60. Rxf3 Bxf3 61. Kxf3 Kxc3 {Black's pawns are simply far too much for the white king and bishop to cope with}) 56... e4 $1 {A decisive breakthrough.} 57. Kg3 Rxf3+ 58. Rxf3 exf3 59. Bxf6 a5 {Black's two extra passed pawns are far too far apart for White to have any hope of defending.} 60. Bd4 a4 0-1

