1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 a6 6. N5c3 Bc5 {Having been allowed to retain the dark-squared bishop, it makes sense for Black to immediately put that piece to good use.} 7. Bc4 d6 8. O-O Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc8e6,Gb7b5] Our standard initial set-up in the 6. [N5c3] variation. We're now all set to castle, then begin to fight back on the light squares and in the centre with ...[Be6] and/or ...[b5].} 9. a3 {Creating an escape square for the bishop, as well as aiming to prevent Black from quickly causing problems with ...[b5]-[b4].} (9. a4 {This perhaps makes more sense, properly restraining the black b-pawn, and has also been seen in practice.} O-O 10. Bg5 h6 $1 {Just like when this position arises without [a4] and ...[O-O], i.e. 9. [Bg5] [h6], prodding the bishop without delay poses White a certain dilemma.} 11. Bxe7 {(( 11.Bh4?! g5! There's also 11...[Be6] if you really don't like this, but seizing some useful space while side lining White's dark-squared bishop is certainly positionally justified. 12.Bg3 Be6 And now it's time to challenge White's other bishop. Once again, Black would welcome the central control 13.Bxe6?! fxe6 would supply, while in any case ...[Rc8] is imminent and perhaps ...[Nd4]. As for the queen, she may simply step up to [d7] or even consider taking up a more aggressive role on [b6].))} Nxe7 12. Nd5 Ng6 $5 {This retained a knight in Heinechen-Vergara Jofre, Montevideo 2016, while preparing to play around the one on [d5]. Black can complete queenside mobilisation with ...[Be6] and ...[Rc8], after which it might be time to begin to generate some action on the kingside after ...[Qg5].}) 9... O-O {[%cal Gc8e6,Gc5d4,Gg8h8] All is set for ...[Be6], although that's not Black's only useful move. Indeed, it may be possible to be a little disruptive with ...[Bd4] or to be super aggressive with ...[Kh8], lining up ...[f5].} 10. Nd5 {As so often, White finds herself needing to leap forward so as the knight on [b1] hasn't anywhere better to go than [c3].} Nxd5 {[%csl Gd8] Black is happy to exchange one pair of knights, to avoid any slight cramp while also opening up a potential path over to the kingside for the queen on [d8].} 11. Bxd5 {An obvious and even fairly necessary recapture.} (11. Qxd5 $4 Nd4 {The trap springs shut on the white queen, who is all set to be rounded up after} 12. Z0 Be6 13. Qxb7 Ra7 {.}) (11. exd5 $2 Qh4 $1 {Even stronger than retreating the knight to [e7] then going ...[f5]. Black angles after exchanges to acquire the bishop-pair, while also getting ready to head forwards with some purpose and seize the initiative with ...[Nd4] and/or ...[Bg4].}) 11... Be6 {Completing development whilst, once again, hoping White will exchange on [e6], thereby opening the f-file for Black and leaving him with good central control.} 12. Nc3 Bd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4c3,Ga8c8]} (12... Bd4 {Beginning to cause problems by tickling the knight on c3 and if now} 13. Qd3 {then} Rc8 {would continue to be a little annoying for White.}) 13. Ne2 {Prodding the bishop in turn, a piece that Black would really rather preserve.} Bc5 $5 {Continuing the provocation while seeing if White is in a peaceful mood and so will aim to repeat moves.} (13... Ba7 {Had the players repeated, perhaps this, albeit on move 15, would have been Codirlasu's choice, keeping the bishop safe ahead of involving the queen's rook.}) 14. b4 {[%csl Rc5] Szikszai takes up the challenge.} Ba7 15. c4 Nd4 (15... Rc8 $5 {Maintaining the tension so whilst making a useful move which have been a touch more precise than immediately invading the hole on [d4], as Black does in the game.}) 16. Qd3 $6 {Allowing Black to favourably transform the structure, one of the ideas behind 15...[Nd4].} (16. Be3 $1 Bxd5 17. exd5 Nxe2+ 18. Qxe2 {This way White would have retained control of the position and, with her rooks heading to [c1] and [d1], been fine.}) 16... Bxd5 $1 17. cxd5 $6 {As so often, one mistake follows another.} (17. exd5 b5 $5 {This looks a little uncomfortable and likely concerned Szikszai, but the engines suggest that White should be able to cope:} 18. Be3 bxc4 19. Qxc4 Qc8 20. Qa2 $1 {Not an obvious move to spot in advance and something of a fairly forced one, but White may well be OK here. 20.Qd3? Qc2! This though overloads the defence to win material.}) 17... f5 $1 {[%csl Ga7,Gf2,Gf8] An obvious if also powerful pawn break, as the bishop on [a7] and rook on [f8] begin to come into their own.} 18. Bb2 $6 {[%csl Rd4] A slightly strange way of dealing with the knight on [d4], but Szikszai may have been thrown by how quickly matters had already started to go wrong.} (18. Be3 $5 fxe4 19. Qd1 Qf6 {Here Black is certainly pressing, but White would have had some chances to defend with [Ng3] the main idea.}) 18... Nxe2+ 19. Qxe2 fxe4 {Ripping open lines, although we can imagine that pushing on to [f4], looking to land the pawn on [f3], must also have been quite tempting.} 20. Qxe4 Rf4 $5 {[%csl Ge4,Gf2][%cal Gd8f6,Ga8f8] Continuing the direct strategy as Black gets ready to triple on the f-file against [f2].} 21. Qe2 Qf6 $5 {Intimidation has won many a chess game.} (21... Rc8 $1 22. Bc1 Rfc4 {This switch of approach would have preserved a pleasant plus for Black.}) 22. Rac1 $4 {Completely underestimating the danger.} (22. Bc1 $1 Rf5 23. Be3 $1 {Suddenly [f2] is secure and White would have been right back in the game, but backwards moves are ever easy to overlook, especially when you're feeling under pressure.}) 22... Rf8 {[%cal Gf4f2] With a rather direct threat.} 23. Rc2 {[%csl Ga7] The defence which White was rather reliant on, but she has misjudged just how powerful Black's play is down the [g1]-[a7] diagonal.} Qg6 $1 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gf4f2] A deadly sidestep.} (23... Rxf2 $5 24. Rxf2 Qg6 {Even here White would have been in some trouble thanks to a forcing line:} 25. Qd1 Rxf2 26. Rxf2 Qf5 27. Qe1 Bxf2+ 28. Qxf2 Qb1+ 29. Qf1 Qxb2 {And Black regains the piece with an extra pawn and near-decisive advantage.}) 24. Kh1 ({There's just nothing good to do in view of} 24. Qe1 {(to keep [f2] covered)} Qxc2 {.}) 24... Rxf2 25. Rxf2 Rxf2 {[%csl Gc2,Ge2,Gg2]} 26. Rc8+ Kf7 27. Rc7+ Kf6 $1 {[%cal Gf2e2,Gg6g2] White is out of checks and must give up the queen.} 0-1

